as Sudan and DRC.","tier":"alleged-credible"},{"mineral":"Gold","stage":"end","actor":"Global bullion · Russian reserves · Gulf markets","detail":"The end-buyer opacity is the point: gold that funds junta survival and Russian sanctions-evasion arrives on the market indistinguishable from clean supply.","tier":"documented"}],"patterns":["dubai-gold"],"history":{"roots":"Burkina Faso's present cannot be read without Thomas Sankara — and Sankara cannot be read without what he was against. Colonial Upper Volta was a labor reserve: France administered it to export men to Ivorian plantations, a deliberate underdevelopment Rodney's framework describes exactly. Sankara's four years (1983-87) were the continent's most radical answer: land reform, mass vaccination and literacy, women in government, refusal of odious debt ('the debt cannot be repaid... if we don't pay, our creditors will not die'), self-reliance down to the renamed country itself — 'land of upright people.' His assassination in 1987 — with Compaoré's coup, and questions about French and Ivorian complicity that a Burkinabè court finally adjudicated in 2022 — restored the client model for 27 years. Traoré's junta today wraps itself in Sankara's iconography while running a military regime Sankara would not recognize; the jihadist fire it fights burns hottest in the neglected north the labor-reserve economy never developed.","timeline":[{"date":"1960","e":"Independence from France (as Upper Volta)."},{"date":"1983-87","e":"Thomas Sankara's revolutionary, anti-imperialist presidency; assassinated in 1987 — a template Traoré now invokes."},{"date":"2015","e":"Jihadist violence spills over from Mali."},{"date":"2022","e":"Two coups; Capt. Ibrahim Traoré takes power in September."},{"date":"2023","e":"French troops expelled; pivot to Russia's Africa Corps."},{"date":"2024","e":"AES confederation formed with Mali and Niger; exit from ECOWAS."},{"date":"2025-26","e":"Burkina remains the world's most terrorism-affected country; JNIM contests much of the north and east."}],"actors":[{"name":"Capt. Ibrahim Traoré","bio":"Seized power in the 2022 coup at age 34; a pan-Africanist icon who invokes Sankara, expelled France, and embraced Russia. Popular abroad; presides over worsening violence at home."},{"name":"JNIM","bio":"Al-Qaeda's Sahel affiliate; the dominant jihadist force, blockading towns and contesting the countryside."},{"name":"Russia (Africa Corps)","bio":"Replaced France as security partner, trading regime protection for gold concessions and influence."},{"name":"VDP militias","bio":"State-armed civilian auxiliaries — force multiplier and a driver of ethnic-reprisal atrocities."}],"bridge":"The current war is the labor-reserve map on fire: JNIM recruits where the state never built, among Fulani communities the colonial cash-crop order marginalized and the VDP militias' reprisals now radicalize further. The anti-French pivot draws real power from Sankara's memory — the popular legitimacy is genuine, the grievance earned — but Russia's Africa Corps has simply moved into the patron's chair with gold concessions where France had CFA seigniorage: the extraction structure survived the flag change. Burkina is the test of whether sovereignty rhetoric without Sankara's redistributive substance can hold a country together; the world's-worst-terrorism ranking is the running answer.","sources":[{"work":"Thomas Sankara Speaks: The Burkina Faso Revolution 1983-87","author":"Thomas Sankara (collected speeches)","year":"1988/2007","note":"Primary texts — the debt speech (OAU, 1987), women's emancipation, self-reliance doctrine."},{"work":"Thomas Sankara: An African Revolutionary","author":"Ernest Harsch","year":"2014","note":"The standard scholarly biography and the assassination's politics."},{"work":"How Europe Underdeveloped Africa","author":"Walter Rodney","year":"1972","note":"The labor-reserve and deliberate-underdevelopment framework Upper Volta exemplified."},{"work":"Jihadism in the Sahel / Burkina Faso conflict data","author":"ACLED & Crisis Group Sahel reports","year":"2019-26","note":"Primary event data on the insurgency's geography — the neglected north and east."}]},"human":{"dead":26000,"disp":2100000,"famine":false,"aid":"blockaded towns","note":"World's most terrorism-affected state; ~2.1M displaced; JNIM blockades starve towns as siege policy."}},{"id":"mali","cat":"military","region":"West / Central Africa","subregion":"Sahel Core","name":"Mali — JNIM Economic Warfare + FLA/Azawad","sub":"Renewed Jul 4 offensive (Anefis/Aguelhoc/Gao) · $50M UAE ransom to JNIM","domain":"Jihadist Insurgency / Economic Siege","sev":"critical","status":"escalating","since":"2012","esc":92,"lat":17.6,"lon":-3,"trend":"up","w14":false,"exchange_active":false,"esc_history":[0,91,92,92,92,92,92,92,92,92],"cas":"29% of Sahel militant deaths; 207 JNIM deaths Jan-Apr; Defense Min Camara killed","disp":"~2M displaced","flag":"🇲🇱","note":"JUL 1: JNIM launched SEVEN coordinated attacks across Ségou + Kayes regions incl. Kayes city itself — region home to ~80% of Mali's industrial gold production, previously largely spared · army claims 80+ militants killed; JNIM claims dozens of soldiers + 100+ vehicles + governor's residence damage (DISPUTED figures) · JNIM threatened Kayes/Nioro blockade next day · Crisis Group: testing urban defenses, aiming to \"encourage the regime's collapse from within\" · 245,000+ Malian refugees now in Mauritania (~5% of its population) · JUL 4: renewed FLA/JNIM offensive at Anefis, Aguelhoc, Gao · Africa Center CONFIRMED: JNIM received $50M from UAE for release of 2 Emirati citizens — direct external-cash-to-jihadist link · JNIM adopting HTS-model (nationalist \"single front to dismantle the junta\" rhetoric; asked Russia to stay neutral) · army+Wagner mass-grave executions of Fulani continuing (HRW: 22 bodies Diafarabé)","leverage":[{"actor":"JNIM","asset":"Bamako fuel blockade — economic siege of the capital; 6,000 fighters; taxes/governance","str":"hi"},{"actor":"FLA (Azawad Liberation Front)","asset":"Seized Kidal; structured JNIM alliance; northern control","str":"hi"},{"actor":"Goïta junta + Africa Corps","asset":"Su-24 airstrikes, drones; but withdrew from Kidal region","str":"md"},{"actor":"Coastal neighbors (Senegal/CI)","asset":"95% of Mali fuel transits their routes — chokepoint leverage","str":"md"}],"gov":[{"src":"Mali Armed Forces General Staff","detail":"Confirmed Apr 25 coordinated attacks 'by unidentified armed terrorist groups'; Foreign Min Diop calls ECOWAS exit 'final'"},{"src":"US/UK Embassies","detail":"Urged citizens to 'depart immediately'; pulled diplomatic staff (Oct 2025)"},{"src":"Mali Education Ministry","detail":"Ordered schools shut Oct 26-Nov 9 due to blockade"},{"src":"Mali Armed Forces","detail":"Claims 80+ militants killed repelling the Jul 1 seven-site assault (figures disputed by JNIM claims)"},{"src":"Mauritania Government","detail":"245,000+ Malian refugees registered — equivalent to ~5% of Mauritania's population"}],"mil":"Mali accounts for 29% of Sahel militant-Islamist fatalities. The April 25 offensive was the largest since the 2012 rebellion: JNIM and the Azawad Liberation Front (FLA) launched coordinated attacks on Bamako, Kati, Mopti, Sévaré and Gao, killed Defense Minister Sadio Camara, and wounded the intelligence chief. The FLA seized Kidal after Malian and Africa Corps forces withdrew. Violence in Kayes, Sikasso, and Segou surged to the highest monthly levels since ACLED began recording in 1997.","pol":"JNIM's signature weapon is economic warfare: since September 2025 it has blockaded fuel into landlocked Bamako, attacking tanker convoys (130+ tankers destroyed per Bellingcat) along the Senegal and Côte d'Ivoire corridors that carry 95% of Mali's fuel. Prices spiked over 400% (to ~$130/litre); schools and embassies closed; Russia pledged 200,000 tons of petroleum to relieve the siege. Crisis Group's Ibrahim: 'If one of these countries falls, the rest will be in trouble.'","eco":"The fuel blockade paralyzed civil services, forced rolling blackouts (fuel prioritized for the state electricity provider), and brought Bamako to a standstill — the first time JNIM has used siege tactics on the capital itself.","assess":"Mali rises to 92. The July 1 Kayes strike is a strategic marker: seven simultaneous attacks hundreds of kilometers apart, hitting the region that produces ~80% of Mali's industrial gold and anchors the Senegal trade corridor. Crisis Group reads it as JNIM testing urban defenses and trying to induce regime collapse from within — the urban phase declared in 2024 is now operational. A DISPUTED single-source claim of Ukrainian involvement in coordinating April's attacks (likely info-op) is logged but not credited.","econlev":[{"holder":"JNIM","channel":"Commodity + corridor","exp":"HIGH","detail":"Kayes region = ~80% of industrial gold output, now under attack; 95% of fuel transits Senegal/CI corridors JNIM blockades"}],"external":[{"actor":"🇷🇺 Russia (Africa Corps)","side":"junta","flow":"~2,500 personnel; combat ops; gold-refinery support + nuclear/solar deals","tier":"documented","for":"Gold, mining concessions; $2.5B+ African gold → Ukraine war"},{"actor":"🇹🇷 Turkey","side":"junta","flow":"Bayraktar TB2 drones (displaced French suppliers)","tier":"documented","for":"Arms market; no-conditions influence"},{"actor":"🇮🇷 Iran","side":"junta","flow":"Mohajer-6/Shahed drones + IRGC-Quds explosives training; but Quds also coordinates with JNIM for safe havens","tier":"alleged-credible","for":"Artisanal gold; anti-Western alignment"},{"actor":"🇺🇸 US (corruption signal)","side":"junta-adjacent","flow":"Trump admin lifted Russia-sanctions on 3 senior Malian officials designated for facilitating Wagner (early 2026)","tier":"documented","for":"Attempted security-cooperation re-opening"}],"ext_flag":true,"tclass":"conflict","tier":"CRITICAL","hist_real":true,"as_of":"15 Jul 2026","tracked_since":"Wk4 (2026)","domain_tag":"Military","contested":{"summary":"Security services traded for gold. The security didn't arrive.","claims":[{"claim":"Russia's Africa Corps provides counter-terrorism support to the junta.","who":"Both — Moscow gets mining concessions and UN votes; the junta gets regime survival with no governance conditions.","evid":"Jihadist violence ROSE after Russian deployment in both Mali and Burkina. The arrangement is not failing at its actual purpose — its actual purpose is regime survival, not counter-terrorism.","status":"CONTESTED — judge it by what it's for"}]},"pipeline":[{"mineral":"Gold","stage":"mine","actor":"Loulo-Gounkoto, Fekola, Syama, Sadiola","detail":"Africa's 3rd-largest gold reserves. Barrick's Loulo-Gounkoto (Mali's biggest mine) did 723k oz in 2024 — then the junta seized a gold stockpile (Jan 2025), shut it, and forced a settlement: Barrick paid $253M and gave up ground under the 2023 Mining Code (state stake up to 35%). Restarted Dec 2025 at ~260-290k oz.","who":"Junta captures a rising share via the 2023 Mining Code; resource nationalism as regime finance","tier":"documented"},{"mineral":"Gold","stage":"process","actor":"Russia-backed national refinery (Bamako)","detail":"Mali broke ground (Oct 2025) on a Russia-and-Switzerland-backed gold refinery — the sovereignty play. West Africa produces 400+ tonnes/yr (Mali, Ghana, Burkina, Guinea) with NO globally certified refinery, so the region loses the refined-export margin. Framed as 'transparency,' it also routes value through a Russian partner.","who":"Russia (Yadran/partner) co-builds; Africa Corps takes security-for-gold concessions","tier":"documented"},{"mineral":"Gold","stage":"mid","actor":"Exported via UAE + Russia channels","detail":"Alongside industrial output, Mali loses billions/yr to smuggled artisanal gold — off-book, headed for Gulf refiners. The Russian refinery aims to capture that; JNIM also taxes artisanal gold at chokepoints (part of the ~$100M Sahel jihadist war economy).","who":"UAE/Gulf refiners + Russia; JNIM taxes the artisanal share","tier":"alleged-credible"},{"mineral":"Gold","stage":"end","actor":"Global bullion · Russian reserves","detail":"Refined gold is fungible — the end-buyer opacity is the point. Gold that funds junta survival and Russian sanctions-evasion arrives on the market indistinguishable from clean supply.","tier":"documented"},{"mineral":"Lithium","stage":"mine","actor":"Goulamina (China's Ganfeng)","detail":"Mali's largest lithium deposit (200M+ tonnes of ore) — majority-owned by China's Ganfeng Lithium, with Australia's Leo Lithium and a Malian state minority. The battery-metal future layered onto the gold economy.","who":"China (Ganfeng) controls the flagship lithium asset","tier":"documented"},{"mineral":"Lithium","stage":"end","actor":"China → EV batteries","detail":"Spodumene concentrate ships to China for conversion to battery-grade lithium — the same China-controlled processing dependency as the DRC's cobalt and Indonesia's nickel.","tier":"documented"}],"patterns":["china-refine","dubai-gold","resource-nationalism"],"history":{"roots":"Mali carries one of the world's great civilizational inheritances — Ghana, Mali, and Songhai empires; Timbuktu's manuscript libraries proving centuries of African scholarship the colonial canon denied existed — and a colonial rupture that inverted it. French conquest made the Sahel a periphery of the coast: the trans-Saharan trading world that had made Timbuktu rich was strangled in favor of export corridors to Dakar and Abidjan, and the north — Tuareg and Arab pastoral country — was administered as a militarized margin. Every independent Malian government inherited that inversion; four Tuareg rebellions (1963, 1990, 2006, 2012) are its recurring bill. Baz Lecocq's and Bruce Hall's work shows the racial hierarchies colonial rule codified between 'white' desert and 'Black' river populations still structuring the conflict. The 2012 collapse — rebellion, jihadist capture, coup, French intervention — began the present decade; the junta's break with France and embrace of Russia completes a sovereignty revolt whose grievances are old and real, even as its methods (Wagner massacres at Moura, junta permanence) betray them.","timeline":[{"date":"1960","e":"Independence from France."},{"date":"2012","e":"Tuareg rebellion + jihadist takeover of the north; a coup topples the government."},{"date":"2013","e":"French Operation Serval retakes northern towns."},{"date":"2020-21","e":"Two coups bring Assimi Goïta's junta to power."},{"date":"2022","e":"France's Barkhane force expelled; Wagner arrives."},{"date":"2023","e":"UN peacekeeping mission (MINUSMA) forced out."},{"date":"2024","e":"AES formed with Burkina and Niger; ECOWAS exit."},{"date":"2025-26","e":"JNIM's fuel blockade chokes Bamako; western Mali (Kayes) offensive."}],"actors":[{"name":"Gen. Assimi Goïta","bio":"Junta leader since the 2020-21 coups; architect of the Russia pivot and the break with France and ECOWAS."},{"name":"JNIM","bio":"Al-Qaeda's Sahel coalition; besieging Bamako economically via fuel blockades rather than assaulting it directly."},{"name":"Russia (Africa Corps)","bio":"Regime-security provider and gold-concession holder; co-building a national refinery."},{"name":"Tuareg (CSP/CMA)","bio":"Northern separatists whose 2012 rebellion started the war; a smoldering unresolved grievance."}],"bridge":"Today's war maps onto the colonial inversion precisely: JNIM's strength lies along the strangled trans-Saharan axes and among pastoralist communities the export-corridor economy abandoned; Bamako's fuel blockade is the periphery besieging the corridor state. The Russia-backed gold refinery is the sovereignty argument made concrete — capture the refining margin France's system exported — while Africa Corps massacres rerun the colonial column's methods under an anti-colonial flag. And Timbuktu's manuscripts, rescued from jihadist burning by its own librarians in 2013, remain the standing rebuke to every narrative that this land lacks its own order to restore.","sources":[{"work":"Disputed Desert: Decolonisation, Competing Nationalisms and Tuareg Rebellions in Northern Mali","author":"Baz Lecocq","year":"2010","note":"The definitive account of the north's rebellions as decolonization's unfinished business."},{"work":"A History of Race in Muslim West Africa, 1600–1960","author":"Bruce S. Hall","year":"2011","note":"The racial categories — desert/river, 'white'/'Black' — colonialism codified and the conflict still speaks."},{"work":"The Meanings of Timbuktu","author":"Shamil Jeppie & Souleymane Bachir Diagne (eds.)","year":"2008","note":"The manuscript civilization — primary proof of the intellectual world the 'no written history' myth erased."},{"work":"Moura massacre documentation","author":"UN OHCHR / Human Rights Watch","year":"2022-23","note":"Primary documentation of Wagner/FAMa atrocities — the sovereignty revolt's betrayal in practice."}]},"human":{"dead":15000,"disp":400000,"famine":false,"aid":"constrained","note":"Bamako fuel blockade + western offensive; Moura-type massacres in the record on the state/Wagner side too."}},{"id":"niger","cat":"military","region":"West / Central Africa","subregion":"Sahel Core","name":"Niger — ISSP + JNIM + Kidnapping Hub","sub":"Kirtachi camp overrun · Niamey/Tahoua airports · Tiani to 2030","domain":"Jihadist Insurgency","sev":"critical","status":"escalating","since":"2015","esc":88,"lat":17.6,"lon":8,"trend":"ss","w14":false,"esc_history":[0,88,88,88,88,88,88,88,88,88],"cas":"17% of Sahel militant deaths; Kirtachi 12 soldiers killed + 7 captured","disp":"500,000+ displaced","flag":"🇳🇪","note":"NEW STANDALONE · ISSP + JNIM outbidding · JNIM overran Kirtachi National Guard camp (12 killed, 7 captured) · ISSP hit Niamey Airport (Jan) + Tahoua Airport (Mar) + Niger-Benin oil pipeline sabotage · record Westerner kidnapping hub · Tiani dissolved parties, 5-yr transition to 2030 · ISSP leader Souleymane Ag Bakawa arrested by Mali/Africa Corps (Ménaka) · ACLED: Tillaberi now DEADLIEST region in central Sahel (1,200+ fatalities 2025, surpassing all Mali/Burkina regions); ISSP primary driver; Tera dept worst-hit (Burkina border)","leverage":[{"actor":"ISSP (IS Sahel)","asset":"Airport strikes; pipeline sabotage; kidnapping outsourcing; Nigeria-border bridge","str":"hi"},{"actor":"JNIM","asset":"Kirtachi camp seizure; western Niger expansion","str":"md"},{"actor":"Tiani junta + Africa Corps","asset":"AES Unified Force air campaigns; capital defense (failing)","str":"lo"},{"actor":"Niger-Benin pipeline","asset":"Oil-export lifeline — a sabotage target = economic leverage","str":"md"}],"gov":[{"src":"Niger Government","detail":"Confirmed AES Unified Force 'intense air campaigns' after Apr 25; accuses France of sponsoring attacks; cancelled May 1 parades for security"},{"src":"Tiani transitional decree","detail":"Dissolved all political parties (Mar 2025); 5-year transitional mandate to 2030"}],"mil":"Niger accounts for 17% of Sahel militant-Islamist fatalities. JNIM overran a National Guard camp at Kirtachi (12 soldiers killed, 7 captured), while ISSP has hit high-value infrastructure: Niamey Airport (January), Tahoua Airport (March), and repeated sabotage of the Niger-Benin oil pipeline. ISSP is expanding rear bases southward toward the Nigeria border, replicating Sahel massacre patterns via local 'Lakurawa' recruits.","pol":"Niger is now the epicenter of the Sahel's Westerner-kidnapping economy — ISSP outsources abductions to criminal networks, driving record-high kidnapping in Mali and Niger. General Tiani dissolved all political parties after a stage-managed national conference and began a five-year transitional mandate running to 2030. The government blames France for sponsoring regional attacks.","eco":"The Niger-Benin oil pipeline is both the country's export lifeline and a repeated ISSP sabotage target — economic warfare mirroring JNIM's Mali blockade.","assess":"Niger enters at 88. It is the ISSP stronghold to Mali/Burkina's JNIM core, and the JNIM-ISSP outbidding competition is driving both toward higher-impact attacks (airports, pipelines, kidnappings). Tiani's extension to 2030 confirms the coup's justification — that juntas would restore security — has not been met. The Nigeria-border bridge is the key expansion vector.","external":[{"actor":"🇷🇺 Russia (Africa Corps)","side":"junta","flow":"MoU for uranium extraction; security presence","tier":"documented","for":"Uranium (SOMAÏR nationalized), migration leverage"},{"actor":"🇮🇷 Iran","side":"junta","flow":"Advanced drones-for-uranium deal: ~300 metric tons yellowcake (~$56M) for drones + SAMs + economic aid","tier":"alleged-credible","for":"Uranium for nuclear program — the sharpest resource-for-arms swap"},{"actor":"🇹🇷 Turkey","side":"junta","flow":"Turkish Class III armed drones","tier":"documented","for":"Arms market expansion"}],"ext_flag":true,"tclass":"conflict","tier":"SEVERE","hist_real":true,"as_of":"13 Jul 2026","tracked_since":"Wk4 (2026)","domain_tag":"Military","econlev":[{"holder":"ISSP / JNIM","channel":"Kidnapping + trade-route tax","exp":"HIGH","detail":"Niger is the Sahel's kidnapping hub — ISSP shifted to high-value foreign abductions (an Austrian in Agadez, 4 Moroccan truckers) because foreigners command higher ransoms"},{"holder":"Niger state","channel":"Uranium nationalization","exp":"HIGH","detail":"Seized Orano's Somaïr; uranium is the state's counter-leverage against France/the West"}],"contested":{"summary":"No significant narrative-war dimension identified in this theater at present. The main claims are broadly consistent with the evidence, or the disputes are policy disagreements rather than contested facts. This is stated affirmatively rather than left blank — the absence of an information operation is itself a finding.","claims":[]},"pipeline":[{"mineral":"Uranium","stage":"mine","actor":"Arlit / SOMAÏR (nationalized from Orano)","detail":"World's ~8th-largest uranium producer. The junta stripped France's Orano of its 63.4% SOMAÏR stake (June 2025), nationalized the mine, and declared it would sell 'to whoever wishes to buy.' Grievance: Orano took 86.3% of commercialized uranium since 1971, above its equity share.","who":"Junta (via SOPAMIN/TNUC) seized operational control; expelled the French operator","tier":"documented"},{"mineral":"Uranium","stage":"process","actor":"Yellowcake stranded at Airbase 101, Niamey","detail":"THE CHOKEPOINT: 1,000-1,500 tonnes of yellowcake sit on trucks that haven't moved in weeks, next to Niamey's airport. An ICSID tribunal (Sept 2025) ordered Niger NOT to sell/transfer SOMAÏR output pending Orano's claim — so no Western buyer, insurer, or shipper will touch it. Sovereignty without a market.","who":"ICSID ruling blocks legitimate buyers; the uranium is Niger's and unsellable","tier":"documented"},{"mineral":"Uranium","stage":"mid","actor":"Rosatom / Uranium One (Russia) — the only buyer","detail":"Niger signed a July-2025 Rosatom MoU and a Dec-2025 TNUC-Uranium One deal; reportedly agreed to sell Rosatom ~1,000t of yellowcake. Russia is 'almost certainly' the buyer willing to defy the tribunal. Iran also pursued a ~300t yellowcake-for-drones swap (~$56M). Western majors (Global Atomic's Dasa) still operate with junta blessing.","who":"Russia (Rosatom) is the only actor willing to move stranded, litigated uranium","tier":"alleged-credible"},{"mineral":"Uranium","stage":"end","actor":"Nuclear fuel · Russian/Iranian programs","detail":"Enriched into reactor fuel — the strategic prize. Niger's ~40% of the old EU-supply picture is now being locked into the Russian nuclear-fuel orbit while the West forfeits it, mirroring the Kazakhstan reactor-bid loss.","tier":"documented"}],"patterns":["resource-nationalism"],"history":{"roots":"Niger's uranium story is Françafrique in its purest concentrate. From 1971, France's Orano (né Areva/Cogema) mined Arlit under agreements that Nigerien scholar Rahmane Idrissa and others document as near-tributary: Niger — consistently at the bottom of the Human Development Index — powered one in three French lightbulbs while Arlit's workers breathed radioactive dust and the state took a sliver of the value (the junta's figure: 86.3% of commercialized uranium taken above equity share since 1971). The CFA franc, French basing rights, and aid conditionality completed the package Nkrumah had named in 1965: neo-colonialism, independence's form without its substance. The 2023 coup rode genuine popular rage at that bargain — the crowds at the French base were not manufactured — and the SOMAÏR nationalization is the bill presented. That the uranium now sits stranded, sellable only to Rosatom, is the tragedy of a revolt that could name the extractor but not build the alternative.","timeline":[{"date":"1960","e":"Independence from France; uranium mining begins soon after."},{"date":"2010s","e":"Niger becomes a key US/French counterterrorism hub (drone base at Agadez)."},{"date":"26 Jul 2023","e":"Presidential guard coups President Bazoum."},{"date":"2023","e":"French forces expelled; junta joins the anti-Western Sahel bloc."},{"date":"2024","e":"US forced to leave the Agadez drone base; AES confederation formed."},{"date":"Jun 2025","e":"Junta nationalizes Orano's SOMAÏR uranium mine."},{"date":"2025-26","e":"Uranium stranded by an ICSID ruling; Rosatom the only willing buyer."}],"actors":[{"name":"Gen. Abdourahamane Tiani","bio":"Presidential-guard commander who led the 2023 coup and now heads the junta; expelled Western forces, seized the uranium."},{"name":"Orano (France)","bio":"The French nuclear firm stripped of its Niger uranium stake — the extraction relationship the junta upended."},{"name":"Russia (Rosatom)","bio":"The only actor willing to buy litigated, stranded Nigerien uranium — Moscow's Sahel foothold."},{"name":"JNIM / IS-Sahel","bio":"Jihadist groups exploiting the border zones; the original rationale for the Western presence now gone."}],"bridge":"The stranded yellowcake at Airbase 101 is the whole predicament in 1,500 tonnes: sovereignty asserted (the seizure), the old patron expelled (Orano, the French army, the US drone base), and the extraction structure still standing — only the buyer's flag changes, France's grid swapped for Rosatom's supply chain, with the ICSID tribunal enforcing the old order's law against the new order's claim. Jihadist violence meanwhile spreads through the borderlands the uranium economy never developed. Niger is the platform's cleanest test of whether resource nationalism without processing capacity is leverage or just a different dependency.","sources":[{"work":"The Politics of Islam in the Sahel: Between Persuasion and Violence","author":"Rahmane Idrissa","year":"2017","note":"Nigerien scholarship on the state, religion, and the Sahel crisis from inside."},{"work":"Neo-Colonialism: The Last Stage of Imperialism","author":"Kwame Nkrumah","year":"1965","note":"The primary theorization of independence-without-substance that the uranium arrangements exemplified."},{"work":"Being Nuclear: Africans and the Global Uranium Trade","author":"Gabrielle Hecht","year":"2012","note":"Arlit's labor and health history — how Nigerien uranium was made invisible in 'French' nuclear power."},{"work":"From Empires to NGOs in the West African Sahel","author":"Gregory Mann","year":"2015","note":"How sovereignty leaked from Sahelian states to external administrators — the vacuum the juntas now claim to fill."}]}},{"id":"benin-togo","cat":"military","region":"West / Central Africa","subregion":"Coastal Frontier","name":"Benin & Togo — JNIM Coastal Expansion","sub":"Benin deadliest on record · JNIM emir appointed · Kpendjal","domain":"Jihadist Spillover","sev":"high","status":"escalating","since":"2019","esc":72,"lat":10.5,"lon":1.5,"trend":"up","w14":false,"esc_history":[0,72,72,72,72,72,72,72,72,72],"cas":"Benin 305 deaths (+76%, record); Togo 54 civ + 8 soldiers","disp":"Northern border displacement","flag":"🇧🇯🇹🇬","note":"NEW · Crisis Group: Benin + Togo 'in greatest peril' · Benin 305 militant deaths = deadliest on record (+76%) · JNIM appointed an EMIR for Benin · Koualou attack (disputed Benin-Burkina border) · Togo: Kpendjal Prefecture worst-hit, 54 civ killed · 450+ incidents/yr within 50km of coastal borders","leverage":[{"actor":"JNIM","asset":"Appointed Benin emir; deliberate strategic expansion (not spillover); border-zone control","str":"hi"},{"actor":"Benin/Togo states","asset":"Militarized north; refugee-vetting (Ivorian model); regional coordination","str":"md"},{"actor":"Coastal ports","asset":"Landlocked-Sahel dependence = leverage over AES fuel/trade","str":"md"}],"gov":[{"src":"Togo Government","detail":"Established one of the sub-region's most important security systems in the north; Cinkassé/Kpendjal front lines"},{"src":"Benin Government","detail":"Military positions at Koualou attacked; disputed border zone with Burkina Faso"},{"src":"AES-ECOWAS (Togo-mediated)","detail":"Togo FM Dussey offered to 'bridge' AES and ECOWAS — first formal interaction since May 2025"}],"mil":"Benin recorded 305 militant-Islamist-linked fatalities over the past year — the deadliest on record and a 76% jump — while Togo saw at least 54 civilians and 8 soldiers killed, concentrated in Kpendjal Prefecture wedged between the Burkina and Benin borders. JNIM launched a coordinated attack on military positions at Koualou (a Benin-Burkina disputed border town). Crisis Group assesses this as deliberate strategic expansion, not mere spillover.","pol":"The clearest signal of intent: JNIM's leadership appointed a dedicated emir for Benin. ACLED-recorded JNIM incidents in Benin rose from 6 (2019-21) to 66 in 2022, 173 in 2023, 138 in 2024 — a sustained campaign. Togo has built one of the sub-region's most robust northern security systems; its FM is mediating between the AES and ECOWAS.","eco":"Both states are the coastal outlet for the landlocked AES — giving them chokepoint leverage over Sahel fuel/trade, but also making their northern borders the frontier of the jihadist advance toward the sea.","assess":"Benin and Togo enter as a clustered coastal-frontier theater at 72 — the leading edge of JNIM's southward push toward the Gulf of Guinea. Crisis Group names them 'in greatest peril.' The appointment of a Benin emir and the record death tolls mark the transition from spillover to a deliberate coastal campaign. This is the frontier to watch for whether the Sahel war reaches the Atlantic.","tclass":"conflict","tier":"ELEVATED","hist_real":true,"as_of":"15 Jul 2026","tracked_since":"Wk4 (2026)","domain_tag":"Military","external":[{"actor":"🏴 JNIM","side":"insurgents","flow":"Katiba Hanifa faction pushing into Alibori, Borgou, Atacora; a dedicated emir appointed for Benin","tier":"documented","for":"Coastal access — converting a landlocked insurgency into one with port reach"},{"actor":"🇫🇷 France / EU","side":"coastal states","flow":"Security assistance to the littoral states as the buffer against Sahel spillover","tier":"documented","for":"Hold the line at the Gulf of Guinea after being expelled from the Sahel"},{"actor":"🇺🇸 US","side":"coastal states","flow":"Counter-terror cooperation; Benin also pledged up to 2,000 troops to Haiti's GSF","tier":"documented","for":"Prevent jihadist coastal breakout; hemispheric goodwill trade"}],"econlev":[{"holder":"JNIM","channel":"Coastal taxation + trafficking","exp":"HIGH","detail":"Pushing toward the Gulf of Guinea ports — the strategic prize is access to coastal trade, smuggling routes, and a port economy the Sahel lacks"}],"contested":{"summary":"No significant narrative-war dimension identified in this theater at present. The main claims are broadly consistent with the evidence, or the disputes are policy disagreements rather than contested facts. This is stated affirmatively rather than left blank — the absence of an information operation is itself a finding.","claims":[]},"history":{"roots":"Benin and Togo entered independence on opposite tracks that converged in vulnerability. Dahomey (Benin) — heir to a sophisticated precolonial kingdom whose royal art France looted (and only began returning in 2021) — cycled through coups before Kérékou's Marxist state, then pioneered Africa's democratic renewal with the 1990 National Conference, the model the continent copied. Togo went the other way: Sylvanus Olympio, independence's champion who challenged the CFA franc's grip, was assassinated in 1963 in Africa's first post-colonial coup — by soldiers including Gnassingbé Eyadéma, whose family has now ruled for 58 years, the longest dynasty in Africa, constitutionally renovated as recently as 2024. Both states' norths — Muslim, pastoral, poorer, distant from the coastal capitals where colonial and post-colonial investment pooled — are the classic neglected periphery, and it is exactly there that JNIM now recruits.","timeline":[{"date":"1960","e":"Both independent from France."},{"date":"1967/2005","e":"Togo: Gnassingbé père seizes power; son inherits amid violence."},{"date":"2021","e":"First JNIM attacks cross into northern Benin."},{"date":"2022-24","e":"W-Pendjari park complex becomes the southern front; Benin's losses mount."},{"date":"2024","e":"Togo's constitutional change — Gnassingbé's indefinite super-premiership."},{"date":"2025-26","e":"Deadliest attacks yet on Beninese positions; AES rupture blocks joint operations; Accra Initiative moribund."}],"actors":[{"name":"JNIM","bio":"The Sahel franchise expanding to the coast — sanctuary in Burkina, targets in the parks, recruitment in the marginalized north."},{"name":"Benin (Talon)","bio":"The democracy under strain fighting the war hardest — hundreds of casualties, drone purchases, and a political system narrowing as it fights."},{"name":"Togo (Gnassingbé)","bio":"The dynasty — 58 years of family rule, now constitutionalized; the northern front is also a regime-security pretext."},{"name":"The AES juntas","bio":"The severed partners — Burkina's rupture with the coastal states is the seam the jihadists exploit."}],"bridge":"The jihadist push into the W-Pendjari parks finds the coastal states' soft seam: northern communities for whom the southern state is a tax collector and a checkpoint, not a school or a clinic — the same core-periphery extraction geometry as everywhere on this board, in miniature. Benin fights hardest and bleeds most while its democratic model narrows; Togo's dynasty converts the threat into a security rationale for its constitutional coup. And the AES rupture — the juntas' feud with the coast — has severed the joint operations the border requires, proving that the region's political fractures are themselves a jihadist force-multiplier. Olympio's fate remains the region's original lesson in what challenging the monetary order cost.","sources":[{"work":"Le Togo sous Eyadéma","author":"Comi M. Toulabor","year":"1986","note":"Togolese scholarship on the dynasty's construction — the machinery still running in 2026."},{"work":"Soldier and State in Africa (Togo chapter: the 1963 coup)","author":"Claude E. Welch Jr. (ed.)","year":"1970","note":"The scholarly treatment of Africa's first post-colonial coup and the army politics behind Olympio's assassination — replacing an earlier under-verified citation."},{"work":"Democratic Experiments in Africa (Benin's National Conference model)","author":"Michael Bratton & Nicolas van de Walle","year":"1997","note":"Benin 1990 as the template of the continent's democratic renewal — the inheritance now under strain."},{"work":"Coastal West Africa spillover reporting","author":"Crisis Group / ACLED","year":"2022-26","note":"Primary tracking of JNIM's southward expansion into the parks complex."}]}},{"id":"ghana","cat":"military","region":"West / Central Africa","subregion":"Coastal Frontier","name":"Ghana — Frontier State + Galamsey Nexus","sub":"Logistical rear base · galamsey = #1 security threat · Bawku","domain":"Pre-Insurgency / Organized Crime","sev":"medium","status":"escalating","since":"2022","esc":58,"lat":9.5,"lon":-1,"trend":"up","w14":false,"esc_history":[0,58,58,58,58,58,58,58,58,58],"cas":"No large-scale attack yet; Bawku ethnic conflict deaths","disp":"Northern displacement risk","flag":"🇬🇭","note":"NEW · Ghana's own ECOWAS Parliament submission: militants use N. Ghana for LOGISTICAL + MEDICAL support · galamsey (illegal gold mining) named #1 national security threat (KAIPTC) — organized crime/corruption nexus · Bawku Mamprusi-Kusasi conflict · Zongo-community radicalization risk · no confirmed large-scale attack inside Ghana yet","leverage":[{"actor":"JNIM/ISGS","asset":"Rear-base logistics + medical staging in N. Ghana; galamsey recruitment pool","str":"md"},{"actor":"Ghanaian state","asset":"NCCRM early-warning (Act 1070); northern DSF redeployment; democratic legitimacy","str":"md"},{"actor":"Galamsey networks","asset":"Financiers + political-economic actors; environmental destruction; organized-crime ecosystem","str":"md"}],"gov":[{"src":"Ghana ECOWAS Parliament submission","detail":"Warned militants use N. Ghana for logistical/medical support; risk of escalation within borders"},{"src":"NCCRM (Act 1070, 2021)","detail":"National Centre for Coordination of Early Warning; monitors crime, governance, terrorism; monthly reports to ECOWAS"},{"src":"NAIMOS anti-galamsey","detail":"3 monitoring bases in Western Region (Ellembelle, Amenfi East, Ahanta West); galamsey ravaged 11 of 14 districts"}],"mil":"Ghana has so far avoided a large-scale jihadist attack, but its own ECOWAS Parliament submission confirms Islamic militant groups use parts of northern Ghana for logistical and medical support connected to Sahel insurgencies. Suspected fighters participate in artisanal gold mining in the Ghana-Burkina border forests. The Bawku conflict (Mamprusi-Kusasi ethnic violence) and farmer-herder tensions provide local fracture points.","pol":"KAIPTC and Ghanaian security institutions name galamsey (illegal gold mining) the country's top emerging national-security threat — a highly organized, mechanized ecosystem of financiers, equipment suppliers, and political-economic actors linked to organized crime, environmental destruction, and potential extremist recruitment. Ghana established the NCCRM early-warning centre (Act 1070) and relaunched an anti-galamsey campaign with the NAIMOS bases. Zongo (Hausa-trader) communities are flagged as radicalization risks.","eco":"Galamsey bypasses formal taxation, pollutes major rivers (Pra, Birim, Ankobra, Offin), disrupts cocoa production, and creates an unemployed youth pool vulnerable to recruitment — the crime-corruption-security nexus in one.","assess":"Ghana enters at 58 as a frontier state — not yet in open conflict but structurally exposed. The distinctive thread is the fusion you asked to track: galamsey is simultaneously the #1 crime/corruption problem and a potential security on-ramp, linking illegal mining, organized crime, and jihadist recruitment. Ghana's democratic institutions and early-warning architecture (NCCRM) are its resilience; its northern marginalization and galamsey grievances are the vulnerabilities.","econlev":[{"holder":"United States","channel":"Portfolio securities","exp":"LOW","detail":"$2.0B US securities (2024 TIC), debt-heavy — small against the galamsey shadow economy"}],"tclass":"watch","tier":"ELEVATED","hist_real":true,"as_of":"15 Jul 2026","tracked_since":"Wk4 (2026)","domain_tag":"Military","contested":{"summary":"No significant narrative-war dimension identified in this theater at present. The main claims are broadly consistent with the evidence, or the disputes are policy disagreements rather than contested facts. This is stated affirmatively rather than left blank — the absence of an information operation is itself a finding.","claims":[]},"external":[{"actor":"🇺🇸🇬🇧 West / IMF","side":"creditor","flow":"$3B IMF program conditionality driving the fiscal recovery; Western mining and cocoa buyers","tier":"documented","for":"Debt-service compliance and a stable ECOWAS anchor against the Sahel juntas"},{"actor":"🇨🇳 China","side":"creditor + buyer","flow":"Major bilateral creditor in the debt restructuring; gold and bauxite offtake; infrastructure loans","tier":"documented","for":"Gold, bauxite, and a coastal foothold in a stable West African state"},{"actor":"🇧🇫 Sahel juntas (AES)","side":"destabilizing neighbor","flow":"Spillover pressure — jihadist violence and smuggling creeping south into the coastal frontier","tier":"documented","for":"N/A — Ghana is the buffer the AES instability threatens"}],"ext_flag":true,"history":{"roots":"Ghana is Pan-Africanism's first proof and first warning. Nkrumah made the Gold Coast's 1957 independence explicitly continental — 'the independence of Ghana is meaningless unless it is linked up with the total liberation of Africa' — hosted the All-African People's Conference, wrote the book that named neo-colonialism, and pushed industrialization (Akosombo, the Volta scheme) to escape the cocoa-and-gold export trap Britain built. The 1966 coup that removed him — welcomed and, the declassified record shows, encouraged by Washington — was the warning: the trap defends itself. Rawlings' revolutions and the Fourth Republic built the region's sturdiest democracy atop the same export structure, and the 2022 default showed the structure's teeth again: a middle-income star brought down by the oldest arrangement in the book — borrowing against commodities priced elsewhere.","timeline":[{"date":"1957","e":"First sub-Saharan independence; Nkrumah's Pan-African beacon."},{"date":"1966-81","e":"Coup era; Rawlings' revolutions."},{"date":"1992","e":"Fourth Republic — the durable two-party democracy begins."},{"date":"2022","e":"Debt default — $30B restructuring, IMF program."},{"date":"2024","e":"Mahama returns to power; ECOWAS loses the AES states."},{"date":"2025-26","e":"IMF-tracked recovery; gold windfall + galamsey crisis; northern-border jihadist watch."}],"actors":[{"name":"John Mahama","bio":"The returned president — managing IMF discipline, gold-sector cleanup, and the democratic brand West Africa needs intact."},{"name":"The IMF / creditors","bio":"The $3B program's authors — the conditionality shaping every budget line."},{"name":"Gold (formal + galamsey)","bio":"Africa's top producer — record prices fund the recovery while illegal mining poisons rivers and leaks billions."},{"name":"The Sahel spillover","bio":"The northern threat probing Bawku's local conflict — the seam between Ghana's stability and the region's fire."}],"bridge":"Ghana's present is Nkrumah's diagnosis running on schedule: the IMF program dictates the budget of gold's African leader while record bullion prices mostly reward refiners and creditors abroad; galamsey poisons the rivers because the formal economy can't absorb the miners; and the GoldBod reforms — state purchasing, refining ambitions — are the first structural push toward his answer since Akosombo. Meanwhile the AES juntas quote Nkrumah against the very ECOWAS Ghana anchors: the contest over his inheritance — sovereignty by institution-building or by rupture — is the region's live ideological war, and Ghana's stability is its stake.","sources":[{"work":"Neo-Colonialism: The Last Stage of Imperialism","author":"Kwame Nkrumah","year":"1965","note":"The primary text — written from Accra, naming the system that would soon remove its author."},{"work":"Africa Must Unite","author":"Kwame Nkrumah","year":"1963","note":"The continental program Ghana's independence was declared to serve."},{"work":"The Political and Social Thought of Kwame Nkrumah","author":"Ama Biney","year":"2011","note":"The scholarly recovery of Nkrumah beyond both hagiography and Cold War caricature."},{"work":"Declassified US records on the 1966 coup","author":"US State Dept/CIA (FRUS series)","year":"released 1999-","note":"Primary documentation of Washington's foreknowledge and satisfaction — the warning made explicit."}]}},{"id":"cote-divoire","cat":"political","region":"West / Central Africa","subregion":"Coastal Frontier","name":"Côte d'Ivoire — Electoral Crisis + Coup Disinformation","sub":"Ouattara 4th term · opposition barred · coordinated coup-rumor campaigns · JNIM northern pressure","domain":"Electoral Crisis / Information Warfare","sev":"medium","status":"volatile","since":"2020","esc":62,"lat":8.5,"lon":-5.5,"trend":"up","w14":false,"esc_history":[54,54,54,54,54,54,54,54,62,62],"cas":"No current conflict deaths; 2010-11 post-election civil war killed ~3,000 — the precedent driving present fear","disp":"Northern border communities under JNIM pressure; no mass displacement currently","flag":"🇨🇮","note":"REFRAMED (Wk15) — the theater's live risk is POLITICAL + INFORMATIONAL, not (yet) kinetic · COUP DISINFORMATION: recurring coordinated campaigns (May 2025, again ~Apr 2026) falsely claim a military takeover — same fabricated beats each time (army chief Lassina Doumbia 'assassinated,' Ouattara 'missing/dead,' 'internet cut') · Ivorian news agency: claims are 'completely unfounded... the result of a deliberate and coordinated disinformation campaign' · Ouattara chaired a routine cabinet meeting + public ceremony during the alleged 'coup'; NO credible Ivorian outlet (state or private) reported the violence; most viral posts written in ENGLISH in a Francophone country — a tell · fact-checkers flagged the videos as misleading; ~9,700 Facebook users discussed the fake coup in one day · analysts describe 'a campaign to promote military coups across West Africa' · REAL UNDERLYING TENSION: Ouattara nominated by RHDP for a 4TH TERM (widely resented); opposition leader Tidjane Thiam (ex-Credit Suisse CEO) STRUCK from the electoral roll (Apr 2025) over a French-nationality technicality — he's appealing, calls it political; Gbagbo + others barred over past convictions · 2010 election spiraled into civil war (~3,000 dead) — that memory drives the fear · widespread sympathy for the AES juntas (Mali/Burkina), who are anti-France unlike the Paris-aligned Ouattara · protesters call the govt a puppet of France + the US; criticism of expanding AFRICOM presence · JNIM pressure on the northern border continues (the original theater rationale)","leverage":[{"actor":"Ouattara / RHDP","asset":"Incumbency + control of the courts/electoral roll (used to bar Thiam and Gbagbo); French + US backing; strong economic record","str":"hi"},{"actor":"Opposition (Thiam/PDCI, Gbagbo)","asset":"Popular legitimacy + street mobilization; the 4th-term grievance; but excluded from the ballot","str":"md"},{"actor":"Information operators (unattributed)","asset":"Coordinated coup-rumor campaigns exploiting the AES-sympathy fault line — manufacturing the appearance of rupture in the region's key French-aligned economy","str":"md"},{"actor":"France / US","asset":"Ouattara's patrons; AFRICOM presence expanding — but that presence is itself now the grievance the campaigns exploit","str":"md"},{"actor":"JNIM","asset":"Northern-border pressure; would benefit from an Ivorian political rupture","str":"md"}],"gov":[{"src":"Ivorian news agency (AIP)","detail":"Coup claims on X are 'completely unfounded... the result of a deliberate and coordinated disinformation campaign'"},{"src":"Al Jazeera / News24 / fact-checkers","detail":"Verified: Ouattara chaired a cabinet meeting during the alleged coup; army chief Doumbia not assassinated; viral videos flagged as misleading; no credible Ivorian outlet reported violence"},{"src":"Ivorian courts (Apr 2025)","detail":"Struck opposition leader Tidjane Thiam from the electoral roll over a French-nationality technicality; Gbagbo and others barred over past convictions"}],"mil":"Not a kinetic theater — and the central analytical point is that claims to the contrary are fabricated. Recurring coordinated campaigns (May 2025, again around April 2026) have falsely announced a military coup, always with the same manufactured beats: army chief of staff Lassina Doumbia assassinated, President Ouattara missing or dead, internet access severed. Each time, the claims collapsed on contact with evidence — Ouattara chaired cabinet meetings during the alleged takeovers, no credible Ivorian outlet reported the violence, and most viral posts were written in English in a Francophone country. The real military dimension is JNIM's continuing pressure on the northern border as it pushes toward the Gulf of Guinea.","pol":"The genuine crisis is electoral. Ouattara was nominated by his RHDP party for a fourth term that many Ivorians resent, while the courts struck opposition leader Tidjane Thiam from the electoral roll over a French-nationality technicality (he is appealing and calls it political) and barred Gbagbo and others over past convictions. The memory of 2010 — when a disputed election spiraled into a civil war that killed roughly 3,000 — is what gives the fear its charge. Analysts note widespread Ivorian sympathy for the young military leaders who seized power in Mali and Burkina Faso, who are hostile to France, unlike the Paris-aligned Ouattara. Protesters call the government a puppet of France and the United States, with growing criticism of the expanding AFRICOM presence.","eco":"Côte d'Ivoire is the world's largest cocoa producer and West Africa's economic hub — Ouattara is genuinely credited with a decade and a half of rapid growth and relative political peace, which is the strongest argument for the status quo and the reason a rupture here would transmit far beyond its borders.","assess":"Côte d'Ivoire is re-scored to 62 (ELEVATED, watch-class) and reframed: its live risk is political and informational rather than kinetic. The coup that keeps being announced is not happening — Ivorian authorities call it a deliberate, coordinated disinformation campaign, and every verification test confirms that. But the campaigns are themselves the signal worth tracking: they are engineered to exploit a real fault line — resentment of a fourth term, an opposition excluded by the courts, and open sympathy for the anti-France juntas next door — in the region's most important French-aligned economy. Analysts describe a broader effort to promote military coups across West Africa. This is the AES-vs-ECOWAS contest fought through information rather than arms, which is why the theater now sits in that bloc. Attribution remains unresolved and is labeled as such. Watch the Thiam appeal, whether Ouattara formally stands, the election timetable, and whether the disinformation campaigns escalate around key dates.","econlev":[{"holder":"Côte d'Ivoire","channel":"Cocoa","exp":"HIGH","detail":"World's largest cocoa producer — the regional economic hub; political rupture here would transmit directly into global cocoa markets and West African stability"},{"holder":"France / West","channel":"Patronage + AFRICOM","exp":"MED","detail":"Ouattara's Paris alignment and the expanding US military presence are the exact grievances the coup-disinformation campaigns weaponize"}],"tclass":"watch","tier":"ELEVATED","hist_real":true,"as_of":"15 Jul 2026","tracked_since":"Wk4 (2026)","domain_tag":"Political","external":[{"actor":"🇫🇷 France","side":"Ouattara","flow":"Former colonial power; close ties to Ouattara; backed his forces in the 2011 civil war","tier":"documented","for":"Retain its last major West African anchor after expulsion from the Sahel"},{"actor":"🇺🇸 US (AFRICOM)","side":"Ouattara","flow":"Expanding regional military presence — increasingly the target of protest criticism","tier":"documented","for":"Fill the counter-terror vacuum left by France's Sahel expulsion; hold the coastal line"},{"actor":"❓ Unattributed info-ops","side":"anti-Ouattara / pro-coup narrative","flow":"Coordinated multi-platform campaigns fabricating a military takeover; analysts describe a broader push promoting coups across West Africa","tier":"alleged-credible","for":"Manufacture the appearance of AES-style rupture in the region's key French-aligned state [ATTRIBUTION UNRESOLVED]"},{"actor":"🏴 JNIM","side":"insurgents","flow":"Northern-border pressure from the Sahel; would exploit any political rupture","tier":"documented","for":"Coastal expansion toward Gulf of Guinea ports"}],"contested":{"summary":"The coup that keeps being announced and keeps not happening. The campaign is the event.","claims":[{"claim":"Coordinated posts claim a military coup has taken place; the army chief is assassinated; Ouattara is missing or dead.","who":"Whoever benefits from making AES-style rupture look inevitable in the region's key French-aligned economy. Attribution unresolved.","evid":"DISPROVEN. Ouattara chaired a routine cabinet meeting during the alleged coup. Doumbia was not assassinated. No credible Ivorian outlet — state or private — reported the violence. Most viral posts were in ENGLISH in a Francophone country: the audience was never Ivorian.","status":"DISPROVEN"},{"claim":"The government frames all opposition grievance as foreign-driven disinformation.","who":"Ouattara — conflating fabricated coups with legitimate protest delegitimizes both.","evid":"The disinformation is real AND the grievances are real: Thiam was struck from the ballot on a citizenship technicality, Gbagbo is barred, and the fourth term is widely resented. Both things are true at once.","status":"CONTESTED — don't let the fake coup bury the real crisis"}]},"history":{"roots":"Côte d'Ivoire was Françafrique's showcase — and the showcase's price is the present fragility. Houphouët-Boigny ran the model partnership: cocoa's world leadership, French capital and troops welcome, the CFA franc defended — he coined 'Françafrique' approvingly — and prosperity real enough to draw millions of workers from the Sahel. The model's flaw was baked in: growth built on migrant labor with citizenship left ambiguous. When cocoa prices fell and Houphouët died, his heirs weaponized the ambiguity as 'Ivoirité,' stripping northerners and migrants of belonging — Mike McGovern's work traces how an economic identity crisis was converted into an ethnic-legal one — and the 2002-2011 wars followed, ending with France's Licorne force deciding the endgame in Ouattara's favor. Recovery since has been real and narrow: strong growth, aging leadership, opposition exclusion, and the north — the war's old grievance map — now the jihadist probe line.","timeline":[{"date":"1960","e":"Independence; Houphouët-Boigny's 33-year Franco-Ivorian miracle."},{"date":"2002-11","e":"Civil wars over 'Ivoirité'; Ouattara wins with French backing."},{"date":"2020","e":"Ouattara's contested third term — protests and deaths."},{"date":"2025","e":"Fourth term amid opposition exclusion; fabricated-coup campaigns intensify."},{"date":"2026","e":"Growth continues; northern probes continue; the disinformation war is the active front."}],"actors":[{"name":"Alassane Ouattara","bio":"The octogenarian president-economist — stability's guarantor and its single point of failure; the succession is the real question."},{"name":"The disinformation networks","bio":"Russia/AES-aligned campaigns manufacturing coups in English for a Francophone country — the tell of an external audience."},{"name":"France","bio":"The patron whose base drew down but whose commercial and security web remains — the relationship the info-ops attack."},{"name":"Cocoa + the economy","bio":"The world's cocoa leader — the prosperity that is both the stability's source and the contrast the juntas' narrative must explain away."}],"bridge":"The disinformation campaigns manufacturing coups in Abidjan are aimed at exactly the showcase's cracks: a fourth-term president, excluded rivals, northern grievance, and the standing question of French tutelage — every fabricated story exploits a real seam. Côte d'Ivoire is the coast's ideological prize: if the AES model (rupture, Russia, sovereignty rhetoric) can be exported anywhere rich, it is here, which is why the info-ops run in English for external amplification while JNIM probes the parks. The succession, when it comes, is the hinge on which the Gulf of Guinea's alignment may turn.","sources":[{"work":"Making War in Côte d'Ivoire","author":"Mike McGovern","year":"2011","note":"How 'Ivoirité' converted economic crisis into identity war — the standard scholarly account."},{"work":"Houphouët-Boigny et la crise ivoirienne","author":"Frédéric Grah Mel (Ivorian biographer)","year":"2003-2010","note":"The Ivorian-authored assessment of the model partnership and its unraveling."},{"work":"The CFA Franc Zone: Common Currency, Uncommon Challenges","author":"Ali Zafar / and Ndongo Samba Sylla & Fanny Pigeaud, 'Africa's Last Colonial Currency'","year":"2021","note":"The monetary architecture at the center of the sovereignty contest — Sylla's is the leading African critique."},{"work":"Ivorian government disinformation attributions","author":"CNSP/ANSSI-CI statements & DFRLab analyses","year":"2025-26","note":"Primary attribution record of the fabricated-coup campaigns."}]}},{"id":"nigeria","cat":"military","region":"West / Central Africa","subregion":"Central Africa","name":"Nigeria — ISWAP + Ansaru + Bandits + IPOB","sub":"JNIM first Nigeria attacks · Ansaru re-emergence · Lakurawa","domain":"Multi-Threat Insurgency","sev":"high","status":"escalating","since":"2009","esc":70,"lat":11.5,"lon":9.5,"trend":"up","w14":false,"esc_history":[67,68,68,68,68,68,68,68,68,70],"cas":"Tumfa airstrike: Amnesty alleges 100+ civilians; Niger/Kwara fatalities doubled","disp":"2.2M+ Lake Chad Basin","flag":"🇳🇬","note":"US MILITARY INTERVENTION + 'CHRISTIAN GENOCIDE' FRAMING (major, was untracked) · Trump designated Nigeria a 'Country of Particular Concern' (Oct 31 2025) over alleged persecution of Christians · CHRISTMAS DAY 2025: US airstrikes on ISWAP/ISIS in Sokoto (Trump-ordered, Nigeria-coordinated) · MAY 16 2026: joint US-Nigeria operation launched — SEAL raids + airstrikes killed an ISIS leader (al-Minuki) + ~175 militants by mid-May; further strikes in Metele/Arege (Borno) Jun 2026 · Trump: further strikes 'if they continue to kill Christians'; claims US action 'largely ended the slaughter' · CONTESTED FRAMING: Nigeria's govt (FM Tuggar), Crisis Group + ACLED reject the 'Christian genocide' label — ACLED found religiously-targeted killings = ~5% of civilian-targeting events; they call it largely resource/criminal/banditry violence miscast as religious war · analysts (Bangura) argue the real US aim is leverage over Nigerian critical-minerals access · IPOB (Biafra separatists) said they'd 'fully support' a Trump intervention — a sovereignty/secession wrinkle · UPDATED · JNIM claimed its FIRST Nigeria attacks (killed soldiers, Kwara/Niger border) · Ansaru re-emergence (AQIM/JNIM-allied), shifted to Kwara/Niger States · Lakurawa (ISGS-linked) in Kebbi/Sokoto, cooperating w/ Boko Haram Sadiku faction · ISWAP officer-killings (5 in 5 months) · banditry = most armed violence in NW","leverage":[{"actor":"ISWAP / IS","asset":"Drones; officer-targeting; Niger-Nigeria bridge linking ISSP+ISWAP","str":"hi"},{"actor":"JNIM + Ansaru","asset":"First Nigeria attacks; Kwara/Niger forest bases near Benin border","str":"md"},{"actor":"Bandits (NW)","asset":"Most armed violence in NW; kidnap-for-ransom economy","str":"md"},{"actor":"Nigerian state","asset":"Dangote refinery, CBN FX reform, state-policing framework","str":"md"}],"gov":[{"src":"Nigerian Armed Forces","detail":"Multi-front operations; to embed journalists to improve security reporting; requested French support"},{"src":"US/France","detail":"ISR + Lakurawa precision airstrikes; deepening security footprint"},{"src":"CBN / NUPRC","detail":"FX reform + petroleum licensing — economic stability layer"}],"mil":"Nigeria's threat picture widened materially: JNIM claimed its first-ever attacks in Nigeria (killing soldiers in the Kwara/Niger border forests), while Ansaru — the AQIM/JNIM-allied group that split from Boko Haram in 2012 — re-emerged, shifting operations from Kaduna to Kwara and Niger States near the Benin border. ISGS-linked 'Lakurawa' cells in Kebbi/Sokoto cooperate with Boko Haram's Sadiku faction. Niger and Kwara State fatalities doubled. ISWAP killed five high-level officers in five months.","pol":"The structural risk is convergence: IS is attempting to bridge ISSP (Sahel) and ISWAP (Lake Chad) across the Niger-Nigeria border, which would connect two of Africa's most powerful jihadi networks. Organized criminal 'bandits' remain the largest source of armed violence in the northwest. The decentralized state-policing plan advances; Nigeria deepened US/French security ties.","eco":"Dangote refinery, CBN FX reforms, and NUPRC licensing (from the uploaded stability layer) are the resilience variables; easing oil prices relieve fuel-cost pressure.","assess":"Nigeria rises to 68. It is the hinge where the Sahel and Lake Chad theaters are fusing: JNIM's first Nigeria strikes, Ansaru's revival, and the Lakurawa-Boko Haram cooperation all point to a merging jihadi geography across the Niger-Nigeria border. The four-front problem (ISWAP, Sahel-linked groups, bandits, IPOB/ESN) makes Nigeria the most multi-dimensional theater in West Africa.","econlev":[{"holder":"United States","channel":"Portfolio securities","exp":"MED","detail":"$8.0B US securities (2025 TIC; 3→8 over decade); mostly long-term debt, equity <$0.5B"}],"external":[{"actor":"🇺🇸 US (intervention)","side":"counter-ISIS / pressure","flow":"Designated Nigeria a CPC (Oct 2025); Christmas-2025 Sokoto airstrikes; joint May-2026 operation (SEAL raids + airstrikes, killed ISIS leader al-Minuki + ~175); threatens more strikes over 'Christian genocide' — a framing Abuja + ACLED + Crisis Group dispute","tier":"documented","for":"Counter-ISIS optics + leverage over Nigerian critical minerals; the genocide narrative is the lever, resource access the suspected aim"},{"actor":"🇹🇷 Turkey","side":"state","flow":"TB2s, Songar tactical drones, ANKA-S co-production talks; tied to Dec strike that killed 85+ civilians","tier":"documented","for":"Arms market; training ties since 2018"},{"actor":"🇦🇪 UAE","side":"state","flow":"Armoured vehicles used vs Boko Haram","tier":"documented","for":"Counter-terror partnership"},{"actor":"🇨🇳 China","side":"state","flow":"72 drones (Wing Loong, CH-series); no human-rights conditionality","tier":"documented","for":"Arms market; strategic access"},{"actor":"🇮🇷 Iran","side":"soft-power","flow":"Al-Mustafa University network + cultural centres (Abuja) — ideological screening/recruitment nodes","tier":"alleged-credible","for":"Influence; intelligence deniability"}],"ext_flag":true,"tclass":"conflict","tier":"ELEVATED","hist_real":true,"as_of":"15 Jul 2026","tracked_since":"Wk4 (2026)","domain_tag":"Military","contested":{"summary":"The killings are real. Whether they are a 'Christian genocide' — and who benefits from saying so — is the contest.","claims":[{"claim":"Nigeria is committing (or tolerating) a 'Christian genocide' — the basis for US strikes and CPC designation.","who":"The Trump administration + US conservative circles — the framing justifies intervention and pressure on Abuja; Nigeria's govt denies it entirely.","evid":"ACLED (2020-22) found religiously-targeted killing of Christians = ~5% of civilian-targeting events; Crisis Group + Nigeria's FM call the violence largely resource/criminal/banditry-driven, hitting Muslims and Christians alike. Intersociety's much higher Christian-death figures are assessed by the BBC as unverified. Real mass killing is documented; the 'genocide' characterization is disputed.","status":"CONTESTED — killings documented, genocide framing disputed"},{"claim":"The US intervention is a humanitarian action to protect Christians.","who":"Trump — 'we largely ended the slaughter'; critics see a resource-leverage play.","evid":"Analysts (Yusuf Bangura et al.) argue the aim is to pressure Nigeria into opening critical-minerals supply chains to US firms. Both framings coexist; only the humanitarian one is offered publicly.","status":"CONTESTED — humanitarian frame vs resource-leverage aim"}]},"pipeline":[{"mineral":"Crude Oil","stage":"mine","actor":"Niger Delta — Bonny Light, Forcados, Escravos","detail":"Africa's largest oil producer, but output fell from ~2.1M bpd (2018) to ~1.3M bpd — bled by pipeline vandalism and industrial-scale THEFT (NNPC once said it was losing 'nearly all' output at the Bonny hub). Bonny Light (light, sweet, low-sulfur) traded above $110 during the Iran war. Shell/Exxon are back with deepwater (Bonga North).","who":"NNPC + IOCs; theft/vandalism siphon a chronic share before crude reaches port","tier":"documented"},{"mineral":"Crude Oil","stage":"process","actor":"Dangote Refinery, Lekki (650k→1.4M bpd)","detail":"THE INVERSION: the $20B Dangote refinery — the world's largest single-train — turned Nigeria from a fuel IMPORTER into a net EXPORTER. Petrol imports fell from 42M litres/day (Dec 2025) to 3M (Feb 2026). But the paradox: NNPC can't supply enough crude (committed to loan-service deals), so Dangote IMPORTS crude from the US, Libya, UAE — and just switched to DOLLAR pricing because naira-for-crude failed.","who":"Dangote (private) captures the refining margin the state's 3 idle refineries never could","tier":"documented"},{"mineral":"Refined fuel","stage":"mid","actor":"Jet fuel/diesel → Europe (ARA hub) + West Africa","detail":"Dangote is now displacing Gulf and US barrels in Europe — ~half of June loadings were jet fuel, ~96k bpd to the Netherlands/Amsterdam-Rotterdam-Antwerp hub. Diesel goes regionally to 11 refinery-less West African states. It may end the $17B/yr Europe→Africa gasoline trade.","who":"Reverses the old flow — Africa now refines and ships to Europe, not the other way","tier":"documented"},{"mineral":"Refined fuel","stage":"end","actor":"West African pumps · European jet fuel · a $40B IPO","detail":"The end state is energy sovereignty as an asset: Dangote is prepping a ~$4B IPO at a ~$40B valuation (potentially Africa's largest listing) with dollar-linked dividends. The extraction lens inverted — value captured at home, sold abroad, floated on the exchange.","tier":"documented"}],"patterns":["resource-nationalism"],"history":{"roots":"Nigeria is an amalgamation that was never asked. Britain fused the Sokoto Caliphate's north, the Yoruba west, the Igbo east, and hundreds of other polities into one colony in 1914 for administrative economy — Lugard's indirect rule governing each through different structures, hardening difference into political architecture (Mamdani's citizen/subject again). Decolonization handed that architecture three regions engineered for rivalry; the first decade delivered coups, pogroms, and Biafra — a million-plus dead, mostly Igbo children starved under blockade, a war Achebe's memoir insists Nigeria never honestly reckoned with. Oil then remade the federation into a rentier state: the Niger Delta's crude funds the center while the Delta itself got Ken Saro-Wiwa's hanging (1995) for demanding its share — the extraction-without-development pattern in domestic form. The north's poverty belt, the Middle Belt's land conflicts, and the Delta's militancy are all children of the same design: a state built to extract and allocate, not to develop.","timeline":[{"date":"1960","e":"Independence from Britain."},{"date":"1967-70","e":"Biafra civil war (~1M+ dead) — the secession wound that still echoes."},{"date":"2009","e":"Boko Haram launches its insurgency in the northeast."},{"date":"2014","e":"Chibok schoolgirls kidnapped; global outrage."},{"date":"2016","e":"Boko Haram splinters; ISWAP emerges as the stronger faction."},{"date":"2020s","e":"Northwest 'bandit' mass-kidnappings; Middle Belt farmer-herder killings escalate."},{"date":"2024-25","e":"Lakurawa (Sahel-linked) appears in the far northwest."},{"date":"Oct 2025","e":"US designates Nigeria a 'Country of Particular Concern' over Christian killings."},{"date":"May 2026","e":"Joint US-Nigeria military operation against ISIS; 'genocide' framing disputed by ACLED/Crisis Group."}],"actors":[{"name":"ISWAP","bio":"Islamic State's West Africa Province; the strongest jihadist faction in the northeast, running a proto-state around Lake Chad."},{"name":"Boko Haram (JAS)","bio":"The original insurgency; diminished but still active in Borno."},{"name":"Bola Tinubu (govt)","bio":"Nigeria's president since 2023; managing overlapping insurgencies, economic strain, and now US pressure."},{"name":"United States","bio":"Newly intervening militarily under a contested 'Christian genocide' framing; suspected of a critical-minerals leverage motive."},{"name":"IPOB","bio":"Biafran separatists in the southeast who said they'd welcome a US intervention — a sovereignty wrinkle."}],"bridge":"Each of today's four insurgencies maps to a seam of the 1914 design: Boko Haram/ISWAP in the impoverished former-Caliphate north; banditry and Lakurawa in the northwest the state never reached; IPOB separatism in the east Biafra's unreckoned wound keeps open; Delta theft in the extraction zone itself. The US intervention adds the newest layer — a 'Christian genocide' framing that ACLED's own data contradicts, doing narrative work for a critical-minerals agenda — while the Dangote refinery represents the counter-story: the first time in the oil era that the refining margin stays in Africa. Nigeria's question since 1914 has never changed: can a state built as an extraction manifold be rebuilt as a country?","sources":[{"work":"There Was a Country: A Personal History of Biafra","author":"Chinua Achebe","year":"2012","note":"The primary literary-historical testimony of Biafra and the unfinished reckoning."},{"work":"A History of Nigeria","author":"Toyin Falola & Matthew Heaton","year":"2008","note":"The standard survey — amalgamation, indirect rule, oil-state formation — led by the dean of Nigerian historians."},{"work":"Genocide in Nigeria: The Ogoni Tragedy","author":"Ken Saro-Wiwa","year":"1992","note":"Primary text of the Delta's case against extraction-without-development, by its executed author."},{"work":"Citizen and Subject","author":"Mahmood Mamdani","year":"1996","note":"Indirect rule's machinery — how Lugard's Nigeria became the template of bifurcated rule."},{"work":"ACLED Nigeria religious-targeting analysis","author":"ACLED","year":"2020-26","note":"The event data (religious targeting ≈5% of civilian-targeting incidents) contradicting the 'Christian genocide' framing."}]},"human":{"dead":40000,"disp":3400000,"famine":false,"aid":"partial NE","note":"Boko Haram-era cumulative ~40k+ dead, 3.4M displaced across the four insurgencies; the US strikes add a new casualty stream."}},{"id":"drc","cat":"military","region":"West / Central Africa","subregion":"Central Africa","name":"DRC — M23/Rwanda + ADF + Cobalt + Ebola","sub":"Uvira: M23 \"withdrew\" but plainclothes militants occupy · Rubaya mine fight","domain":"Proxy War / Resource War","sev":"critical","status":"escalating","since":"2022","esc":82,"lat":-1.5,"lon":29.2,"trend":"ss","w14":false,"esc_history":[81,82,82,82,82,82,82,82,82,82],"cas":"10,000+ since 2022; ADF killed 149 civ in Ituri last month (ACLED)","disp":"6M+ IDPs","flag":"🇨🇩","note":"JUL 15 — EBOLA OUTPACING CONTAINMENT: WHO reports 80% of NEW Ebola cases in eastern DRC now emerge from UNKNOWN transmission chains — the outbreak is spreading faster than it can be tracked, and the ADF-violence/epidemic convergence in Ituri (already flagged) is the mechanism: the war zone is the blind spot · C64 opposition coalition POSTPONED nationwide protests after Burundian President Ndayishimiye's mediation — the political fuse burns slower, for now · PIPELINE + RWANDA EXPANDED (Wk16) · The extraction chain is now traced mine→end-buyer for all 4 minerals — see the ⛓ Pipeline board · RWANDA is the load-bearing external actor: 7,000–12,000 RDF troops fight with M23 (RDF sanctioned by OFAC Mar 2026); Rubaya coltan (~15% of world tantalum) is smuggled via Goma–Gisenyi, relabelled 'Rwandan' with ITSCI tags applied AFTER the border, and laundered into Apple/Microsoft/Sony/Nvidia/Toyota supply chains (Global Witness, 10 Jun 2026, 2,000+ tonnes traced); M23 earns ~$800k/mo at $4/kg · GOLD laundered via Gasabo Gold refinery (OFAC/EU sanctioned) → Dubai, mirroring the RSF/UAE circuit · COBALT: China owns 15/19 mines, CMOC sets the price → Kinshasa's Feb-2025 ban → Oct-2025 quota (96,600t/yr) → US Washington Accords counter (Virtus $700M, first US operator back in a decade) · 200+ killed in a Mar-2026 Rubaya shaft collapse · UPDATED · ADF killed 149 civilians in Ituri last month (=Jan-Apr total combined, ACLED) · Ebola now in 4th province (Bundibugyo strain, WHO) · ADF shifting north from N.Kivu into Ituri = both violence hotspot + Ebola-response center · M23 took Uvira; FARDC killed M23 spokesman Ngoma in record drone campaign · DRC + M23 pledged comprehensive peace agreement by MID-AUGUST; both sides reinforcing South Kivu — possible imminent battle for Uvira · Uvira status murky: M23 claimed retreat under US pressure but plainclothes militants still occupy + clash with Wazalendo · FARDC record air/drone campaign (killed spokesman Ngoma) around Rubaya coltan mine · Rwanda-Burundi powder keg (Uvira 26km from Bujumbura); comprehensive peace deal still pledged mid-Aug","leverage":[{"actor":"Rwanda (Kagame / RDF)","asset":"7,000–12,000 troops embedded with M23 + control of the Goma–Gisenyi smuggling corridor — turns eastern DRC's minerals into 'Rwandan' exports. The war IS the business model.","str":"hi"},{"actor":"M23","asset":"Physical control of Rubaya (~15% of world tantalum) + a parallel tax state ($4/kg coltan, ~$800k/mo). Whoever holds the mine holds the war chest.","str":"hi"},{"actor":"China (CMOC)","asset":"Owns 15/19 cobalt mines and sets the global cobalt price — the incumbent Kinshasa is trying to dilute without losing the investment","str":"hi"},{"actor":"United States (Accords)","asset":"Offtake + DFC finance + serial OFAC sanctions on the smuggling network — financial firepower deployed instead of industrial presence","str":"md"},{"actor":"The traceability gap (ITSCI/RMAP)","asset":"The geographic bypass — tagging ore AFTER the border launders conflict minerals into 'compliant' supply chains. Paperwork is the laundering tool, not the safeguard.","str":"md"},{"actor":"ADF (IS-affiliate)","asset":"Ituri massacres (149 killed last month) disrupting the Ebola response — a second, jihadist war layered on the mineral one","str":"md"}],"gov":[{"src":"WHO","detail":"Confirmed Ebola (Bundibugyo virus) spread to 4th province; Ituri insecurity limiting containment"},{"src":"DRC Government / FARDC","detail":"Record drone/air campaign; killed M23 spokesman Willy Ngoma"},{"src":"G7 / Élysée","detail":"Critical Minerals Alliance targeting cobalt/rare-earth concentration"}],"mil":"ACLED recorded at least 149 civilian fatalities in Ituri province last month alone — equaling the total ADF-related civilian deaths there for January-April combined. As the ADF (an IS affiliate) shifts northward from North Kivu, Ituri has become both a hotspot of Islamist violence and the center of the region's Ebola response — the insecurity directly limits humanitarian access. Separately, M23 seized Uvira and FARDC killed M23 spokesman Willy Ngoma in a record drone campaign.","pol":"The dual-track war (Rwanda-backed M23 in the east + ADF/IS in Ituri) continues under G7 mineral-de-risking pressure and Qatari/US mediation. The public-health emergency is widening fast.","eco":"The WHO confirmed Ebola (Bundibugyo strain) has reached a fourth province — the entire northeast is now affected — with ADF violence in Irumu/Mambasa territories blocking containment. The cobalt chemical chain (Kolwezi) recovered as Hormuz normalized.","assess":"DRC rises to 82. The compounding factor is the ADF-Ebola convergence in Ituri: the same territory is the Islamist-violence hotspot and the epidemic epicenter, and the violence is actively preventing the epidemic response — a lethal feedback loop. Rwanda's M23 proxy (now holding Uvira) remains the 'hi' geopolitical lever; the ADF is the humanitarian accelerant.","diplomacy_active":true,"diplomacy":[{"name":"DRC-M23 comprehensive peace agreement","desc":"Both sides pledged to sign by mid-August (Qatar/US-mediated) while reinforcing South Kivu positions — sign-or-fight dynamic around Uvira","status":"active","next":"MID-AUGUST deadline"}],"econlev":[{"holder":"Rwanda","channel":"Smuggled-mineral re-export","exp":"HIGH","detail":"Coltan exports up 2.5x (2021-25); gold now the #1 export earner — a national revenue stream built substantially on ore that never legally left the DRC. This is why OFAC sanctioned the RDF itself, not just the middlemen."},{"holder":"China (CMOC)","channel":"Cobalt price-setting","exp":"HIGH","detail":"By owning most mines and overproducing, CMOC sets the world cobalt price from Kolwezi — the leverage that forced Kinshasa into an export ban then a quota to defend its own revenue"},{"holder":"DRC (Kinshasa)","channel":"Export quota + E-Trace","exp":"MED","detail":"The 96,600t/yr cobalt cap and the mine-to-export tracking platform are Kinshasa asserting price power and ESG credibility to court Western capital — Africa's boldest mineral-sovereignty play in decades"},{"holder":"US / UAE","channel":"Offtake + gold refining","exp":"MED","detail":"Washington redirects copper/cobalt via offtake deals; Abu Dhabi locks in gold via a ~$2B supply deal — two Western-aligned channels prising open a Chinese-dominated market"}],"external":[{"actor":"🇷🇼 Rwanda (RDF + M23)","side":"M23 proxy / occupier","flow":"7,000–12,000 RDF troops fight alongside M23; RDF sanctioned by OFAC (Mar 2026). M23 seized Goma, Bukavu, the Rubaya mines and pushed on Uvira. Kagame calls the mineral theft 'an imaginary problem.'","tier":"documented","for":"Coltan, gold, tin & tungsten smuggled across the border and relabelled 'Rwandan' — mineral revenue that made Rwanda's coltan exports rise 2.5x (2021-25) and gold its #1 earner"},{"actor":"🇨🇳 China (CMOC / Zijin / Huayou)","side":"resource incumbent","flow":"Owns 15 of 19 cobalt mines and most big copper assets; CMOC sets the global cobalt price; Sicomines gave ~$93B of rights for ~$3B of infrastructure","tier":"documented","for":"~80% of DRC cobalt and most copper, routed to China for refining — processing dominance over the metals of the energy transition"},{"actor":"🇺🇸 US (Washington Accords)","side":"strategic challenger","flow":"Dec 4 2025 DRC-Rwanda accord + Regional Economic Integration Framework; Virtus Minerals ($700M) first US operator back in a decade; DFC financing + offtake; serial OFAC sanctions on the smuggling network (Mar/Apr/Jun 2026)","tier":"documented","for":"Privileged access to copper, cobalt, lithium, tantalum — redirecting Congolese minerals away from Chinese and informal channels without owning the mines"},{"actor":"🇦🇪 UAE","side":"gold offtaker","flow":"April 2026 ~$2B DRC gold-supply deal keeping the UAE the refining point; June 2026 flight-tracking caught UAE cargo flights Abu Dhabi→Kinshasa arming Tshisekedi (cross-link: UAE theater)","tier":"documented","for":"Congolese gold into an Emirati refining monopoly under a US economic umbrella"},{"actor":"🇧🇷🇪🇺 Traders (Traxys) / smelters","side":"laundering conduit","flow":"Traxys was near-exclusive buyer of African Panther's Rwandan coltan (denies Rubaya origin); 8 Asian smelters passed RMAP audits while ≥4 processed likely-Rubaya ore","tier":"alleged-credible","for":"Clean-looking tantalum for global electronics — the point where conflict ore becomes 'compliant' on paper"}],"ext_flag":true,"tclass":"conflict","tier":"SEVERE","hist_real":true,"as_of":"15 Jul 2026","tracked_since":"Wk4 (2026)","domain_tag":"Military","contested":{"summary":"Everyone knows where the coltan goes. The paperwork says otherwise.","claims":[{"claim":"Rwanda denies backing M23.","who":"Rwanda — and every downstream buyer who needs the minerals to be Rwandan-origin.","evid":"UN Group of Experts panels have documented Rwandan Defence Force troops, equipment, and command support repeatedly. Rwanda's coltan exports exceed what its own deposits can plausibly produce.","status":"DOCUMENTED-BUT-DENIED"},{"claim":"Minerals entering global supply chains are certified conflict-free.","who":"The electronics and EV industries; the certification schemes themselves.","evid":"Laundering through Rwanda is the documented mechanism by which conflict coltan becomes compliant coltan. The certification is downstream of the fraud.","status":"CONTESTED — the paperwork is the problem"}]},"pipeline":[{"mineral":"Coltan → Tantalum","stage":"mine","actor":"Rubaya mines, Masisi (North Kivu)","detail":"~15% of the world's tantalum; ~half of Congolese coltan. Artisanal miners dig in deadly conditions — a March 2026 shaft collapse killed 200+, including children. M23's parallel 'ministry' issues permits and doubles wages to keep output up.","who":"M23 controls the mines (seized Apr 2024) — the war's main revenue source","tier":"documented"},{"mineral":"Coltan → Tantalum","stage":"process","actor":"M23 taxation + cross-border smuggling to Rwanda","detail":"M23 levies $4/kg (above Rwanda's own $3/kg state tax) → ~$800k/month per UN experts. ~1,400t crossed in year one, in daylight through the Goma–Gisenyi crossing. In Kigali it's mixed with local ore and relabelled 'Rwandan' with ITSCI tags applied AFTER the border — the geographic bypass that defeats traceability.","who":"Rwanda Defence Force (OFAC-sanctioned Mar 2026); exporters African Panther, Sunrise, Boss Mining, Kanzamin, Philbert","tier":"documented"},{"mineral":"Coltan → Tantalum","stage":"mid","actor":"Smelters in China, Kazakhstan, Thailand","detail":"Trucked Kigali → Dar es Salaam / Mombasa → 8 smelters (incl. Kazakhstan's Ulba Metallurgical Plant). Global Witness links ≥4 to Rubaya ore. All 8 passed RMAP audits while sourcing it — once refined into metal, origin is undetectable without geochemical fingerprinting (which Rwanda refuses).","who":"Trader Traxys was African Panther's near-exclusive buyer (denies Rubaya origin)","tier":"alleged-credible"},{"mineral":"Coltan → Tantalum","stage":"end","actor":"Tantalum capacitors → global electronics & EVs","detail":"A phone holds ~40mg of tantalum. Global Witness names Apple, Microsoft, Sony, Amazon, Nvidia, Toyota, Honda, Vodafone, LG Display, Ericsson as brands whose chains 'may unwittingly carry' the conflict metal. DRC filed complaints against Apple subsidiaries in France & Belgium (2024). The lesson: 'paperwork is not provenance.'","who":"Consumer demand is, indirectly, an armed-group financing mechanism","tier":"documented"},{"mineral":"Cobalt","stage":"mine","actor":"Kolwezi belt — Tenke Fungurume, Kisanfu, Mutanda","detail":"DRC = ~76% of world cobalt. Mostly mined as a copper by-product. Artisanal sector ~2% of output but the human face of it. Kinshasa banned mixing artisanal ore with industrial output and launched E-Trace mine-to-export tracking.","who":"China owns 15 of DRC's 19 operating cobalt mines","tier":"documented"},{"mineral":"Cobalt","stage":"process","actor":"CMOC (China Molybdenum) — the price-setter","detail":"Bought Tenke Fungurume from Freeport (2016, $2.65B); now the world's #1 cobalt supplier. Its overproduction crashed prices ~60%, so Kinshasa imposed a Feb 2025 export BAN → Oct 2025 QUOTA (96,600t/yr for 2026-27, <half of 2024 output). CMOC opposed; Glencore accepted — the Western-vs-Chinese split over African sovereignty in one dispute.","who":"Sicomines 2007 deal: mining rights worth ~$93B for ~$3B of infrastructure","tier":"documented"},{"mineral":"Cobalt","stage":"mid","actor":"Refined in China → cathode / battery precursor","detail":"~80% of DRC cobalt is controlled by China and routed home for refining. THE US COUNTER (Washington Accords, Dec 4 2025): Virtus Minerals ($700M, via Chemaf's Étoile + Mutoshi) is the first US operator back in a decade; Gécamines to ship ~100,000t of Tenke copper to US buyers; DFC financing + offtake deals rather than owning mines.","who":"Contest: CMOC/Zijin/Huayou (China) vs Virtus/KoBold (US, backed by Gates & Bezos)","tier":"documented"},{"mineral":"Cobalt","stage":"end","actor":"EV batteries · phones · military jets · aerospace","detail":"On the US critical-minerals list. The whole quota-and-Accords fight is about who controls the metal at the end of this line — Beijing (via refining) or Washington (via offtake). The DRC's play is to make both bid.","tier":"documented"},{"mineral":"Gold","stage":"mine","actor":"Eastern DRC artisanal gold fields","detail":"High-value, low-volume, easy to smuggle — the ideal conflict mineral. Extracted in M23/RDF-controlled and contested zones.","who":"M23 + Rwanda Defence Force move it physically across the border","tier":"documented"},{"mineral":"Gold","stage":"process","actor":"Gasabo Gold refinery, Rwanda","detail":"OFAC (Jun 2026) + EU sanctioned: RDF/M23 hand gold directly to Gasabo, which refines it. ≥60kg (millions of $) moved from eastern DRC to Gasabo in early 2026. Chairman Jean Malic Kalima also controls Bugambira, Wolfram Mining, Rwinkwavu — a whole Rwandan mining network.","who":"Gold is now Rwanda's #1 export earner; coltan #2","tier":"documented"},{"mineral":"Gold","stage":"mid","actor":"Refined bars → Dubai / global bullion market","detail":"Rwandan-refined gold enters international bullion flows with its conflict origin obscured — the same Dubai-centric laundering circuit the UAE runs for Sudanese gold (cross-link: UAE 'quiet empire' theater).","tier":"alleged-credible"},{"mineral":"Gold","stage":"end","actor":"Jewellery · central-bank reserves · electronics","detail":"Once refined and sold, it is fungible and untraceable — which is exactly why gold, not coltan, is the preferred value-transfer metal for both the M23/Rwanda and RSF/UAE conflict economies.","tier":"documented"},{"mineral":"Copper","stage":"mine","actor":"Katanga Copperbelt — Kamoa-Kakula, Tenke, Manono-adjacent","detail":"DRC = world's #2 copper producer (~3.3M t in 2024). Mined alongside cobalt. KoBold (US, Gates/Bezos-backed) holds 3,000+ km² but WON'T advance disputed blocks; Zijin (China) builds on contested ground anyway — speed-to-market is China's edge.","who":"US firms stayed away for a decade over conflict/corruption; now returning under the Accords","tier":"documented"},{"mineral":"Copper","stage":"process","actor":"Cathode — refined largely in/for China","detail":"Chinese firms (CMOC, Zijin) control most large copper assets and have routed output to China for refining for over a decade. Gécamines' new marketing rights (2023 CMOC renegotiation) let it redirect ~100,000t of Tenke copper to US buyers — the first crack in that monopoly.","tier":"documented"},{"mineral":"Copper","stage":"end","actor":"Grid · electronics · EVs · construction · defense","detail":"On the US critical list. Trump's reassertion of the Monroe Doctrine in the National Security Strategy frames Congolese copper as a strategic-inventory question — the metal at the end of this line is now great-power infrastructure, not just plumbing.","tier":"documented"}],"patterns":["china-refine","dubai-gold","resource-nationalism"],"history":{"roots":"Congo's condition was engineered, and Congolese scholarship has named the engineers for fifty years. Georges Nzongola-Ntalaja's people's history runs the line straight: Leopold's Congo Free State (up to 10 million dead for rubber quotas — hands severed for shortfalls) → Belgian colonial rule that trained not one Congolese officer or administrator class → independence sabotaged in its first year, when Lumumba, the elected champion of a unitary sovereign Congo, was murdered in 1961 with Belgian operational involvement and CIA sanction (both since officially acknowledged) → Mobutu, the West's Cold War custodian, licensed to loot for three decades so long as the minerals flowed. The eastern wars since 1996 — 'Africa's World War,' millions dead, documented in the UN Mapping Report — continue the design with new subcontractors: Rwanda's proxies hold the mines, transnational firms buy the ore, and the traceability paperwork launders it. The DRC has never had a decade in which its resources were governed for its people; that is not a misfortune but a maintained arrangement.","timeline":[{"date":"1885-1908","e":"King Leopold II's Congo Free State: extraction by mass atrocity sets the template."},{"date":"1965-97","e":"Mobutu's kleptocracy hollows out the state."},{"date":"1994","e":"Rwandan genocide; Hutu genocidaires flee into eastern Zaire, forming the FDLR."},{"date":"1996-2003","e":"Two Congo Wars ('Africa's World War') kill millions; Rwanda and Uganda intervene for minerals."},{"date":"2012","e":"M23 rebellion (Rwanda-backed) briefly seizes Goma, then collapses."},{"date":"2021","e":"M23 re-emerges, better armed, with overt Rwandan support."},{"date":"Early 2025","e":"M23 seizes Goma and Bukavu, the two eastern provincial capitals."},{"date":"4 Dec 2025","e":"Washington Accords signed by DRC and Rwanda under US mediation."},{"date":"Dec 2025","e":"M23 takes Uvira days after the signing — the accord's hollowness exposed."},{"date":"Mar 2026","e":"US sanctions the Rwandan army (RDF) for backing M23; peace stalls."}],"actors":[{"name":"Félix Tshisekedi","bio":"DRC's president since 2019; has courted the US (Washington Accords, minerals-for-security) while accusing Rwanda of invasion. Manages a coup-risk-laden, militarily weak position."},{"name":"Paul Kagame (Rwanda)","bio":"Rwanda's president since 2000; runs a strategy of 'controlled instability' in eastern DRC — backing M23 to secure minerals and regional dominance while denying involvement."},{"name":"M23 / AFC (Corneille Nangaa)","bio":"The Rwanda-backed rebel movement holding Goma, Bukavu, Uvira and the Rubaya mines; runs a parallel tax state on coltan."},{"name":"FDLR","bio":"Hutu militia descended from the 1994 génocidaires; Rwanda's stated casus belli and a Congolese-government ally against M23."},{"name":"United States","bio":"Brokered the Washington Accords and is redirecting Congolese minerals via offtake deals to counter China's dominance — sanctions the RDF while courting Kinshasa."}],"bridge":"Every node on this platform's DRC pipeline is the Free State's architecture modernized: Rubaya's coltan diggers stand where the rubber gatherers stood; M23's $4/kg tax is the quota system privatized; Kigali plays the entrepôt Brussels played; and the smelter audits that 'certify' the ore perform the same legitimating function as Leopold's Philanthropic Association. The Washington Accords and the cobalt quota are Kinshasa's most serious attempt yet to break the buyer's market — resource sovereignty a century late — while the Ebola-ADF convergence in Ituri shows what a deliberately hollowed state costs in the present tense. Lumumba's question — who shall govern Congo's wealth — remains the war's only real subject.","sources":[{"work":"The Congo from Leopold to Kabila: A People's History","author":"Georges Nzongola-Ntalaja","year":"2002","note":"The Congolese-authored standard — Free State to the eastern wars as one continuous struggle over sovereignty."},{"work":"The Assassination of Lumumba","author":"Ludo De Witte","year":"1999","note":"The investigation that forced Belgium's 2002 parliamentary acknowledgment of responsibility."},{"work":"UN Mapping Report on the DRC (1993-2003)","author":"UN OHCHR","year":"2010","note":"Primary documentation of the eastern wars' atrocities, including Rwandan army crimes — the report power tried to bury."},{"work":"Congo's Violent Peace","author":"Kris Berwouts","year":"2017","note":"The post-2003 order — elections without sovereignty, the eastern war economy's persistence."},{"work":"Global Witness / UN Group of Experts reports on 3T minerals","author":"Global Witness; UN GoE","year":"2022-26","note":"Primary supply-chain tracing: Rubaya → Rwanda → smelters → global brands."}]},"human":{"dead":6000000,"disp":7000000,"famine":false,"aid":"blocked in Ituri (Ebola zone)","note":"~6M dead across the eastern wars since 1996 (IRC-lineage estimates); ~7M displaced now; Ebola response strangled by ADF violence."}},{"id":"haiti","cat":"military","region":"Caribbean","subregion":"Caribbean","name":"Haiti — Viv Ansanm / State Collapse","sub":"Gang Suppression Force deploying · Chad 1,500 lead · gangs still hold ~90% of capital","domain":"Criminal Insurgency / State Collapse","sev":"critical","status":"escalating","since":"2020","esc":94,"lat":18.5,"lon":-72.3,"trend":"up","w14":false,"diplomacy_active":true,"esc_history":[0,94,94,94,94,94,94,94,94,94],"cas":"~16,000 killed since 2022; 1,200+ killed in drone strikes (60 civilians); recent gang attacks 70+ dead","disp":"1.5M+ displaced; famine-level food insecurity","flag":"🇭🇹","note":"JUL UNSC CYCLE — THE NUMBERS BEHIND 94: BINUH Q1 report: 1,642 killed + 745 injured Jan-Mar, and 69% OF CASUALTIES OCCURRED DURING SECURITY-FORCE OPERATIONS — HNP + the Vectus Global-supported Special Security Task Force, incl. summary executions; the SG warns the HNP itself 'should be listed' next year if child violations repeat (620 children killed/maimed; Gran Grif, Kraze Barye, 400 Mawozo added to the child-violations annexes) · FIRST MAJOR CRACK IN VIV ANSANM: May 9-11 intra-alliance clashes over Plaine du Cul-de-Sac (400 Mawozo/Chyen Mechan/Taliban vs Pierre VI/Terre Noire) killed 78, displaced 5,300 — ACLED: fragile internal arrangements, but collapse unlikely as gangs conserve force ahead of GSF combat ops · GSF REALITY: <1,000 of 5,500 deployed (Chadian contingent present), combat operations only now beginning; Guterres toured PaP Jun 16 ('glimmers of hope') — 2,300 killed + 1.5M displaced THIS YEAR · SG report due Jul 14; 90-day UNSC briefing this month; UNODC to brief on arms-trafficking routes · UN-backed GANG SUPPRESSION FORCE (GSF) now deploying — replaces the Kenya-led MSS (on ground since Jun 2024, made little progress) · authorized by UNSC Res 2793 (Oct 2025, US+Panama-penned); 5,500-person ceiling, mostly UN-budget-funded, empowered to make ARRESTS + run intel-based ops (unlike the MSS which only supported HNP) · FIRST TROOPS: Chadian advance team arrived Apr 1 2026 (Vertières base) · UNSC vote 12-0 with China, Russia, Pakistan ABSTAINING (Russia's Nebenzia: mandate 'rushed,' lets force act vs 'anyone labelled gangs') · full 5,500 expected on ground 'between fall and end of 2026' · ~16,000 killed since 2022; 1.5M+ displaced; gangs (~26 groups) hold ~90% of Port-au-Prince · new govt installed Feb 7 2026 (PM Alix Didier Fils-Aimé); gangs scaled back attacks in the lull, likely reassessing · concerns: a UN report alleged Kenyan MSS members committed sexual violence incl. rape of minors; Haiti's history of harmful intervention (MINUSTAH cholera killed ~10,000)","leverage":[{"actor":"Armed gangs (~26 groups)","asset":"Control ~90% of Port-au-Prince; territorial + extortion economy; can wait out foreign forces","str":"hi"},{"actor":"Gang Suppression Force","asset":"5,500 mandate + arrest/intel powers + UN-budget funding — the tool the MSS never had","str":"md"},{"actor":"United States","asset":"Force architect + financier ($300M+); shapes the mission while keeping an African-led face","str":"hi"},{"actor":"Chad","asset":"Lead troop contributor — converts the deployment into US diplomatic goodwill","str":"md"}],"gov":[{"src":"UNSC Resolution 2793 (Oct 2025)","detail":"Transformed the Kenya-led MSS into the Gang Suppression Force; 5,500 ceiling, arrest powers, intel-led ops; adopted 12-0-3 (China/Russia/Pakistan abstained)"},{"src":"GSF command (Christofides / Batsuuri)","detail":"SA's Jack Christofides as Special Representative; Mongolia's Maj. Gen. Batsuuri as Force Commander; troop pledges exceeded the 5,500 ceiling"},{"src":"UN / OHCHR","detail":"~16,000 killed since 2022; 1.5M+ displaced; a UN report alleged sexual violence by Kenyan MSS members"}],"mil":"Haiti is effectively a state-collapse theater. The gang federation Viv Ansanm — a US-designated Foreign Terrorist Organization led by Jimmy 'Barbecue' Chérizier — controls an estimated 70-90% of Port-au-Prince and the strategic corridors into the Artibonite and Centre departments. The country has had no president since Moïse's 2021 assassination. The UN-authorized Gang Suppression Force (Chad, Kenya contingents) has begun combat operations but with fewer than 1,000 of a planned 5,550 troops, and is badly underfunded. Even the Defense Ministry's cabinet director was kidnapped.","pol":"UN figures: 2,300 killed and 1.5 million displaced in 2026 alone — more than 1 in 10 Haitians homeless. Guterres visited in June, citing 'glimmers of hope' against a harder reality. Crisis Group calls Viv Ansanm 'the most severe threat Haiti has faced in decades' and documents its ideological pivot — Chérizier reframing the gangs as anti-elite, anti-colonial 'revolutionaries,' even announcing a political party, while seeking a general amnesty as the transitional government winds down.","eco":"Extortion, kidnapping-for-ransom, and drug/arms trafficking are the core revenue; gang blockades of roads, the airport, and the seaport have isolated the country and choked humanitarian aid. In Artibonite, gangs burn crops and hound farmers.","assess":"Haiti holds critical (94) but the variable has shifted from pure collapse to a contested intervention. The UN-backed Gang Suppression Force — authorized by Resolution 2793 and replacing the ineffective Kenya-led MSS — is now deploying, with Chad the lead contributor (1,500 troops, first to arrive April 1) alongside pledges from Benin (up to 2,000), Bangladesh (1,500), and Mongolia (which supplies the force commander). Unlike its predecessor, the GSF can make arrests and run intelligence-led operations, and it is funded from the UN budget rather than voluntary contributions. Two things temper the hope: the force won't reach its 5,500 strength until late 2026, and the intervention is contested — China, Russia, and Pakistan abstained, warning the mandate is dangerously vague, against the backdrop of Haiti's scarring history of foreign missions (the MINUSTAH cholera outbreak, alleged MSS sexual violence). The Chad deployment also links to the Sudan theater: Chadian civil society questioned sending troops abroad while facing Sudan-war spillover on its own eastern border. Whether the GSF breaks the gangs' ~90% grip on the capital or becomes 'another false dawn' is the central question.","tclass":"conflict","tier":"CRITICAL","hist_real":true,"as_of":"15 Jul 2026","tracked_since":"Wk4 (2026)","domain_tag":"Military","external":[{"actor":"🇹🇩 Chad","side":"GSF lead contributor","flow":"1,500 troops (2 battalions) — first to deploy (Apr 1); combat-experienced, French-speaking; at Vertières base","tier":"documented","for":"Reboot US military cooperation after the 2024 rupture (AFRICOM visits) — even as Chad takes ~$2B in UAE loans and hosts the UAE→RSF arms pipeline feeding the Sudan war on its other border"},{"actor":"🇧🇩 Bangladesh","side":"GSF contributor","flow":"1,500 police officers pledged","tier":"documented","for":"UN peacekeeping standing; longstanding blue-helmet contributor role"},{"actor":"🇧🇯 Benin","side":"GSF contributor","flow":"Pledged up to 2,000 soldiers (largest single pledge)","tier":"documented","for":"Regional/African security leadership; US alignment"},{"actor":"🇲🇳 Mongolia","side":"GSF command","flow":"Provides Force Commander Maj. Gen. Erdenebat Batsuuri (ex-UN Cyprus) + 100 personnel","tier":"documented","for":"UN peacekeeping profile"},{"actor":"🇺🇸 US","side":"lead backer","flow":"Co-penned Res 2793; ~$300M+ pledged; logistics/finance/medical support — but African-led by design to avoid direct US footprint","tier":"documented","for":"Stabilize the hemisphere without US boots; Donroe-era regional order"},{"actor":"🇨🇳🇷🇺 China/Russia","side":"skeptics","flow":"Abstained on Res 2793; Russia calls mandate 'rushed,' warns of force abuses","tier":"documented","for":"Resist US-led hemispheric intervention precedent"}],"ext_flag":true,"econlev":[{"holder":"Gangs (~26 groups)","channel":"Territorial extortion","exp":"HIGH","detail":"Control ~90% of Port-au-Prince — taxing ports, roads, fuel, and commerce; the extortion economy IS the war economy"},{"holder":"United States","channel":"GSF funding + design","exp":"HIGH","detail":"$300M+ and the architecture of the force — shaping the intervention while keeping an African-led face"}],"contested":{"summary":"An African-led force, American-designed. Ask who wrote the mandate.","claims":[{"claim":"The Gang Suppression Force is an African-led intervention.","who":"The US — which architected and financed it ($300M+) while keeping its own boots off the ground.","evid":"True on its face — Chad leads with 1,500 troops, Benin pledged 2,000, Bangladesh 1,500, Mongolia commands. Also true: the US co-penned Resolution 2793 and pays for it. 'African-led' describes the personnel, not the authorship.","status":"CONTESTED — both framings are accurate; only one is offered"},{"claim":"China, Russia, and Pakistan abstained, calling the mandate 'rushed' and dangerously vague.","who":"Those states — resisting the precedent of US-designed hemispheric intervention.","evid":"The objection is self-interested AND substantive: the mandate authorizes force against 'anyone labelled with the vague term gangs.' Haiti's history (MINUSTAH cholera, ~10,000 dead; alleged MSS sexual violence) gives it weight.","status":"UNRESOLVED"}]},"history":{"roots":"Haiti's collapse is the endpoint of two centuries of extraction and instability. The world's first Black republic (1804) was forced to pay France a crippling 'independence debt' that beggared it for generations. US occupation, the Duvalier dictatorships, coups, and disasters followed. The 2021 assassination of President Moïse removed the last elected authority; since then gangs — armed and financed partly by political and business elites — have overrun Port-au-Prince, controlling ~85% of the capital. A Kenya-led international force has failed to reverse it. The roots: a state deliberately kept weak, elites who use gangs as tools, and an international community that intervenes episodically without fixing the underlying void.","timeline":[{"date":"1804","e":"Haiti wins independence — the first Black republic — after a slave revolution."},{"date":"1825","e":"France extorts a massive 'independence debt,' crippling Haiti's economy for over a century."},{"date":"1915-34","e":"US military occupation."},{"date":"1957-86","e":"Duvalier ('Papa/Baby Doc') dictatorships."},{"date":"2010","e":"Catastrophic earthquake kills ~250,000."},{"date":"7 Jul 2021","e":"President Jovenel Moïse assassinated; the last elected authority gone."},{"date":"2024","e":"Gangs overrun Port-au-Prince; a Kenya-led MSS force deploys."},{"date":"2025-26","e":"Gangs control ~85% of the capital; the transitional council flounders."}],"actors":[{"name":"Viv Ansanm gang coalition","bio":"The alliance of gangs (led by figures like Jimmy 'Barbecue' Chérizier) controlling most of Port-au-Prince."},{"name":"Transitional Presidential Council","bio":"The unelected body meant to steer Haiti to elections; weak and internally divided."},{"name":"Kenya-led MSS","bio":"The UN-backed multinational security mission; under-resourced and unable to dislodge the gangs."},{"name":"Elites","bio":"Political and business figures who have historically armed and financed gangs as instruments of control."}],"bridge":"Haiti's present is the bill for being first: James showed the revolution that abolished slavery by arms; Trouillot showed how the world silenced it; the 1825 indemnity — independence ransomed at gunpoint, paid to the enslavers' heirs into the 20th century — is the quantified theft (the NYT reconstruction: billions in today's terms) beneath the 'poorest nation' framing. The gang order is not the absence of that history but its product: a state kept deliberately weak by ransom, occupation, and patronage now rented out to armed brokers, while the GSF reruns the century-old pattern of external forces substituting for the sovereignty the ransom foreclosed. The BINUH finding that 69% of casualties occur in security-force operations closes the circle: the cure and the disease share a payroll.","sources":[{"work":"The Black Jacobins: Toussaint L'Ouverture and the San Domingo Revolution","author":"C.L.R. James","year":"1938","note":"The foundational history of the revolution that made Haiti first — and made it unforgivable."},{"work":"Silencing the Past: Power and the Production of History","author":"Michel-Rolph Trouillot","year":"1995","note":"The Haitian anthropologist on how the revolution was made unthinkable — the erasure this platform writes against."},{"work":"The Ransom (1825 indemnity reconstruction)","author":"New York Times investigative series","year":"2022","note":"The quantified primary accounting of the independence debt's extraction."},{"work":"BINUH quarterly reports","author":"UN Integrated Office in Haiti","year":"2024-26","note":"Primary casualty and rights documentation, including the security-force findings."}]},"human":{"dead":15000,"disp":1500000,"famine":true,"aid":"gang-taxed","note":"~5.6k killed 2024 + 2.3k this year (BINUH); 1.5M displaced; catastrophic hunger levels in gang-held zones; 69% of casualties in security-force ops."}},{"id":"jamaica","cat":"military","region":"Caribbean","subregion":"Caribbean","name":"Jamaica — Security Turnaround (Counter-Case)","sub":"31-year murder low · SoE model · fragile gains","domain":"Organized Crime / State Response","sev":"medium","status":"declining","since":"ongoing","esc":42,"lat":18.1,"lon":-77.3,"trend":"dn","w14":false,"esc_history":[0,42,42,42,42,42,42,42,42,42],"cas":"~673 murders 2025 (31-yr low, -43%); 33 in Jan 2026 (record-low month)","disp":"N/A","flag":"🇯🇲","note":"NEW · COUNTER-CASE (de-escalating) · 31-year murder low: ~673 in 2025 (-43%), 33 in Jan 2026 = lowest month since records began 2001 · built on 20+ States of Emergency since 2018 · ACLED warns SoEs don't durably suppress gangs + carry police-brutality costs · still among highest per-capita murder rates in hemisphere","leverage":[{"actor":"Jamaican state (Holness)","asset":"Plan Secure Jamaica; SoE powers; JDF-JCF joint ops; institutional reform","str":"hi"},{"actor":"Gangs","asset":"Persistent but suppressed; extortion; deportee-linked networks","str":"md"},{"actor":"SoE mechanism","asset":"Temporary violence reduction — but ACLED: no durable gang suppression","str":"md"}],"gov":[{"src":"Jamaica OPM / JCF","detail":"PM Holness: 33 murders Jan 2026 = lowest month since 2001; Plan Secure Jamaica framework"},{"src":"STATIN / JIS","detail":"~673 murders 2025 = 31-year low, -43%; -32% shootings; official national statistics"},{"src":"US State Dept OSAC","detail":"JCF reported 666 murders Jan-Dec 27 2025 (-41.7%); still among highest per-capita in hemisphere"}],"mil":"Jamaica is deliberately included as the region's counter-case: not everything escalates. The Jamaica Constabulary Force and STATIN report a 31-year low of ~673 murders in 2025 (down 43%), and the Office of the Prime Minister confirmed 33 murders in January 2026 — the lowest monthly figure since national crime-data collection began in 2001. Shootings fell 32%, rape 28%.","pol":"PM Holness credits 'Plan Secure Jamaica,' a whole-of-government framework of enforcement, prevention, and institutional reform sustained since 2016. But the gains rest heavily on repeated States of Emergency — 20+ since 2018 — and ACLED's cross-Caribbean analysis warns SoEs produce temporary reductions without durably suppressing gangs, while carrying rising police-brutality and human-rights costs.","eco":"Improved security underpins tourism, investment, and growth — Holness frames it as central to development. The US State Dept notes non-violent crime (robbery, break-ins) actually rose even as violent crime fell.","assess":"Jamaica enters at 42, trend down — the platform's clearest de-escalation and a methodological anchor: it proves the framework tracks improvement, not just crisis. The turnaround is real and government-data-verified, but fragile — built on emergency powers ACLED judges non-durable, and still leaving Jamaica among the hemisphere's highest per-capita murder rates. The counter-case to Haiti's collapse next door.","tclass":"watch","tier":"GUARDED","hist_real":true,"as_of":"13 Jul 2026","tracked_since":"Wk4 (2026)","domain_tag":"Military","econlev":[{"holder":"Jamaica","channel":"Counter-case","exp":"LOW","detail":"Tracked as the region's positive counter-example: homicides down sharply — proof that Caribbean state collapse is not inevitable"}],"contested":{"summary":"No significant narrative-war dimension identified in this theater at present. The main claims are broadly consistent with the evidence, or the disputes are policy disagreements rather than contested facts. This is stated affirmatively rather than left blank — the absence of an information operation is itself a finding.","claims":[]},"external":[{"actor":"🇺🇸 US","side":"security partner","flow":"Anti-trafficking cooperation, deportation flows, and Caribbean Basin security assistance","tier":"documented","for":"Drug-transit interdiction and a stable Caribbean partner"},{"actor":"🇨🇳 China","side":"infrastructure creditor","flow":"Road, port and infrastructure loans; Belt-and-Road-adjacent financing","tier":"documented","for":"A Caribbean logistics foothold and diplomatic alignment"}],"ext_flag":true,"history":{"roots":"Jamaica's security story is the long tail of Cold War-era garrison politics. In the 1970s-80s, the two parties armed Kingston's neighborhoods; the guns stayed when the ideology left, evolving into posses and dons whose transnational networks run drugs and guns between Kingston, Miami, and London. The state's answer — repeated states of emergency, the 2010 Tivoli incursion (~70+ dead) — brought episodic calm without dismantling the structure. Homicide rates remain among the world's highest per capita, driven by US-sourced firearms. The 2024-26 period brought real declines under sustained SOEs and international gun-interdiction — progress that is genuine and reversible.","timeline":[{"date":"1962","e":"Independence from Britain."},{"date":"1970s-80s","e":"Garrison politics — the parties arm the neighborhoods."},{"date":"2010","e":"Tivoli Gardens incursion to extradite Dudus Coke — ~70+ dead."},{"date":"2018-","e":"Rolling states of emergency become standing policy."},{"date":"2024-26","e":"Homicides decline markedly; US gun-pipeline interdiction; the durability question."}],"actors":[{"name":"The gangs / posses","bio":"The garrison inheritance — transnational, gun-fed, politically descended and now politically orphaned."},{"name":"The state (Holness)","bio":"SOEs as governance — effective suppression, contested rights record, unresolved roots."},{"name":"The US gun pipeline","bio":"The supply side — most murder weapons trace to US purchases; interdiction is the real security policy."},{"name":"The diaspora economy","bio":"Remittances and deportee flows — the transnational circuit the violence rides."}],"bridge":"Gray's 'demeaned but empowered' captures the garrison inheritance exactly: the parties armed the poor to fight their elections, and the poor kept the arms when the parties no longer needed the fighting — the dons becoming what Thomas calls the state's exceptional violence privatized. The Tivoli Commission's own findings (the 2010 incursion's civilian toll, unaccounted) are the primary record that the cure shares the disease's methods. The current homicide decline is real; whether it is dismantlement or another suppression cycle is the question the SOE model has never yet answered — and the US gun pipeline it cannot answer alone.","sources":[{"work":"Demeaned but Empowered: The Social Power of the Urban Poor in Jamaica","author":"Obika Gray","year":"2004","note":"The Jamaican political scientist on garrison politics from below."},{"work":"Exceptional Violence: Embodied Citizenship in Transnational Jamaica","author":"Deborah A. Thomas","year":"2011","note":"The scholarly frame for state violence and the dons' order."},{"work":"West Kingston Commission of Enquiry report","author":"Government of Jamaica COE","year":"2016","note":"The primary official record of the 2010 Tivoli incursion."}]}},{"id":"south-africa","cat":"political","region":"Southern Africa","subregion":"Southern Africa","name":"South Africa — Xenophobic Mobilization","sub":"Jun 30 deadline passed without mass eruption · mobilization persists","domain":"Xenophobic Unrest / Political Violence","sev":"high","status":"volatile","since":"2008","esc":58,"lat":-26.2,"lon":28,"trend":"dn","w14":false,"esc_history":[0,61,59,59,58,58,58,58,58,58],"cas":"5 Ethiopians killed (3 in a McDonald's); 4+ dead recent unrest; 62 killed in 2008","disp":"Thousands displaced; camps in Durban/Cape Town","flag":"🇿🇦","note":"Government declared Jun 30 \"a normal working day\" — no national shutdown materialized · rhetoric moderated after govt warnings (Kubayi) · toll to date: 3 foreign nationals killed, journalists assaulted, thousands repatriated · SAPS ~R600M deployment + Fidelity private-security backup · fact-checkers flagged AI-GENERATED fake government notices endorsing the deadline · Wits (Landau): blame what govt has/hasn't done \"since 2008\"","leverage":[{"actor":"March&March / Operation Dudula","asset":"Street mobilization; 'arrests'/paper-checks; June 30 ultimatum; online amplification","str":"md"},{"actor":"MK Party (Zuma) / ActionSA","asset":"Legitimizing anti-migrant agenda; KZN electoral mobilization ahead of 2026 locals","str":"md"},{"actor":"GNU state (Ramaphosa)","asset":"SAPS deployment; but Union Buildings meeting legitimized the groups (Wits critique)","str":"md"},{"actor":"Sending states (Nigeria etc.)","asset":"Evacuations; diplomatic/continental backlash on trade/tourism","str":"md"}],"gov":[{"src":"SAPS / acting Police Min Cachalia","detail":"Police leave cancelled, resources deployed ahead of June 30; officers deployed to affected areas"},{"src":"President Ramaphosa / Justice Min Kubayi","detail":"June 30 'a normal working day'; violence 'not justified'; National Action Plan on Racism/Xenophobia"},{"src":"Union Buildings meeting (25 May)","detail":"Ministers met March&March leadership — Wits: this legitimized the groups"},{"src":"SA Government (official X)","detail":"'Tuesday 30 June 2026 remains a normal working day' — dismissed shutdown; flagged AI-generated fake notices with govt insignia"}],"mil":"South Africa faces its most serious xenophobic mobilization since 2008. Movements March and March and Operation Dudula have set a June 30 deadline (today) for undocumented migrants to leave, conducting unauthorized street 'arrests' and paper-checks. Five Ethiopians were killed (three shot inside a McDonald's), Malawians and Zimbabweans have fled to displacement camps, and Nigeria is evacuating 271+ citizens. SAPS cancelled police leave and deployed ahead of the deadline.","pol":"The analytical core, from Wits University's Xenowatch researchers, is that South African xenophobia is not a spontaneous grassroots eruption but a political enterprise co-produced by vigilante groups and the state — through acts of commission and omission. March and March has clear links to Zuma's MK Party (projected to surge in KZN), and the May 25 Union Buildings ministerial meeting with the group's leadership is criticized as lending it legitimacy. The National Action Plan on Racism 'contains almost no plan.'","eco":"Drivers are structural: 30%+ unemployment (60%+ youth), unresolved apartheid-era inequality. The continental backlash threatens tourism, trade, and investment in Africa's largest economy. Data shows migrants are not the source of crime or job loss the movements claim.","assess":"South Africa eases to 59 — the feared 2008-scale eruption did not materialize on the deadline, thanks to a R600M security deployment, cancelled police leave, and late rhetorical moderation by organizers. But the de-escalation is tactical, not structural: three people are dead, thousands repatriated, the movements retain their MK/ActionSA political cover, and the AI-generated fake-government-notice campaign shows an information-warfare layer now attached to the xenophobic mobilization. The 2026 local elections remain the driver.","econlev":[{"holder":"South Africa","channel":"PGMs + G20 standing","exp":"MED","detail":"Platinum-group metals + the continent's deepest capital markets; hosts the 2025-26 G20 presidency"}],"tclass":"watch","tier":"ELEVATED","hist_real":true,"as_of":"13 Jul 2026","tracked_since":"Wk4 (2026)","domain_tag":"Political","contested":{"summary":"No significant narrative-war dimension identified in this theater at present. The main claims are broadly consistent with the evidence, or the disputes are policy disagreements rather than contested facts. This is stated affirmatively rather than left blank — the absence of an information operation is itself a finding.","claims":[]},"external":[{"actor":"🇺🇸 US","side":"strained","flow":"AGOA-access tensions, friction over the ICJ Israel case and non-alignment; tariff and sanctions signaling","tier":"documented","for":"Leverage over a BRICS swing state and access to platinum-group metals"},{"actor":"🇨🇳 China / BRICS","side":"aligned","flow":"Largest trading partner; BRICS-plus anchor; infrastructure and mineral offtake","tier":"documented","for":"A G20 African anchor and PGM/manganese supply"},{"actor":"🇷🇺 Russia","side":"partner","flow":"Diplomatic alignment, naval exercises, and non-condemnation over Ukraine","tier":"alleged-credible","for":"A sympathetic voice in African and BRICS forums"}],"ext_flag":true,"pipeline":[{"mineral":"Platinum-group metals","stage":"mine","actor":"Bushveld Complex — Rustenburg, Mogalakwena","detail":"South Africa holds ~90% of world PGM reserves and produces most global platinum, palladium, rhodium (Anglo American Platinum/Valterra, Impala, Sibanye-Stillwater). PGMs are essential for catalytic converters, hydrogen fuel cells, and electronics — a genuine near-monopoly.","who":"SA majors mine it; deep, capital-intensive, labour-heavy operations","tier":"documented"},{"mineral":"PGMs","stage":"process","actor":"Smelted/refined largely in South Africa","detail":"Unlike the DRC (China-refined) or Indonesia (China-refined), SA retains much of its own PGM refining — the value-chain position the resource-nationalist states envy. This is the counter-example: an African producer that kept the midstream.","who":"SA refiners retain the processing margin — the model the DRC and Mali want","tier":"documented"},{"mineral":"PGMs","stage":"mid","actor":"Refined metal → global autocatalyst + H2 supply","detail":"Ships to the auto industry (catalytic converters), the hydrogen economy (fuel-cell/electrolyser catalysts), and electronics. As a BRICS swing state, SA sits between Western buyers and Chinese offtake — a leverage position over the energy transition's precious-metal inputs.","who":"Contest: Western autos + H2 vs Chinese offtake; SA plays both as a BRICS anchor","tier":"documented"},{"mineral":"PGMs","stage":"end","actor":"Catalytic converters · fuel cells · jewellery","detail":"The end products are the emissions and hydrogen technologies of the transition. SA's near-monopoly gives it real leverage — the platinum counterpart to Indonesia's nickel and the DRC's cobalt, but with the refining kept onshore.","tier":"documented"}],"history":{"roots":"South Africa's inequality is not apartheid's residue — it is apartheid's economy, politically renovated. Terreblanche's history runs the long arc: three centuries of land seizure (codified in the 1913 Natives Land Act reserving 93% of land for whites), the mining revolution built on the migrant-labor compound system that priced Black labor below subsistence, and grand apartheid as that labor system's constitutional form. Biko's insight — that the system's deepest work was psychological — and the liberation movement's answer (the Freedom Charter's 'the people shall share in the country's wealth') framed a struggle that won the state in 1994 but negotiated away the economy: the transition entrenched property, moved capital offshore, and swapped broad transformation for a narrow Black elite — the compromise Fanon's chapter on the national bourgeoisie had predicted for every decolonization. The world's highest Gini coefficient, 33% unemployment, and the failing grid are that bargain's balance sheet.","timeline":[{"date":"1948-94","e":"Apartheid — and the long liberation struggle."},{"date":"1994","e":"Mandela's election — the political miracle."},{"date":"2009-18","e":"Zuma era: state capture hollows the state."},{"date":"2024","e":"ANC loses its majority — the GNU coalition era begins."},{"date":"2023-26","e":"ICJ case against Israel; BRICS expansion host; US relations strained (AGOA, land-policy friction)."}],"actors":[{"name":"Cyril Ramaphosa / the GNU","bio":"The president managing a coalition of former enemies — reform promises against a patronage machine's inertia."},{"name":"The ANC","bio":"The liberation party at its weakest — still the system's center of gravity, no longer its owner."},{"name":"The US","bio":"The strained partner — AGOA access, the ICJ case, and non-alignment friction under a transactional Washington."},{"name":"BRICS / China","bio":"The chosen lane — largest trading partner and the multipolar identity Pretoria leads Africa's wing of."}],"bridge":"Every current South African fault line prices the unfinished economics: land reform stalled at a fraction of targets (the 1913 Act's map essentially intact), 'state capture' as the elite-enrichment bargain metastasized, xenophobic violence as the poor fighting the poorer for scraps, and the ANC's lost majority as the electorate's verdict on thirty years of political freedom without economic transformation. Abroad, the ICJ genocide case and BRICS anchoring are the liberation inheritance turned outward — the Freedom Charter's internationalism as foreign policy — which is precisely why Washington's pressure on Pretoria reads, from here, as the old demand that Africa's politics stay junior to its minerals. The PGM near-monopoly remains the quiet counter-leverage.","sources":[{"work":"A History of Inequality in South Africa, 1652–2002","author":"Sampie Terreblanche","year":"2002","note":"The long-arc economic history — land, labor compounds, and the negotiated transition's costs."},{"work":"I Write What I Like","author":"Steve Biko","year":"1978","note":"Primary texts of Black Consciousness — the psychological dimension of the system and its answer."},{"work":"The Freedom Charter","author":"Congress of the People, Kliptown","year":"1955","note":"The primary programmatic text — the economic clauses against which the transition is measured."},{"work":"The Wretched of the Earth (ch. 'The Pitfalls of National Consciousness')","author":"Frantz Fanon","year":"1961","note":"The predicted capture of liberation by a national bourgeoisie — the transition's sharpest mirror."},{"work":"Truth and Reconciliation Commission Report","author":"TRC","year":"1998-2003","note":"Primary record — including the institutional-hearings volumes on business and apartheid the settlement left unenforced."}]}},{"id":"iran-us","cat":"military","region":"Middle East","subregion":"Middle East","name":"US–Israel vs. Iran — Spike & Settle","sub":"IRAN DECLARES HORMUZ CLOSED · firing on ships · US hits 140 targets (3rd round) · Jordan base struck","domain":"Interstate War → Managed Standoff","sev":"critical","status":"active","since":"Feb 28 2026","esc":96,"lat":32,"lon":51,"trend":"up","w14":false,"disputed":true,"exchange_active":true,"diplomacy_active":true,"esc_history":[79,79,79,78,82,88,92,89,94,96],"cas":"13 US service members killed to date; 1 Iranian navy Lt killed at Jask; thousands of Iranian/Lebanese civilians killed; 1 Indian seafarer missing","disp":"Shipping caution; demining disputed","flag":"🌐","note":"JUL 17 — SIXTH CONSECUTIVE NIGHT: US completed its latest strike wave 9:40 PM ET — bombing now reaching DEEP inside Iran, beyond the southern coast (Chabahar port hit, smoke column verified) · Iran calls Hormuz an 'UNBREAKABLE RED LINE'; foreign ministry: no plans for negotiations · Gulf splash zone widens: Qatar intercepted a missile over Doha tonight, Jordan's Prince Hassan Air Base struck, UAE/Bahrain under drone-missile threats, EASA warns airlines off parts of Gulf airspace · BLOCKADE METRICS: first blockade (Apr 13–Jun 18) intercepted 140+ vessels and cost Iran ~$4.8B in oil revenue by May 1 (DoD); the reinstated blockade redirected 2 vessels in its first 17 hours and disabled a tanker running for Kharg Island · counter-signals: Iran RELEASED an American detainee (Dec 2024 case) as a 'goodwill gesture'; Vance publicly ruled OUT ground troops/regime change ('we're not in that business anymore') — coercion capped below invasion · JUL 16 — AROUND-THE-CLOCK PHASE: US military now striking Iran continuously, 'stepping up the pace' — framed as protecting Hormuz shipping after Iranian attacks on vessels · IRGC threatens to choke off ALL the region's oil and gas — escalation from Hormuz-only to a total regional energy threat · Iran firing missiles at neighboring US bases · Iran ramping up EXECUTIONS of political prisoners amid the war (CNN/human-rights data) — the domestic terror dimension rising with the external one · JUL 15 — TOLL DEAD, BLOCKADE BACK, STRIKES RESUMED: Trump DROPPED the 20% Hormuz transit-fee plan after Gulf 'kings and emirs' offered to 'invest billions in the US' instead — the toll monetization replaced by Gulf capital commitments ('I don't think anybody should be able to charge a fee for the strait') · US REIMPOSED its naval blockade on Iran and ran a FOURTH round of overnight strikes into Jul 15 — an army barracks hit, ≥7 troops killed, ~260 wounded across the country (Iranian figures) · 'We Kill Trump' billboard with Trump-in-coffin imagery up in Tehran's Islamic Revolution Sq — regime signaling, not fringe · JUL 13: Hormuz closure holding; the Houthi declaration of a simultaneous Bab el-Mandeb closure extends Iran's chokepoint leverage to a second waterway without Tehran firing another shot · Oman strait-management proposal remains the one live diplomatic track · HIGHEST ESCALATION YET (Jul 11-12): IRGC DECLARED THE STRAIT OF HORMUZ CLOSED — fired warning shots + struck at least 2 vessels ('violating regulations'); a container ship was damaged and abandoned, 1 Indian national missing · US/CENTCOM/JMIC insist the strait is OPEN (southern Oman-coast route) — but traffic has reduced to A TRICKLE · US 3rd round of strikes this week: 140 targets (missile/drone sites, naval capabilities, ammo storage, comms networks, coastal surveillance) using ships, fighters, drones; also struck railways moving military supplies · Iran killed 1 navy Lt at Jask port · IRGC struck Prince Hassan Air Base (JORDAN) with ballistic missiles + a US base in Qatar; UAE+Qatar intercepted missiles; Qatar told vessels to SUSPEND ALL SAILING · new Supreme Leader Mojtaba Khamenei: 'we pledge to avenge the blood of the martyred leader' · Ghalibaf: 'the era of one-sided deals is OVER'; adviser: Hormuz 'more important than dozens of atomic bombs' · Iran privately told US advisers the ship attacks were a 'mistake' by an 'errant sect of hardliners' + want to keep talking (US Amb. Waltz publicly doubts it) · OMAN drafted a tentative strait-management proposal; talks in Oman Sat · MoU (to ~Aug 18) in tatters; US revoked oil waiver · 13 US service members dead in the war to date; >$100B spent (Sanders)","leverage":[{"actor":"Iran (IRGC)","asset":"Hormuz control + horizontal reach (Gulf capitals) + sole-demining claim","str":"hi"},{"actor":"United States","asset":"Strike power + $300B gatekeeping + sanctions relief","str":"hi"},{"actor":"Israel","asset":"Spoiler veto; Katz prepping independent strike","str":"md"},{"actor":"Qatar/GCC","asset":"$6B custodian; Doha venue; toll rejection","str":"md"}],"gov":[{"src":"US CENTCOM","detail":"Confirmed 10-target strike; 'powerful response'"},{"src":"Bahrain/Kuwait govts","detail":"Condemned Iranian strikes as 'dangerous escalation'"},{"src":"Iran parliament (Azizi)","detail":"Strait 'governed by Iran'; strike was 'ceasefire management'"},{"src":"Iran state TV (Qalibaf)","detail":"'Sovereignty of the Strait of Hormuz lies with Iran and Oman' — joint-administration + passage-fee claim after 60-day MOU"},{"src":"Qatar MOFA","detail":"'Positive progress' on Islamabad MOU issues; next meeting after Khamenei funeral ends July 9; emergency communication channel agreed"}],"mil":"The strike exchange ran its full arc in 96 hours: after the US June 26 strikes, Iran drone-struck a second tanker (M/T Kiku) June 27; CENTCOM hit 10 Iranian military targets; on June 28 Iran struck US sites in Bahrain and Kuwait — horizontal escalation — before both sides stood down, with talks moving to Doha June 30.","pol":"Iran's parliamentary security chief Azizi declared the strait 'governed by Iran' and the tanker strike 'ceasefire management, not a breach.' Trump warned Iran 'will no longer exist' if strikes continue; both then stepped back. Iran received $6B via Qatar and rejected a France/Oman demining offer.","eco":"Oil stayed 'relatively contained' through the exchange thanks to reserve releases and oversupply; $6B unfrozen.","assess":"Iran-US surges to 94 (CRITICAL) — the highest reading in the theater's history and now the platform's joint-top alongside Sudan. Iran has crossed the decisive threshold: the IRGC formally declared the Strait of Hormuz CLOSED, fired on vessels attempting to transit, and struck a US base in Qatar and Jordan's Prince Hassan Air Base with ballistic missiles. The US answered with its third round of strikes in a week — 140 targets including missile sites, naval capabilities, and the railways moving Iranian military supplies — while insisting the strait remains open, though traffic has slowed to a trickle and Qatar has told vessels to suspend all sailing. New Supreme Leader Mojtaba Khamenei has pledged to 'avenge the blood of the martyred leader.' The one thread of hope: Iran privately told US advisers the ship attacks were a 'mistake' by an errant hardline faction and that it wants to keep talking, and Oman has drafted a proposal to manage strait traffic. But with Washington demanding a public admission it doubts will come, and Iran's negotiator declaring 'the era of one-sided deals is over,' this is the most dangerous moment of the war.","diplomacy":[{"name":"Oman strait-management proposal","desc":"Oman drafted a tentative proposal to manage Hormuz traffic; Araghchi-Omani talks focused on the strait — the one live diplomatic track","status":"active","next":"Oman talks"},{"name":"MoU (to ~Aug 18)","desc":"In tatters — Trump declared it 'over,' US revoked the oil waiver, Iran calls that a breach; Article 5 (reopen trade route) is the contested core","status":"collapsed","next":"US says no nuclear progress until the strait is secure"},{"name":"Back-channel (Vance/Kushner/Witkoff/Rubio)","desc":"Iran privately conceded the ship attacks were a 'mistake' by hardliners and wants to keep talking; US wants a public admission; Waltz publicly skeptical","status":"active","next":"US demands public acknowledgment"}],"econlev":[{"holder":"Iran","channel":"Hormuz transit control","exp":"HIGH","detail":"The IRGC's transit regime (authorization + 'maritime service fees') could be worth tens of $B/yr AND is a permanent strategic lever — Mojtaba Khamenei has enshrined it as doctrine; an adviser called it 'more important than dozens of atomic bombs'"},{"holder":"United States","channel":"Oil-export waiver + sanctions","exp":"HIGH","detail":"Revoked Iran's oil-export waiver (the core of the MoU) — cutting off Iran's main revenue; the US can also blockade Iranian ports"}],"tclass":"conflict","tier":"CRITICAL","hist_real":true,"as_of":"17 Jul 2026","tracked_since":"Wk4 (2026)","domain_tag":"Military","external":[{"actor":"🇮🇱 Israel","side":"US coalition","flow":"Co-belligerent from the Feb 2026 opening ('Operation Epic Fury'); strikes on Iran + the Lebanon front","tier":"documented","for":"Destroy Iranian nuclear/missile capability; degrade the Axis of Resistance"},{"actor":"🇷🇺 Russia","side":"Iran (limited)","flow":"Political cover, no direct intervention; the Iran-Russia drone/arms relationship predates the war","tier":"documented","for":"Keep the US pinned in the Middle East while it fights in Ukraine"},{"actor":"🇨🇳 China","side":"Iran (economic)","flow":"Principal buyer of Iranian oil; opposes the sanctions architecture; ~half its oil imports transit Hormuz","tier":"documented","for":"Energy security — China is the biggest loser from a closed Hormuz"},{"actor":"🇴🇲🇶🇦🇵🇰 Oman/Qatar/Pakistan","side":"mediators","flow":"Oman drafted the strait-management proposal; Qatar shuttles between the sides; Pakistan's Dar urging dialogue","tier":"documented","for":"De-escalation — all are directly exposed to Hormuz closure"},{"actor":"🇪🇺 European states","side":"restraint","flow":"Several European nations BARRED the US from using their bases/airspace for offensive operations; UK allowed only 'limited defensive' use","tier":"documented","for":"Avoid complicity in an escalation they oppose"}],"contested":{"summary":"Two governments give incompatible accounts of the same waterway. Both cannot be true, and the gap is where the war lives.","claims":[{"claim":"Iran says the Strait of Hormuz is CLOSED. The US says it is OPEN.","who":"Iran gains a permanent revenue stream and strategic lever if transit requires IRGC authorization. The US needs free passage to hold the position that its strikes are working.","evid":"Lloyd's List: no vessel over 10,000 dwt has transited the US-coordinated route with AIS on since Jul 7. Traffic is 'a trickle.' Qatar told owners to suspend all sailing. Iran has fired on and struck ships. Functionally, Iran's claim is closer to the observable truth than Washington's.","status":"CONTESTED — evidence favors Iran's account"},{"claim":"Iran privately told US advisers the ship attacks were a 'mistake' by an 'errant sect of hardliners.'","who":"Iran — if believed, it de-escalates without conceding the Hormuz doctrine. The US doubts it: Amb. Waltz said so publicly.","evid":"Reported via back-channel (Vance/Witkoff/Kushner). Unverifiable. It sits against Mojtaba Khamenei's public enshrinement of 'the lever of closing the Strait' as doctrine — which cuts the other way.","status":"UNRESOLVED"},{"claim":"The US frames its strikes as defensive; CENTCOM labeled the Jul 9 round 'offensive.'","who":"The US — 'self-defense' is legally and diplomatically cheaper than 'offensive war.'","evid":"CENTCOM's own language changed. 140 targets including railways moving military supplies, and a strike ~900 miles from Hormuz near Aqqala — well outside any strait-protection rationale.","status":"CONTESTED — the framing shifted with the facts"}]},"history":{"roots":"The US-Iran war did not begin in 1979 — it began in 1953, when the CIA and MI6 overthrew Mosaddegh's elected government for nationalizing Iranian oil, restored the Shah, and taught Iranian politics that constitutionalism gets couped and only hard power protects sovereignty. Abrahamian's histories trace the line directly: the Shah's SAVAK police state was the coup's maintenance system, the 1979 revolution its delayed answer, and the Islamic Republic's nuclear program and 'Axis of Resistance' the institutionalization of never-again. Every escalation since — the hostage crisis, the Iraq war years (when the West armed Saddam's invasion of Iran, chemical weapons included), sanctions, the JCPOA's collapse — reinforced the same lesson on both sides. The Feb 2026 assassination of Khamenei was 1953's method applied at the top of the state; Mojtaba's succession and the Hormuz war are the system answering as it was built to.","timeline":[{"date":"1979","e":"Islamic Revolution topples the Shah; US embassy hostage crisis begins the enmity."},{"date":"1980-88","e":"Iran-Iraq War; the Revolutionary Guard (IRGC) becomes the regime's core."},{"date":"2002","e":"Iran's covert enrichment program is exposed, beginning the nuclear standoff."},{"date":"2015","e":"JCPOA nuclear deal caps enrichment in exchange for sanctions relief."},{"date":"2018","e":"US withdraws from the JCPOA; 'maximum pressure' sanctions return."},{"date":"2020","e":"US kills IRGC Quds commander Qassem Soleimani."},{"date":"2024","e":"President Raisi dies in a helicopter crash, muddying the succession."},{"date":"28 Feb 2026","e":"Ali Khamenei assassinated in a joint US-Israeli strike; the war begins."},{"date":"8 Mar 2026","e":"Mojtaba Khamenei named Supreme Leader; hardline continuity."},{"date":"Apr 2026","e":"Fragile two-week ceasefire tied to reopening the Strait of Hormuz; repeatedly broken."},{"date":"Jul 2026","e":"Ceasefire shattered by fresh strikes; Oman floats a two-route Hormuz plan."}],"actors":[{"name":"Mojtaba Khamenei","bio":"Son of the assassinated Ali Khamenei, named Supreme Leader March 2026. A hardliner with deep IRGC ties, never elected — his selection signals continuity, not compromise."},{"name":"IRGC (Revolutionary Guard)","bio":"The regime's ideological military and the custodian of the nuclear and missile programs and the proxy network. More powerful than the regular army."},{"name":"United States","bio":"Co-belligerent with Israel; insists the Strait of Hormuz stay open and opposes Iranian tolls on shipping. Balancing decapitation strikes against a wider-war risk."},{"name":"Israel","bio":"Views an Iranian bomb as existential; has vowed to target any Iranian leadership. The prime mover of the strikes that began the war."},{"name":"Oman / Qatar","bio":"The regional mediators — Oman drafted the two-route Hormuz proposal; Gulf states fear the war swallowing their economies (F1 races cancelled, oil disrupted)."}],"bridge":"The current war runs on 1953's logic from both directions: Washington again betting that decapitation reorders Iran, Tehran again converting external assault into internal consolidation (the execution surge is the revolution's oldest reflex). The Hormuz closure is the oil nationalization fight returned as geography — Iran monetizing the strait as Mosaddegh tried to monetize the wells, and the abandoned US toll plan shows even Washington briefly adopting the logic. Nothing in this theater is aberrant; it is a 73-year feedback loop at maximum amplitude.","sources":[{"work":"A History of Modern Iran","author":"Ervand Abrahamian","year":"2008 (2nd ed. 2018)","note":"The standard structural history — 1953, the Shah's police state, the revolution's social base."},{"work":"The Coup: 1953, the CIA, and the Roots of Modern U.S.-Iranian Relations","author":"Ervand Abrahamian","year":"2013","note":"The oil-nationalization coup as the relationship's founding event — from declassified records."},{"work":"All the Shah's Men","author":"Stephen Kinzer","year":"2003","note":"The operational history of TPAJAX and its blowback thesis."},{"work":"Declassified CIA acknowledgment of the 1953 coup","author":"CIA (FOIA release)","year":"2013","note":"Primary admission — 'the military coup... was carried out under CIA direction.'"}]},"refs":[{"t":"CNN live: sixth night of strikes, Doha intercept","u":"https://www.cnn.com/2026/07/16/world/live-news/iran-war-trump"},{"t":"CBS live: blockade metrics, Chabahar strike","u":"https://www.cbsnews.com/live-updates/iran-us-war-trump-strait-of-hormuz-persian-gulf-strikes/"},{"t":"NPR: sixth day, Kharg tanker","u":"https://www.npr.org/2026/07/15/nx-s1-5894582/us-iran-updates"},{"t":"Fox live: detainee release, Vance no-ground-troops","u":"https://www.foxnews.com/live-news/iran-war-trump-israel-hormuz-oil-july-15-2026"}]},{"id":"lebanon","cat":"military","region":"Middle East","subregion":"Middle East","name":"Lebanon — Framework Signed (Contested)","sub":"Trilateral framework signed · Hezbollah 'null & void'","domain":"Framework → Disputed Implementation","sev":"high","status":"volatile","since":"Jun 22 2026","esc":75,"lat":33.3,"lon":35.4,"trend":"dn","w14":false,"diplomacy_active":true,"esc_history":[76,76,76,76,75,75,75,75,75,75],"cas":"IDF Cpt. Hazutt killed; hundreds since Apr 17","disp":"1M+ displaced (>20% of Lebanon)","flag":"🇱🇧","note":"JUL 14-15 — ROME TALKS: Israeli and Lebanese officials in a new round of US-mediated talks in Rome (two days), following the June preliminary agreement to end the fighting · Trump told Netanyahu directly to start REDEPLOYING out of Lebanon (and Syria) — patron pressure now points toward de-escalation on this front · Trilateral framework SIGNED Jun 26 — IDF withdraws from 2 pilot zones, LAF oversees disarmament · Hezbollah (Qassem): 'null & void' · Katz: not 'a millimeter' more · Haaretz: 'Gaza Strip 2' · permanent-deal odds 1.4% · Israeli drone strikes/artillery continued across the south (Nabatieh al-Fawqa, Bint Jbeil) despite framework; relief volunteers under fire · US told Iran at Doha it would \"restrain Israel\"; pilot-zone withdrawal framed as \"first step\" · Israeli strikes continued across south post-framework; permanent-deal odds remain low; US \"restrain Israel\" pledge untested","leverage":[{"actor":"Israel","asset":"Occupation of S.Lebanon zone; pilot-zone withdrawal as chip","str":"hi"},{"actor":"United States","asset":"Mediation; ties Lebanon to Iran track","str":"hi"},{"actor":"Hezbollah","asset":"Spoiler veto — rejected framework as 'null & void'","str":"md"},{"actor":"Lebanese Armed Forces","asset":"To receive pilot zones + oversee disarmament (untested)","str":"md"}],"gov":[{"src":"US State Dept (Rubio)","detail":"Announced framework as 'beginning of the beginning'"},{"src":"Israel (Katz)","detail":"'No territorial ambitions' but won't withdraw 'a millimeter' beyond pilot zones"},{"src":"Lebanese government","detail":"Signed; declared Hezbollah 'enemy of Lebanon'"}],"mil":"The trilateral framework was signed June 26 in Washington: IDF withdraws from two pilot zones, the LAF takes over and oversees Hezbollah disarmament. But violence continued — Hezbollah killed IDF Cpt. Hazutt, and a car-bomb attempt struck Holon inside Israel.","pol":"Katz won't withdraw 'a millimeter' beyond the pilot zones until Hezbollah disarms; Qassem calls the framework 'null and void,' a 'surrender.' Haaretz warns of a 'Gaza Strip 2'; permanent-deal odds fell to 1.4%.","eco":"Weak energy-market transmission; over 1M displaced (>20% of Lebanon).","assess":"Lebanon holds at 76 — it rose because the framework got signed, but of its three negotiation strands one is signed, one collapsed (disarmament), and one stalled. The signed paper may institutionalize an indefinite Israeli presence rather than resolve anything.","tclass":"conflict","tier":"SEVERE","hist_real":true,"as_of":"15 Jul 2026","tracked_since":"Wk4 (2026)","domain_tag":"Military","external":[{"actor":"🇮🇷 Iran","side":"Hezbollah","flow":"Historic funder/armer; supply lines degraded after Syria's fall + the 2026 war","tier":"documented","for":"Forward deterrence; the Axis of Resistance's last major arm"},{"actor":"🇮🇱 Israel","side":"belligerent","flow":"Continues strikes; demands Hezbollah disarmament as the framework's core","tier":"documented","for":"Eliminate the northern threat"},{"actor":"🇺🇸🇫🇷 US/France","side":"Lebanese state","flow":"Back the framework + the LAF as the sole armed authority; financial conditionality","tier":"documented","for":"Rebuild a state monopoly on force; break Iranian influence"}],"contested":{"summary":"The fight over who won, who must disarm, and whose money rebuilds — every number is a weapon.","claims":[{"claim":"Hezbollah won a 'divine victory' by surviving; disarmament is off the table and reconstruction is its to lead.","who":"Hezbollah — the survival-as-victory frame that preserves its armed status and social legitimacy.","evid":"Command decimated, arsenal degraded, Iranian resupply constricted, community surveys show declining confidence in its reconstruction capacity — but it retains weapons and the state cannot compel disarmament. Both 'defeated' and 'undefeated' are simultaneously arguable, which is the problem.","status":"CONTESTED — victory narrative vs degraded reality"},{"claim":"Gulf/IMF reconstruction conditionality is Western blackmail against the resistance.","who":"Hezbollah-aligned media — reframing donor conditions as aggression.","evid":"The ~$7B GCC pledges and IMF program are explicitly conditioned on disarmament and banking reform — that's documented leverage, not hidden. Calling it blackmail is the counter-frame that makes accepting it betrayal.","status":"DOCUMENTED conditionality, CONTESTED meaning"}]},"econlev":[{"holder":"Gulf states (Saudi + UAE)","channel":"Conditional reconstruction pledges","exp":"HIGH","detail":"~$7B in combined GCC pledges — Saudi ~$5B tied explicitly to Hezbollah disarmament, UAE ~$2B tied to banking reform. Both conditional, both unmet as of 2026. The money is the lever: it flows only if the state, not Hezbollah, controls the south."},{"holder":"IMF / World Bank","channel":"Program + bridge financing","exp":"HIGH","detail":"IMF disbursements blocked pending parliamentary action on the banking-restructuring, BdL-governance and depositor-protection laws. ~$14B war damage, $11B+ reconstruction need, Eurobonds at 6-10 cents on the dollar since the 2020 default — no restructuring without an IMF deal first."},{"holder":"Hezbollah / Iran","channel":"Parallel patronage (declining)","exp":"MED","detail":"Hezbollah historically funded post-war reconstruction directly (2006 model). Community surveys now show declining confidence in its ability to repeat that — the war weakened both the group and its Iranian financing, opening space for the state to reclaim legitimacy."},{"holder":"Diaspora remittances","channel":"Rentier lifeline","exp":"MED","detail":"Lebanon's independence-era model relies on diaspora remittances and Gulf inflows over domestic industry — a rentier structure that makes it acutely vulnerable to external shocks and to the political mood of Gulf donors."}],"history":{"roots":"Lebanon's fragility is built into its founding bargain. Independence (1943) came with a sectarian power-sharing system dividing power among Maronite Christians, Sunnis, and Shias — a formula that calcified into gridlock and warlord fiefdoms. A 15-year civil war (1975-90) devastated the country; Syria and Israel occupied parts of it. Out of the war and Israel's occupation of the south rose Hezbollah — a Shia militia-cum-party, armed by Iran, stronger than the national army. Its wars with Israel, the 2019 financial collapse (one of the worst in modern history), and the 2020 Beirut blast hollowed the state. The 2024 war badly weakened Hezbollah, opening a fraught chance to rebuild state authority. The roots: sectarian power-sharing, a state weaker than its militias, and a rentier economy dependent on outside money.","timeline":[{"date":"1943","e":"Independence with a sectarian power-sharing system."},{"date":"1975-90","e":"Civil war devastates Lebanon."},{"date":"1982","e":"Israel invades; Hezbollah forms in resistance, backed by Iran."},{"date":"2005","e":"PM Hariri assassinated; Syria forced to withdraw."},{"date":"2006","e":"Hezbollah-Israel war."},{"date":"2019","e":"Financial system collapses; savings wiped out."},{"date":"2020","e":"Beirut port explosion devastates the capital."},{"date":"2024","e":"Israel-Hezbollah war badly degrades Hezbollah."},{"date":"2025-26","e":"Reconstruction and disarmament tied to conditional Gulf/IMF money."}],"actors":[{"name":"Hezbollah","bio":"Iran-backed Shia party and militia, long stronger than the state; weakened by the 2024 war, resisting disarmament."},{"name":"Lebanese state","bio":"A weak, sectarian government trying to reclaim authority and unlock frozen Gulf/IMF reconstruction funds."},{"name":"Iran","bio":"Hezbollah's patron; its regional setbacks reduce the flow that once made Hezbollah dominant."},{"name":"Gulf states / IMF","bio":"Hold the reconstruction purse strings — conditioned explicitly on Hezbollah's disarmament and banking reform."}],"bridge":"The reconstruction-for-disarmament standoff is the founding bargain renegotiated at gunpoint: Traboulsi's history shows every Lebanese settlement (1943, Taif) has been a sectarian shareholders' agreement underwritten by outside money — and the ~$7B Gulf conditionality is simply the new term sheet, with Hezbollah's arsenal as the contested collateral. The Rome talks and Trump's redeploy push could close the southern front; nothing on the table yet touches the deeper structure — a state whose every rebuilding has been financed by patrons who thereby own a faction.","sources":[{"work":"A History of Modern Lebanon","author":"Fawwaz Traboulsi","year":"2007 (2nd ed. 2012)","note":"The Lebanese-authored standard — sectarianism as political economy, not ancient hatred."},{"work":"Hezbollah: The Global Footprint of Lebanon's Party of God","author":"Matthew Levitt / balanced against Amal Saad, 'Hizbullah: Politics and Religion'","year":"2013 / 2002","note":"Paired readings — the security-state view and the movement's own social logic."},{"work":"World Bank Lebanon Economic Monitors","author":"World Bank","year":"2019-26","note":"Primary record of the financial collapse — 'among the world's worst since the 1850s.'"}]},"human":{"dead":4000,"disp":1200000,"famine":false,"aid":"reconstruction-gated","note":"2024 war ~4k dead, 1.2M displaced at peak; return blocked by rubble and the disarmament standoff."}},{"id":"gaza","cat":"military","region":"Middle East","subregion":"Middle East","name":"Israel–Gaza War","sub":"Hamas DISSOLVED Gaza govt Jul 6 · phase two launched · toll 73,074","domain":"Counterinsurgency","sev":"critical","status":"stalemate","since":"Oct 7 2023","esc":77,"lat":31.35,"lon":34.3,"trend":"ss","w14":false,"diplomacy_active":true,"esc_history":[77,77,77,77,77,77,77,77,77,77],"cas":"73,074+ Palestinians killed (20,179 children); 1,072+ killed since ceasefire began","disp":"2.2M+ Gazans","flag":"🇵🇸","note":"JUL 15 — ISRAELI POLITICAL LAYER MOVES: Knesset PASSED the law weakening the attorney-general — the 'cornerstone of the judicial overhaul'; petitions to the High Court filed within hours (checks-and-balances crisis returns mid-ceasefire) · Trump reportedly being swayed by ARAB LEADERS that Netanyahu himself is the obstacle to regional peace (Times of Israel) — patron-client friction at the top · Eisenkot's new Yashar party now polls AHEAD of Likud in some surveys · strikes continue inside the truce (Deir al-Balah residential hit Jul 15, 'Hamas operative' targeted) · Shaky ceasefire (since Oct 10 2025) persists · JUL 6: HAMAS DISSOLVED its Gaza government to hand to Palestinian technocratic committee (NCAG) — symbolic pressure on Israel; made NO mention of disarmament · phase TWO launched (last hostage body returned; Board of Peace 'productive' Cyprus meetings) but NCAG stuck in Cairo, int'l stabilization force hasn't materialized · Israel seizing ~70% of Strip (Netanyahu May 28 order), won't withdraw past 'yellow line' · toll: 73,074+ killed (20,179 children) since Oct 2023; 1,072+ killed in 3,463 wounded since ceasefire (≈1 child/day) · Jun: UN commission found ongoing genocide (Israel: 'political blood libel') · reconstruction est. $70B · Jul 7-8: Hamas dissolution of its Gaza govt formalized, handing to NCAG (Ali Shaath) under the Board of Peace; Netanyahu: no reconstruction until Hamas disarmed + Gaza demilitarized (the unresolved crux)","leverage":[{"actor":"Israel","asset":"'Unlimited' Gaza security-zone control; Yellow Line enforcement","str":"hi"},{"actor":"Hamas","asset":"Refusal to disarm; rejected Mladenov plan; residual hostage/body leverage","str":"md"},{"actor":"Board of Peace / Gulf","asset":"$5B+ reconstruction capital (competing with Iran $300B)","str":"md"}],"gov":[{"src":"UNRWA","detail":"73,000+ Palestinian deaths (mid-2026)"},{"src":"Board of Peace (Mladenov)","detail":"Gaza demilitarization plan apparently rejected by Hamas"}],"mil":"Gaza continues to smolder under a shaky ceasefire. The Jerusalem Post notes Israel is 'running out of quality targets' — now hitting low-level operatives rather than senior figures. IDF strikes on Khan Younis tent camps killed two June 29.","pol":"The Board of Peace's demilitarization plan, presented by Nickolay Mladenov, was apparently rejected by Hamas. The Gulf-capital competition with Iran's $300B reconstruction persists.","eco":"Reconstruction pledged ($5B+) but not flowing; Gulf capital is being pulled toward Iran's larger $300B ask.","assess":"Gaza holds at 77. The July 6 move is significant diplomatically if not on the ground: Hamas dissolved its government to hand governance to the technocratic NCAG — but pointedly omitted disarmament, the phase-two crux — putting symbolic pressure back on Israel while changing nothing about who controls the streets. Phase two has 'launched' (last hostage body returned, Board of Peace meeting in Cyprus), yet the NCAG remains stuck in Cairo, the international stabilization force hasn't materialized, Israel is seizing ~70% of the Strip, and the toll keeps climbing (73,074+; roughly one child a day since the ceasefire). A June UN commission found ongoing genocide. The war's kinetic phase is largely spent; the political phase is deadlocked on disarmament.","diplomacy":[{"name":"Gaza peace plan phase two","desc":"Launched after last hostage body returned; full demilitarization + reconstruction + NCAG governance — but no timeline set, int'l force not deployed","status":"active","next":"NCAG handover conditions unset"},{"name":"Hamas government dissolution","desc":"Jul 6: Hamas dissolved its Gaza govt to hand to technocratic committee — but omitted disarmament (the phase-two crux); analysts call it a savvy pressure move on Israel","status":"active","next":"Israel response / NCAG entry"},{"name":"Hamas disarmament","desc":"Still refused; Israel says it will restart fighting to 'complete the mission' if Hamas won't disarm","status":"stalled","next":"the central deadlock"}],"tclass":"conflict","tier":"SEVERE","hist_real":true,"as_of":"15 Jul 2026","tracked_since":"Wk4 (2026)","domain_tag":"Military","external":[{"actor":"🇺🇸 US","side":"Israel / Board of Peace","flow":"Architect of the Board of Peace framework; funds and arms Israel; oversees the NCAG transition","tier":"documented","for":"Regional order; the Abraham-Accords normalization track"},{"actor":"🇶🇦🇪🇬🇹🇷 Qatar/Egypt/Turkey","side":"mediators / Hamas channel","flow":"Brokered the ceasefire and the Hamas dissolution; Egypt controls Rafah; Qatar hosts the political bureau","tier":"documented","for":"Regional standing; prevent a Gaza spillover"},{"actor":"🇮🇷 Iran","side":"Hamas/PIJ (degraded)","flow":"Historic patron of the Axis of Resistance; severely degraded after the 2026 war","tier":"documented","for":"Forward deterrence against Israel — now largely dismantled"}],"econlev":[{"holder":"Israel","channel":"Crossings + reconstruction","exp":"HIGH","detail":"Controls all cargo crossings; Netanyahu ties reconstruction to Hamas disarmament + demilitarization — aid as leverage over the political outcome"}],"contested":{"summary":"A ceasefire whose central term neither side agrees on.","claims":[{"claim":"Netanyahu ties reconstruction to Hamas disarmament and demilitarization.","who":"Israel — conditioning aid preserves leverage over the political outcome indefinitely.","evid":"Hamas's dissolution of its Gaza government is formalized (handed to the NCAG under the Board of Peace). Disarmament is not agreed. Reconstruction is therefore hostage to an unresolved condition.","status":"CONTESTED — the crux is deliberately unresolved"}]},"history":{"roots":"The Gaza war is the most violent chapter of a conflict as old as the state of Israel. Gaza — a tiny, densely populated strip — filled with Palestinian refugees expelled or fleeing during Israel's 1948 founding (the Nakba). Israel occupied it in 1967, withdrew settlers in 2005, and imposed a blockade after Hamas — an Islamist movement committed to armed resistance — won elections and seized the strip in 2007. Successive wars followed. Hamas's Oct 7 2023 attack, the deadliest day for Jews since the Holocaust, triggered an Israeli campaign of unprecedented destruction. The root is the unresolved question of Palestinian statehood and self-determination, and two peoples' claims to the same land.","timeline":[{"date":"1948","e":"Israel's founding; the Nakba displaces ~700,000 Palestinians, many into Gaza."},{"date":"1967","e":"Israel occupies Gaza in the Six-Day War."},{"date":"2005","e":"Israel withdraws settlers and soldiers from Gaza."},{"date":"2007","e":"Hamas seizes Gaza; Israel and Egypt impose a blockade."},{"date":"2008-21","e":"Repeated Israel-Hamas wars."},{"date":"7 Oct 2023","e":"Hamas attack kills ~1,200 in Israel; ~250 taken hostage."},{"date":"2023-24","e":"Israel's campaign devastates Gaza; tens of thousands killed."},{"date":"2025","e":"A fragile ceasefire and hostage-exchange framework is implemented."},{"date":"2026","e":"Truce holds unevenly; hundreds reported killed since signing; reconstruction and governance unresolved."}],"actors":[{"name":"Hamas","bio":"Islamist movement governing Gaza since 2007; launched the Oct 7 attack. Weakened militarily but not eliminated; the governance question after it is unresolved."},{"name":"Israel","bio":"Seeks the destruction of Hamas and return of hostages; faces international legal scrutiny (an ICJ case) over the campaign's conduct."},{"name":"United States","bio":"Israel's chief backer and the broker of the ceasefire framework and the 'Board of Peace' transition plan."},{"name":"Egypt / Qatar","bio":"Mediators and would-be trainers of a post-Hamas Gaza police force; Egypt controls the Rafah crossing."}],"bridge":"The current 'day after' fight is the hundred-year question in miniature: every proposed administrator of Gaza (the Board of Peace, Egyptian-trained police, a reformed PA) is an answer to who rules Palestinians other than Palestinians — the arrangement Khalidi's century of declarations, mandates, and accords has always produced. The Knesset's attorney-general law and the Netanyahu-as-obstacle briefings show the occupier's own institutions buckling under the war's weight; the ICJ case and the US anti-ICC campaign show the legal order itself becoming a front. The ceasefire holds bodies apart; nothing yet has touched the question.","sources":[{"work":"The Hundred Years' War on Palestine","author":"Rashid Khalidi","year":"2020","note":"The Palestinian-authored framework — a century of externally imposed settlements, 1917 to the present."},{"work":"The Question of Palestine","author":"Edward W. Said","year":"1979","note":"The foundational text on Palestine as seen versus Palestine as lived."},{"work":"The Ethnic Cleansing of Palestine","author":"Ilan Pappé","year":"2006","note":"The 1948 expulsions from the Israeli 'new historians' archive."},{"work":"UN OCHA / ICJ provisional-measures orders","author":"UN / ICJ","year":"2024-26","note":"Primary casualty documentation and the live legal record."}]},"human":{"dead":70000,"disp":1900000,"famine":true,"aid":"throttled at crossings","note":"Health-ministry-basis toll ~70k with excess-death studies higher; ~90% of population displaced at peak; famine-condition findings in the north."}},{"id":"ukraine","cat":"military","region":"Europe / Russia","subregion":"Europe","name":"Russia–Ukraine War","sub":"Russia back to NET GAINS (+31 sq mi June) · Pokrovsk mostly taken","domain":"Interstate War","sev":"critical","status":"escalating","since":"Feb 2022","esc":85,"lat":49,"lon":32,"trend":"up","w14":false,"exchange_active":true,"esc_history":[84,84,84,84,85,85,85,85,85,85],"cas":"~1.4M Russian casualties (Ukraine est.); 250-300k Ukrainian","disp":"~10M Ukrainians","flag":"🇺🇦","note":"JUL 16-17 — ZELENSKYY FIRES DEFENSE MINISTER FEDOROV: the popular minister removed mid-war — a wartime governance shakeup landing days after Graham's death and Starmer's resignation thinned the external support structure; succession at the ministry and the reason for the firing are the immediate watch-items · JUL 16 — THE SUPPORT STRUCTURE LOSES TWO PILLARS IN A DAY: Sen. Lindsey Graham DIED — Ukraine's most relentless champion in the US Senate, hours after visiting Kyiv · UK PM Keir Starmer RESIGNED — the Coalition of the Willing's co-anchor gone mid-war; successor's Ukraine posture unknown · both losses land as Russia answers the Patriot tech-share with strike waves · JUL 15 NIGHT — strike wave Odesa→Kharkiv: ~12 killed, 90 injured across Ukrainian cities (UPI) — Russia answering the Patriot tech-share announcement inside 48h · JUL 13 — PATRIOT TECH-SHARING: Trump announced at the NATO summit that the US will SHARE Patriot air-defense TECHNOLOGY with Ukraine (not just batteries) — a rare transfer of one of the most sought-after Western systems, upgrading Ukraine from recipient to co-producer of top-tier air defense · REVERSAL of the Dec25-May26 net-loss picture: DeepState OSINT — Russia made a NET GAIN of ~31 sq mi (June 2-30 2026), grinding at Pokrovsk (mostly Russian-controlled by Jan 2026), Siversk, Huliaipole, Kupiansk; took parts of Dnipropetrovsk + Sumy · BUT CSIS: still <1.5% of Ukraine taken since 2024, Pokrovsk pace ~70m/day (slower than the Somme); Russia ~1.2M casualties / up to 325k killed · Ukraine lost Kursk foothold in spring; on the defensive · Russian economy strained (deficit, expensive ruble, low oil) but hasn't buckled · Jul 7: active clashes Pokrovsk/Lyman/Kupiansk directions","leverage":[{"actor":"Ukraine","asset":"Deep-strike drones halting ~40% of Russian oil exports + Flamingo missiles","str":"hi"},{"actor":"Russia","asset":"Missile/drone barrage; but ground offensive largely halted","str":"md"},{"actor":"E3/EU/NATO","asset":"Weapons, financing, EU accession; NATO summit","str":"md"},{"actor":"US (Trump)","asset":"Signaled Russian-oil re-sanctioning; swing broker","str":"md"}],"gov":[{"src":"ISW / Critical Threats Project","detail":"Russia gained 40.64 sq km but lost 281.1 sq km Dec25-May26; 7.87% of 2025 pace"},{"src":"Ukraine General Staff","detail":"Record ~660-drone assault; Pokrovsk-direction advances"}],"mil":"ISW data resolves the prior disputed map: Russia gained 40.64 sq km but lost 281.1 sq km of controlled territory Dec 2025-May 2026 — a net loss — seizing only 7.87% as much as in 2025. The offensive is 'largely halted' and, ISW stresses, not for seasonal reasons. Ukraine is advancing at Pokrovsk.","pol":"Putin is resisting his own economic officials' warnings to cut defense spending, betting he can win before the economy breaks. The NATO summit is the next inflection.","eco":"Ukraine's deep-strike lever is decisive: ~40% of Russian oil export capacity halted, refining at a 16-year low.","assess":"Ukraine rises to 85. This reverses the v14 read: after the winter's net-loss period, Russia is again making incremental net gains (~31 sq mi in June per DeepState), has taken most of Pokrovsk, and pushed into Dnipropetrovsk and Sumy. The crucial caveat holds — CSIS notes Russia has still seized under 1.5% of Ukrainian territory since 2024, advancing at a Somme-slow ~70m/day for approximately 1.2M casualties. It is grinding progress, not breakthrough, bought at historically extreme cost, with the Russian economy strained but unbroken. Ukraine is