nvolvement was long denied by both Moscow and Pyongyang.","who":"Both — it exposes Russian manpower shortage and DPRK dependence.","evid":"Now effectively acknowledged. DPRK troops are fighting and dying in exchange for Russian technology, energy, and food.","status":"DOCUMENTED"}]},"history":{"roots":"Russia's invasion is an attempt to reverse 1991 — to deny Ukraine's existence as a nation independent of Moscow. After the USSR collapsed, Ukraine drifted west; the 2004 Orange Revolution and 2014 Maidan uprising (which ousted a pro-Russian president) convinced the Kremlin it was losing Ukraine to NATO and the EU. Russia annexed Crimea in 2014 and fomented a separatist war in the Donbas. Putin's 2022 full-scale invasion sought a quick decapitation of Kyiv; it failed, becoming Europe's largest war since 1945. The roots run to Putin's conviction that Russia's security and identity require Ukraine inside its sphere — and to Ukraine's equally firm conviction, forged in this war, that its future is European.","timeline":[{"date":"1991","e":"Ukraine votes for independence as the USSR dissolves."},{"date":"2004","e":"Orange Revolution overturns a rigged pro-Russian election."},{"date":"2014","e":"Maidan ousts Yanukovych; Russia annexes Crimea and ignites the Donbas war."},{"date":"24 Feb 2022","e":"Russia's full-scale invasion; the drive on Kyiv fails."},{"date":"2022","e":"Ukraine retakes Kharkiv and Kherson; the front stabilizes."},{"date":"2023","e":"Ukraine's counteroffensive stalls against dug-in Russian defenses."},{"date":"2024-25","e":"Grinding attrition; Russia makes slow, costly gains in the east."},{"date":"2025","e":"US-brokered diplomacy under Trump; POW swaps and holiday truces, no settlement."},{"date":"2026","e":"Front largely frozen; Russia gaining ~30 sq mi/month; 66% of Ukrainians favor negotiating."}],"actors":[{"name":"Volodymyr Zelenskyy","bio":"Ukraine's wartime president; proposed a June 2026 frontline ceasefire and 'all-for-all' prisoner exchange. Navigating war-weariness at home and wavering US support."},{"name":"Vladimir Putin","bio":"Frames the war as existential to Russian security and identity; has set truce terms around religious holidays while pressing territorial demands."},{"name":"United States (Trump)","bio":"Shifted from Biden-era backing to pushing a negotiated end; reduced aid, blamed Kyiv at times — leverage over both sides."},{"name":"Europe / NATO","bio":"Ukraine's economic and military lifeline; divided on how far to back Kyiv as US commitment wavers."}],"bridge":"The 2026 stalemate is the longue durée compressed: Plokhy's 'gates of Europe' thesis — Ukraine as the contested frontier where empires define themselves — playing out as attrition math (+31 sq mi/month) and coalition politics. The Patriot tech-share raises Ukraine from client to co-producer, the first structural change in its dependency since 2022; Graham's death and Starmer's resignation in one day show how thin the personal load-bearing beams of Western support have become. Whether the war ends by exhaustion, negotiation, or a Russian system failure, its verdict decides more than borders: it decides whether conquest works again in Europe.","sources":[{"work":"The Gates of Europe: A History of Ukraine","author":"Serhii Plokhy","year":"2015 (rev. 2021)","note":"The Ukrainian-authored standard — statehood's deep history against the 'artificial country' narrative."},{"work":"Bloodlands: Europe Between Hitler and Stalin","author":"Timothy Snyder","year":"2010","note":"The territory's 20th-century catastrophe — context for why sovereignty is existential here."},{"work":"Russia Matters / Economist frontline metrics","author":"Harvard Belfer; The Economist","year":"2024-26","note":"Primary attrition data (the +31 sq mi/30 days figure this file cites)."}]},"refs":[{"t":"NPR World: Fedorov fired","u":"https://www.npr.org/sections/world/"}],"human":{"dead":400000,"disp":10000000,"famine":false,"aid":"functioning","note":"Combined military deaths est. ~400k+ (both sides, ranges wide) + tens of thousands civilian; ~6M refugees abroad + ~4M internal."}},{"id":"pak-afg","cat":"military","region":"South / Central Asia","subregion":"South Asia","name":"Pakistan–Afghanistan War","sub":"Mandokhail airstrike · Iran-deal broker","domain":"Interstate War","sev":"critical","status":"stalemate","since":"Feb 27 2026","esc":74,"lat":33.5,"lon":69.2,"trend":"dn","w14":false,"esc_history":[76,76,76,76,74,74,74,74,74,74],"cas":"289+ civilian casualties; Mandokhail strike killed children","disp":"115,000+ border regions","flag":"🇵🇰","note":"JUL — Pakistan's nuclear arsenal now underpins the new Saudi-led axis (Saudi/Qatar/Turkey/Egypt) via the Saudi-Pakistani defense framework — 'extended deterrence' against both Iran and Israel in theory; analysts note no Pakistani doctrine exists for nuclear use outside South Asia, and forward-deployment would trigger Indian reassessment · Islamabad also brokered early Iran-war mediation before Qatar took over · Gulf-powers + Türkiye brokering has calmed the Afghanistan-Pakistan dispute (Crisis Group: Xi left it to them while propping up Myanmar junta) · low-intensity Durand Line exchanges continue but no major flare-up since the Mandokhail strikes · both nuclear-armed; TTP safe-haven problem unresolved · Pakistan retains Iran-deal mediator standing (co-brokered Doha w/ Qatar; PM Sharif attending Khamenei funeral)","leverage":[{"actor":"Pakistan","asset":"Iran-deal mediator (Doha w/ Qatar) — diplomatic capital","str":"md"},{"actor":"Taliban","asset":"TTP safe haven; Afghan territory","str":"md"},{"actor":"China","asset":"CPEC; mediation leverage","str":"md"}],"gov":[{"src":"Taliban officials","detail":"Report Pakistani airstrikes killed civilians incl. children at Mandokhail"},{"src":"Pakistan (via RFERL)","detail":"Co-mediating US-Iran Doha track with Qatar"}],"mil":"A fresh flare-up: Taliban officials report Pakistani airstrikes killed civilians, including children, at Mandokhail. Low-intensity Durand Line exchanges continue; both states nuclear-armed.","pol":"Pakistan's diplomatic standing stays elevated via Iran-deal mediation even as the border conflict simmers and the Taliban shelters the TTP.","eco":"Pakistan under IMF pressure; easing oil relieves fuel-import strain.","assess":"Pakistan-Afghanistan eases to 74. The border dispute has settled into a managed, lower-intensity state under Gulf and Turkish brokering, with no major flare-up since the Mandokhail strikes. Crisis Group frames it as a conflict others are containing while Washington is absent. Pakistan's diplomatic stock stays elevated via its Iran-deal mediation role (PM Sharif is at Khamenei's funeral), but the structural problems — the TTP safe haven, nuclear adjacency — remain unresolved.","tclass":"conflict","tier":"ELEVATED","hist_real":true,"as_of":"15 Jul 2026","tracked_since":"Wk4 (2026)","domain_tag":"Military","external":[{"actor":"🇮🇳 India","side":"Afghanistan (Taliban outreach)","flow":"Upgraded ties with Kabul — encircling Pakistan diplomatically","tier":"documented","for":"Strategic encirclement of Pakistan; counter its Kashmir leverage"},{"actor":"🇨🇳 China","side":"Pakistan","flow":"All-weather ally; CPEC investment; shields Pakistan diplomatically","tier":"documented","for":"Secure the CPEC corridor to the Arabian Sea"},{"actor":"🇺🇸 US","side":"transactional","flow":"Working Pakistani intermediaries on the Iran file (Vance/Witkoff/Kushner channel) — Pakistan's standing has risen","tier":"documented","for":"Iran mediation; counter-terror access"}],"econlev":[{"holder":"Pakistan","channel":"Transit trade + border closure","exp":"MED","detail":"Controls landlocked Afghanistan's main trade corridor; border closures are its principal coercive tool"}],"contested":{"summary":"No significant narrative-war dimension identified in this theater at present. The main claims are broadly consistent with the evidence, or the disputes are policy disagreements rather than contested facts. This is stated affirmatively rather than left blank — the absence of an information operation is itself a finding.","claims":[]},"history":{"roots":"The Pakistan-Afghanistan war is blowback completing its circle. Pakistan built the Taliban in the 1990s for 'strategic depth' against India, sheltered them through the US war, and celebrated their 2021 return to Kabul — only to find the TTP (the Pakistani Taliban) operating from Afghan sanctuary with their blessing. Border clashes escalated into open war: Pakistani airstrikes on Afghan soil, Taliban counterattacks, mass deportations of Afghan refugees, and the Durand Line — the colonial border no Afghan government ever accepted — as the permanent casus belli. Gulf mediation (Qatar/Saudi) brokers pauses; the axis membership now formalizes Pakistan's nuclear weight; nothing resolves the core: each state hosts the other's insurgency.","timeline":[{"date":"1893","e":"The Durand Line drawn — never accepted by Kabul."},{"date":"1979-89","e":"Soviet war; Pakistan becomes the mujahideen pipeline."},{"date":"1994","e":"Pakistan midwifes the Taliban."},{"date":"2001-21","e":"US war; Pakistan plays both sides; TTP emerges (2007)."},{"date":"2021","e":"Taliban retake Kabul — Pakistan's 'victory' turns toxic."},{"date":"2024-25","e":"Cross-border strikes; mass Afghan deportations; open border war."},{"date":"2026","e":"Gulf-brokered calm; Pakistan's arsenal anchors the Saudi axis."}],"actors":[{"name":"Pakistan (army/ISI)","bio":"The creator fighting its creation — nuclear-armed, economically fragile, now the axis's deterrence provider."},{"name":"Afghan Taliban","bio":"The emirate that won — sheltering the TTP it won't disown, ruling by decree, recognized by almost no one."},{"name":"TTP","bio":"The Pakistani Taliban — the blowback insurgency killing Pakistani soldiers from Afghan sanctuary."},{"name":"Qatar / Saudi","bio":"The mediators whose money and offices keep the pauses alive."}],"bridge":"Rashid's quarter-century-old warning — that the Taliban project would consume its sponsor — is now the theater's operating fact: the TTP kills Pakistani soldiers from the sanctuary Pakistan built, the Durand Line remains the colonial artifact no Kabul government will bless, and Coll's Directorate S archive explains why neither state can simply disown its instrument. The axis membership adds the newest inversion: the army that lost control of its western project now sells nuclear deterrence to the Gulf — strategic depth sought westward after failing eastward. The Gulf-brokered pauses manage the symptom; each state still hosts the other's insurgency, which is the disease.","sources":[{"work":"Taliban: Militant Islam, Oil and Fundamentalism in Central Asia","author":"Ahmed Rashid","year":"2000 (rev. 2010)","note":"The Pakistani journalist's foundational account — written before the blowback it predicted."},{"work":"Directorate S: The C.I.A. and America's Secret Wars in Afghanistan and Pakistan","author":"Steve Coll","year":"2018","note":"The double-game's documentary history."},{"work":"Durand Line Agreement","author":"British India–Afghanistan","year":"1893","note":"The primary colonial text of the border no Afghan government has accepted."}]},"human":{"dead":8000,"disp":1200000,"famine":false,"aid":"deportation-strained","note":"Border-war casualties + TTP campaign; mass Afghan deportations from Pakistan create the newest displacement stream."}},{"id":"taiwan","cat":"military","region":"East Asia / Pacific","subregion":"East Asia","name":"Taiwan Strait — China Gray Zone","sub":"China = top Hormuz beneficiary · G7 minerals de-risking","domain":"Geopolitical / Gray Zone","sev":"high","status":"escalating","since":"Ongoing","esc":70,"lat":23.7,"lon":121,"trend":"ss","w14":false,"esc_history":[70,70,70,70,70,70,70,70,70,70],"cas":"No kinetic casualties","disp":"N/A","flag":"🇹🇼","note":"Crisis Group: Trump 'has not revised US policy on Taiwan' — hard to imagine ceding the high-end chip industry or regional primacy to China · PLA gray-zone pressure continues; no kinetic change · China remains largest Hormuz oil customer (stake in Iran ceasefire holding) · G7 Critical Minerals Alliance still targeting China rare-earth/magnet dominance; TSMC 90%+ advanced chips = the mutual hold","leverage":[{"actor":"China (PRC)","asset":"Rare-earth + permanent-magnet dominance; semiconductor demand","str":"hi"},{"actor":"Taiwan","asset":"90%+ of advanced semiconductors (TSMC)","str":"hi"},{"actor":"G7","asset":"Critical Minerals Alliance — de-risking China","str":"md"}],"gov":[{"src":"G7 / Élysée","detail":"Critical Minerals Alliance vs China rare-earth dependence"}],"mil":"PLA gray-zone pressure continues; the Taiwan Strait is one of seven mapped global escalation nodes.","pol":"China remains the largest Hormuz oil customer, so the renewed exchange re-exposed its supply interest. The G7 minerals alliance targets its rare-earth dominance.","eco":"Taiwan produces 90%+ of advanced semiconductors — the mutual supply-chain hold.","assess":"Taiwan holds at 70. Crisis Group confirms US policy is explicitly unchanged — Washington has not revised its Taiwan stance and is not about to cede the semiconductor industry or regional primacy to Beijing. The gray-zone pressure and the mutual supply-chain hold (TSMC chips vs. Chinese rare earths) are steady. China's large stake in the Iran ceasefire holding is the indirect linkage that keeps Taiwan coupled to the Middle East theaters.","econlev":[{"holder":"Mutual (PRC/Taiwan)","channel":"Semiconductors vs rare earths","exp":"HIGH","detail":"90%+ advanced chips (TSMC) vs rare-earth/magnet dominance — the mutual supply-chain hold"}],"tclass":"watch","tier":"ELEVATED","hist_real":true,"as_of":"13 Jul 2026","tracked_since":"Wk4 (2026)","domain_tag":"Military","contested":{"summary":"Both sides wage the war over inevitability itself — whether 'reunification' is history's verdict or a threat to 23 million people's self-rule.","claims":[{"claim":"Taiwan has always been part of China and reunification is inevitable — resisting it is separatist provocation.","who":"Beijing — the framing that legitimizes coercion and pre-justifies force; amplified globally through state media and UN Res. 2758 reinterpretation.","evid":"The PRC has never governed Taiwan for a single day. Res. 2758 seated Beijing at the UN but says nothing about Taiwan's status. Polling consistently shows large Taiwanese majorities reject unification. The 'inevitability' is a narrative objective, not a legal or demographic fact.","status":"CONTESTED — sovereignty claim vs never-governed reality"},{"claim":"US commitment to Taiwan is unreliable — Washington will trade the island away.","who":"Beijing's information operations + genuine Taiwanese anxiety ('yimeilun' — US-skepticism discourse); the doubt itself weakens deterrence.","evid":"US arms sales and the TSMC-Arizona interlock argue commitment; strategic-ambiguity doctrine and episodic Trump-era signals feed the doubt. The claim's power is that it cannot be disproven until tested.","status":"CONTESTED — deterrence credibility is the battlefield"}]},"external":[{"actor":"🇺🇸 US","side":"security guarantor","flow":"Arms sales, Taiwan Relations Act commitments, and strategic-ambiguity posture; TSMC's Arizona fabs tie US industrial policy to Taiwan's survival","tier":"documented","for":"A democratic semiconductor anchor inside the first island chain and denial of the chip supply to Beijing"},{"actor":"🇨🇳 China (PRC)","side":"claimant","flow":"Near-daily ADIZ incursions, gray-zone pressure, and a standing reunification-by-force option; economic integration used as leverage","tier":"documented","for":"Absorption of the island Beijing regards as a breakaway province — and the chip industry with it"},{"actor":"🇯🇵 Japan","side":"aligned","flow":"'Taiwan contingency is a Japan contingency' posture; Nansei island-chain buildup; intelligence and basing relevance to any conflict","tier":"documented","for":"Forward defense of its own southwestern approaches and sea lanes"}],"ext_flag":true,"history":{"roots":"The Taiwan question is the unfinished business of the Chinese civil war. When the Communists won in 1949, the defeated Nationalists (KMT) fled to Taiwan, each side claiming to be China's legitimate government. Taiwan evolved into a vibrant democracy and the world's most advanced semiconductor producer, while Beijing never renounced its claim or the option of force. The US shifted recognition to Beijing in 1979 but kept arming Taipei under 'strategic ambiguity.' As China's military power grew and Taiwanese identity hardened away from unification, the status quo became harder to sustain. The roots: two governments' rival claims to be China, a democracy that doesn't want to be absorbed, and chips that make the island indispensable to the world.","timeline":[{"date":"1949","e":"Nationalists flee to Taiwan after losing the civil war."},{"date":"1971","e":"UN seat transfers from Taipei to Beijing."},{"date":"1979","e":"US switches recognition to Beijing; Taiwan Relations Act preserves arms sales."},{"date":"1996","e":"Taiwan's first direct presidential election; China fires missiles to intimidate."},{"date":"2016-24","e":"Pro-sovereignty DPP governs; cross-strait ties chill."},{"date":"2022","e":"Pelosi visit triggers major PLA exercises rehearsing a blockade."},{"date":"2024-26","e":"Near-daily incursions; TSMC's Arizona fabs tie US industrial policy to Taiwan."}],"actors":[{"name":"Taiwan (ROC)","bio":"A democracy of 23 million and the maker of most advanced chips; increasingly identifies as distinct from China, resisting unification."},{"name":"China (PRC)","bio":"Claims Taiwan as a breakaway province; has never renounced force and rehearses blockades."},{"name":"United States","bio":"Taiwan's arms supplier under 'strategic ambiguity'; treats the island's chips and democracy as strategic assets."},{"name":"TSMC","bio":"The chipmaker at the center of it all — the 'silicon shield' that makes Taiwan's fate a global economic question."}],"bridge":"The 2026 pressure cycle — daily incursions, blockade rehearsals, the chip interlock — is the 1949 question priced by 2026 stakes: Rigger's core point stands, that Taiwan matters not as a piece on someone's board but as a functioning democratic society whose 23 million people have built the strongest practical refutation of the claim that Chinese culture and democracy don't mix. The TSMC-Arizona hedge cuts both ways — diversifying the silicon shield thins it — and the deterrence question is now openly triangular: Beijing's capability, Taipei's will, and a Washington whose reliability its own allies debate.","sources":[{"work":"Why Taiwan Matters: Small Island, Global Powerhouse","author":"Shelley Rigger","year":"2011 (rev. 2021)","note":"The standard case for Taiwan's democratic society as the stake itself."},{"work":"Strait Talk: United States–Taiwan Relations and the Crisis with China","author":"Nancy Bernkopf Tucker","year":"2009","note":"The diplomatic history of strategic ambiguity's construction."},{"work":"Taiwan Relations Act","author":"US Congress","year":"1979","note":"The primary legal text of the arms-sales commitment."}]}},{"id":"us-politics","cat":"political","region":"North America","subregion":"North America","name":"US Foreign Policy — Strikes + Brokerage","sub":"Doha + 3 tracks + DONROE DOCTRINE hemisphere portfolio","domain":"Geopolitical Strategy","sev":"high","status":"volatile","since":"Jan 2025","esc":64,"lat":38.9,"lon":-77,"trend":"ss","w14":false,"diplomacy_active":true,"esc_history":[63,64,64,64,64,64,64,64,64,64],"cas":"N/A","disp":"N/A","flag":"🇺🇸","note":"JUL 16 — Sen. Lindsey Graham dies (the Senate's leading hawk, hours after a Kyiv visit) — recalibrates the Hill's war-powers and Ukraine math · Senate opens confirmation hearing for Todd Blanche (Trump's defense lawyer) as ATTORNEY GENERAL · CNN investigation: Trump promoted companies on Truth Social days after personally buying their stock (e.g. Nvidia Apr 2025, $200-500k position before a permit-expediting post) — the presidential feed as a market-moving, personally-traded instrument · JUL 14 — SENATE BLOCKS THE DEFENSE BILL OVER THE IRAN WAR: Democrats defeated the motion to proceed on the $1.15T NDAA 50-46, strictly party-line, citing Trump's resumption of the Iran conflict WITHOUT congressional authorization — the war-powers fight now has budget leverage · Senate had earlier approved a resolution requiring withdrawal from hostilities against Iran · SCOTUS requesting $18.9M for justice protection (threats projected +40% this year) · ICE: body-cams mandated for arrest teams after two fatal shootings; most vehicle stops halted · Struck Iran (10 targets) + brokered Lebanon + Doha Jun 30 · UAE arms-sale fork on Sudan · African visa-embassy drawdown · DONROE DOCTRINE: post-Maduro corollary asserting right to intervene at will in Western Hemisphere — Venezuela occupied-by-leverage, Mexico indictments, Colombia election endorsement, Cuba strangulation · Congress notified of \"non-international armed conflict\" with cartels · JUL 7: US launched fresh strikes on Iran + revoked oil waiver after Hormuz tanker attacks — force-and-pressure posture back on; UK/France deploying Hormuz armada","leverage":[{"actor":"White House","asset":"Strike power + $300B gatekeeping + arms sales + multi-track mediation","str":"hi"},{"actor":"Congress (Graham)","asset":"War Powers; UAE arms conditioning","str":"md"},{"actor":"Truth Social","asset":"Real-time signaling that moves events","str":"md"}],"gov":[{"src":"US State Dept","detail":"3 mediation tracks (Doha, Lebanon, Sudan-Boulos); African visa-processing drawdown"},{"src":"US CENTCOM","detail":"10-target Iran strike"}],"mil":"A high-tempo week: the US struck 10 Iranian targets, then brokered the stand-down and Doha talks — force and diplomacy in 96 hours.","pol":"Three simultaneous mediation tracks define US posture (Iran/Doha, Lebanon, Sudan/Boulos), each with cross-pressures — most sharply the UAE arms-sale fork, where the lever most effective on Sudan is the partnership needed for Iran's $300B.","eco":"Oil stayed contained; the $300B funding question and post-IEEPA tariff cliff loom.","assess":"US foreign policy holds at 63 — striking Iran while running three mediation tracks. The central tension: US leverage over the UAE is the most effective unused lever on Sudan, yet the UAE is needed for the Iran coalition. Volatile stays right.","tclass":"watch","tier":"ELEVATED","hist_real":true,"as_of":"16 Jul 2026","tracked_since":"Wk4 (2026)","domain_tag":"Political","econlev":[{"holder":"United States","channel":"Sanctions + dollar system","exp":"HIGH","detail":"The master lever behind most theaters on this board — oil waivers, secondary sanctions, SWIFT access, tariff threats"}],"contested":{"summary":"The information environment is itself the theater: who gets to say what the war, the law, and the election mean.","claims":[{"claim":"The Iran war is constitutional and 'largely ended' threats — congressional authorization is unnecessary.","who":"The administration — Article II maximalism; the Senate's 50-46 NDAA block and withdrawal resolution are the institutional counter.","evid":"No AUMF covers Iran; the War Powers fight is now live with budget leverage. Whether 'success' claims match ground truth (blockade reimposed, strikes ongoing) is itself contested.","status":"CONTESTED — war-powers constitutional dispute, unresolved"},{"claim":"US strikes in Nigeria answer a 'Christian genocide.'","who":"The administration + advocacy networks; Nigeria's government, ACLED and Crisis Group dispute the characterization.","evid":"Mass killings documented; religious-targeting is ~5% of civilian-targeting events (ACLED). Analysts read the framing as leverage for critical-minerals access (cross-link: Nigeria theater).","status":"CONTESTED — humanitarian frame vs resource-leverage aim"}]},"history":{"roots":"The US theater tracks the superpower's internal contest over what its power is for. The second Trump term operationalized a doctrine the platform tags 'Donroe': hemispheric assertion (Venezuela, cartels, Panama), transactional alliances, tariff statecraft, and executive maximalism at home — mass deportations, National Guard deployments, institutional purges. The counterweights — courts, a blocking Senate minority, states, streets — fight a running battle over each instrument. The Iran war sharpened it into a constitutional question: strikes without authorization, answered by a 50-46 defeat of the defense bill. The world's variable is no longer what America wants, but which America shows up.","timeline":[{"date":"2016/2020","e":"Trump's first win; the contested 2020 aftermath and Jan 6."},{"date":"2024","e":"Trump returns with unified control."},{"date":"2025","e":"Deportation surge; Guard deployments; tariff statecraft; Venezuela operation."},{"date":"Feb-Mar 2026","e":"The Iran war begins without authorization — the war-powers clash ignites."},{"date":"Jul 2026","e":"Senate blocks the $1.15T NDAA 50-46 over the war; ICC pressure campaign; the institutional contest deepens."}],"actors":[{"name":"The administration","bio":"Article II maximalism as doctrine — war, trade, and enforcement run from the White House, courts permitting or not."},{"name":"Congress (the blocking minority)","bio":"The NDAA defeat shows the remaining veto — money as the last war power."},{"name":"The courts","bio":"The contested referee — injunctions, emergency dockets, and the question of compliance."},{"name":"The states + streets","bio":"The federalism front — sanctuary fights, Guard federalization battles, mass protest as counterweight."}],"bridge":"Schlesinger named the arc a half-century ago: the imperial presidency grows in war and emergency, and Congress's power of the purse is the last constraint standing when authorization dies. The 50-46 NDAA block is that constraint exercised — the first time budget leverage has met this presidency's Article II maximalism head-on — while the ICC campaign, the deportation architecture, and the Guard federalization fights test Levitsky-Ziblatt's forbearance thesis in real time: the rules survive only while both sides decline to use them fully. The platform tracks this as a theater because every other theater's American variable is decided here.","sources":[{"work":"The Imperial Presidency","author":"Arthur M. Schlesinger Jr.","year":"1973","note":"The classic arc of executive war power — written after the last unauthorized war fight."},{"work":"How Democracies Die","author":"Steven Levitsky & Daniel Ziblatt","year":"2018","note":"The forbearance-and-guardrails frame the current contest tests."},{"work":"War Powers Resolution + Senate NDAA vote record","author":"US Congress","year":"1973 / Jul 2026","note":"The primary legal text and the live vote applying its logic through the purse."}]}},{"id":"global-economy","cat":"economic","region":"Global","subregion":"Global","name":"Global Economy — Contained Through Exchange","sub":"Oil 'relatively contained' · $6B unfrozen · resilient","domain":"Macro / Energy","sev":"medium","status":"declining","since":"Mar 2026","esc":55,"lat":null,"lon":null,"trend":"dn","w14":false,"esc_history":[55,55,55,55,55,55,55,55,55,55],"cas":"War cost: airlines $6.5B/mo fuel at peak","disp":"Developing-world fuel crisis easing","flag":"📊","note":"JUL 15-17 — CHINA'S AI-EXPORT QUARTER: GDP boosted by strong exports 'thanks partly to the boom in artificial intelligence' while consumer spending and business investment lag — the export-led AI economy compensating for domestic softness · global perception surveys shift TOWARD China and away from the US (post Trump-Xi Beijing summit) — the soft-power ledger moving with the hard-power one · Oil 'relatively contained' through exchange (Swissquote) — reserve releases + oversupply · $6B Iran assets unfrozen · Kenya/Comoros fuel protests · shipping normalization s