nge: from one integrated market toward blocs. Three shocks stacked — the pandemic, the Ukraine war, and the tariff wars — breaking the assumptions of frictionless trade. Weaponized interdependence became doctrine: export controls on chips, rare-earth counter-controls, sanctions architectures, friend-shoring. The 2026 Hormuz crisis added the energy-chokepoint shock; US tariff statecraft rewired supply chains by decree; and the AI capex boom became the growth engine and the bubble question simultaneously. The platform reads it all through one lens: interdependence is no longer a stabilizer — it's the arsenal.","timeline":[{"date":"2008","e":"Financial crisis — the last system-wide rescue consensus."},{"date":"2018","e":"US-China tariff war begins the decoupling era."},{"date":"2020-22","e":"Pandemic + Ukraine war break the supply-chain assumptions."},{"date":"2022-","e":"Chip controls vs rare-earth controls — weaponized interdependence formalized."},{"date":"2025-26","e":"Universal tariff regime; Hormuz energy shock; AI capex boom carries growth; gold at records as the hedge."}],"actors":[{"name":"The US (tariff statecraft)","bio":"The system's author now its re-writer — access to the American market as the universal lever."},{"name":"China (the counter-arsenal)","bio":"Rare earths, refining chokeholds, and the export-control mirror — decoupling managed, not suffered."},{"name":"Central banks + gold","bio":"The de-dollarization hedge made visible — record central-bank gold buying as the system's trust gauge."},{"name":"The AI capex complex","bio":"The growth engine and the bubble question — data centers as the decade's infrastructure race."}],"bridge":"Farrell and Newman named the platform's operating premise: networks built for efficiency became instruments of coercion — the dollar clearing system, the chip chain, the rare-earth chokehold — and the 2026 economy is their thesis at full deployment: tariff statecraft, export-control duels, an energy chokepoint war, and gold's record run as the exit hedge. Rodrik's trilemma supplies the constraint: deep integration, national sovereignty, and democratic politics cannot all be maximized — and every bloc is now choosing which to sacrifice. The platform reads prices as politics because, in this regime, they are.","sources":[{"work":"Underground Empire: How America Weaponized the World Economy","author":"Henry Farrell & Abraham Newman","year":"2023","note":"The weaponized-interdependence thesis — this platform's economic lens, formalized."},{"work":"The Globalization Paradox","author":"Dani Rodrik","year":"2011","note":"The trilemma constraining every bloc's choices."},{"work":"Central-bank gold purchase series","author":"World Gold Council / IMF COFER","year":"2022-26","note":"Primary data behind the de-dollarization gauge."}]},"refs":[{"t":"NPR: China GDP / AI exports; perception shift","u":"https://www.npr.org/sections/world/"}]},{"id":"chokepoints","cat":"strategic","region":"Global","subregion":"Global","name":"Maritime Chokepoints — Hormuz Managed-Access","sub":"HORMUZ DECLARED CLOSED by Iran · traffic a trickle · Qatar suspends all sailing · ships struck","domain":"Maritime Security","sev":"critical","status":"volatile","since":"Ongoing","esc":94,"lat":25,"lon":50,"trend":"up","w14":false,"disputed":true,"esc_history":[65,67,67,66,69,74,78,74,88,94],"cas":"N/A","disp":"$trillions in trade; 2 tankers struck this week","flag":"🔭","note":"JUL 17 — THE STRAIT AS GOVERNED BATTLESPACE: blockade 2.0 running (2 vessels redirected in 17h; Kharg-bound tanker disabled); first-blockade baseline now public — 140+ interceptions, ~$4.8B cost to Iran by May 1 · a 'Persian Gulf Strait Authority' has formed around the designated-route regime — chokepoint governance institutionalizing mid-war · EASA airspace warnings extend the chokepoint from sea to sky; Doha/Bahrain intercepts price the whole Gulf as the risk zone · JUL 16 — IRGC widens the threat from Hormuz to ALL regional oil and gas — if executed, Bab el-Mandeb + Hormuz + Gulf load-ports simultaneously; US strikes now framed explicitly as convoy protection; the strait is a shooting gallery with tankers in it · JUL 15 — THE TOLL IS DEAD: Trump abandoned the 20% Hormuz transit fee after Gulf states offered US investment instead — chokepoint monetization traded for capital flows; the blockade on Iran is REIMPOSED and strikes resumed (4th round), so transit risk premium stays live even as the fee vanishes · JUL 13 — DUAL-CHOKEPOINT RISK NOW EXPLICIT: with Hormuz already declared closed by Iran, the Houthis announced intent to close BAB EL-MANDEB simultaneously, naming $200 oil as the objective · Bab el-Mandeb = ~12% of global maritime trade, 26-29km wide; throughput already fell 8.8M→~4M bbl/day in the earlier campaign · Hormuz (~1/5 of seaborne oil) + Bab el-Mandeb together is roughly a THIRD of seaborne energy trade under simultaneous interdiction — the largest tail risk the platform has ever logged · UNSC Res 2722/2812 Houthi-attack reporting renewal due 15 Jul · COUNTER-READ logged: both Iran and the Houthis have historically stopped short of full closure because it invites confrontation they cannot win · CRISIS (Jul 11-12): IRGC DECLARED HORMUZ CLOSED and is firing on vessels — struck at least 2 ships; a container vessel damaged + abandoned (crew rescued, 1 Indian national missing) · dueling claims: Iran's transit authority says passage 'not possible'; US CENTCOM/Trump/JMIC insist the southern Oman-coast route is OPEN for two-way traffic — but tracking shows traffic reduced to A TRICKLE · Qatar advised owners to SUSPEND ALL SAILING + maritime activity · Iran demands transit fees + IRGC authorization via its own designated lane; US objects, pushes the Omani route (Iran calls this an MoU violation) · Oman drafting a strait-management proposal — the live diplomatic path · ~20M bbl/day (1/5 of global oil) normally transits · Brent ~$73-76 · Bab el-Mandeb also stressed","leverage":[{"actor":"Iran","asset":"Hormuz — strike + 'governed by Iran' doctrine + sole-demining + route designation","str":"hi"},{"actor":"US 5th Fleet","asset":"Escort + strike; can't compel safety","str":"md"},{"actor":"France/Oman","asset":"Demining offer — rejected by Iran","str":"lo"},{"actor":"Houthis/China","asset":"Bab el-Mandeb + Taiwan Strait (rising)","str":"md"}],"gov":[{"src":"Iran FM Araghchi","detail":"Warns against 'separate arrangements'; claims sole Hormuz control"},{"src":"US/GCC/Oman","detail":"Reject any Iranian toll/control claim"}],"mil":"Hormuz is now an Iranian managed-access regime under contestation: Iran struck two tankers (Ever Lovely, Kiku) for using the US-cleared Omani route, declared the strait 'governed by Iran,' and rejected a France/Oman demining offer. The stand-down restored free transit but the governance dispute heads to Doha.","pol":"Iran's leverage is now doctrinal — a sovereign-management claim the US rejects but can't easily counter short of permanent escort.","eco":"The exchange slowed but didn't reverse normalization; demining is entangled in the sovereignty dispute.","assess":"Chokepoints jumps to 88 (CRITICAL) — the platform's third-highest theater and its most consequential for global markets. Iran's IRGC has formally declared the Strait of Hormuz closed and is firing on ships that attempt to transit, striking at least two vessels; Qatar has advised owners to suspend all sailing. Washington insists the southern Oman-coast route remains open, but tracking data shows traffic has fallen to a trickle. The dispute is now about who governs the waterway: Iran demands IRGC authorization and transit fees through its designated lane, the US insists on free passage via Oman, and each calls the other's position a treaty violation. With roughly a fifth of the world's oil normally transiting, this is the single largest live risk in the investment bridge's energy and defense exposure. Oman's draft strait-management proposal is the one diplomatic path open.","tclass":"watch","tier":"CRITICAL","hist_real":true,"as_of":"17 Jul 2026","tracked_since":"Wk4 (2026)","domain_tag":"Strategic","econlev":[{"holder":"Iran","channel":"Hormuz transit regime","exp":"HIGH","detail":"IRGC authorization + 'maritime service fees' for passage — an attempt to convert a chokepoint into a permanent revenue stream and strategic lever"},{"holder":"Global energy market","channel":"Price transmission","exp":"HIGH","detail":"~20M bbl/day (1/5 of global oil) normally transits Hormuz; closure transmits directly into Brent, war-risk insurance, and every energy-exposed position"}],"contested":{"summary":"No significant narrative-war dimension identified in this theater at present. The main claims are broadly consistent with the evidence, or the disputes are policy disagreements rather than contested facts. This is stated affirmatively rather than left blank — the absence of an information operation is itself a finding.","claims":[]},"history":{"roots":"The chokepoints theater tracks the physics of globalization: a handful of straits and canals through which the world's energy and trade must pass, and the powers who learned to price that necessity. Hormuz (a fifth of world oil), Bab el-Mandeb/Suez (the Europe-Asia artery), Malacca, the Bosphorus, Panama — each a geography lesson in leverage. The 2020s militarized them in sequence: Houthi Red Sea attacks rerouted shipping around Africa; the 2026 Iran war closed then conditionally reopened Hormuz — the first sustained closure attempt in history, with tolls proposed and abandoned. The platform treats them as a single system: when one narrows, all reprice.","timeline":[{"date":"1956/1967","e":"Suez crises — the original chokepoint wars."},{"date":"1980s","e":"Tanker War — Hormuz militarized the first time."},{"date":"2021","e":"Ever Given blocks Suez — six days, $60B in trade queued."},{"date":"2023-25","e":"Houthi campaign closes the Red Sea route for Western shipping."},{"date":"2026","e":"Hormuz: closure, designated-route regime, toll proposal floated and dropped; blockade reimposed — the strait as negotiating table."}],"actors":[{"name":"Iran (Hormuz)","bio":"The closure card played at last — mining, designated routes, and the toll experiment; leverage spent is leverage revealed."},{"name":"The Houthis (Bab el-Mandeb)","bio":"The non-state chokepoint power — proving a militia can reroute world trade."},{"name":"The US Navy + allies","bio":"The convoy system's underwriter — freedom of navigation as the imperial commons, now contested."},{"name":"Shipping + insurance markets","bio":"The pricing mechanism — war-risk premiums as the real-time gauge of every crisis."}],"bridge":"Khalili's Gulf logistics work supplies the correction the 2026 crisis proves: the 'freedom of the seas' was always a built order — dredged, insured, garrisoned, priced — and whoever can interrupt the build owns leverage over everyone who forgot it was built. Iran's closure experiment, the Houthis' militia-scale trade veto, and the abandoned US toll plan are three actors reading the same map: the strait as a rentable asset. The platform treats war-risk insurance as the honest gauge because underwriters, unlike statements, price what they actually believe.","sources":[{"work":"Sinews of War and Trade: Shipping and Capitalism in the Arabian Peninsula","author":"Laleh Khalili","year":"2020","note":"The critical scholarship on Gulf maritime logistics as constructed power."},{"work":"World Oil Transit Chokepoints","author":"US Energy Information Administration","year":"updated series","note":"The primary flow data (Hormuz ~1/5 of world oil) behind every scenario here."},{"work":"Joint War Committee listings / marine war-risk premia","author":"Lloyd's JWC","year":"2023-26","note":"The market's primary real-time risk gauge."}]},"refs":[{"t":"CBS live: blockade metrics","u":"https://www.cbsnews.com/live-updates/iran-us-war-trump-strait-of-hormuz-persian-gulf-strikes/"},{"t":"Hormuz crisis overview (Strait Authority)","u":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2026_Strait_of_Hormuz_crisis"}]},{"id":"geopolitical","cat":"strategic","region":"Global","subregion":"Global","name":"Geopolitical Blocs — AES / Gulf / China-Cuba","sub":"AES sovereignty bloc · Gulf hinge · Bejucal · OTS-Hungary","domain":"Strategic Competition","sev":"watch","status":"watch","since":"2026","esc":60,"lat":null,"lon":null,"trend":"up","w14":false,"esc_history":[58,60,60,60,60,60,60,60,60,60],"cas":"N/A — analytical + intelligence layer","disp":"N/A","flag":"🔭","note":"JUL 14 — US LAUNCHES SWEEPING ANTI-ICC CAMPAIGN: Washington announced a pressure campaign against the International Criminal Court itself, including pushing OTHER countries to withdraw support — a systemic attack on the post-1998 international-justice architecture, not just case-specific sanctions · compounding: ICC chief prosecutor Karim Khan's suspension upheld by the UK Bar Standards Board (sexual-misconduct allegations); ICC oversight body votes this month on removing him — the court is under external assault and internal crisis simultaneously · UPDATED · AES Confederation as sovereignty bloc: 15,000 Unified Force, joint passport/bank, 0.5% import levy, quit ECOWAS, reciprocal US travel-ban response · Gulf = $6B custodian + Doha venue + $300B · Bejucal SIGINT · OTS-Hungary · AES condemnation of US over Venezuela/Maduro now has full context: the Jan 3 capture + Donroe Doctrine — Pan-African + Latin American sovereignty pushback converging · EXTERNAL-ACTOR LAYER (v16): three patronage models mapped into W/C Africa — gold-for-guns (Russia/UAE), drone diplomacy (Turkey/China), aid-as-cover/aid-washing (UAE, Qatar softer). US aid withdrawal (~83% Sub-Saharan cut) + French expulsion created the vacuum. Qatar Al Mansour $103bn pledge + UAE now a top-3 Africa investor; Iran-war may delay $100B+ Gulf African investment.","leverage":[{"actor":"AES (Mali/Burkina/Niger)","asset":"15,000 Unified Force; resource sovereignty (uranium/gold); anti-French r