 post-capture)","tier":"documented","for":"Oil foothold in US sphere"}],"ext_flag":true,"tclass":"conflict","tier":"ELEVATED","hist_real":true,"as_of":"15 Jul 2026","tracked_since":"Wk4 (2026)","domain_tag":"Military","contested":{"summary":"A government was removed, and the oil now moves through an account almost nobody can see. That opacity is not incidental.","claims":[{"claim":"US administration of Venezuelan oil is framed as stabilization/transition.","who":"The US and the interim arrangement — 'transition' is a far easier sell than 'seizure.'","evid":"Revenue reportedly routes through an opaque Qatari account. The mechanism, the beneficiaries, and the accounting are not public. The absence of an audit trail is itself the finding.","status":"UNRESOLVED — follow the account"},{"claim":"Maduro's capture is framed as a counter-narcotics/law-enforcement action.","who":"The US — a criminal frame avoids the words 'regime change' and the legal architecture that comes with them.","evid":"The action removed a head of state and installed an interim government aligned with US energy interests. Both things can be true; only one is being said.","status":"CONTESTED"}]},"history":{"roots":"Venezuela's crisis is the implosion of a petrostate under authoritarian mismanagement. Sitting atop the world's largest proven oil reserves, Venezuela became a socialist showcase under Hugo Chávez (1999-2013), funded by high oil prices. When prices crashed and Chávez died, his successor Nicolás Maduro presided over economic collapse: hyperinflation, the exodus of ~8 million people, and the gutting of democracy. Maduro clung to power through a disputed 2024 election widely seen as stolen from the opposition. US sanctions, recognition fights, and — by 2025-26 — direct US military pressure over drug-trafficking and migration turned Venezuela into a hemispheric flashpoint. The roots: overdependence on oil, the hollowing of institutions, and a ruler who won't leave.","timeline":[{"date":"1999","e":"Hugo Chávez begins his 'Bolivarian Revolution.'"},{"date":"2013","e":"Chávez dies; Maduro succeeds him as oil prices peak."},{"date":"2014-19","e":"Economic collapse; hyperinflation; mass emigration begins."},{"date":"2019","e":"Guaidó's rival-presidency bid fails to dislodge Maduro."},{"date":"2024","e":"Maduro claims a disputed election win over Edmundo González."},{"date":"2025","e":"US ramps up pressure — sanctions, cartel-designations, naval posture."},{"date":"2026","e":"Direct US military pressure over drugs and migration; regional flashpoint."}],"actors":[{"name":"Nicolás Maduro","bio":"President since 2013; holds power through the military and disputed elections despite economic ruin and mass exodus."},{"name":"Opposition (Machado / González)","bio":"María Corina Machado and Edmundo González, widely seen as the true winners of the 2024 vote, sidelined by the regime."},{"name":"United States","bio":"Applying sanctions and, by 2026, military pressure — framed around drugs and migration, with Venezuela's oil in the background."},{"name":"Military (FANB)","bio":"The institution that keeps Maduro in power; its loyalty is the regime's survival."}],"bridge":"Coronil's 'magical state' — a petrostate that performs miracles with oil money until the oil turns on it — is the arc from Chávez's missions to the exodus, and the 2026 transition is the sequel: Washington's phased plan (oil licenses first, elections last) rebuilds the extraction relationship before the democracy, with Figuera's negotiators seated and Machado's excluded — the patron choosing its counterpart, as in every Venezuelan cycle since the Gómez concessions. The 4,333 earthquake dead and the doubled oil exports in the same quarter is the magical state's oldest juxtaposition: the subsoil recovering faster than the society above it.","sources":[{"work":"The Magical State: Nature, Money, and Modernity in Venezuela","author":"Fernando Coronil","year":"1997","note":"The Venezuelan anthropologist's classic — the petrostate as performance, boom to collapse."},{"work":"Dragon in the Tropics: Venezuela and the Legacy of Hugo Chávez","author":"Javier Corrales & Michael Penfold","year":"2011 (2nd ed. 2015)","note":"The institutional account of the Chávez-Maduro system."},{"work":"UN Fact-Finding Mission on Venezuela reports","author":"UN HRC FFM","year":"2020-25","note":"Primary documentation of the repression apparatus the transition must dismantle or inherit."}]}},{"id":"colombia","cat":"political","region":"South America","subregion":"South America","name":"Colombia — Rightward Rupture + US Collision","sub":"Petro rejects results, alleges fraud/coup · transition SUSPENDED · inauguration Aug 7","domain":"Electoral Rupture / Security Pivot","sev":"high","status":"volatile","since":"2025","esc":73,"lat":4.7,"lon":-74.1,"trend":"up","w14":false,"diplomacy_active":true,"esc_history":[66,66,66,66,67,67,67,70,70,73],"cas":"Election-night clashes in Cali; armed-group coercion reported in rural areas","disp":"3M+ Venezuelan refugees hosted","flag":"🇨🇴","note":"JUL 15-16 — THE RIGHT WINS THE RUNOFF (preliminary): Trump-backed far-right candidate Abelardo de la Espriella celebrates winning the preliminary count in a razor-tight presidential runoff — the answer to the 2026 question this theater's history posed: the left's experiment ends, Washington's decertification pressure worked as electoral leverage, and 'total peace' policy dies with the transition · contested-count risk in a margin this thin · NEW THEATER (backfilled) · MAY 31 first round: Espriella 43.7% / Cepeda 40.9% · JUN 21 runoff: Espriella 49.66% vs 48.70% (~250k votes; 63.6% turnout; 12.9M votes = most in Colombian history) · certified Jun 24; Cepeda conceded; Petro alleged fraud/foreign interference but recognized results · INAUGURATION AUG 7 · pledges: 90-day military offensive, 10 Bukele-style mega-prisons, fracking, end peace talks, Israel ties + Jerusalem embassy · pre-arc: DEA named Petro 'priority target', US sanctioned him · DISPUTED: worker-coercion complaints (59 companies), armed-group pressure, AtlasIntel poll suspension · inauguration AUG 7 approaching; transition tensions rising · UPDATE (Jul 7-10): Petro REFUSES to recognize Espriella's win, alleges 'electoral fraud via algorithms' + 'prohibited foreign financing' (accused Thomas Greg & Sons + Israel, no evidence presented) · Historic Pact coalition filing lawsuit to ANNUL the runoff · Espriella suspended the transition, accused Petro of attempting a 'coup d'etat' to cling to power, called on the Public Force + international community to defend constitutional order · election widely assessed free/fair (251,800-vote margin certified Jun 24) · incoming FM Bula: will CLOSE embassies in Cuba+Nicaragua ('won't legitimize dictatorships'), restore US+Israel ties, stay 'very close' to Venezuela's Rodríguez transition · inauguration Aug 7","leverage":[{"actor":"Espriella (from Aug 7)","asset":"Trump endorsement + mandate for force; 12.9M votes but razor margin + divided Congress","str":"md"},{"actor":"United States","asset":"Sanctions precedent on Petro; DEA targeting; tariff/decert threats — hemisphere's template case","str":"hi"},{"actor":"Armed groups (ELN/dissidents/Clan del Golfo)","asset":"Expected to strike back at the 90-day offensive; rural electoral coercion already shown","str":"md"},{"actor":"Petro camp","asset":"48.7% opposition bloc + fraud narrative; street mobilization capacity","str":"md"}],"gov":[{"src":"Registraduría / CNE","detail":"Certified Jun 24: 49.66% vs 48.70%; 63.6% turnout; AtlasIntel polls suspended May 19 over methodology (probe ongoing)"},{"src":"US State (Rubio) / Trump","detail":"Endorsement + 'Colombia's best days are ahead'; earlier sanctioned Petro; DEA priority-target designation"},{"src":"Colombia Ombudsman / Min. of Labor","detail":"Pre-election warnings on armed-group coercion; complaints from workers of 59 companies alleging vote coercion"}],"mil":"The security stakes activate at inauguration (Aug 7): Espriella has pledged a 90-day military offensive against armed groups, ten mega-prisons on the Bukele model, and intensified strikes on smuggling aircraft/boats. Analysts expect ELN, FARC dissidents, and Clan del Golfo to hit back — election night already saw clashes in Cali. The 'total peace' talks era ends.","pol":"The full arc fits inside our tracked window: DEA priority-target designation and US sanctions on Petro; the May 31 first round; the June 21 razor-margin runoff (250k votes); certification June 24 with Petro alleging fraud and foreign interference while recognizing results. Colombia completes the regional rightward sweep (Milei, Kast, Noboa, Paz, Bukele...). Election-integrity threads stay flagged DISPUTED, not credited.","eco":"Espriella pledges fracking and reversal of Petro's hydrocarbon-contract moratorium — an oil-and-gas reopening aligned with Washington. High public debt constrains the program; the razor margin constrains everything else.","assess":"Colombia rises to 70 (ELEVATED), trend up as the August 7 handover turns turbulent. Outgoing President Petro refuses to recognize Espriella's certified win, alleging algorithmic fraud and foreign financing (without presented evidence), and his coalition is suing to annul the runoff — prompting Espriella to suspend the transition and accuse Petro of attempting a coup. The election was widely assessed as free and fair. The incoming government's foreign-policy pivot is sharp: closing embassies in Cuba and Nicaragua, restoring US and Israel ties, and staying close to Venezuela's Rodríguez transition — hardening the regional pressure bloc around Caracas. The inauguration-day transition crisis is the near-term fuse.","tclass":"watch","tier":"ELEVATED","hist_real":true,"as_of":"16 Jul 2026","tracked_since":"Wk4 (2026)","domain_tag":"Political","econlev":[{"holder":"United States","channel":"Trade + certification","exp":"HIGH","detail":"Decertification + tariff leverage over an economy deeply tied to US trade; the incoming Espriella government will realign toward Washington"}],"contested":{"summary":"A certified election, and an outgoing president calling it a coup.","claims":[{"claim":"Petro alleges 'electoral fraud via algorithms' and prohibited foreign financing.","who":"Petro — annulling the runoff is the only path to retaining influence.","evid":"NO evidence presented. The election was widely assessed as free and fair; the 251,800-vote margin was certified Jun 24. His coalition is suing to annul.","status":"UNSUPPORTED"},{"claim":"Espriella accuses Petro of attempting a coup d'état.","who":"Espriella — framing the dispute as a coup mobilizes the security forces and international opinion behind him.","evid":"Petro is disputing a certified result and his coalition seeks annulment. Whether that constitutes an attempted coup or a legal challenge is the contested question.","status":"CONTESTED"}]},"external":[{"actor":"🇺🇸 US","side":"strained partner","flow":"Decertification tensions, aid conditionality, and friction with Petro over drug policy and Venezuela; historic Plan Colombia legacy","tier":"documented","for":"Cocaine-supply reduction and a stable partner on Venezuela's border"},{"actor":"🇻🇪 Venezuela","side":"cross-border spillover","flow":"Shared border with armed-group sanctuary (ELN, FARC dissidents), migration flows, and Maduro-Petro diplomatic complexity","tier":"documented","for":"Buffer and leverage; the border economy sustains armed groups on both sides"},{"actor":"🏴 Armed groups (ELN / dissidents)","side":"non-state","flow":"Control of coca corridors and mining; 'total peace' negotiations stalled","tier":"documented","for":"Drug and gold revenue; territorial autonomy the state cannot yet reclaim"}],"ext_flag":true,"history":{"roots":"Colombia is the longest war in the hemisphere refusing to fully end. Six decades of conflict — FARC's Marxist insurgency, paramilitary terror, cartel wars — killed ~450,000 before the 2016 peace accord demobilized the FARC. But the state never filled the vacated territory: FARC dissidents, the ELN, and the Gulf Clan carved it up, funded by record coca output and illegal gold. Petro — the first leftist president, an ex-guerrilla — bet on 'total peace' negotiations; the talks stalled, the violence adapted. US relations, once Plan Colombia's showcase, strained over drug policy and decertification threats under Trump. The 2026 election decides whether the left's experiment continues.","timeline":[{"date":"1964","e":"FARC founded — the long war begins."},{"date":"1980s-90s","e":"Cartel wars (Escobar); paramilitary expansion."},{"date":"2000","e":"Plan Colombia — the US partnership era."},{"date":"2016","e":"Havana accord — FARC demobilizes; the vacuum opens."},{"date":"2022","e":"Petro — the first leftist president; 'total peace' launched."},{"date":"2025-26","e":"Talks stall; dissident violence up; US decertification friction; election year."}],"actors":[{"name":"Gustavo Petro","bio":"The ex-guerrilla president — total peace stalled, US relations strained, legacy on the 2026 ballot."},{"name":"ELN + FARC dissidents","bio":"The accord's orphans and refusers — coca- and gold-funded, Venezuela-sanctuaried."},{"name":"The Gulf Clan","bio":"The paramilitary inheritance turned narco-corporation — the largest cocaine exporter."},{"name":"The US","bio":"The half-century partner turned skeptic — decertification threats as leverage over drug policy."}],"bridge":"Colombia's own Truth Commission wrote the bridge already: the war persisted because it profited — land concentrated, coca monetized, politics armed — and peace fails where those returns survive demobilization. The 2026 runoff verdict (the Trump-backed right on preliminary count) tests the Commission's warning in real time: 'total peace' dies, US decertification pressure becomes electoral leverage vindicated, and the vacated-territory economy (dissidents, ELN, Gulf Clan) meets a state promising iron fist over negotiation — the cycle the ¡Basta Ya! report documented across six decades, queued for another turn.","sources":[{"work":"Hay futuro si hay verdad — Informe Final","author":"Comisión de la Verdad (Colombia)","year":"2022","note":"The primary national truth-commission record — the war's political economy in the country's own findings."},{"work":"¡Basta Ya! Colombia: Memorias de guerra y dignidad","author":"Grupo de Memoria Histórica","year":"2013","note":"The national memory report — 220,000 dead accounted, patterns named."},{"work":"Between Legitimacy and Violence: A History of Colombia, 1875–2002","author":"Marco Palacios","year":"2006","note":"The Colombian historian's structural survey."}]}},{"id":"mexico","cat":"political","region":"North America","subregion":"North America","name":"Mexico — Cartel-FTO Confrontation / Sovereignty Squeeze","sub":"Sinaloa governor indicted · 'hitting land' threat · USMCA lever","domain":"Coercive Diplomacy / Cartel War","sev":"high","status":"escalating","since":"Jan 2026","esc":62,"lat":19.43,"lon":-99.13,"trend":"up","w14":false,"esc_history":[61,61,62,62,62,62,62,62,62,62],"cas":"Cartel violence ongoing; no US kinetic strikes on Mexican soil to date","disp":"Record-low border migration flows","flag":"🇲🇽","note":"NEW THEATER (backfilled from W1) · APR 29 (=our W1): DOJ indicted 10 Mexican officials incl. SITTING Sinaloa Gov. Rubén Rocha Moya (AMLO ally, Morena), Sen. Inzunza, Culiacán mayor — extradition demanded · Nat'l Drug Control Strategy 2026: cartels = FTOs, fentanyl = WMD, extraterritorial-ops authority · Trump post-Maduro: 'We are going to start hitting land... The cartels are running Mexico' · Sheinbaum: charges 'political'; first public criticism of Amb. Johnson in 14 months; ~70% approval · cooperation continues: 10,000 troops to border, 90+ extraditions · Jun: Sheinbaum rejects Espriella labeling Mexican cartels military targets; warns vs Mexico as Nov-2026-midterm rhetoric · UPDATE (Jul): Sheinbaum publicly rebuffed Colombia President-elect Espriella's designation of Mexican cartels as military targets in Colombian territory ('each sovereign nation manages its own internal security'); warned again against Mexico as US Nov-2026-midterm rhetoric · skipped Trump's 'Shield of the Americas' Doral summit (with Lula + Petro) — the 3 big left-led economies absent · Americas Counter-Cartel Coalition (A3C, Hegseth/SOUTHCOM Miami) advancing around her · still NO US strikes on Mexican soil; Rocha Moya extradition decision still pending","leverage":[{"actor":"United States","asset":"FTO/WMD legal architecture + extraterritorial authority + tariff/USMCA-nonrenewal threat + indictment-extradition pressure","str":"hi"},{"actor":"Sheinbaum government","asset":"Migration cooperation (Trump's signature win depends on it) + 80% of exports to US = mutual dependence + 70% approval","str":"md"},{"actor":"Cartels (Sinaloa/CJNG)","asset":"Reduced fentanyl shipments under pressure — adaptive, not defeated; state-capture depth the indictments expose","str":"md"},{"actor":"Morena party dynamics","asset":"Rocha Moya = AMLO ally; extradition decision risks splintering the ruling party","str":"md"}],"gov":[{"src":"US DOJ / DEA (Cole)","detail":"Apr 29: 10 officials charged incl. sitting Sinaloa governor — 'No one is above the law'; extradition requested"},{"src":"National Drug Control Strategy 2026","detail":"Cartels designated FTOs; fentanyl classified WMD; measurable compliance benchmarks; expanded extraterritorial authority"},{"src":"Sheinbaum govt","detail":"Rejected charges as political; 10,000 security forces deployed to border; 90+ extraditions delivered; record-low migration flows"}],"mil":"No US strikes on Mexican soil yet — but the architecture is built: FTO designations enable military targeting authorities, fentanyl-as-WMD reframes trafficking as a weapons issue, and Congress has been notified of a 'non-international armed conflict' with cartels. Trump's post-Maduro statement — 'we are going to start hitting land... the cartels are running Mexico' — is the declared trajectory. Mexico's counter: 10,000 troops to the border and visible enforcement wins that reduce the pretext.","pol":"The April 29 indictment of a sitting governor (and AMLO ally) converted the pressure campaign into a domestic crisis for Sheinbaum: extraditing Rocha Moya risks splintering Morena; refusing risks tariffs, USMCA non-renewal, or worse. Her balancing act — cooperation on migration/extraditions while defending sovereignty rhetorically — has held approval near 70%, but the US strategy's compliance benchmarks are designed to force choices. She has also pushed back regionally, rejecting Espriella's 'military target' framing of Mexican cartels and warning against Mexico as US midterm rhetoric.","eco":"The US takes ~80% of Mexico's exports; USMCA review is the standing guillotine. Compliance benchmarks now reach into Mexico's financial sector. Cartel adaptation (reduced fentanyl shipments) shows economic pressure registering inside illicit markets too.","assess":"Mexico enters at 62, trend up. This is the hemisphere's most consequential slow-burn: the Venezuela precedent plus the FTO/WMD legal stack means the distance from indictments to kinetic action is shorter than it has ever been, while mutual dependence (migration for Trump, exports for Mexico) is the stabilizer neither side can afford to break. The Rocha Moya extradition decision is the fuse to watch — it forces Sheinbaum to choose between her party and her northern flank. JULY UPDATE: Sheinbaum is holding the line — no US strikes have hit Mexican soil, she skipped Trump's Doral 'Shield of the Americas' summit alongside Lula and Petro (the three big left-led economies conspicuously absent), and she rebuffed Colombia's president-elect for declaring Mexican cartels military targets. Her 'each nation manages its own security' sovereignty framing holds at ~70% approval, but the A3C counter-cartel coalition is consolidating around her and the Rocha Moya extradition fuse is still unlit.","tclass":"watch","tier":"ELEVATED","hist_real":true,"as_of":"13 Jul 2026","tracked_since":"Wk4 (2026)","domain_tag":"Political","econlev":[{"holder":"United States","channel":"Trade (USMCA) + tariffs","exp":"HIGH","detail":"~80% of Mexican exports go to the US — the ultimate asymmetric lever, now tied explicitly to cartel enforcement"}],"contested":{"summary":"No significant narrative-war dimension identified in this theater at present. The main claims are broadly consistent with the evidence, or the disputes are policy disagreements rather than contested facts. This is stated affirmatively rather than left blank — the absence of an information operation is itself a finding.","claims":[]},"external":[{"actor":"🇺🇸 US","side":"pressure + partner","flow":"Tariff threats, fentanyl-and-migration leverage, cartel terrorist-designations, and USMCA dependence; possible unilateral strike rhetoric on cartel targets","tier":"documented","for":"Border control, drug-flow reduction, and nearshoring supply chains away from China"},{"actor":"🇨🇳 China","side":"economic","flow":"Investment and use of Mexico as a tariff-arbitrage assembly platform into the US market","tier":"documented","for":"A back door into North American supply chains around US-China trade barriers"},{"actor":"🏴 Cartels (CJNG/Sinaloa)","side":"non-state power","flow":"Territorial control, fentanyl production, and state-capture of institutions — the de facto external-actor problem inside Mexico's own borders","tier":"documented","for":"Drug revenue and impunity; the state's monopoly on force is the contested asset"}],"ext_flag":true,"history":{"roots":"Mexico's security crisis is the cartel wars' third decade meeting a transformed state. The 2006 militarization ('Calderón's war') fragmented the cartels into warring factions — CJNG and the Sinaloa network chief among them — that diversified from drugs into extortion, fuel theft, and territorial governance. Fentanyl made them Washington's problem; ~30,000 homicides a year made them Mexico's. Morena's dominance (AMLO, now Sheinbaum) rebuilt the state's social legitimacy while militarizing security further. Trump's second term weaponized the relationship: tariffs, terrorist designations, strike threats — sovereignty versus supply-chain integration, with USMCA as the hostage.","timeline":[{"date":"2006","e":"Calderón militarizes the drug war — the fragmentation begins."},{"date":"2014","e":"Ayotzinapa disappearances — the impunity emblem."},{"date":"2019","e":"Culiacanazo — the state releases El Chapo's son under fire."},{"date":"2024","e":"Sheinbaum elected; Sinaloa civil war erupts (Mayo Zambada's betrayal-capture)."},{"date":"2025-26","e":"Cartels designated terrorist organizations; tariff-and-strike pressure; record extraditions as bargaining chips."}],"actors":[{"name":"Claudia Sheinbaum","bio":"The president holding sovereignty's line — cooperating on cartels and migration while refusing US unilateralism, with USMCA leverage cutting both ways."},{"name":"CJNG + the Sinaloa factions","bio":"The warring networks — fentanyl's manufacturers, territory's governors, and now designated terrorists."},{"name":"The US (Trump)","bio":"The pressure engine — tariffs, designations, strike talk; the border is the leverage and the flashpoint."},{"name":"The military (SEDENA)","bio":"The institution that won the state's security portfolio — airports, trains, customs — power without accountability."}],"bridge":"Trejo and Ley's finding decodes the present: cartel violence in Mexico tracks political transition — fragmentation of protection rackets when parties alternate — which is why militarization keeps winning budgets and losing wars. The Trump-era layer (designations, tariffs, strike talk) imports the hemisphere's oldest asymmetry into the relationship's newest instrument: supply-chain integration as hostage. Sheinbaum's line — cooperation without subordination — is the sovereignty position every Mexican government since 1848 has had to hold with the leverage it has; the extraditions-as-bargaining-chips show what that looks like priced.","sources":[{"work":"Votes, Drugs, and Violence: The Political Logic of Criminal Wars in Mexico","author":"Guillermo Trejo & Sandra Ley","year":"2020","note":"The scholarly standard — why democratization fragmented the cartel order into war."},{"work":"GIEI Ayotzinapa reports","author":"Interdisciplinary Group of Independent Experts","year":"2015-23","note":"The primary forensic record of the impunity emblem."},{"work":"El narco: Inside Mexico's Criminal Insurgency","author":"Ioan Grillo","year":"2011","note":"The narrative history of the drug war's construction."}]}},{"id":"cuba","cat":"political","region":"Caribbean","subregion":"Caribbean","name":"Cuba — Post-Intervention Shock + Strangulation","sub":"Island-wide grid COLLAPSE Jul 6 (7th in 18mo) · US seeks Díaz-Canel ouster · \"Cuba is next\"","domain":"Economic Strangulation / Regime Pressure","sev":"medium","status":"escalating","since":"Jan 2026","esc":66,"lat":23.1,"lon":-82.4,"trend":"ss","w14":false,"esc_history":[63,63,63,63,66,66,66,66,66,66],"cas":"32 Cuban soldiers killed in Jan 3 Caracas op; sanctions-linked excess-death risk (Lancet: 564k/yr globally from sanctions)","disp":"Emigration wave amid 15+ hr blackouts, ~100k surgery backlog, food spoilage","flag":"🇨🇺","note":"NEW THEATER (backfilled) · JUL 6: total national grid collapse — 3rd this year, 7th in 18 months (Nuevitas Unit 6 cascade) · US cut Cuba's oil when it captured Maduro (Jan) + forced acting Venezuela govt to halt shipments; Mexico also halted a shipment under US tariff threat · only ONE oil tanker (Russian Anatoli Kolodkin, Matanzas) docked all year · May: Trump exec order sanctioning Cuba energy/defense/mining/finance sectors · US NOW SEEKS DÍAZ-CANEL OUSTER (NYT/AP) + regime change 'by end of year'; talks ongoing, Cuba released 2,000+ prisoners as goodwill · Trump: 'Cuba is next... I'll have the honor of taking Cuba' · Axios: US intel claims Cuba acquired 300+ Russia/Iran attack drones since 2023, 'discussed plans to attack US' — Cuba calls it fraudulent pretext for military action · Díaz-Canel: 'genocidal energy blockade,' calls for 'war of the entire nation' · UN: ~100,000 pending surgeries backlog, humanitarian 'collapse' risk; blackouts up to 15+ hrs/day · Bejucal SIGINT (China) cross-link retained · UPDATE (Jul 6-10): another full national grid collapse Jul 6 (derelict grid, millions dark) · Cuba's legislature passed 100+ market-friendly reforms (private business + private investment stakes) — major concessions under US pressure; US dismissed as 'superficial smoke signals' + imposed MORE sanctions (military-owned firm + a Castra family member) · Communist Party endorsed Raúl Castro's grandson (Raúl Guillermo Rodríguez Castro) as intermediary for US talks · Colombia's incoming govt to close its Havana embassy · strangulation trajectory holding","leverage":[{"actor":"United States","asset":"Venezuela-oil cutoff + embargo + 'next' threat — strangulation without strikes","str":"hi"},{"actor":"Cuban state","asset":"Security apparatus intact; emigration as pressure valve; martyrdom narrative from the 32","str":"md"},{"actor":"China","asset":"Bejucal SIGINT + economic lifeline potential — hemispheric counter-presence","str":"md"},{"actor":"Russia","asset":"Symbolic solidarity; limited material capacity while consumed by Ukraine","str":"lo"}],"gov":[{"src":"Cuban Government (official)","detail":"Confirmed 32 soldiers killed 'carrying out missions' at Venezuela's request; Díaz-Canel condemned 'state terrorism'"},{"src":"US policy (Brookings/CRS synthesis)","detail":"Oil-to-Cuba interdiction intended to immiserate and spur uprising against the 'Castroite regime'"},{"src":"US Executive Order (May 2026)","detail":"Authorizes sanctioning entities in Cuba's energy, defense, mining, and financial sectors"}],"mil":"No kinetic theater — Cuba's 32 dead in Caracas were the spillover. The pressure is systemic: the Venezuelan oil lifeline is being interdicted deliberately, the island's grid is failing (the user's staged 52D layer independently maps the utility crisis and the short-lived Matanzas fuel relief), and Trump has placed Cuba on the 'could be next' list.","pol":"Díaz-Canel's 'state terrorism' framing and the Raúl Castro tribute converted the 32 dead into regime legitimacy fuel — martyrdom as cohesion. The bet on both sides is endurance: Washington bets immiseration produces uprising; Havana bets six decades of siege-adaptation outlasts one administration. The Bejucal SIGINT relationship with China is the strategic wildcard that could convert strangulation into confrontation.","eco":"Blackouts, fuel shortage, and a tourism collapse compound the oil cutoff. Emigration remains the escape valve that paradoxically stabilizes the regime by exporting discontent.","assess":"Cuba rises to 66, now escalating rather than stalemate. The July 6 island-wide grid collapse — the third total blackout of the year and seventh in 18 months — makes the strangulation strategy's endpoint concrete: with only one oil tanker (Russian) docked all year, the Soviet-era grid is failing outright. Washington has moved from pressure to explicit regime change, openly seeking Díaz-Canel's ouster and, per Trump, 'taking Cuba' next after Venezuela and Iran. The Axios drone-attack allegation — which Cuba calls a fraudulent pretext for military action — echoes the exact information-operation pattern that preceded the Venezuela intervention, making Cuba the clearest candidate for the next Donroe-Doctrine escalation. The same Mohajer/Shahed drone line alleged here runs through the Venezuela wargame layer and the Sahel theaters — one sanctions-bloc weapons ecosystem spanning three continents.","econlev":[{"holder":"United States","channel":"Energy interdiction","exp":"HIGH","detail":"Cut Venezuelan oil lifeline + pressured Mexico to halt shipments; only 1 tanker docked all year; May exec order sanctions energy/mining/finance sectors — grid collapse as coercion"},{"holder":"Russia","channel":"Oil lifeline","exp":"MED","detail":"Anatoli Kolodkin (Matanzas) sole 2026 shipment; symbolic more than sufficient"}],"external":[{"actor":"🇺🇸 US","side":"pressure/regime-change","flow":"Oil blockade (cut Venezuela + pressured Mexico to halt shipments); May exec order sanctioning energy/defense/mining/finance; explicit push for Díaz-Canel ouster","tier":"documented","for":"Regime change 'by end of year'; hemispheric Donroe consolidation"},{"actor":"🇷🇺 Russia","side":"regime lifeline","flow":"Anatoli Kolodkin tanker (Matanzas) — the ONLY oil shipment to dock all year; reaffirmed commitment; alleged attack-drone supplier (Axios)","tier":"documented","for":"Caribbean foothold in US sphere; anti-US solidarity"},{"actor":"🇨🇳 China","side":"regime","flow":"Bejucal SIGINT station (contested); economic-lifeline potential","tier":"alleged-credible","for":"Signals-intelligence reach into US; hemispheric counter-presence"},{"actor":"🇮🇷 Iran","side":"regime","flow":"Alleged co-supplier of the 300+ attack drones (Axios/US intel) — same Mohajer/Shahed line as Venezuela/Sahel","tier":"alleged-credible","for":"Sanctions-bloc solidarity; asymmetric reach"}],"ext_flag":true,"tclass":"watch","tier":"ELEVATED","hist_real":true,"as_of":"13 Jul 2026","tracked_since":"Wk4 (2026)","domain_tag":"Political","contested":{"summary":"Havana's crisis is real; the fight is over whether its cause is the embargo or the system — and what the Russia/Iran hardware means.","claims":[{"claim":"Cuba hosts 300+ Russian/Iranian attack drones and growing SIGINT facilities aimed at the US.","who":"US intelligence (Axios reporting); Havana denies entirely.","evid":"The Bejucal SIGINT complex is documented history; the drone claim rests on US intel leaks not yet independently verified. Cuba's denial is categorical. Logged, not asserted.","status":"ALLEGED-CREDIBLE vs categorical denial"},{"claim":"The collapse (blackouts, exodus) is caused by the US embargo alone.","who":"Havana — the six-decade external-cause frame.","evid":"The embargo demonstrably constrains the economy AND the system's own structural failures (state-sector paralysis, failed monetary reform) are documented by Cuban economists. Single-cause narratives on either side don't survive the data.","status":"CONTESTED — embargo vs system, both load-bearing"}]},"history":{"roots":"Cuba is the revolution that outlived its patron and now outlives its own economy. Castro's 1959 revolution, the missile crisis, and six decades of US embargo made it the hemisphere's defining standoff. The USSR's collapse brought the first starvation-era 'Special Period'; the 2020s brought the second: the tourism collapse, a failed monetary reform, the island's largest protests (2021), a million-person exodus (~10% of the population), and a grid that now fails island-wide. Russia and Iran court the wreckage — fuel, and allegedly drones and SIGINT — returning Cuba to its Cold War function: leverage 90 miles from Florida, priced in desperation.","timeline":[{"date":"1959","e":"Revolution; Castro takes Havana."},{"date":"1962","e":"Missile crisis — the closest nuclear call."},{"date":"1991","e":"Soviet collapse; the first Special Period."},{"date":"2021","e":"Largest protests since the revolution."},{"date":"2021-25","e":"~1M emigrate; grid collapses repeatedly; monetary reform fails."},{"date":"2026","e":"Russian fuel lifeline; alleged drone/SIGINT buildout (US intel; Havana denies)."}],"actors":[{"name":"The regime (Díaz-Canel)","bio":"The post-Castro management — administering scarcity with the same security state, minus the revolutionary legitimacy."},{"name":"Russia / Iran","bio":"The suitors — fuel and hardware for position; the alleged drone/SIGINT axis is the new leverage play."},{"name":"The US","bio":"The embargo's author and the exodus's destination — maximum pressure meets migration blowback."},{"name":"The exodus","bio":"~10% of the population gone in four years — the demographic verdict on the system."}],"bridge":"Ferrer's long history makes the present legible: Cuba and the United States were made in each other's shadow for two centuries, and the current wreckage — exodus, blackouts, Russian fuel, alleged Iranian drones — is the standoff's late style, with Havana again renting its geography to Washington's rivals because geography is the asset the embargo cannot reach. The exodus is the demographic verdict no narrative survives: a tenth of the population chose exit over voice. The platform logs the drone/SIGINT claims at their tier — alleged, denied — because ninety miles' worth of history shows exactly how intelligence claims about Cuba have been both true and manufactured.","sources":[{"work":"Cuba: An American History","author":"Ada Ferrer","year":"2021","note":"The Pulitzer-winning entangled history by the Cuban-born scholar — two centuries of mutual making."},{"work":"Cuba: Between Reform and Revolution","author":"Louis A. Pérez Jr.","year":"5th ed. 2015","note":"The standard survey of the republic and revolution."},{"work":"Cuban economists' independent analyses (e.g., Pedro Monreal)","author":"Cuban economic scholarship","year":"2020-26","note":"The internal diagnosis of the monetary-reform failure and state-sector paralysis."}]}},{"id":"myanmar","cat":"military","region":"Southeast Asia","subregion":"Southeast Asia","tclass":"conflict","name":"Myanmar — Civil War + Rare-Earth Supply War","sub":"KIA controls ~94% of China's heavy-REE feedstock · junta offensives on Kachin mines","domain":"Civil War / Resource Chokehold","sev":"critical","status":"active","since":"2021 coup","esc":88,"lat":25.38,"lon":97.4,"trend":"up","esc_history":[87,87,88,88,88,88,88,88,88,88],"cas":"~3.5M displaced since 2021 coup; ongoing airstrikes (Ponnagyun market strike killed ~20)","disp":"3.5M+ internally displaced","flag":"🇲🇲","note":"NEW THEATER (Phase 3 · SE Asia) · civil war since 2021 coup now fused with a rare-earth supply war · KIA (Kachin Independence Army) seized the Irrawaddy-basin REE belt in 2024 — controls mines supplying ~94% of China's heavy rare-earth imports (dysprosium/terbium for EVs, wind, missiles, robotics) · junta launched renewed offensives (Chipwi/Pangwa) to retake the mining belts · China plays BOTH sides — backs junta + maintains KIA ties for mineral-flow stability over ideology; closed border to pressure KIA into peace talks, KIA counter-closed crossings, halting exports · India (via Pax Silica) + US now courting KIA to diversify off China · Dec 2025-Jan 2026 junta 'sham elections' returned USDP (339/420 seats); Rakhine/Ponnagyun airstrikes continue","leverage":[{"actor":"KIA / KIO","asset":"Physical control of the Irrawaddy REE belt — ~94% of China's heavy-REE feedstock; can halt exports at will","str":"hi"},{"actor":"China","asset":"Sole processing destination + border/trade leverage; backs both junta and rebels for flow stability","str":"hi"},{"actor":"Myanmar junta (USDP)","asset":"Airpower + foreign backing; retaking mines to restore leverage — but holds shrinking territory","str":"md"},{"actor":"India / US (Pax Silica)","asset":"Alternative buyers courting KIA to break China's monopoly — nascent","str":"md"}],"gov":[{"src":"Global Witness / Chinese customs","detail":"Myanmar REE exports to China ~$773M in H1 2023; 300+ mining sites (40% rise since 2021)"},{"src":"KIO rare-earth mining regulation (2025)","detail":"Rebel political wing now taxing + regulating mining as a governance/revenue function"}],"econlev":[{"holder":"China","channel":"REE processing monopoly","exp":"HIGH","detail":"Myanmar supplies ~94% of China's heavy-REE imports; China controls the only processing/magnet chain — dual chokehold"},{"holder":"KIA/KIO","channel":"Resource control","exp":"HIGH","detail":"Physical control of the mines = revenue + political leverage; 2024 export halt proved the chokehold works both ways"}],"external":[{"actor":"🇨🇳 China","side":"both (junta + KIA)","flow":"Backs junta politically + maintains KIA ties; border closures to force peace talks; capital + mining equipment","tier":"documented","for":"~94% of its heavy-REE feedstock — flow stability over ideology"},{"actor":"🇮🇳 India","side":"KIA-courting","flow":"Pax Silica member; obtained dysprosium/terbium samples; exploring cross-border road access","tier":"alleged-credible","for":"Diversify critical-minerals supply off China"},{"actor":"🇺🇸 US","side":"either side","flow":"Considering working with either side of the war; Pax Silica framework","tier":"alleged-credible","for":"Break China's heavy-REE monopoly"}],"mil":"The civil war and the resource war are now the same war. Since the 2021 coup, ~3.5M have been displaced and ethnic armies govern much of the north — Kachin, Shan, Rakhine, Chin, Karenni. The strategic inflection was the KIA's 2024 seizure of the Irrawaddy-basin rare-earth belt, which handed a rebel army control of the feedstock for ~94% of China's heavy-REE imports. The junta's renewed 2026 offensives on Chipwi and Pangwa are explicitly aimed at retaking those mining belts — military maneuvers sitting atop dysprosium and terbium deposits, not random front movement.","pol":"The Dec 2025-Jan 2026 elections were a junta legitimation exercise (USDP took 339 of 420 seats) that resolved none of the core democracy-deficit or ethnic-autonomy questions; for many ethnic armies, de facto independence is already the lived reality. ASEAN is split — Thailand pushing to soften toward the junta, the Philippines (2026 chair) holding the non-recognition line.","eco":"Rare earths are the economy of the war now. The KIA/KIO taxes and regulates the mines as a governance function; China applies border and trade pressure to keep feedstock flowing; and India and the US are courting the rebels to diversify supply. The environmental cost is severe — acid-leach extraction poisoning the Irrawaddy headwaters and, downstream, Thailand's rivers.","assess":"Myanmar enters at 88 (SEVERE, conflict), trend up — a top-tier theater the platform was previously missing entirely. It is the sharpest live example of the platform's whole thesis: a civil war whose trajectory is set by a resource chokehold, where a rebel army holding ~94% of China's heavy-REE feedstock has more structural leverage than most states. It plugs directly into the critical-minerals system, and the China-plays-both-sides dynamic is the purest 'flow stability over ideology' case on the board. Watch the junta's Kachin offensives and any KIA export halt — either can move global magnet/REE prices.","tier":"SEVERE","hist_real":false,"as_of":"13 Jul 2026","tracked_since":"Wk13 (Jul 2026)","domain_tag":"Military","contested":{"summary":"China backs the junta and trades with the rebels holding the mines. Flow beats ideology.","claims":[{"claim":"China supports the junta.","who":"China — but the KIA rebels control the mines supplying ~94% of its heavy rare-earth feedstock.","evid":"China maintains ties with BOTH the junta and the KIA. The material interest overrides the political one: what matters is that the dysprosium keeps moving.","status":"DOCUMENTED — the contradiction is the policy"}]},"pipeline":[{"mineral":"Heavy Rare Earths","stage":"mine","actor":"Kachin State — Chipwi, Pangwa (KIA-controlled)","detail":"The world's largest source of HEAVY rare earths (dysprosium, terbium) — ion-adsorption clays leached in ~2,700 pits across 370+ sites. USGS logs Myanmar as a major producer (22,000t in 2025) but lists reserves as 'NA': the deposits sit in militia-controlled frontier and officially 'do not exist.' In-situ leaching poisons the water; landslides bury workers.","who":"KIA seized Chipwi/Pangwa (Oct 2024), taxes Chinese operators ~$200M/yr; UWSA runs Shan State sites","tier":"documented"},{"mineral":"Heavy Rare Earths","stage":"process","actor":"Trucked into Yunnan → Chinese separation plants","detail":"Almost ALL of Myanmar's output crosses into Yunnan — China controls 90%+ of global heavy-REE separation. ~2/3 of China's rare-earth imports by value come from Myanmar. The KIA's control of the mines is the one lever that has brought Beijing to the negotiating table.","who":"China (state-linked entities set up the mines and buy 100% of output)","tier":"documented"},{"mineral":"Heavy Rare Earths","stage":"mid","actor":"NdFeB permanent magnets (JL Mag, China Southern)","detail":"Separated oxides → sintered into heat-resistant permanent magnets, ~90% of dysprosium/terbium's value. Global Witness: even 'recycled' magnet supply gets 'contaminated' with Myanmar material because sources mix during processing. If you buy a high-grade magnet, some of it likely came from Kachin.","who":"Bosch and Nidec buy magnets from JL Mag; both claim recycled-only sourcing","tier":"alleged-credible"},{"mineral":"Heavy Rare Earths","stage":"end","actor":"EV motors · wind turbines · defense · robotics","detail":"The magnets go into EV traction motors, wind-turbine generators, missiles and robotics — demand for the Nd-Pr + Dy-Tb magnet pairs is projected to grow ~7x to ~$70B by 2040. Western EVs indirectly depend on Kachin ore refined in China. India (IREL) is now testing KIA ore samples as an alternative — the one crack in the monopoly.","who":"The energy transition runs on conflict minerals it cannot officially trace","tier":"documented"}],"patterns":["china-refine"],"history":{"roots":"Myanmar's war is the violent unraveling of a 2021 coup. After decades of military dictatorship, a democratic opening (2011-2021) let Aung San Suu Kyi's party win landslides — until the army (Tatmadaw) seized power again in Feb 2021. This time the resistance fought back: a nationwide civil war pitting the junta against ethnic armed organizations (some fighting since independence in 1948) and new pro-democracy militias (PDFs). The junta is losing ground, especially in the resource-rich borderlands where ethnic armies control the jade, rare-earth, and drug economies. The roots: a military that has never accepted civilian rule, and a patchwork of ethnic nations never fully integrated into the Burman-dominated state.","timeline":[{"date":"1948","e":"Independence from Britain; ethnic insurgencies begin almost immediately."},{"date":"1962","e":"Military coup begins decades of junta rule."},{"date":"2011","e":"Gradual democratic opening begins."},{"date":"2015","e":"Aung San Suu Kyi's NLD wins elections."},{"date":"2017","e":"Rohingya genocide drives ~700,000 into Bangladesh."},{"date":"1 Feb 2021","e":"Military coup; mass protests met with lethal force."},{"date":"2021","e":"Armed resistance (PDFs) forms; nationwide civil war."},{"date":"2023-24","e":"'Operation 1027' — ethnic alliances seize vast territory from the junta."},{"date":"2025-26","e":"Junta on the defensive; ethnic armies control the rare-earth/jade borderlands."}],"actors":[{"name":"Tatmadaw (junta / SAC)","bio":"The military that has ruled Myanmar for most of its independent history; seized power in 2021 and is now losing the civil war."},{"name":"KIA (Kachin Independence Army)","bio":"One of the oldest ethnic armies; controls heavy-rare-earth mining that feeds China's magnet industry — taxes it heavily."},{"name":"NUG / PDFs","bio":"The parallel civilian government and its allied People's Defense Forces born from the anti-coup resistance."},{"name":"China","bio":"Buys the borderlands' rare earths, hedges between the junta and ethnic armies to protect its mineral supply and BRI corridors."}],"bridge":"Thant Myint-U's warning — that Myanmar's crisis is a collapse of the state idea itself, not a democracy-vs-junta morality play — is the frame the rare-earth economy proves: the borderlands never belonged to the Burman center, and now their militias tax the minerals of the global energy transition while the junta loses the interior. The KIA's Kachin mines financing both resistance and Chinese magnets is the platform's purest case of conflict and commerce fused; the India-IREL probe is the first crack in the monopoly and a Watchlist off-ramp. Whatever state emerges will be negotiated between armed nations, not restored from Naypyidaw.","sources":[{"work":"The Hidden History of Burma: Race, Capitalism, and the Crisis of Democracy","author":"Thant Myint-U","year":"2019","note":"The Burmese historian-statesman's structural account — the state idea's collapse beneath the transition story."},{"work":"UN Independent Fact-Finding Mission on Myanmar report","author":"UN HRC","year":"2018","note":"The primary record of the Rohingya genocide."},{"work":"Global Witness heavy-rare-earth investigations","author":"Global Witness","year":"2022-26","note":"Primary supply-chain tracing: Kachin pits to Chinese magnet-makers."}]},"human":{"dead":75000,"disp":3500000,"famine":false,"aid":"junta-obstructed","note":"Post-coup conflict deaths ~75k+ (ACLED-basis); 3.5M displaced; Rohingya (~1M in Bangladesh) counted under Bangladesh hosting."}},{"id":"south-china-sea","cat":"strategic","region":"Southeast Asia","subregion":"Southeast Asia","tclass":"conflict","name":"South China Sea — Philippines-China Gray Zone","sub":"Scarborough/Second Thomas Shoal clashes · $3.4T trade · MDT tripwire","domain":"Maritime Gray-Zone Confrontation","sev":"high","status":"escalating","since":"2023 (acute)","esc":71,"lat":15.2,"lon":117.8,"trend":"up","esc_history":[66,66,67,67,68,68,68,68,68,71],"cas":"No deaths yet; ramming, water cannon, military-grade lasers, injuries in resupply clashes","disp":"Fishing communities displaced from traditional grounds","flag":"🌊","note":"JUN-JUL ESCALATION SEQUENCE: China SANCTIONED Philippine Defense Sec. Gilberto Teodoro (Jun 11) — sanctioning a sitting allied defense minister for 'egregious conduct'; AFP leadership rallied behind him · RARE NAVAL STANDOFF (Jun 21-23): PH frigate BRP Diego Silang vs FOUR PLA warships near Scarborough, radio challenges exchanged, helicopter launched — timed to the close of Salaknib 2026 (7,000+ troops: PH/US/JP/NZ/AUS) · China's Sept-2025 'nature reserve' + May floating platform in Scarborough lagoon read as creeping-occupation pretext ('Mischief Reef playbook') · JUL 12: 10th anniversary of the PCA ruling — US, UK, Japan + ~12 states jointly demanded China comply; Beijing: the award is 'a poisoned tree' · NEW THEATER (Phase 3 · SE Asia) · China's nine-dash line overlaps EEZs of Philippines, Vietnam, Malaysia, Brunei, Indonesia · flashpoints: Second Thomas Shoal (BRP Sierra Madre resupply), Scarborough Shoal (China deploying floating 'structures'), Xianbin/Sabina Reef · escalating ramming, water cannon, military-grade lasers, flares fired at PH patrol aircraft · Apr 2026: PH lab-confirmed CYANIDE in bottles alleged used by Chinese vessels (environmental warfare claim) · ~$3.4T annual trade transits; est. 11B barrels oil + 190T cu ft gas · PH 2026 ASEAN chair pushing Code of Conduct (10th anniv of 2016 arbitral ruling China rejects) · US Mutual Defense Treaty (Art. IV) = tripwire; Balikatan war games w/ Japan as full participant; Japan supplying used warships to PH","leverage":[{"actor":"China","asset":"Coast guard + maritime militia mass; island bases; nine-dash-line claim enforced by presence","str":"hi"},{"actor":"Philippines","asset":"2016 arbitral ruling (legal high ground) + US MDT tripwire + ASEAN 2026 chair + new Japan/US basing","str":"md"},{"actor":"United States","asset":"MDT Art. IV commitment; first-island-chain doctrine; Balikatan; the deterrent that caps escalation","str":"hi"},{"actor":"ASEAN claimants (Vietnam/Malaysia)","asset":"Overlapping claims + Vietnam's own Spratly buildup — dilutes a unified front","str":"md"}],"gov":[{"src":"PACC 2016 Arbitral Tribunal","detail":"Ruled China's nine-dash-line claim has no legal basis; China rejects as 'illegal and invalid'"},{"src":"PH National Security Council (Apr 2026)","detail":"Lab-confirmed cyanide in bottles alleged deployed by Chinese vessels — environmental-warfare allegation"}],"econlev":[{"holder":"China","channel":"Sea-lane + resource control","exp":"HIGH","detail":"Controls presence over $3.4T/yr trade route + 11B bbl oil / 190T cu ft gas estimated reserves via nine-dash line"},{"holder":"Global trade","channel":"Chokepoint dependence","exp":"HIGH","detail":"~1/3 of global shipping transits; disruption ripples worldwide — the leverage cuts both ways"}],"external":[{"actor":"🇺🇸 US","side":"Philippines","flow":"Mutual Defense Treaty (Art. IV tripwire); Balikatan war games; EDCA base access; surveillance","tier":"documented","for":"First-island-chain containment of China"},{"actor":"🇯🇵 Japan","side":"Philippines","flow":"Supplying used warships; joined Balikatan as full participant; 'normative power' aid","tier":"documented","for":"Rule-of-law-at-sea; counter-China presence"},{"actor":"🇨🇳 China","side":"claimant","flow":"Coast guard + maritime militia; island-building; water cannon/laser gray-zone coercion","tier":"documented","for":"Nine-dash-line sovereignty; sea-lane + hydrocarbon control"}],"mil":"A gray-zone confrontation engineered to stay just below the threshold of war: China uses coast guard and maritime-militia mass — ramming, water cannon, military-grade lasers, and flares fired at Philippine aircraft — rather than naval gunfire, precisely to avoid triggering the US Mutual Defense Treaty. The recurring flashpoints are the Second Thomas Shoal (where the Philippines resupplies the grounded BRP Sierra Madre) and Scarborough Shoal (where China has deployed floating 'structures' analysts fear presage an island base). The danger is miscalculation: a single death could invoke MDT Article IV.","pol":"The Philippines holds the legal high ground (the 2016 arbitral ruling China rejects) and the 2026 ASEAN chair, and is pushing to conclude a Code of Conduct on the ruling's 10th anniversary — while deepening US and Japanese security ties. ASEAN unity is the weak point: Cambodia has historically blocked consensus on China's behalf, and claimant states' overlapping claims dilute a common front.","eco":"The stakes are a ~$3.4T annual trade artery and an estimated 11 billion barrels of oil and 190 trillion cubic feet of gas. The April 2026 cyanide allegation adds an environmental-warfare dimension to the resource contest.","assess":"South China Sea enters at 68 (ELEVATED, conflict-class for the active gray-zone clashes), trend up. It belongs in the platform as the maritime counterpart to Taiwan — the same US-China first-island-chain contest, fought by coast guards instead of navies. Its defining feature is calibrated ambiguity: every actor manages escalation to stay below the MDT tripwire, which makes accidental escalation the primary risk. Watch Scarborough Shoal construction and any loss of life.","tier":"ELEVATED","hist_real":false,"as_of":"15 Jul 2026","tracked_since":"Wk13 (Jul 2026)","domain_tag":"Strategic","contested":{"summary":"A decade after the PCA ruling, the contest is whether law or presence defines the sea.","claims":[{"claim":"China has 'indisputable historic sovereignty' over the nine-dash line; the 2016 PCA award is 'a poisoned tree... a cynical parody of justice' (Xinhua).","who":"Beijing — rejecting the ruling wholesale while building the physical facts (bases, reserves, platforms) that make it moot.","evid":"The PCA ruled unanimously in 2016 that the nine-dash claim has no legal basis under UNCLOS — a treaty China signed. Scarborough, Second Thomas and Mischief Reef sit inside the Philippine EEZ. China refused to participate and ignores the award; ten years on (Jul 12 2026) the US, UK, Japan + ~12 states jointly demanded compliance.","status":"DOCUMENTED ruling vs DOCUMENTED defiance — law and power on parallel tracks"},{"claim":"China's Scarborough structures are 'temporary scientific research' and a 'national nature reserve.'","who":"Beijing — the environmental/scientific cover story for creeping occupation.","evid":"The 'nature reserve' (Sept 2025) and floating platforms (May 2026) follow the exact Mischief Reef playbook: huts→structures→airstrip. Manila calls it 'a clear pretext for occupation.' China removed one platform under scrutiny — the probe-and-pause pattern.","status":"CONTESTED — science framing vs occupation precedent"}]},"history":{"roots":"The South China Sea dispute is the collision between a rules-based map and a power-based one. China's nine-dash line — inherited from a 1947 Nationalist map — claims most of a sea through which a third of global shipping passes, overlapping five neighbors' EEZs. From 2013 Beijing built the facts: dredged reefs into fortress islands (Mischief, Subi, Fiery Cross), militarized them despite pledges, and deployed a coast-guard-and-militia swarm to enforce the claim daily. The 2016 PCA ruling demolished the line's legal basis; Beijing called it 'a poisoned tree' and kept building. The Philippines under Marcos chose confrontation-by-transparency — filming every ramming — and the US alliance commitment is the tripwire the whole region watches.","timeline":[{"date":"1947","e":"The nine-dash line drawn on a Nationalist Chinese map."},{"date":"1995/2012","e":"Mischief Reef, then Scarborough Shoal, taken by increments."},{"date":"2013-16","e":"Island-building: reefs become military bases."},{"date":"Jul 2016","e":"PCA rules the line has no legal basis; Beijing ignores it."},{"date":"2023-25","e":"Second Thomas Shoal water-cannon sieges; Philippine transparency campaign."},{"date":"2026","e":"China sanctions the Philippine defense secretary; 4-warship standoff at Scarborough; 'nature reserve' pretext; the PCA's 10th anniversary demands."}],"actors":[{"name":"China (CCG + militia)","bio":"The claimant enforcing by presence — gray-zone coercion calibrated below the threshold that triggers the US treaty."},{"name":"Philippines (Marcos)","bio":"The frontline state that chose exposure over acquiescence — every ramming filmed, every incursion publicized."},{"name":"United States","bio":"The mutual-defense treaty ally — the ambiguity of when Article IV triggers is the deterrence question."},{"name":"Vietnam/Malaysia/others","bio":"The quieter claimants — building their own islands while Manila absorbs the pressure."}],"bridge":"Ten years after the PCA award, the sea is the world's clearest test of whether adjudicated law constrains accumulated presence — and the running answer is Carpio's: law wins arguments, presence wins reefs, and only documented exposure narrows the gap. The Philippines' transparency campaign is jurisprudence by camera; China's 'nature reserve' at Scarborough is occupation by taxonomy. The July 2026 sequence (a defense minister sanctioned, a four-warship standoff, a fifteen-state compliance demand) shows both tracks accelerating at once — which is what makes the permanent-structure tripwire on this platform's Watchlist the region's live fuse.","sources":[{"work":"The South China Sea Dispute: Philippine Sovereign Rights and Jurisdiction in the West Philippine Sea","author":"Antonio T. Carpio","year":"2017","note":"The Philippine Supreme Court justice's case — the archipelagic view, freely published."},{"work":"PCA Award, The South China Sea Arbitration (Philippines v. China)","author":"Permanent Court of Arbitration","year":"12 Jul 2016","note":"The primary ruling — the nine-dash line's legal demolition."},{"work":"The South China Sea: The Struggle for Power in Asia","author":"Bill Hayton","year":"2014","note":"The standard narrative history of the claims' construction."}]}},{"id":"indonesia","cat":"economic","region":"Southeast Asia","subregion":"Southeast Asia","tclass":"watch","name":"Indonesia — Nickel Superpower + Resource Nationalism","sub":"~50% of global nickel · Prabowo statism · China JV dominance","domain":"Critical-Minerals Leverage / Governance","sev":"medium","status":"stalemate","since":"2020 export ban","esc":52,"lat":-2.5,"lon":118,"trend":"ss","esc_history":[52,52,52,52,52,52,52,52,52,52],"cas":"Nov 2025 floods (China-backed hydro breaches) killed 1,000+; mining-linked environmental deaths","disp":"Mining-displaced communities (Sulawesi, Halmahera)","flag":"🇮🇩","note":"NEW THEATER (Phase 3 · SE Asia) · world's #1 nickel producer (~50% of global supply) — the battery-metal chokehold · 2020 ore-export ban forced downstream processing onshore, drawing massive Chinese JV investment (Tsingshan et al.) · resource-nationalism model: capture the value chain, not just dig ore · revoked permit of China-backed Batangtoru/Sumatra hydro after Nov 2025 floods killed 1,000+ (28 firms penalized) · Prabowo govt statist tilt (Danantara sovereign fund; strategic-sector control) · Natuna EEZ friction w/ China's nine-dash incursions · stock market tumbled early 2026 on investor-confidence wobbles","leverage":[{"actor":"Indonesia","asset":"~50% of global nickel + export-ban leverage forcing onshore processing — the battery-metal spigot","str":"hi"},{"actor":"China","asset":"Dominant nickel-JV investor + processing tech (Tsingshan); controls much of the built downstream capacity","str":"hi"},{"actor":"Prabowo govt","asset":"Statist control via Danantara sovereign fund + strategic-sector nationalism","str":"md"},{"actor":"US/EV West","asset":"IRA sourcing rules push to de-risk from Chinese-controlled Indonesian nickel — buyer leverage","str":"md"}],"gov":[{"src":"Indonesia Min. of Energy/Investment","detail":"2020 nickel-ore export ban; 2026 revoked Batangtoru hydro permit + penalized 28 firms for environmental breaches after fatal floods"},{"src":"Danantara sovereign wealth fund","detail":"Prabowo-era vehicle consolidating state control over strategic sectors"}],"econlev":[{"holder":"Indonesia","channel":"Nickel supply chokehold","exp":"HIGH","detail":"~50% of global nickel; export ban forces value-chain onshoring — the single biggest EV-battery-metal lever"},{"holder":"China","channel":"Processing/JV control","exp":"HIGH","detail":"Chinese firms (Tsingshan) built + control much of Indonesia's downstream nickel capacity — leverage inside the leverage"}],"external":[{"actor":"🇨🇳 China","side":"investment-dominant","flow":"Dominant nickel-JV capital + HPAL processing tech; hydropower (Batangtoru); Belt-and-Road infrastructure","tier":"documented","for":"Control of ~50% of global nickel / EV-battery supply chain"},{"actor":"🇺🇸 US / EU","side":"de-risking buyer","flow":"IRA/CRMA sourcing rules pressuring supply chains to reduce Chinese-controlled Indonesian nickel content","tier":"documented","for":"Battery-supply-chain diversification"}],"mil":"Not a kinetic theater — the friction is economic and maritime. The only armed dimension is periodic naval friction in the Natuna EEZ, where China's nine-dash-line incursions overlap Indonesian waters and Jakarta has deployed frigates and F-16s to assert control.","pol":"Prabowo's government has tilted toward statism — the Danantara sovereign wealth fund consolidating control over strategic sectors, and a willingness to penalize even Chinese-backed investors (the Batangtoru hydro permit revocation after the November 2025 floods that killed over 1,000). The balancing act: harness Chinese capital and processing tech for the nickel build-out while resisting full dependence.","eco":"Indonesia is the battery-metal superpower — roughly half of global nickel supply, weaponized through the 2020 export ban that forced onshore processing and drew tens of billions in Chinese joint-venture investment. The strategic contradiction: the resource-nationalism model succeeded at capturing the value chain, but handed much of the downstream capacity to Chinese firms, so the West's de-risking push now targets Indonesian nickel precisely because it's Chinese-controlled.","assess":"Indonesia enters at 52 (GUARDED, strategic-watch) — the model case for why the watch class matters. No war, but it sits on the single most important EV-battery-metal chokehold on earth and is the arena where resource nationalism, Chinese supply-chain control, and Western de-risking collide. It plugs directly into the critical-minerals system alongside the DRC (cobalt) and Myanmar (rare earths). Watch the nickel price, any export-policy shift, and the Natuna friction.","tier":"GUARDED","hist_real":false,"as_of":"13 Jul 2026","tracked_since":"Wk13 (Jul 2026)","domain_tag":"Economic","contested":{"summary":"No significant narrative-war dimension identified in this theater at present. The main claims are broadly consistent with the evidence, or the disputes are policy disagreements rather than contested facts. This is stated affirmatively rather than left blank — the absence of an information operation is itself a finding.","claims":[]},"pipeline":[{"mineral":"Nickel (laterite)","stage":"mine","actor":"Sulawesi & Halmahera — Morowali, Weda Bay","detail":"Indonesia produces ~60% of world nickel. The 2020 raw-ore EXPORT BAN ('hilirisasi') forced processing onshore — Prabowo calls downstreaming 'the path to national revival.' But the 2026 quota cuts bit hard: Tsingshan's Weda Bay quota collapsed from 42Mt (2025) to 12Mt (2026), -70%. Mining in Raja Ampat was halted after a biodiversity backlash revoked 4 of 5 licenses.","who":"Jakarta uses the ban + quotas to capture value; state miners ANTAM largely confined to supplying ore","tier":"documented"},{"mineral":"Nickel","stage":"process","actor":"Chinese-built HPAL + smelters (75% Chinese-controlled)","detail":"Chinese firms control ~75% of Indonesia's refining; Tsingshan + Jiangsu Delong alone >70%, ~$14-15B invested and 'embedded, cannot be relocated.' Tsingshan's HPAL (with GEM/CATL/Huayou) converts low-grade laterite → MHP for batteries. Powered by captive COAL — 4-5x the CO2 of Canadian nickel, the ESG stain. The May 2026 CCCI letter to Prabowo protesting taxes/quotas is the leverage fight in the open.","who":"China (Tsingshan, Huayou, CATL/Lygend) — the processing chokehold Jakarta built and now negotiates against","tier":"documented"},{"mineral":"Nickel","stage":"mid","actor":"MHP → nickel sulphate → NCM battery cathodes","detail":"MHP refines to nickel sulphate (>2x the value of ferronickel) then into NCM cathodes. Indonesia began exporting sulphate in 2023 — the move up the value chain. But a HORMUZ cross-link: HPAL needs sulfur, most shipped from the Middle East through the strait — the Iran war pushed smelting costs up ~$300/t and paused half of Huayou's Huafei output (cross-link: chokepoints theater).","who":"CATL + LG (Korea) build cathode/battery plants; the ecosystem Jakarta wants onshore","tier":"documented"},{"mineral":"Nickel","stage":"end","actor":"EV batteries · stainless steel — but IRA-excluded","detail":"~75% of nickel still goes to stainless steel; the rest to EV batteries. THE CATCH: the US Inflation Reduction Act EXCLUDES Indonesian nickel from EV tax credits precisely because of the Chinese ownership — so the world's biggest nickel producer is locked out of the biggest EV-subsidy market. And Tesla's shift toward LFP (nickel-free) batteries threatens the demand thesis.","who":"China's EV industry is the anchor buyer; the West's IRA wall keeps Indonesian nickel Chinese-bound","tier":"documented"}],"patterns":["china-refine","resource-nationalism"],"history":{"roots":"Indonesia is the giant that chose leverage over alignment. The world's fourth-most-populous state and largest Muslim-majority democracy, it emerged from Suharto's three-decade dictatorship (1998) into a raucous decentralized democracy — and under Jokowi and now Prabowo, into a resource-nationalist power. The 2020 nickel export ban ('hilirisasi') forced the world's EV supply chain onshore, built a Chinese-financed refining empire, and made Indonesia the test case of whether a producer can climb the value chain by decree. Non-aligned by doctrine since Bandung (1955), it joins BRICS while buying US planes — the swing state of the Indo-Pacific, selling access to all sides.","timeline":[{"date":"1945-49","e":"Independence war from the Dutch."},{"date":"1965-66","e":"Anti-communist massacres (~500k+); Suharto's New Order begins."},{"date":"1998","e":"Suharto falls; democratization."},{"date":"2020","e":"Nickel raw-ore export ban — hilirisasi begins."},{"date":"2024","e":"Prabowo elected — the general returns as democrat."},{"date":"2025-26","e":"BRICS membership; quota cuts hit Chinese smelters; IRA exclusion bites; Raja Ampat backlash."}],"actors":[{"name":"Prabowo Subianto","bio":"The Suharto-era general turned president — 'downstreaming is national revival'; non-alignment as leverage-maximization."},{"name":"China (Tsingshan et al.)","bio":"Built ~75% of the refining Indonesia's ban created — the partner-hostage relationship both sides now renegotiate."},{"name":"The US / IRA wall","bio":"The market that excludes Chinese-controlled Indonesian nickel — the wall Jakarta wants tunneled."},{"name":"ANTAM / the state","bio":"The domestic champion largely confined to supplying ore — the gap between sovereignty rhetoric and ownership reality."}],"bridge":"Hilirisasi is Bandung's economics arriving seventy years late: the non-aligned founding promise — sovereignty meaning more than a flag — attempted through export bans and smelter decrees. The catch the platform tracks is Roosa's shadow: the 1965-66 massacres that built the New Order also built the political economy (military-business fusion, foreign-capital bargain) that Chinese refining capital now occupies; Jakarta captured the midstream's location without its ownership. The IRA wall and the quota fight are the same negotiation from both ends — whether the world's nickel superpower can convert geology into leverage that survives its partners' veto.","sources":[{"work":"A History of Modern Indonesia since c.1200","author":"M.C. Ricklefs","year":"4th ed. 2008","note":"The standard survey — from the sultanates through Reformasi."},{"work":"Pretext for Mass Murder: The September 30th Movement and Suharto's Coup d'État","author":"John Roosa","year":"2006","note":"The 1965 foundation of the New Order's political economy."},{"work":"The Killing Season: A History of the Indonesian Massacres","author":"Geoffrey Robinson","year":"2018","note":"The fullest account of 1965-66 — the suppressed founding violence."}]}},{"id":"thailand-cambodia","cat":"military","region":"Southeast Asia","subregion":"Southeast Asia","tclass":"watch","name":"Thailand-Cambodia — Border War Aftermath","sub":"Dec 2025 border war → fragile ceasefire · Trump-brokered · energy-deal collapse","domain":"Interstate Border Conflict","sev":"medium","status":"stalemate","since":"2025","esc":48,"lat":14.4,"lon":104,"trend":"dn","esc_history":[50,49,48,48,48,48,48,48,48,48],"cas":"Dec 2025 border war: dozens of civilian + combatant deaths across multiple provinces","disp":"Widespread civilian displacement along border provinces","flag":"🇹🇭","note":"NEW THEATER (Phase 3 · SE Asia) · worst Thai-Cambodian border clashes in years: 5-day war Jul 2025 → 3-week war Dec 7-27 2025 (heavy weapons, multiple provinces, dozens dead) · 2nd ceasefire late Dec (Malaysia + US mediation; Trump pushed truce, Cambodia welcomed it) · Thailand exited 25-yr joint offshore energy-exploration deal w/ Cambodia (overlapping maritime claims now unresolved) · Cambodia rebuilding US ties (USS Cincinnati at Ream Naval Base Jan 2026; joining Trump's Board of Peace; resuming US joint exercises) despite US scam-center crackdown · China views the conflict as a threat to its Maritime Silk Road + Malacca-hedge strategy","leverage":[{"actor":"Thailand","asset":"Larger military + economy; exited the joint energy deal to pressure Cambodia; US 'key partner' designation","str":"md"},{"actor":"Cambodia","asset":"US-rapprochement (Ream base access) hedging its China dependence; Trump Board of Peace seat","str":"md"},{"actor":"United States","asset":"Ceasefire broker + courting both (Ream visit, exercises) to pull Cambodia off China","str":"md"},{"actor":"China","asset":"Belt-and-Road stakes in both; wants stability for its Malacca-hedge corridor — mediating pressure","str":"md"}],"gov":[{"src":"Malaysia/US ceasefire mediation","detail":"Brokered 28 Jul 2025 truce + late-Dec 2025 second ceasefire; 18 Cambodian soldiers returned by Thailand Dec 31"},{"src":"Thai govt","detail":"Exited 25-year joint offshore energy-exploration agreement with Cambodia post-conflict"}],"econlev":[{"holder":"Thailand/Cambodia (disputed)","channel":"Offshore energy","exp":"MED","detail":"Overlapping maritime claims + collapsed 25-yr joint-exploration deal leave Gulf of Thailand gas reserves locked and contested"},{"holder":"China","channel":"BRI infrastructure","exp":"MED","detail":"Belt-and-Road stakes in both states; conflict threatens the Maritime Silk Road + Malacca-hedge corridor"}],"external":[{"actor":"🇺🇸 US","side":"broker / Cambodia-courting","flow":"Ceasefire mediation; USS Cincinnati at Ream Naval Base; resuming joint exercises; Board of Peace","tier":"documented","for":"Pull Cambodia off China; Southeast Asia influence vs Beijing"},{"actor":"🇨🇳 China","side":"both (BRI)","flow":"Belt-and-Road investment in both; mediation pressure for stability","tier":"documented","for":"Protect Maritime Silk Road + Malacca-Dilemma hedge"},{"actor":"🇲🇾 Malaysia","side":"mediator","flow":"Co-brokered both ceasefires as ASEAN convener","tier":"documented","for":"Regional stability; ASEAN centrality"}],"mil":"Two interstate wars in one year between ASEAN neighbors: a five-day clash in July 2025 and a far larger three-week war from December 7-27, 2025, involving heavy weapons across multiple border provinces and reaching into Siem Reap, with dozens of civilian and combatant deaths and widespread displacement. A second ceasefire (Malaysia and US mediation) held into 2026, but low-intensity landmine incidents and mutual accusations keep it fragile.","pol":"The war accelerated a strategic realignment: Cambodia, long seen as China's closest ASEAN partner, is rebuilding US ties — hosting the USS Cincinnati at Ream Naval Base, joining Trump's Board of Peace, and resuming US military exercises — even through the US crackdown on Cambodian scam centers. Thailand, designated a US 'key partner,' exited its 25-year joint offshore energy deal with Cambodia, locking up contested Gulf of Thailand gas.","eco":"The economic casualty is the collapsed joint offshore energy-exploration agreement — overlapping maritime claims now leave Gulf of Thailand gas reserves contested and undeveloped. China's Belt-and-Road stakes in both states give Beijing a stability interest, since the conflict threatens its Maritime Silk Road and its Malacca-Dilemma hedging strategy.","assess":"Thailand-Cambodia enters at 48 (GUARDED, strategic-watch), trend down as the ceasefire holds. It earns a place less for the (now-paused) fighting than for what it reveals: a US-China influence contest playing out through a border war, where Washington is using the crisis to pull Cambodia off Beijing, and the collapsed energy deal is a resource dimension to watch. A ceasefire breakdown or a move on the contested Gulf gas would re-escalate it.","tier":"GUARDED","hist_real":false,"as_of":"13 Jul 2026","tracked_since":"Wk13 (Jul 2026)","domain_tag":"Military","contested":{"summary":"No significant narrative-war dimension identified in this theater at present. The main claims are broadly consistent with the evidence, or the disputes are policy disagreements rather than contested facts. This is stated affirmatively rather than left blank — the absence of an information operation is itself a finding.","claims":[]},"history":{"roots":"The Thai-Cambodian border war of 2025-26 is a century-old map dispute weaponized by two domestic crises. The border was drawn by French colonial cartographers (1907); the Preah Vihear temple ruling (ICJ 1962) never settled the surrounding land. The 2025 escalation — landmines, artillery, F-16 strikes, the worst fighting in decades — served both capitals: Cambodia's Hun Sen dynasty rallying nationalism, Thailand's fractured politics (a leaked Hun Sen-Paetongtarn call collapsed her government) needing an external enemy. A US-brokered ceasefire (Trump's tariff leverage) holds unevenly. Beneath it: Cambodia's scam-compound economy, Thai casino politics, and two militaries that profit from the frontier they fight over.","timeline":[{"date":"1907","e":"French-Siamese treaty draws the disputed border."},{"date":"1962","e":"ICJ awards Preah Vihear temple to Cambodia — the land around it stays contested."},{"date":"2008-11","e":"Temple-area clashes kill dozens."},{"date":"Jul 2025","e":"Full escalation: mines, artillery, F-16s; ~40+ dead, 300k displaced."},{"date":"Aug 2025","e":"US-brokered ceasefire (tariff leverage); Paetongtarn's government falls to the leaked call."},{"date":"2026","e":"Ceasefire holds unevenly; monitors deployed; the scam-economy dimension surfaces."}],"actors":[{"name":"Hun Sen / Hun Manet","bio":"Cambodia's dynasty — the leaked call was vintage Hun Sen statecraft; nationalism as regime maintenance."},{"name":"Thailand's military + politics","bio":"The army fights, the coalition churns — the border crisis toppled a Shinawatra government via a phone call."},{"name":"United States (Trump)","bio":"The mediator by tariff — trade leverage as ceasefire enforcement, a new model of intervention."},{"name":"The scam-compound economy","bio":"The borderland's real industry — cyber-fraud cities whose protection rackets entangle both militaries."}],"bridge":"Thongchai's 'geo-body' thesis is this war's decoder: the border being shelled is not ancient — it is the 1907 cartographic line by which Siam learned to be a modern nation, and both states' nationalisms are built on maps whose margins were never agreed. That is why a leaked phone call could topple a Thai government and why Hun Sen could convert temple stones into regime fuel. The US tariff-brokered ceasefire adds the newest layer: trade access as the hemisphere-style enforcement tool arriving in Southeast Asia, holding the line the ICJ's 1962 judgment never fully drew.","sources":[{"work":"Siam Mapped: A History of the Geo-Body of a Nation","author":"Thongchai Winichakul","year":"1994","note":"The Thai scholar's classic — how the map made the nation, and what its edges cost."},{"work":"ICJ Judgment, Temple of Preah Vihear (Cambodia v. Thailand)","author":"International Court of Justice","year":"1962 (interpretation 2013)","note":"The primary ruling and its contested surroundings."},{"work":"A History of Cambodia","author":"David Chandler","year":"4th ed. 2007","note":"The standard Cambodian history — the dynasty politics beneath the border theater."}]},"human":{"dead":60,"disp":300000,"famine":false,"aid":"functioning","note":"The 2025 border war: ~40-60 dead, 300k displaced at peak — small against this board, enormous against the border's history."}},{"id":"korea","cat":"military","region":"East Asia","subregion":"East Asia","tclass":"conflict","name":"Korean Peninsula — Nuclear Standoff + Russia Axis","sub":"NK nuclear expansion · Russia-DPRK war alliance · US-ROK intel friction","domain":"Nuclear Deterrence / Alliance Realignment","sev":"high","status":"escalating","since":"Armistice 1953","esc":70,"lat":38.3,"lon":127.5,"trend":"up","esc_history":[68,68,69,70,70,70,70,70,70,70],"cas":"No active combat; DPRK troops fighting/dying in Russia's Ukraine war","disp":"N/A","flag":"🇰🇷","note":"NEW THEATER (Phase 3 · East Asia) · NK nuclear modernization: could reach 290 warheads by 2035 (ROK est.); 'serious increase' in enrichment capacity (IAEA); Kusong enrichment site exposure sparked US-ROK intel-sharing cut · Kim's dual doctrine: 'war deterrence' (minimum 2nd-strike) + 'war strategy' (tactical-nuke threat to cap a N-S conventional war) · RUSSIA-DPRK AXIS: NK troops + arms to Russia's Ukraine war in exchange for tech/food/energy; Xi-Kim summit; PRC+Russia jointly oppose sanctions · NK tungsten exports to China up 13-fold (2026) · ROK Pres. Lee Jae Myung 'peaceful coexistence' policy vs hardening rhetoric; proposed renaming NK 'Joseon' (implicit two-state recognition) · US reduced-nuclear-umbrella concerns amid alliance transition","leverage":[{"actor":"North Korea","asset":"Nuclear arsenal (~50→290 warheads) + tactical-nuke escalation threat; troops/arms Russia needs; enrichment leverage","str":"hi"},{"actor":"United States","asset":"Extended deterrence (nuclear umbrella) + 28,500 troops + intel-sharing control over ROK","str":"hi"},{"actor":"Russia","asset":"Now DPRK's war patron — tech/energy/food for troops+shells; shields NK at UN","str":"md"},{"actor":"China","asset":"Largest NK trading partner; treats NK arsenal as geopolitical asset vs US; tungsten/mineral buyer","str":"md"}],"gov":[{"src":"IAEA","detail":"Warned of 'serious increase' in North Korean uranium-enrichment capacity"},{"src":"ROK Defense Intelligence / Yonhap","detail":"US reduced NK-nuclear-site intel sharing with Seoul after a lawmaker exposed the Kusong enrichment site"},{"src":"US-ROK-Japan +7 (May 30 2026)","detail":"Joint statement to act against vessels in DPRK sanctions evasion (coal/iron-ore exports)"}],"econlev":[{"holder":"China + Russia","channel":"Sanctions lifeline","exp":"HIGH","detail":"Both oppose DPRK sanctions; China's NK-tungsten imports up 13-fold (2026); Russia trades tech/energy for troops+shells — the arsenal's economic oxygen"}],"external":[{"actor":"🇷🇺 Russia","side":"North Korea","flow":"War alliance: receives DPRK troops + artillery/missiles for Ukraine; supplies tech, energy, food, sanctions cover","tier":"documented","for":"Manpower + shells for the Ukraine war"},{"actor":"🇨🇳 China","side":"North Korea","flow":"Largest trading partner; tungsten/mineral purchases; UN sanctions opposition; Xi-Kim summit","tier":"documented","for":"NK as a strategic buffer + geopolitical lever vs US in the Indo-Pacific"},{"actor":"🇺🇸 US","side":"South Korea","flow":"Extended nuclear deterrence; 28,500 troops; trilateral (US-ROK-Japan) coordination — but cut some intel sharing","tier":"documented","for":"First-island-chain containment; alliance credibility"}],"mil":"The peninsula is escalating structurally without active combat. North Korea is expanding its nuclear arsenal — South Korean estimates project up to 290 warheads by 2035, and the IAEA warns of a serious jump in enrichment — while codifying a two-tier doctrine: 'minimum deterrence' second-strike against the US, plus a 'war strategy' that threatens tactical nuclear use to stop a North-South conventional war from escalating. The most consequential shift is external: North Korean troops are now fighting and dying in Russia's war in Ukraine.","pol":"The Russia-DPRK war alliance is the defining 2026 development — Pyongyang trades troops and artillery for Russian technology, energy, and food, while Moscow and Beijing jointly shield it from sanctions at the UN. South Korea's President Lee Jae Myung pursues 'peaceful coexistence' (even proposing to rename the North 'Joseon,' an implicit two-state recognition), but faced a hardening moment after a lawmaker's exposure of the Kusong enrichment site led Washington to curtail intelligence sharing with Seoul — a rare alliance friction.","eco":"Sanctions are the battleground: the US, ROK, Japan and seven partners target DPRK sanctions-evasion shipping, while China and Russia openly oppose the regime and keep it afloat — Chinese tungsten imports from North Korea jumped more than 13-fold in early 2026. The arsenal runs on this Sino-Russian economic oxygen.","assess":"Korea enters at 70 (ELEVATED, conflict-class), trend up. It belongs in the platform not for active fighting but as a nuclear flashpoint being reshaped by the Ukraine war — the Russia-DPRK alliance has converted a frozen standoff into a live node of the global sanctions-evasion and great-power-competition systems. The US-ROK intel-sharing friction is a warning sign about alliance cohesion. Watch DPRK warhead/enrichment milestones, any tactical-nuke test, and the depth of Russian tech transfer in return for troops.","tier":"ELEVATED","hist_real":false,"as_of":"15 Jul 2026","tracked_since":"Wk13 (Jul 2026)","domain_tag":"Military","contested":{"summary":"The contest is over whether North Korea's arsenal is a bargaining chip or a permanent fact — and who must adjust to whom.","claims":[{"claim":"North Korea is a rational, permanent nuclear state; denuclearization is dead and the world must deal with Pyongyang as it is.","who":"Pyongyang (constitutional enshrinement of nuclear status) — and increasingly, quiet acceptance in some Western analysis; Russia's arms-for-tech partnership functionally endorses it.","evid":"290-warhead trajectory by 2035 (ROK est.), 'serious increase' in enrichment (IAEA), Kusong site exposure. The capability facts are documented; 'permanence' is the narrative the capability is built to enforce.","status":"CONTESTED — capability documented, acceptance is the fight"},{"claim":"US-ROK exercises are rehearsals for invasion justifying the arsenal.","who":"Pyongyang + Beijing's 'dual suspension' framing — inverting cause and effect for a domestic and international audience.","evid":"Exercises are defensive-postured and announced; the arsenal predates their modern scale. The claim's function is to cast deterrence responses as provocations — a loop both sides now feed.","status":"CONTESTED — the provocation-spiral narrative"}]},"history":{"roots":"The Korean peninsula is the Cold War's last unresolved front. Divided in 1945, devastated by the 1950-53 war that ended in armistice (never peace), it froze into the world's most militarized border. The North built the Kim dynasty's totalitarian garrison state and, from the 1990s, the nuclear program that is its survival insurance — through famine, sanctions, and three generations. Every diplomatic cycle (1994, 2000s, 2018-19) collapsed on the same rock: Pyongyang won't trade the arsenal that keeps it alive. The Ukraine war transformed the equation — North Korean shells and troops for Russian technology — making Kim a wartime ally of a great power for the first time since 1953, and pushing the arsenal toward 290 warheads by 2035.","timeline":[{"date":"1945/1950-53","e":"Division, then the war — armistice, not peace."},{"date":"1994","e":"Agreed Framework — the first failed nuclear bargain."},{"date":"2006","e":"First nuclear test."},{"date":"2011","e":"Kim Jong Un inherits — purges, acceleration."},{"date":"2018-19","e":"Trump-Kim summits collapse at Hanoi."},{"date":"2023-","e":"Russia alliance: shells and troops for tech; enrichment 'serious increase' (IAEA)."},{"date":"2026","e":"290-warhead trajectory; constitutional nuclear status; the acceptance fight."}],"actors":[{"name":"Kim Jong Un","bio":"Third-generation ruler — the arsenal is the dynasty's insurance and the Russia alliance its first great-power leverage since the USSR."},{"name":"South Korea","bio":"The economic superpower neighbor debating its own nuclear option as US extended deterrence wobbles."},{"name":"Russia","bio":"The new patron — arms-for-tech trade that functionally endorses the arsenal and breaks the sanctions regime."},{"name":"United States / China","bio":"The deterrence anchor and the reluctant enabler — both preferring a frozen problem to any available solution."}],"bridge":"The Russia alliance is the peninsula's biggest structural change since 1953: Cumings' long thesis — that the Korean War never ended, only paused — now has Pyongyang fighting in a European war and being paid in the technology every prior diplomatic framework tried to deny it. The 290-warhead trajectory converts the old denuclearization question into an acceptance question, and Seoul's own nuclear debate is the alliance system pricing American reliability in real time. The armistice's 73rd year finds all its assumptions inverted except one: nobody can afford the war's resumption.","sources":[{"work":"Korea's Place in the Sun: A Modern History","author":"Bruce Cumings","year":"1997 (rev. 2005)","note":"The revisionist standard — the war's origins in division, not invasion alone."},{"work":"Brothers at War: The Unending Conflict in Korea","author":"Sheila Miyoshi Jager","year":"2013","note":"The war as a 70-year continuing contest, not an event."},{"work":"IAEA DPRK safeguards reports","author":"IAEA","year":"2023-26","note":"Primary enrichment findings ('serious increase') behind this theater's assessments."}]}},{"id":"kazakhstan","cat":"economic","region":"Central Asia","subregion":"Central Asia","tclass":"watch","name":"Kazakhstan — Uranium Pivot + Multi-Vector Squeeze","sub":"40% of global uranium · Russia+China reactor lock-in · 10% output cut","domain":"Critical-Minerals Leverage / Great-Power Hedging","sev":"medium","status":"stalemate","since":"2022 (post-Ukraine)","esc":46,"lat":48,"lon":66.9,"trend":"up","esc_history":[44,45,45,46,46,46,46,46,46,46],"cas":"N/A","disp":"N/A — Central Asian migrant mistreatment in Russia a friction point","flag":"🇰🇿","note":"NEW THEATER (Phase 3 · Central Asia) · world's #1 uranium producer — ~40% of global supply (Kazatomprom) · 2026: cutting output ~10% (32,777→~29,697 tU), tightening a ~5% slice of global supply → upward price pressure · reactor politics = leverage map: 1st NPP to Russia's Rosatom, 2nd+3rd to China's CNNC — US 'wasn't even in the room' (no bid) · Rosatom/Uranium One divested some mine stakes under sanctions pressure; France's Orano (KATCO JV) + Macron pushing EU export boost · 'multi-vector' Tokayev doctrine: bridge between poles, reduce Russia dependence, but China now largest economic player · yuan bonds, Belt-and-Road middle corridor · sulfuric-acid supply = production bottleneck","leverage":[{"actor":"Kazakhstan (Kazatomprom)","asset":"~40% of global uranium; output-cut lever tightens world supply; multi-vector hedging","str":"hi"},{"actor":"Russia","asset":"Rosatom builds 1st NPP + owns ~26% of uranium deposits + processing/transit control + EAEU pull","str":"hi"},{"actor":"China","asset":"CNNC builds 2nd+3rd NPPs; largest economic player; BRI middle-corridor + yuan financing","str":"hi"},{"actor":"West (France/US/Canada)","asset":"Orano KATCO JV + Cameco Inkai stake; ~19% of exports — but forfeited reactor bids","str":"md"}],"gov":[{"src":"Kazatomprom","detail":"World's largest uranium producer (~40% global); announced ~10% 2026 output cut, tightening ~5% of global supply"},{"src":"Kazakhstan govt (2024 referendum)","detail":"Public voted for nuclear power; awarded 1st NPP to Rosatom, 2nd+3rd to China's CNNC; US submitted no bid"}],"econlev":[{"holder":"Kazakhstan","channel":"Uranium supply","exp":"HIGH","detail":"~40% of global uranium; the output-cut decision moves world prices — the single largest nuclear-fuel lever on earth"},{"holder":"Russia + China","channel":"Reactor + processing lock-in","exp":"HIGH","detail":"Rosatom (1st NPP, ~26% of deposits) + CNNC (2nd+3rd NPPs) capture Kazakhstan's downstream nuclear future; West forfeited"}],"external":[{"actor":"🇷🇺 Russia","side":"incumbent patron","flow":"Rosatom builds 1st NPP ($14.4B, 2 VVER-1200); owns ~26% uranium deposits + Kazatomprom stake; processing/transit control; EAEU","tier":"documented","for":"Retain nuclear-sector dominance + regional leverage despite sanctions erosion"},{"actor":"🇨🇳 China","side":"rising patron","flow":"CNNC to build 2nd+3rd NPPs; largest economic player; BRI middle corridor; yuan bonds/loans","tier":"documented","for":"Upstream critical-minerals control + de-dollarized financial integration"},{"actor":"🇫🇷 France / 🇺🇸 US","side":"de-risking challenger","flow":"Orano KATCO JV; Macron push for EU export boost; Wabtec locomotive deal — but no reactor bid","tier":"documented","for":"Uranium supply diversification off Russia"}],"mil":"Not a kinetic theater — Kazakhstan is a strategic-watch node defined by resource leverage and great-power hedging. The nearest security dimensions are indirect: the mistreatment of Central Asian migrant workers in Russia as a friction point, and the ever-present 'shadow of Russian leverage' as an EAEU member bordering both Russia and China.","pol":"President Tokayev's 'multi-vector' doctrine — positioning Kazakhstan as a 'middle power' bridging conflicting geopolitical poles — is being tested by infrastructure lock-in. The reactor awards are the tell: Russia's Rosatom won the first nuclear plant and China's CNNC the second and third, while the US 'wasn't even in the room' with no bid submitted. Astana has made subtle moves to reduce Russian ownership (Uranium One divested some mine stakes under sanctions pressure), but China has become the largest single economic player.","eco":"Kazakhstan is the uranium superpower — roughly 40% of global supply through Kazatomprom — and in 2026 it wielded that position by cutting output ~10%, tightening about 5% of world supply and pressuring prices upward. The strategic contest is over who controls the downstream: Russia and China locked in the reactor builds and much of the processing and financing (yuan bonds, Belt-and-Road corridor), while France's Orano and Canada's Cameco hold minority mine stakes and the West pushes to de-risk.","assess":"Kazakhstan enters at 46 (GUARDED, strategic-watch), trend up — the missing uranium node in the critical-minerals system. It's the nuclear-fuel counterpart to the DRC's cobalt, Niger's uranium, Myanmar's rare earths, and Indonesia's nickel: a stable state whose ~40% grip on global uranium gives it real leverage, now being locked into the Russian and Chinese nuclear orbit while the West forfeits the reactor contracts that determine long-term alignment. Watch Kazatomprom's output decisions (they move global prices) and any Western re-entry into the fuel cycle.","tier":"GUARDED","hist_real":false,"as_of":"13 Jul 2026","tracked_since":"Wk13 (Jul 2026)","domain_tag":"Economic","contested":{"summary":"A 'multi-vector' state whose vectors were decided in the reactor bids.","claims":[{"claim":"Kazakhstan pursues a balanced 'multi-vector' foreign policy.","who":"Tokayev — hedging is more sellable domestically than alignment.","evid":"Rosatom won the first nuclear plant; China's CNNC won the second and third. The US submitted NO BID — 'wasn't even in the room.' Infrastructure lock-in outlives rhetoric.","status":"CONTESTED — the hedge is already tipping"}]},"pipeline":[{"mineral":"Uranium","stage":"mine","actor":"Kazatomprom ISR mines — Budenovskoye, Inkai","detail":"The world's #1 uranium producer — ~40%+ of global supply, 25,839 tU in 2025, targeting 27,500-29,000t in 2026. Extracted by low-cost in-situ recovery. 2025 Subsoil Code amendments force Kazatomprom's stake to ≥75% in new contracts — resource nationalism, uranium edition. Of 13 projects, 10 are JVs (Cameco, Orano, CNNC, Rosatom).","who":"Kazatomprom (state) controls all mining; but Budenovskoye's 2024-26 output is 100% committed to RUSSIA","tier":"documented"},{"mineral":"Uranium","stage":"process","actor":"Conversion + the enrichment chokehold","detail":"THE BOTTLENECK: Kazakhstan mines the ore but cannot enrich it. It bought conversion tech from Cameco (2020) but holds only a 10% stake in Russia's Angarsk enrichment center — access, not control. Sanctions on Russia make selling to the West hard, so Kazatomprom sits between a Russian enrichment dependency and Western buyers it struggles to reach.","who":"Russia (Rosatom) provides the enrichment Kazakhstan lacks — the dependency that defines the relationship","tier":"documented"},{"mineral":"Uranium","stage":"mid","actor":"The reactor contest — Rosatom vs CNNC","detail":"Whoever builds the reactors locks in decades of fuel dependency. After a 2024 referendum (71% yes), Kazakhstan gave the FIRST plant (Balkash/Ulken, 2 VVER-1200s, ~$14B) to Russia's ROSATOM — and the 2nd AND 3rd to China's CNNC, which underbid at ~$5.47B. This is the live Russia-vs-China contest for Central Asia's nuclear future, playing out on one country's grid.","who":"Russia (incumbent, Soviet-standard, finance) vs China (cheaper, 67% of Kazakh uranium already goes to China)","tier":"documented"},{"mineral":"Uranium","stage":"end","actor":"Reactor fuel — China, Russia, EU, Japan","detail":"~67% of China's uranium imports come from Kazakhstan; France leaned on it harder after losing Niger's ~20% share to the junta. Kazatomprom signed 2025 supply deals with Swiss Axpo, Czech ČEZ and Japan's Kansai — the multi-vector hedge. The end-buyer competition IS the geopolitics: everyone needs the fuel, and Astana sells to all sides.","who":"The multi-vector strategy — sell to China, Russia, EU and Japan at once, depend fully on none","tier":"documented"}],"patterns":["china-refine","resource-nationalism"],"history":{"roots":"Kazakhstan is the multi-vector state par excellence — a resource giant (world's #1 uranium, major oil) wedged between Russia and China, selling to everyone and belonging to no one. Independent since 1991 under Nazarbayev's three-decade personalist rule, it weathered his managed succession to Tokayev, then the January 2022 unrest that Tokayev survived with CSTO help — before distancing from Moscow once Ukraine burned. Its uranium feeds China (67% of imports), its oil crosses Russia, its enrichment happens in Russia, and its new reactors are split between Rosatom and CNNC — dependency diversified into leverage. The 2025 Subsoil Code (state stake ≥75%) is resource nationalism, Astana-style: quiet, legal, total.","timeline":[{"date":"1991","e":"Independence; Nazarbayev's three-decade rule begins; Semipalatinsk nukes renounced."},{"date":"2019","e":"Managed succession to Tokayev."},{"date":"Jan 2022","e":"'Qandy Qantar' unrest; CSTO intervention; Tokayev consolidates."},{"date":"2022-","e":"Distancing from Moscow post-invasion; Middle Corridor rises."},{"date":"2024","e":"Nuclear referendum (71% yes)."},{"date":"2025-26","e":"Rosatom gets plant #1, CNNC plants #2-3; Subsoil Code stake-floor; record uranium output committed multi-vector."}],"actors":[{"name":"Kassym-Jomart Tokayev","bio":"The career-diplomat president — survived 2022, distanced Moscow, and plays Russia, China, and the West against each other by design."},{"name":"Kazatomprom","bio":"The state uranium champion — world's #1 producer whose output and stake-floors move global prices."},{"name":"Russia (Rosatom)","bio":"The enrichment chokehold and reactor incumbent — the dependency Astana dilutes but can't drop."},{"name":"China (CNNC)","bio":"The rising buyer-builder — 67% of Kazakh uranium and two of three new plants; the eastern vector winning share."}],"bridge":"Kazakhstan's multi-vector method is the small-state answer to the platform's biggest pattern: sitting on the resource (uranium #1) while lacking the midstream (enrichment), it converts dependency into auction — Rosatom's plant against CNNC's two, Western utilities against Chinese offtake, the Subsoil Code's 75% floor as the house's rake. Cooley and Heathershaw's 'dictators without borders' frame adds the caveat: the same statecraft that hedges empires also exports the elite's capital and quiets its politics. January 2022 showed the model's floor; the reactor auction shows its ceiling.","sources":[{"work":"Dictators Without Borders: Power and Money in Central Asia","author":"Alexander Cooley & John Heathershaw","year":"2017","note":"The transnational political economy of Central Asian statehood."},{"work":"World Nuclear Association / Kazatomprom disclosures","author":"WNA; Kazatomprom","year":"2024-26","note":"Primary production and contract data behind this theater's uranium figures."},{"work":"Qandy Qantar (January 2022) documentation","author":"Human Rights Watch / Adilet","year":"2022","note":"The primary record of the unrest and its suppression."}]}},{"id":"balkans","cat":"political","region":"Europe","subregion":"Europe","tclass":"conflict","name":"Western Balkans — Serbia-Kosovo + Bosnia Fracture","sub":"Frozen Kosovo dispute · Republika Srpska secession threat · KFOR lid","domain":"Frozen Ethno-Territorial Conflict","sev":"high","status":"volatile","since":"1990s (unresolved)","esc":60,"lat":43,"lon":20.5,"trend":"up","esc_history":[58,58,59,60,60,60,60,60,60,60],"cas":"Sept 2023 Banjska clash killed a Kosovo police officer; periodic incidents","disp":"Legacy displacement; parallel-institution friction in N. Kosovo","flag":"🇽🇰","note":"NEW THEATER (Phase 3 · Europe) · TWO linked flashpoints: (1) Serbia-Kosovo frozen conflict — Serbia won't recognize Kosovo; friction over 4 Serb-majority N. municipalities; police raids on Serb institutions spark protests; Sept 2023 Banjska armed incursion (killed a KP officer, equipment traced to Serbia) · (2) Bosnia — Republika Srpska's Dodik threatening secession; Crisis Group: 'national collapse may be closer than ever'; Dayton framework straining at 30 yrs · new Croatia-Albania-Kosovo military pact alarms Belgrade · Serbia rocked by anti-Vučić student protests (Novi Sad canopy collapse killed 16) · NATO KFOR cut 4,700→3,000-3,500 · Russia backs Serbia's non-recognition + hybrid info ops; EU accession stalled","leverage":[{"actor":"Serbia (Vučić)","asset":"Military buildup (regional lead); 'protect co-nationals' doctrine over Kosovo/Bosnia/Montenegro; Russia/China ties","str":"hi"},{"actor":"NATO (KFOR)","asset":"Peacekeeping force = the physical lid preventing escalation; the ultimate deterrent","str":"hi"},{"actor":"Kosovo (Kurti)","asset":"Centralizing control over the north; Croatia-Albania military pact; US/EU recognition","str":"md"},{"actor":"Russia","asset":"Backs Serbian non-recognition + Republika Srpska; hybrid info ops; blocks normalization","str":"md"},{"actor":"EU","asset":"Accession carrot (stalled) + dialogue mediation; economic interdependence","str":"md"}],"gov":[{"src":"European Commission Enlargement Report","detail":"Flagged undue political influence over Kosovo judiciary + media-freedom decline (Kosovo 99th of 180, lowest in EU-Balkans)"},{"src":"NATO/KFOR","detail":"Cut peacekeepers 4,700→3,000-3,500 citing improved north security; bolstered posture after Sept 2023 Banjska clash"},{"src":"Kosovo Specialist Chambers","detail":"War-crimes prosecutions continue (Thaçi trial) alongside national courts"}],"external":[{"actor":"🇷🇺 Russia","side":"Serbia / Rep. Srpska","flow":"Political backing for non-recognition; support for Dodik secession threats; hybrid information operations","tier":"documented","for":"Block Western Balkans EU/NATO integration; keep a foothold in Europe's soft underbelly"},{"actor":"🇺🇸 US / 🇪🇺 EU","side":"Kosovo / Bosnia integrity","flow":"KFOR (NATO); EU accession framework; Western Balkans Democracy and Prosperity Act (2026 NDAA)","tier":"documented","for":"Regional stability; complete the European integration project"},{"actor":"🇨🇳 China","side":"Serbia","flow":"Infrastructure investment + arms sales to Serbia","tier":"documented","for":"European foothold; Belt-and-Road terminus"}],"mil":"A frozen conflict held down by force. The Serbia-Kosovo dispute centers on the four Serb-majority municipalities of northern Kosovo, where Pristina's assertions of authority trigger protests, barricades, and periodic armed incidents — most seriously the September 2023 Banjska clash, when heavily armed men crossed from Serbia, killed a Kosovo police officer, and left behind equipment traced back to Serbia. NATO's KFOR is the physical lid; its drawdown from 4,700 to ~3,000-3,500 is a calculated bet that the north has stabilized.","pol":"Two crises compound. In Bosnia, Republika Srpska's Milorad Dodik openly threatens secession, and Crisis Group warns national collapse may be closer than ever as the 30-year-old Dayton framework strains. In Serbia, President Vučić faces the largest protests in decades (sparked by the Novi Sad station-canopy collapse that killed 16), which he blames on Western intelligence. A new Croatia-Albania-Kosovo military pact alarms Belgrade, and EU accession has stalled across the region.","eco":"Economic interdependence and the EU accession carrot are the main non-military deterrents to escalation, but the accession timeline's ambiguity is eroding their pull — pushing Western Balkan states to 'assume greater agency' and, in Serbia's case, deeper toward Moscow and Beijing.","assess":"The Western Balkans enters at 60 (ELEVATED, conflict-class), trend up — the sharpest gap in the platform's Europe coverage now filled. It's a textbook frozen conflict: KFOR keeps the lid on while the EU dialogue stalls, and northern Kosovo remains the likeliest trigger for a flare-up, with Bosnia's Republika Srpska secession threat as a second fuse. The Russia dimension makes it part of the broader European-security contest with Ukraine. Watch the KFOR drawdown, Dodik's secession moves, and any repeat of a Banjska-style incident.","tier":"ELEVATED","hist_real":false,"as_of":"13 Jul 2026","tracked_since":"Wk13 (Jul 2026)","domain_tag":"Political","econlev":[{"holder":"EU","channel":"Accession + funding","exp":"MED","detail":"The accession carrot is the main non-military deterrent — but its stalling is pushing Serbia toward Moscow and Beijing"}],"contested":{"summary":"A frozen conflict kept warm by an information campaign.","claims":[{"claim":"Serbia denies involvement in the Banjska incursion.","who":"Belgrade — direct attribution would trigger EU/NATO consequences.","evid":"Equipment left at the scene was traced back to Serbia. A Kosovo police officer was killed.","status":"DOCUMENTED-BUT-DENIED"},{"claim":"Vučić blames the mass protests on Western intelligence services.","who":"Vučić — externalizing a domestic legitimacy crisis (the Novi Sad canopy collapse killed 16).","evid":"No evidence presented. The protests are the largest in decades and have a clear domestic trigger.","status":"UNSUPPORTED"}]},"history":{"roots":"The Balkans carry Europe's unfinished 1990s. Yugoslavia's wars ended in externally-imposed frameworks — Dayton for Bosnia, UNSCR 1244 then supervised independence for Kosovo — that froze conflicts rather than resolving them. Serbia never accepted Kosovo's statehood; Republika Srpska's Dodik works Dayton's seams toward secession; and Russia sponsors both revisionisms as cheap leverage against EU enlargement. The 2020s brought the sharpest tests since the wars: the 2023 Banjska attack in north Kosovo, Dodik's separation laws, and Serbia's massive student-led protest movement shaking Vučić's rule from below. The region's question is whether the EU's gravitational pull outlasts the spoilers' patience.","timeline":[{"date":"1991-99","e":"Yugoslav wars: Croatia, Bosnia (Srebrenica), Kosovo — ~130,000 dead."},{"date":"1995","e":"Dayton freezes Bosnia into two entities — the seams Dodik works."},{"date":"2008","e":"Kosovo declares independence; Serbia + Russia never accept it."},{"date":"2023","e":"Banjska attack — armed Serb incursion in north Kosovo."},{"date":"2024-26","e":"Dodik's secession laws vs state crackdown on him; Serbia's student protests vs Vučić; Russian info-ops back both revisionisms."}],"actors":[{"name":"Aleksandar Vučić","bio":"Serbia's dominant figure — balancing EU accession theater, Russian ties, and the largest protests of his rule."},{"name":"Milorad Dodik","bio":"Republika Srpska's secessionist — convicted, defiant, and Russia's most useful man in Bosnia."},{"name":"Kosovo (Kurti)","bio":"Pressing sovereignty in the Serb-majority north; the Banjska aftermath defines the standoff."},{"name":"Russia / EU","bio":"The spoiler and the anchor — Moscow's cheap leverage against Brussels' slow enlargement."}],"bridge":"The Balkans' 2026 is Dayton's arithmetic reaching its limits: Dodik works the entity seam toward secession while Serbia's streets work Vučić's legitimacy from below — the two pressures Bieber's authoritarian-stabilitocracy model predicted would eventually collide. Russia sponsors the revisionists cheaply; the EU's gravitational pull weakens with every postponed accession. Banjska showed the hardware exists for a Kosovo escalation; the platform's read is that the region's risk is not a new 1990s but a slow secession-by-procedure that tests whether externally imposed settlements can outlive their guarantors' attention.","sources":[{"work":"The Rise of Authoritarianism in the Western Balkans","author":"Florian Bieber","year":"2020","note":"The 'stabilitocracy' model — EU-tolerated strongmen as the region's operating system."},{"work":"ICTY judgments and archives","author":"UN ICTY/IRMCT","year":"1993-2017","note":"The primary adjudicated record of the 1990s wars — the baseline every revisionism contests."},{"work":"The Balkans: Nationalism, War, and the Great Powers","author":"Misha Glenny","year":"1999 (rev. 2012)","note":"The long-arc survey of external-power entanglement."}]}},{"id":"caucasus","cat":"strategic","region":"South Caucasus","subregion":"Caucasus","tclass":"watch","name":"South Caucasus — TRIPP Corridor + Russia's Retreat","sub":"US-brokered Armenia-Azerbaijan peace · Zangezur/TRIPP · Russia+Iran squeezed out","domain":"Connectivity Geopolitics / Post-Conflict Realignment","sev":"medium","status":"declining","since":"2020 war → 2025 peace","esc":45,"lat":40.2,"lon":45.5,"trend":"dn","esc_history":[48,47,46,45,45,45,45,45,45,45],"cas":"2020 war + 2023 Karabakh exodus (100k+ Armenians fled); now de-escalating","disp":"100k+ Karabakh Armenians displaced 2023 (unresolved right of return)","flag":"🇦🇲","note":"JUL 16 — Aliyev lauds Trump as 'a man of peace' crediting him with the Armenia-Azerbaijan deal (Breitbart interview amplified on Trump's feed) — Baku cementing the Washington-brokered corridor order by flattering its broker · NEW THEATER (Phase 3 · Caucasus) · Aug 8 2025: US-brokered Armenia-Azerbaijan peace (Trump/White House; initialed) · centerpiece = TRIPP (Trump Route for Int'l Peace & Prosperity), aka Zangezur Corridor — 42km across S. Armenia linking Azerbaijan to Nakhchivan; Armenia keeps sovereignty but US gets 99-yr development rights · plugs the missing gap in the Middle Corridor (China-Europe trade bypassing Russia+Iran) · Azerbaijan lifted transit ban, sent fuel/grain to Armenia via Georgia (Q1 2026 trade ~$5.75M, historic) · OSCE Minsk Group dissolved · WINNERS: US (permanent S. Caucasus presence), Turkey (gateway), Azerbaijan · LOSERS: Russia (lost traditional ally Armenia + N-S corridor), Iran (condemned as encroachment on its border) · unresolved: Karabakh Armenian right of return; Armenia constitution territorial-claim clause","leverage":[{"actor":"United States","asset":"99-yr TRIPP development rights = permanent S. Caucasus foothold at Russia's southern door + Iran-influence lever","str":"hi"},{"actor":"Azerbaijan (Aliyev)","asset":"2020 military victory + Middle Corridor expansion; 'peace already achieved' leverage over Armenia","str":"hi"},{"actor":"Turkey","asset":"Shortest overland link to Central Asia via corridor; Caucasus gateway to the West","str":"md"},{"actor":"Armenia (Pashinyan)","asset":"Westward pivot for security after Russia failed to defend it in 2020; transit-country upside","str":"md"},{"actor":"Russia + Iran","asset":"Both squeezed — condemn TRIPP as encroachment; Russia retains Georgia leverage + N-S ambitions","str":"lo"}],"gov":[{"src":"US-brokered peace declaration (Aug 8 2025)","detail":"Trump hosted Pashinyan + Aliyev at White House; peace text initialed; TRIPP connectivity deal announced"},{"src":"US-Armenia implementation framework (Jan 2026)","detail":"Published TRIPP corridor implementation plan; rail/fiber/power/gas lines across S. Armenia"},{"src":"OSCE Minsk Group","detail":"Dissolved — confirmation there is 'no longer a Karabakh problem' in the two sides' framing"}],"econlev":[{"holder":"United States","channel":"Corridor control","exp":"HIGH","detail":"99-yr development rights over TRIPP/Zangezur — controls a key Middle Corridor link for China-Europe trade bypassing Russia+Iran"},{"holder":"Middle Corridor bloc","channel":"Trans-Caspian trade","exp":"MED","detail":"Kazakhstan-Azerbaijan-Georgia-Turkey route; TRIPP plugs the missing gap, boosting throughput off the Russia route"}],"external":[{"actor":"🇺🇸 US","side":"broker/developer","flow":"Brokered the peace; secured 99-yr exclusive TRIPP development rights via consortium","tier":"documented","for":"Permanent S. Caucasus presence; squeeze Russia+Iran; shape a China-Europe trade artery"},{"actor":"🇹🇷 Turkey","side":"Azerbaijan","flow":"Backs Azerbaijan; gains shortest overland Central Asia link; Armenia normalization track","tier":"documented","for":"Caucasus gateway role; Turkic-world connectivity"},{"actor":"🇷🇺 Russia","side":"displaced patron","flow":"Condemns TRIPP as US encroachment; lost Armenia as ally after failing to defend it in 2020","tier":"documented","for":"Salvage N-S corridor ambition + regional influence (retains Georgia leverage)"},{"actor":"🇮🇷 Iran","side":"opponent","flow":"Condemns corridor as encroachment on its northern border; threatened the project","tier":"documented","for":"Prevent being bypassed/encircled on its Armenia border"}],"mil":"The trajectory is de-escalation, not conflict — which is precisely why it's a strategic-watch theater. Three decades of Armenia-Azerbaijan war (culminating in the 2020 six-week war and the 2023 Karabakh exodus of over 100,000 Armenians) gave way to a US-brokered peace initialed in August 2025. Fears of renewed military action have receded; Aliyev now says 'peace has already been achieved.' The unresolved wound is the Karabakh Armenians' right of return, which the deal does not address.","pol":"This is a great-power realignment disguised as a peace deal. The US brokered it and secured 99-year development rights over the TRIPP/Zangezur corridor — establishing a permanent presence at Russia's southern doorstep and Iran's northern border. Armenia, abandoned by Russia in 2020, has pivoted west; Russia and Iran both condemn the corridor as encroachment. The OSCE Minsk Group's dissolution confirms the old Russian-mediated order is over.","eco":"Connectivity is the engine. TRIPP plugs the missing gap in the Trans-Caspian 'Middle Corridor,' letting goods flow from China and Central Asia through Azerbaijan into Turkey and Europe without transiting Russia or Iran. Historic first trade flows (Azerbaijani fuel and grain reaching Armenia via Georgia, ~$5.75M in Q1 2026) mark the shift from enemies to trading partners.","assess":"The South Caucasus enters at 45 (GUARDED, strategic-watch), trend down — the platform's clearest example of a de-escalating theater that still matters intensely. It earns its place not for violence but for the leverage realignment: a US-managed corridor squeezing Russia and Iran out of their own backyard, reconnecting the Middle Corridor trade route, and pulling Armenia westward. It ties to the critical-minerals/Middle-Corridor logic (Kazakhstan uranium and Caspian trade flow through here). Watch corridor construction (breaks ground 2026), the Karabakh right-of-return wound, and any Russian or Iranian move to sabotage TRIPP.","tier":"GUARDED","hist_real":false,"as_of":"16 Jul 2026","tracked_since":"Wk13 (Jul 2026)","domain_tag":"Strategic","contested":{"summary":"No significant narrative-war dimension identified in this theater at present. The main claims are broadly consistent with the evidence, or the disputes are policy disagreements rather than contested facts. This is stated affirmatively rather than left blank — the absence of an information operation is itself a finding.","claims":[]},"history":{"roots":"The South Caucasus is where three empires' borderlands became three small states with unfinished wars. Armenia and Azerbaijan fought twice over Nagorno-Karabakh (1990s; 2020) before Azerbaijan's 2023 lightning offensive emptied it of Armenians entirely — 100,000 fled in a week, ending a 35-year conflict by fait accompli. Russia's peacekeepers stood aside, discrediting Moscow's guarantee and pushing Armenia west. The 2025 Washington framework and the TRIPP/Zangezur corridor now redraw the map: a US-brokered transit route stitching Azerbaijan to Turkey through Armenia — the Middle Corridor's missing link, bypassing both Russia and Iran. The region's history of being transited is becoming its leverage.","timeline":[{"date":"1988-94","e":"First Karabakh war — Armenia takes the enclave and surroundings."},{"date":"2020","e":"Second war — Azerbaijan (Turkish drones) retakes most territory."},{"date":"Sep 2023","e":"Azerbaijan's offensive; 100,000 Armenians flee Karabakh in days."},{"date":"2024","e":"Armenia freezes CSTO membership — the break with Moscow."},{"date":"2025","e":"Washington framework + TRIPP corridor agreement."},{"date":"2026","e":"Corridor construction politics; Georgia's drift complicates the western route."}],"actors":[{"name":"Azerbaijan (Aliyev)","bio":"The victor — oil-funded, Turkish-backed, converting military victory into corridor leverage."},{"name":"Armenia (Pashinyan)","bio":"The defeated pivoting west — CSTO frozen, EU/US courted, signing the corridor its public distrusts."},{"name":"Turkey","bio":"Azerbaijan's patron ('one nation, two states') and the corridor's western terminus."},{"name":"Russia / Iran","bio":"The bypassed — both lose transit leverage to TRIPP; both retain the capacity to spoil."}],"bridge":"The TRIPP corridor is the region's history inverted: a land historically partitioned by empires for transit is now selling transit as sovereignty — Armenia signing the route its public distrusts because the alternative is irrelevance between a victorious Azerbaijan and a discredited Russian guarantee. De Waal's 'Black Garden' warning — that Karabakh's grievances outlive its map — hangs over the whole arrangement: 100,000 displaced Armenians are the settlement's unpriced liability, and the corridor's construction politics (plus Georgia's drift on the western route) decide whether the Washington framework becomes architecture or artifact.","sources":[{"work":"Black Garden: Armenia and Azerbaijan Through Peace and War","author":"Thomas de Waal","year":"2003 (rev. 2013)","note":"The definitive Karabakh account — both societies' narratives taken seriously."},{"work":"Washington framework / TRIPP agreement texts","author":"US State Department releases","year":"2025","note":"Primary documents of the corridor architecture."},{"work":"UNHCR displacement reporting on Nagorno-Karabakh","author":"UNHCR","year":"2023-24","note":"The primary record of the exodus — the settlement's human ledger."}]}},{"id":"ethiopia","cat":"military","region":"Horn of Africa","subregion":"Horn / NE Africa","tclass":"conflict","name":"Ethiopia — Tigray/Eritrea Powder Keg + Red Sea Bid","sub":"TPLF-federal clashes · Eritrea war risk · Abiy's Assab ambition · June elections","domain":"Multi-Front Conflict Risk / Regional War","sev":"high","status":"escalating","since":"2020 Tigray War","esc":72,"lat":9,"lon":38.7,"trend":"up","esc_history":[70,71,71,72,72,72,72,72,72,72],"cas":"Tigray War (2020-22) killed ~600,000; Jan 2026 Tselemti/Raya clashes renewed","disp":"5.1M displaced in 2021 (record); 1M+ refugees hosted","flag":"🇪🇹","note":"NEW THEATER (Phase 3 · Horn) · 3-way powder keg: federal govt vs TPLF/Tigray vs Eritrea, 3 yrs after the 600k-death Tigray War · Jan 2026: TDF moved into disputed Tselemti + took Alamata/Korem; federal drone strikes; Ethiopian Airlines cancelled Tigray flights · Abiy accuses Eritrea of a secret TPLF pact (tsimdo rapprochement underway) · Amhara Fano militias turned against federal govt; Oromia OLA insurgency ongoing · ABIY'S RED SEA BID: 'Red Sea and Ethiopia cannot remain separated' — eyeing Eritrea's Assab port (landlocked Ethiopia pays Djibouti ~$1.5B/yr); Somaliland Berbera MoU angered Somalia · SUDAN LINK: Abiy close to UAE (backs RSF); Eritrea sides with SAF+Egypt · Iran-war fuel shortages hampering ENDF · June 2026 elections = flashpoint (TPLF legal status unresolved)","leverage":[{"actor":"Federal govt (Abiy)","asset":"ENDF airpower/drones; controls budget subventions to Tigray; UAE backing; but stretched across Amhara/Oromia/Tigray fronts","str":"md"},{"actor":"TPLF/Tigray (TDF)","asset":"Undemobilized army; controls Tigray; disputed-territory claims (Welkait/Tselemti); possible Eritrea tsimdo","str":"md"},{"actor":"Eritrea (Isaias)","asset":"Occupies parts of W. Tigray; alleged TPLF/Fano/OLA backing; Assab port = Abiy's casus belli; SAF/Egypt axis","str":"md"},{"actor":"UAE","asset":"Key Abiy backer (weapons flights); but Iran-war + RSF-support strains vs Egypt/Saudi (pro-Eritrea)","str":"md"}],"gov":[{"src":"Crisis Group (Briefing 210, Feb 2026)","detail":"'Powder Keg in the Horn' — high war risk 3-way; urges back channels among Addis, Asmara, Mekelle"},{"src":"Pretoria Agreement brokers (Kenya/SA/Nigeria)","detail":"2022 deal fraying; TPLF never demobilized; brokers urged to re-engage before collapse"},{"src":"Ethiopia federal govt","detail":"Revoked TPLF's legal party status (May 2025); struggling to organize June 2026 Tigray elections"}],"external":[{"actor":"🇦🇪 UAE","side":"federal govt","flow":"Weapons flights to ENDF (paused briefly during Iran war, resumed); key Abiy backer","tier":"alleged-credible","for":"Horn/Red Sea influence; counterweight — but conflicts with its RSF support in Sudan"},{"actor":"🇪🇷 Eritrea","side":"anti-TPLF / anti-federal (shifting)","flow":"Occupies W. Tigray; alleged support to Fano/OLA; tsimdo rapprochement w/ Tigray vs Abiy","tier":"alleged-credible","for":"Keep Ethiopia weak/constrained; block Assab ambition"},{"actor":"🇪🇬 Egypt","side":"Eritrea axis","flow":"Aligned with Eritrea + SAF vs Ethiopia; GERD Nile-dam rivalry","tier":"documented","for":"Nile water security; contain Ethiopian regional power"}],"mil":"A three-way powder keg three years after a war that killed an estimated 600,000. In January 2026 the Tigray Defence Forces moved into the disputed Tselemti district and took Alamata and Korem, drawing federal drone strikes and flight cancellations. The federal government is simultaneously fighting Amhara Fano militias (former allies) and the Oromo Liberation Army, while accusing Eritrea of forging a secret pact with the TPLF. Crisis Group's February 2026 briefing calls it a 'powder keg' where war would be easy to start and hard to stop.","pol":"Prime Minister Abiy — a Nobel Peace laureate for the 2018 Eritrea peace — now needs a unifying cause with June 2026 elections looming, and has increasingly signaled that regaining Red Sea access could be it, eyeing Eritrea's port of Assab ('the Red Sea and Ethiopia cannot remain separated'). The TPLF's unresolved legal status is the election flashpoint: if Tigray can't vote, tensions could pass the point of no return.","eco":"Landlocked Ethiopia pays Djibouti ~$1.5B/year for port access, driving the Red Sea/Assab ambition and the Somaliland Berbera MoU that angered Somalia. The economy is under acute strain — an IMF program the government can't jeopardize, and Iran-war fuel shortages that have hampered the military itself.","assess":"Ethiopia enters at 72 (ELEVATED, conflict-class), trend up — the Horn's central powder keg, now tracked. It ties directly into the Sudan theater (Abiy-UAE-RSF vs Eritrea-SAF-Egypt), the chokepoints/Red Sea system (Assab ambition), and the external-actor web (competing Gulf patrons). The June 2026 elections and the TPLF legal-status question are the near-term fuses; the Eritrea war risk is the catastrophic tail. Watch Tselemti/Welkait, the Abiy-Isaias rhetoric, and any Assab move.","tier":"ELEVATED","hist_real":false,"as_of":"15 Jul 2026","tracked_since":"Wk13 (Jul 2026)","domain_tag":"Military","econlev":[{"holder":"Ethiopia","channel":"Port dependency / Assab ambition","exp":"HIGH","detail":"Landlocked Ethiopia pays Djibouti ~$1.5B/yr for port access — driving Abiy's Red Sea/Assab ambition and the Somaliland Berbera MoU that angered Somalia"},{"holder":"UAE","channel":"Weapons + finance","exp":"MED","detail":"Key Abiy backer (weapons flights) — the same patron arming the RSF next door; a UAE-financed RSF training camp reportedly sits in Benishangul-Gumuz near the GERD"}],"contested":{"summary":"The same patron arms both a government and the militia massacring its neighbor's people.","claims":[{"claim":"The UAE backs Abiy's government (weapons flights) while also arming the RSF next door.","who":"The UAE — a Horn/Red Sea position built on both sides of a genocide.","evid":"Weapons flights to the ENDF are credibly reported. A UAE-financed RSF training camp reportedly sits in Benishangul-Gumuz near the GERD. Egypt and Eritrea align against Ethiopia in the same contest.","status":"ALLEGED-CREDIBLE"},{"claim":"Abiy denies preparing a move on Eritrea's Assab port.","who":"Abiy — an election-year unifying cause is a powerful motive to deny until ready.","evid":"'The Red Sea and Ethiopia cannot remain separated' is his own line. Landlocked Ethiopia pays Djibouti ~$1.5B/yr. Crisis Group calls it a powder keg.","status":"CONTESTED"}]},"pipeline":[{"mineral":"Gold","stage":"mine","actor":"Lega Dembi + artisanal (Tigray/Oromia/Benishangul)","detail":"Gold is Ethiopia's top mineral export and a critical hard-currency source for a state under acute IMF strain. Much is artisanal and in conflict-affected regions (Tigray, Oromia) — extraction entangled with the multi-front war.","who":"Federal state banks the FX; artisanal output leaks through conflict zones","tier":"documented"},{"mineral":"Gold","stage":"process","actor":"National Bank purchase → reserves / export","detail":"The central bank buys artisanal gold to build FX reserves — but chronic under-pricing drives large volumes into SMUGGLING toward Gulf refiners, the same leak as Mali and Sudan. Gold is regime lifeline and leak at once.","who":"Smuggling networks route a large share to Dubai, bypassing the state","tier":"alleged-credible"},{"mineral":"Gold","stage":"end","actor":"Central-bank reserves · Gulf bullion market","detail":"Refined gold shores up reserves or vanishes into Dubai. For a government fighting on three fronts and negotiating an IMF program, the gold FX line is strategically load-bearing.","tier":"documented"},{"mineral":"Potash","stage":"mine","actor":"Danakil Depression (Afar) — Circum/others","detail":"World-class potash reserves in the Danakil. Long-stalled by infrastructure and the ~$1.5B/yr port-access problem (landlocked Ethiopia pays Djibouti), it's the resource dimension underneath Abiy's Red Sea/Assab ambition — extraction that needs a coastline Ethiopia doesn't have.","who":"The port-dependency is the bottleneck — the reason Assab is a casus belli","tier":"documented"},{"mineral":"Potash","stage":"end","actor":"Fertilizer → regional + global agriculture","detail":"If the port problem is solved, Danakil potash feeds fertilizer markets — which is why Red Sea access (Assab, Berbera MoU) is framed as existential, and why the resource question is inseparable from the Eritrea war risk.","tier":"documented"}],"patterns":["dubai-gold","water-leverage"],"history":{"roots":"Ethiopia's crises are the politics of an African empire — the only one to defeat a European coloniser at Adwa (1896) and escape the Scramble, but an empire nonetheless. Menelik II's conquests assembled the modern state by incorporating the Oromo, Somali, and southern peoples into an Amhara-dominated imperial core; every Ethiopian regime since — Haile Selassie's monarchy, the Derg's terror, the TPLF's ethnic-federal EPRDF, Abiy's centralizing 'Medemer' — has been an answer to the question that conquest posed: whose state is this? Ethnic federalism (1995) wrote the nations into the constitution without resolving their relationship to the center; Bahru Zewde's history shows each settlement redistributing, never dissolving, the imperial question. Eritrea's secession (1993) — after Africa's longest liberation war — took the coastline, adding the landlocked condition that now drives Abiy's Red Sea revisionism. The Tigray war (~600,000 dead, one of this century's deadliest anywhere) was the ethnic-federal question turned total.","timeline":[{"date":"1991","e":"TPLF-led rebels topple the Derg; ethnic federalism installed."},{"date":"1993","e":"Eritrea secedes, leaving Ethiopia landlocked."},{"date":"1998-2000","e":"Ethiopia-Eritrea border war (~100,000 dead)."},{"date":"2018","e":"Abiy Ahmed becomes PM, sidelines the TPLF, makes peace with Eritrea (wins a Nobel)."},{"date":"2020-22","e":"Tigray war — one of the century's deadliest (~600,000 dead)."},{"date":"2022","e":"Pretoria truce pauses the Tigray war."},{"date":"2023-25","e":"Amhara Fano insurgency; Abiy's Red Sea/Assab push alarms Eritrea."},{"date":"2026","e":"TPLF-federal tensions and Eritrea war-risk reconverge; June election a flashpoint."}],"actors":[{"name":"Abiy Ahmed","bio":"PM since 2018; Nobel laureate turned wartime leader. Centralizer pursuing Red Sea access, at odds with Tigray, the Amhara, and Eritrea."},{"name":"TPLF","bio":"The formerly dominant Tigrayan party; fought the 2020-22 war and remains in uneasy standoff with Addis."},{"name":"Eritrea (Isaias Afwerki)","bio":"Abiy's 2018 peace partner turned likely adversary; the Red Sea ambition puts them on a collision course."},{"name":"Amhara Fano","bio":"An ethnic-Amhara militia-turned-insurgency, once allied with the federal army, now fighting it."}],"bridge":"Every live Ethiopian fault line today is the imperial question unresolved: TPLF-federal standoff (which nation holds the center), the Amhara Fano insurgency (the old core demoted), Oromo insurgency (the largest nation still peripheral), and the Assab obsession (the empire's lost sea). The GERD dam — the greatest pan-Ethiopian project since Adwa — is simultaneously the state's unifying myth and the trigger for Egypt's shadow war via Fano support. Abiy's June 2026 election and the Eritrea war-risk are not new stories; they are the 1896 empire still negotiating its own composition, now with drones.","sources":[{"work":"A History of Modern Ethiopia, 1855–1991","author":"Bahru Zewde","year":"2001","note":"The standard history by Ethiopia's foremost historian — empire-building, Adwa, and the successive settlements of the national question."},{"work":"The Ethiopian Revolution: War in the Horn of Africa","author":"Gebru Tareke","year":"2009","note":"The Derg era and the armed movements (TPLF, EPLF) whose victory built the 1991 order now unraveling."},{"work":"The Struggle for Eritrea's Independence","author":"Ruth Iyob","year":"1995","note":"Africa's longest liberation war and the secession that landlocked Ethiopia — the root of the Assab question."},{"work":"War and Famine reporting / Tigray documentation","author":"Ghent University (Jan Nyssen et al.) & Ethiopia Peace Observatory (ACLED)","year":"2020-26","note":"Primary casualty and atrocity documentation for the Tigray war and current Fano/Oromo conflicts."}]},"human":{"dead":600000,"disp":4000000,"famine":false,"aid":"partial","note":"Tigray war ~600k (AU-cited estimate) is the century's deadliest single war; current Fano/Oromo conflicts add displacement across Amhara/Oromia."}},{"id":"mozambique","cat":"energy","region":"Southern Africa","subregion":"Southern Africa","tclass":"conflict","name":"Mozambique — Cabo Delgado Gas Insurgency","sub":"ISIS-linked insurgency · $20B TotalEnergies LNG restart · Rwandan troops","domain":"Resource Insurgency / Extraction Conflict","sev":"high","status":"active","since":"2017","esc":63,"lat":-12.3,"lon":40.5,"trend":"up","esc_history":[61,62,62,63,63,63,63,63,63,63],"cas":"6,400+ killed since 2017 (ACLED); 2021 Palma attack killed ~800","disp":"1.3M+ displaced from Cabo Delgado","flag":"🇲🇿","note":"NEW THEATER (Phase 3 · S. Africa) · ISIS-linked insurgency (local 'Al-Shabaab', unrelated to Somalia's) in gas-rich Cabo Delgado since 2017 — triggered by gas discovery + extraction locals feel excluded from · Jan 2026: TotalEnergies RESTARTED its $20B LNG project (force majeure lifted after 2021 Palma attack froze it ~40% built); first gas 2029; could make Mozambique a top-10 gas producer (20% of African output by 2040) · Rwandan troops (from 2021) + SADC secured the Afungi enclave after Wagner failed · insurgency persists in the north (beheadings, kidnappings); 'closed enclave' model exposes communities · ExxonMobil $30B Rovuma + ENI Coral also developing · UK+Netherlands withdrew financing Dec 2025; TotalEnergies facing French war-crimes-complicity + GBV complaints","leverage":[{"actor":"TotalEnergies + majors","asset":"$20B (Total) + $30B (Exxon Rovuma) + ENI — capital that makes Cabo Delgado strategic; enclave security","str":"hi"},{"actor":"Mozambique govt (Chapo)","asset":"Gas revenue prize (top-10 producer potential); but pressured to fund project security at its own cost","str":"md"},{"actor":"Rwanda","asset":"Troops securing Afungi = the enabler of the restart; extradition-treaty + influence payback","str":"md"},{"actor":"ISIS-linked insurgents","asset":"Persistent rural violence; can threaten (not stop) the project; feeds on extraction grievance","str":"md"}],"gov":[{"src":"ACLED","detail":"6,400+ killed since 2017; insurgency persists despite military interventions; 'failed military strategy'"},{"src":"UN report 'Voices of Mozambique' (Jun 2026)","detail":"Documents GBV by Mozambican military + Al-Shabaab; coercion by TotalEnergies-linked staff"},{"src":"UK UKEF / Netherlands","detail":"Withdrew ~$1.15B+ project financing Dec 2025 over security/human-rights concerns"}],"econlev":[{"holder":"Western majors (Total/Exxon/ENI)","channel":"LNG megaprojects","exp":"HIGH","detail":"$50B+ combined; Mozambique could supply 20% of African gas by 2040 — Europe/Asia energy-security prize driving the security calculus"},{"holder":"Rwanda","channel":"Security provision","exp":"MED","detail":"Troops securing the enclave = leverage over Mozambique + the majors; extradition/influence payback"}],"external":[{"actor":"🇷🇼 Rwanda","side":"govt/majors","flow":"~1,000+ troops securing the Afungi LNG enclave (from 2021, after Wagner failed); ongoing deployment","tier":"documented","for":"Influence, extradition treaty, standing with France/TotalEnergies + EU"},{"actor":"🇫🇷 France (TotalEnergies)","side":"extractor","flow":"$20B LNG project; funded/supported the Joint Task Force (war-crimes complicity complaint in France)","tier":"alleged-credible","for":"Gas reserves; European energy-security supply"},{"actor":"SADC","side":"govt","flow":"SAMIM multinational force (2021-) alongside Rwanda + Mozambican FADM","tier":"documented","for":"Regional stability; contain jihadist spread"}],"mil":"An ISIS-linked insurgency — the local 'Al-Shabaab,' unrelated to Somalia's — has ravaged the gas-rich Cabo Delgado province since 2017, killing over 6,400 and displacing 1.3 million. The 2021 Palma attack (roughly 800 dead) froze the LNG megaprojects. After Wagner failed, Rwandan and SADC forces secured the Afungi construction enclave, enabling the January 2026 restart, but the insurgency persists in the north with beheadings and kidnappings — a 'closed enclave' model that critics say protects the gas site while exposing surrounding communities.","pol":"The conflict is inseparable from the extraction: the insurgency was triggered in part by the gas discovery and the sense among Cabo Delgado's population — over 80% below the poverty line — that they would not benefit. TotalEnergies faces French legal proceedings including a war-crimes-complicity complaint and a UN-documented gender-based-violence report implicating project-linked staff and the Mozambican military, while the UK and Netherlands withdrew financing in December 2025.","eco":"This is a pure extraction theater. TotalEnergies' $20B project (first gas 2029), ExxonMobil's $30B Rovuma, and ENI's Coral could make Mozambique a top-10 gas producer supplying 20% of African output by 2040 — a European and Asian energy-security prize. The economics drive everything: the government is pressured to fund the project's security at its own cost, and the majors' capital is what makes an impoverished province geopolitically strategic.","assess":"Mozambique enters at 63 (ELEVATED, conflict-class), trend up — the clearest extraction-conflict case in the platform. It's the textbook expression of the framework's thesis: a resource discovery generating an insurgency, foreign troops securing the enclave, foreign majors extracting the value, and the local population bearing the cost. It ties to the critical-minerals/energy logic and the external-actor web (Rwanda, France). Watch the restart's security through construction, insurgent moves toward Palma/Afungi, and the Exxon Rovuma FID.","tier":"ELEVATED","hist_real":false,"as_of":"13 Jul 2026","tracked_since":"Wk13 (Jul 2026)","domain_tag":"Energy","contested":{"summary":"The gas restarted. The insurgency didn't stop. Only the enclave is safe.","claims":[{"claim":"TotalEnergies frames the LNG restart as evidence that security has been restored.","who":"TotalEnergies ($20B), the majors behind Rovuma and Coral, and a government that needs the revenue.","evid":"The Afungi ENCLAVE is secured by Rwandan and SADC troops. The insurgency persists in the north — beheadings, kidnappings continue. UK and Netherlands WITHDREW financing (Dec 2025) over security and human-rights concerns. A UN report documents GBV by the military and project-linked staff; TotalEnergies faces a French war-crimes-complicity complaint.","status":"CONTESTED — 'secure' describes the perimeter, not the province"}]},"pipeline":[{"mineral":"Natural Gas","stage":"mine","actor":"Rovuma Basin, Cabo Delgado (offshore)","detail":"World-class offshore gas discovered 2010 — the discovery that triggered the ISIS-linked insurgency, because a population 80%+ below the poverty line saw no benefit. The 2021 Palma attack (~800 dead) froze everything at ~40% built.","who":"Insurgency feeds on the extraction grievance; the gas is the war's cause","tier":"documented"},{"mineral":"Natural Gas","stage":"process","actor":"Afungi LNG enclave — secured by Rwandan troops","detail":"TotalEnergies restarted its $20B project (Jan 2026, force majeure lifted) after RWANDAN + SADC troops secured the Afungi enclave (Wagner had failed). ExxonMobil's $30B Rovuma + ENI's Coral also developing. The 'closed enclave' model: protect the gas site, expose the surrounding communities.","who":"Rwanda provides enclave security = leverage over Mozambique + the majors","tier":"documented"},{"mineral":"LNG","stage":"mid","actor":"Liquefied → tankers → Europe + Asia","detail":"First gas targeted 2029. Mozambique could become a top-10 gas producer supplying 20% of African output by 2040 — a European and Asian energy-security prize. UK and Netherlands WITHDREW ~$1.15B+ financing (Dec 2025) over security/rights concerns; TotalEnergies faces a French war-crimes-complicity complaint + a UN GBV report.","who":"Western majors (Total/Exxon/ENI) capture the value; the state funds the security","tier":"documented"},{"mineral":"LNG","stage":"end","actor":"European power grids · Asian utilities","detail":"The end-buyer is Europe's post-Russia gas diversification and Asian demand. The extraction lens in full: a resource discovery generating an insurgency, foreign troops securing the enclave, foreign majors extracting, the local population bearing the cost.","tier":"documented"}],"history":{"roots":"Mozambique's gas war was written in its liberation war's own textbook. Eduardo Mondlane — the anthropologist who founded FRELIMO and was assassinated by parcel bomb in 1969 — analyzed Portuguese colonialism as pure extraction: forced cotton labor, migrant miners exported to the Rand, a colony run to service others' economies. FRELIMO won in 1975, inherited that structure, and was immediately bled by Rhodesian- then apartheid-sponsored Renamo in a destabilization war (~1 million dead) that was southern Africa's punishment for hosting the ANC and defying the settler states — a war Anglophone media long miscast as civil when its engine sat in Pretoria. Peace (1992) brought donor-darling growth that repeated the colonial geometry: megaprojects and aluminum smelters for the ledger, poverty for the province — and when Rovuma's gas was found beneath Cabo Delgado, the country's most neglected, Muslim, historically trader-cosmopolitan province, the insurgency that erupted there in 2017 recruited on exactly that exclusion, whatever ISIS flag it flies.","timeline":[{"date":"1975","e":"Independence from Portugal; Frelimo's one-party rule begins."},{"date":"1977-92","e":"Civil war with Renamo — ~1M dead."},{"date":"2010","e":"Rovuma Basin gas discovered — the stakes transform."},{"date":"2017","e":"Cabo Delgado insurgency begins."},{"date":"2021","e":"Palma attack (~800 dead); Total declares force majeure; Rwanda deploys."},{"date":"2024-25","e":"Disputed election; mass protests, hundreds killed."},{"date":"2026","e":"Total restarts the $20B project; UK/Dutch financing withdrawn over rights concerns; first gas targeted 2029."}],"actors":[{"name":"Frelimo (Chapo)","bio":"The 50-year ruling party — survived the ballot crisis; the gas rents are its next lease on power."},{"name":"The insurgency (ISIS-Mozambique)","bio":"The exclusion revolt in the gas province — degraded, displaced, not defeated."},{"name":"Rwanda","bio":"The enclave's guarantor — Kagame's troops protect Total's site; security export as foreign policy."},{"name":"TotalEnergies / the majors","bio":"The $50B+ bet — restarted under a war-crimes-complicity complaint and withdrawn European financing."}],"bridge":"The Total enclave — foreign troops (Rwanda's) guarding foreign capital's gas fenced off from the province that owns it — is Mondlane's diagnosis rebuilt in steel: extraction serviced, hinterland policed. The 'hidden debts' scandal (secret loans through European banks that collapsed the economy) showed the creditor circuit's continuity; the withdrawn UK/Dutch financing and the war-crimes complaint against Total show the same circuit's newer conscience. First gas in 2029 will pose the founding question a third time: does the surplus finally build Mozambique, or does Mozambique keep building others' balance sheets? The 2024 ballot crisis says the population has stopped waiting politely for the answer.","sources":[{"work":"The Struggle for Mozambique","author":"Eduardo Mondlane","year":"1969","note":"The founder's primary analysis of Portuguese extraction — the framework his successors' gas economy now tests."},{"work":"Apartheid's Contras: An Inquiry into the Roots of War in Angola and Mozambique","author":"William Minter","year":"1994","note":"The destabilization war's external engine — Rhodesia and Pretoria's sponsorship of Renamo documented."},{"work":"'Hidden debts' investigations","author":"Kroll audit / Mozambique constitutional council & US DOJ filings","year":"2017-21","note":"Primary record of the secret-loans scandal — the creditor circuit in the democratic era."},{"work":"Cabo Delgado conflict analyses","author":"Joseph Hanlon (ed., Mozambique News Reports & Clippings) / Cabo Ligado (ACLED)","year":"2017-26","note":"The running primary chronicle of the insurgency and the gas economy's collision."}]},"human":{"dead":6000,"disp":600000,"famine":false,"aid":"enclave-shadowed","note":"Cabo Delgado ~6k dead, ~600k displaced (peak 1M) — the province the \u0000B gas enclave is fenced against."}},{"id":"kashmir","cat":"military","region":"South Asia","subregion":"South Asia","tclass":"conflict","name":"India-Pakistan — Kashmir + Water War","sub":"'Armed coexistence' post-May war · Indus Treaty suspended · nuclear dyad","domain":"Nuclear Rivalry / Resource Weaponization","sev":"high","status":"volatile","since":"1947 Partition","esc":66,"lat":34,"lon":74.8,"trend":"ss","esc_history":[65,66,66,66,66,66,66,66,66,66],"hist_real":false,"as_of":"13 Jul 2026","tracked_since":"Wk14 (Jul 2026)","cas":"May 2026 4-day war killed dozens both sides; Apr 2025 Pahalgam attack killed 26; Nov 2025 Delhi bombing killed 8","disp":"Kashmir civilians bear the brunt; border-state displacement","flag":"🇮🇳","note":"NEW THEATER (Phase 3 · South Asia) · nuclear dyad in 'armed coexistence' (Crisis Group) after the most serious clash in decades · Apr 2025 Pahalgam attack (LeT offshoot, 26 killed) → India's May 2026 'Operation Sindoor' (strikes on 9 sites in Pakistan/PaK) → 4-day aerial war, dozens dead, both claimed victory · India SUSPENDED the 6-decade Indus Waters Treaty — Pakistan calls it an existential threat (Indus/Chenab/Jhelum feed its agriculture); potential permanent rupture · Nov 2025 Delhi vehicle bombing (8 dead) India labeled terror after 3 days · virtually no official contact; LoC skirmishes persist · China border (LAC) a 2nd front — mistrust since 2020 Galwan, slow normalization talks · Bangladesh's tilt to Pakistan post-Hasina adds an eastern front for India","leverage":[{"actor":"India","asset":"Upper-riparian control of the Indus system (Treaty suspension = water weapon); conventional military edge; 'Operation Sindoor' precedent","str":"hi"},{"actor":"Pakistan","asset":"Nuclear parity + LeT/proxy leverage in Kashmir; rising geopolitical standing; China alliance","str":"md"},{"actor":"China","asset":"LAC pressure = 2nd front pinning India; Pakistan's patron; CPEC through PaK","str":"md"},{"actor":"Water (Indus system)","asset":"90% of Pakistan's agriculture depends on the Indus rivers India controls upstream — the ultimate coercive lever","str":"hi"}],"gov":[{"src":"Crisis Group","detail":"India-Pakistan in 'armed coexistence' — little room for diplomacy, narrow margin for error; Kashmir conflict 'far from resolved'"},{"src":"Indus Waters Treaty (suspended 2025)","detail":"India withdrew from the 1960 World Bank-brokered treaty after Pahalgam; Pakistan calls it an act of war / existential threat"},{"src":"India MEA / Operation Sindoor (May 2026)","detail":"Struck 9 sites in Pakistan and Pakistan-administered Kashmir; most serious bilateral confrontation since 2019"}],"econlev":[{"holder":"India","channel":"Trans-boundary water","exp":"HIGH","detail":"Upper-riparian control of Indus/Chenab/Jhelum + Treaty suspension = leverage over ~90% of Pakistan's irrigated agriculture — a resource weapon short of war"}],"external":[{"actor":"🇨🇳 China","side":"Pakistan","flow":"All-weather ally; CPEC through Pakistan-administered Kashmir; LAC pressure on India as a second front","tier":"documented","for":"Contain India; secure CPEC/Belt-and-Road corridor to the Arabian Sea"},{"actor":"🇺🇸 US","side":"India (tilt)","flow":"Strategic partner vs China; but urged de-escalation in May war; Pakistan standing has risen","tier":"documented","for":"India as a China counterweight in the Indo-Pacific"}],"mil":"Two nuclear-armed states in what Crisis Group calls 'armed coexistence' — a phase with little room for diplomacy and a narrow margin for error. The 2025-26 cycle was the most dangerous in decades: the April 2025 Pahalgam massacre (26 killed by a Lashkar-e-Taiba offshoot) triggered India's May 2026 'Operation Sindoor,' strikes on nine sites in Pakistan and Pakistan-administered Kashmir, escalating into a four-day aerial war with dozens dead and both sides claiming victory. LoC skirmishes persist, and the China border (LAC) remains a simmering second front since the 2020 Galwan clash.","pol":"The most consequential shift is the weaponization of water: India suspended the six-decade Indus Waters Treaty after Pahalgam, which Pakistan — 90% dependent on the Indus system for agriculture — calls an existential threat and a potential act of war. With virtually no official contact between the two, a December 2025 handshake in Dhaka was notable as the barest sign of thaw. Regionally, the post-Hasina realignment of Bangladesh toward Pakistan opens an eastern front of concern for India.","eco":"Water is the economic weapon. Beyond the Indus leverage, the rivalry disrupts everything from cricket revenue (the India-Pakistan World Cup match moved to neutral Colombo) to regional trade, and pulls both into the US-China contest — India as a Western counterweight, Pakistan rising as China's partner.","assess":"India-Pakistan/Kashmir enters at 66 (ELEVATED, conflict-class) — a nuclear flashpoint the platform was missing. Its defining 2026 feature is the shift from territorial dispute to resource weaponization: the Indus Waters Treaty suspension is a textbook leverage move, giving upper-riparian India a coercive water lever over Pakistan's agriculture short of war. It ties to the Pakistan-Afghanistan theater and the China rivalry. Watch the Treaty status (permanent rupture would be a major escalation), any repeat militant attack, and LoC/LAC flare-ups. Trend estimate — newly entered tracking.","tier":"ELEVATED","domain_tag":"Military","contested":{"summary":"Two nuclear powers each own a truth about Kashmir and deny the other's entirely.","claims":[{"claim":"Kashmir is an integral, settled part of India ('atoot ang'); Article 370's abrogation normalized it; militancy is purely Pakistan-sponsored terrorism.","who":"New Delhi — the framing that forecloses negotiation and internationalization.","evid":"Militancy has genuine cross-border sponsorship (documented) AND indigenous alienation (documented — communications blackouts, detentions, demographic anxieties post-2019). Both realities coexist; each capital's narrative admits only one.","status":"CONTESTED — sponsored terror vs indigenous grievance, both real"},{"claim":"India stages false-flag attacks to justify strikes on Pakistan.","who":"Islamabad — deployed after every major attack (Pulwama, Pahalgam) to deflect sponsorship evidence.","evid":"No credible evidence supports the false-flag claims; investigations have traced major attacks to Pakistan-based groups. But the claim persists because prior Indian information operations (EU DisinfoLab findings) damaged New Delhi's credibility as a narrator.","status":"DEBUNKED claim sustained by the accuser's own credibility deficit"}]},"history":{"roots":"Kashmir is the wound of Partition that two nuclear arsenals now guard. In 1947 the Hindu maharaja of a Muslim-majority princely state acceded to India under invasion; Pakistan never accepted it, and the two states have fought three wars and a permanent proxy conflict over the line since. India's 2019 revocation of Article 370 (Kashmir's autonomy) hardened the map; Pakistan's sponsorship of militant groups sustains the fire; and the 2025 Pahalgam attack triggered the worst crisis in decades — strikes, a shot-down-jets air battle, and India suspending the Indus Waters Treaty, weaponizing water for the first time. Two doctrines now grind: India's 'new normal' of retaliation, Pakistan's nuclear shadow.","timeline":[{"date":"1947","e":"Partition; the maharaja accedes under invasion — the dispute is born."},{"date":"1947/1965/1999","e":"Three wars over the line."},{"date":"1989","e":"Insurgency era begins — indigenous + Pakistan-sponsored."},{"date":"2019","e":"Pulwama attack → Balakot strikes; Article 370 revoked."},{"date":"Apr 2025","e":"Pahalgam massacre → Operation Sindoor: strikes, air battle, IWT suspended."},{"date":"2026","e":"Gulf-brokered calm holds uneasily; water leverage remains on the table."}],"actors":[{"name":"India (Modi)","bio":"The status-quo-plus power — integration policy, retaliation doctrine, and now water leverage via the suspended treaty."},{"name":"Pakistan (army/ISI)","bio":"The revisionist sponsor — militant proxies as strategy, the nuclear umbrella as insurance, now axis-embedded."},{"name":"Kashmiris","bio":"The population both narratives claim and neither consults — alienation is the insurgency's renewable fuel."},{"name":"China","bio":"The third claimant (Aksai Chin) and Pakistan's patron — the trilateral dimension every crisis carries."}],"bridge":"The Indus suspension is the conflict's rubicon: Bose's structural read — that Kashmir is a sovereignty dispute layered on a democracy deficit — now carries a hydrological weapon on top, and Noorani's constitutional archive shows why 2019's revocation forecloses the federal solutions every earlier framework assumed. The Gulf-brokered calm holds because both arsenals make the alternative unusable, not because anything is settled; the platform reads every Pahalgam-type incident as a test of whether the 'new normal' retaliation doctrine and the nuclear shadow can keep coexisting.","sources":[{"work":"Kashmir: Roots of Conflict, Paths to Peace","author":"Sumantra Bose","year":"2003","note":"The standard structural account — sovereignty dispute plus democracy deficit."},{"work":"Article 370: A Constitutional History of Jammu and Kashmir","author":"A.G. Noorani","year":"2011","note":"The Indian constitutional scholar's documentary record of the autonomy the 2019 revocation ended."},{"work":"Indus Waters Treaty","author":"World Bank-brokered treaty text","year":"1960","note":"The primary text of the water architecture now suspended."}]},"patterns":["water-leverage"]},{"id":"bangladesh","cat":"political","region":"South Asia","subregion":"South Asia","tclass":"watch","name":"Bangladesh — Post-Hasina Realignment","sub":"Feb 2026 elections · Hasina death sentence · India-out, Pakistan-in tilt","domain":"Political Transition / Regional Realignment","sev":"medium","status":"volatile","since":"2024 (Hasina ouster)","esc":50,"lat":23.8,"lon":90.4,"trend":"up","esc_history":[49,49,50,50,50,50,50,50,50,50],"hist_real":false,"as_of":"13 Jul 2026","tracked_since":"Wk14 (Jul 2026)","cas":"2024 uprising killed ~1,000; anti-minority (Hindu) violence spikes; political-transition unrest","disp":"Rohingya camps (~1M) persist; minority displacement pressure","flag":"🇧🇩","note":"NEW THEATER (Phase 3 · South Asia) · Yunus interim govt after 2024 ouster of India-ally Sheikh Hasina · Feb 2026 nationwide elections (Awami League gone; antagonistic-to-India parties lead) · Hasina sentenced to DEATH in absentia (Int'l Crimes Tribunal, crimes against humanity); India refuses extradition — a running India-Bangladesh rupture · Dhaka rapprochement with PAKISTAN (Jaishankar handshake at Khaleda Zia funeral = rare thaw signal) · India intensifying deportation of undocumented Bangladeshis; border 'push-in' friction (BGB vs BSF) · far-right Islamist groups emboldened; anti-Hindu violence → protests in India · ~1M Rohingya still in camps","leverage":[{"actor":"Bangladesh interim/elected govt","asset":"Pivot away from India toward Pakistan/China; Hasina extradition demand; border-migration leverage","str":"md"},{"actor":"India","asset":"Hosts Hasina (extradition refusal); upper hand on trade/border/water; deportation pressure","str":"md"},{"actor":"Pakistan","asset":"Rapprochement with Dhaka = strategic gain vs India on its eastern flank","str":"md"},{"actor":"China","asset":"Investment + BRI courtship of the post-Hasina government","str":"md"}],"gov":[{"src":"Bangladesh Int'l Crimes Tribunal","detail":"Sentenced ex-PM Sheikh Hasina to death in absentia for crimes against humanity (2024 crackdown)"},{"src":"Crisis Group","detail":"Suspicion lingers between Dhaka and New Delhi post-Hasina; Feb 2026 elections a chance to reset or deepen the rupture"}],"external":[{"actor":"🇵🇰 Pakistan","side":"interim govt","flow":"Diplomatic rapprochement (rare public thaw); alignment vs shared India antagonism","tier":"documented","for":"Strategic depth on India's eastern flank"},{"actor":"🇮🇳 India","side":"anti-interim / pro-Hasina","flow":"Shelters Hasina; refuses extradition; deportation crackdown on Bangladeshis; border push-ins","tier":"documented","for":"Restore a friendly Dhaka; secure the eastern border"},{"actor":"🇨🇳 China","side":"interim govt","flow":"Investment + BRI courtship of the new government","tier":"alleged-credible","for":"Fill the vacuum left by India's lost influence"}],"mil":"Not a kinetic theater — a political-transition and realignment watch. The violence dimension is domestic and communal: the 2024 uprising that ousted Sheikh Hasina killed roughly 1,000, and anti-minority (Hindu) violence has spiked, spilling into protests and diplomatic friction with India. Border 'push-in' incidents between Bangladesh's BGB and India's BSF are the main interstate friction.","pol":"Bangladesh's realignment is the strategic story. The ouster of India-ally Hasina, her in-absentia death sentence, and India's refusal to extradite her have ruptured a once-close relationship — while Dhaka's interim government (and the parties leading the February 2026 elections) tilt toward Pakistan and China. A Jaishankar-Pakistan handshake at a Dhaka funeral was a rare thaw signal in an otherwise antagonistic regional picture.","eco":"India retains economic leverage (trade, border, shared rivers) and is using deportation of undocumented Bangladeshis as pressure, while China courts the new government with investment. The ~1M Rohingya in camps remain a standing humanitarian and security burden.","assess":"Bangladesh enters at 50 (GUARDED, strategic-watch), trend up — a realignment theater that matters for how it reshapes South Asian alignments. The post-Hasina tilt away from India toward Pakistan and China alters the regional balance and gives India a second front of concern alongside Kashmir. It ties to the Kashmir theater and the displacement system (Rohingya). Watch the February 2026 election outcome, the Hasina extradition standoff, and India-Bangladesh border friction. Trend estimate — newly entered tracking.","tier":"GUARDED","domain_tag":"Political","econlev":[{"holder":"India","channel":"Trade + border + water","exp":"MED","detail":"Retains trade/border/river leverage; using deportation of undocumented Bangladeshis as pressure on the post-Hasina government"}],"contested":{"summary":"No significant narrative-war dimension identified in this theater at present. The main claims are broadly consistent with the evidence, or the disputes are policy disagreements rather than contested facts. This is stated affirmatively rather than left blank — the absence of an information operation is itself a finding.","claims":[]},"history":{"roots":"Bangladesh was born twice — in the 1971 liberation war's bloodbath, and again in the 2024 student revolution that ended Sheikh Hasina's 15-year rule. The world's most densely populated large country built an export-garment economy that lifted millions while its politics stayed a two-dynasty blood feud (Hasina's Awami League vs the BNP). Hasina's escalating autocracy fell to five weeks of student protests (~1,400 killed); Nobel laureate Muhammad Yunus took over an interim government facing an impossible brief: try the old regime, calm the streets, hold elections, manage a million Rohingya refugees, and rebalance between India (Hasina's shelter) and a courting China and Pakistan.","timeline":[{"date":"1971","e":"Liberation war from Pakistan — up to 3M dead; the founding trauma."},{"date":"1975","e":"Mujib assassinated — the dynastic feud begins."},{"date":"2009-24","e":"Hasina's 15-year rule: growth, then autocracy."},{"date":"2017","e":"~700k Rohingya flee Myanmar into Cox's Bazar."},{"date":"Aug 2024","e":"Student revolution ousts Hasina (~1,400 killed); Yunus interim government."},{"date":"2025-26","e":"Hasina tried and convicted in absentia; election timeline contested; India-Dhaka friction over her extradition."}],"actors":[{"name":"Muhammad Yunus","bio":"The Nobel-laureate interim leader — legitimacy without a party, running a transition everyone contests."},{"name":"Sheikh Hasina (exiled)","bio":"The ousted ruler in India — convicted in absentia; her extradition is the India-Bangladesh fault line."},{"name":"The student movement / new parties","bio":"The revolution's owners — impatient with the transition they created."},{"name":"India vs China/Pakistan","bio":"Delhi lost its client; Beijing and Islamabad court the successor — the strategic realignment beneath the transition."}],"bridge":"The 2024 revolution reopened 1971's unfinished accounts all at once: Raghavan's point that Bangladesh's birth was an international event — decided as much in Washington, Moscow and Delhi as in Dhaka — reruns in the transition, with India sheltering Hasina, China and Pakistan courting Yunus, and the trials adjudicating the old regime under the world's gaze. The student movement's impatience is the deeper continuity: both 1971 and 2024 were made by the young against orders their elders had normalized. Whether the interim delivers elections or a new managed order decides which inheritance wins.","sources":[{"work":"1971: A Global History of the Creation of Bangladesh","author":"Srinath Raghavan","year":"2013","note":"The international making of the liberation war."},{"work":"The Blood Telegram: Nixon, Kissinger, and a Forgotten Genocide","author":"Gary J. Bass","year":"2013","note":"The primary-document account of great-power complicity in 1971."},{"work":"UN OHCHR fact-finding report on the 2024 protests","author":"UN OHCHR","year":"2025","note":"The primary casualty record (~1,400) of the revolution this theater's present begins from."}]}},{"id":"lakurawa","cat":"military","region":"West Africa","subregion":"Sahel Core","tclass":"conflict","name":"Lakurawa — NW Nigeria Tri-Border Insurgency","sub":"Nigeria-Niger-Benin tri-border · US airstrikes Dec 2025 · 162 killed in Kwara Feb 2026","domain":"Hybrid Jihadist-Criminal Insurgency","sev":"high","status":"escalating","since":"2018 (terror label 2024)","esc":74,"lat":13.1,"lon":5.2,"trend":"up","esc_history":[66,68,70,71,72,73,74,74,74,74],"hist_real":false,"as_of":"13 Jul 2026","tracked_since":"Wk14 (Jul 2026)","cas":"250+ killed 2024-25 (ACLED/Amnesty); 162 killed in Woro & Nuku, Kwara State (Feb 4 2026)","disp":"Communities displaced across ~500 villages in Sokoto/Kebbi; conversion of settlements to camps","flag":"🇳🇬","note":"NEW THEATER (Phase 3 · Sahel) · hybrid jihadist-criminal group in the Nigeria-Niger-Benin tri-border (Sokoto, Kebbi + expanding to Niger State's Borgu axis + Kwara) · origin: emerged ~2017-18 from a merger of Malian Macina/JNIM-linked Fulani fighters + a Nigerien herder self-defense faction; invited by communities to fight bandits, then turned predatory · declared a terrorist group by Nigeria (Nov 2024/Jan 2025) · US AIRSTRIKES Dec 25 2025 (Trump-announced, Tinubu-approved) on Sokoto/Bauni Forest camps — 'ISIS terrorist scum' · Feb 4 2026: massacred 162 civilians in Woro & Nuku (Kwara) after villagers refused to let them preach · governance model = extortion/'zakat' taxation, livestock confiscation, forced religious code, suppression of rival vigilantes · leader Amir Tajudeen moves between Nigeria/Niger/Mali/Chad · ISS: cooperates with Boko Haram/JAS + ISSP/ISWAP as a 'strategic conduit'; Niger post-2023-coup tension blocks joint ops","leverage":[{"actor":"Lakurawa","asset":"Tri-border sanctuary (ungoverned Nigeria-Niger-Benin space); embedded governance over ~500 villages; Sahel reinforcement pipeline","str":"md"},{"actor":"Nigeria (Op Fansan Yamma)","asset":"Air force + JTF North West offensives; US airstrike backing; but overstretched vs Boko Haram/ISWAP/bandits","str":"md"},{"actor":"United States","asset":"AFRICOM airstrikes (Dec 2025) — signaling willingness to hit NW Nigeria directly; intel/ISR","str":"md"},{"actor":"ISSP / ISWAP / JNIM","asset":"Lakurawa as a conduit linking Sahel IS/AQ franchises toward the Nigerian littoral","str":"md"}],"gov":[{"src":"Nigerian military (Op Fansan Yamma)","detail":"Declared Lakurawa terrorist (Jan 2025); Dec 2025 Borgu camp strike killed 46 fighters; ongoing Sokoto/Kebbi/Niger air + ground ops"},{"src":"US AFRICOM / White House","detail":"Dec 25 2025 airstrikes on Sokoto camps (Trump-announced, Tinubu-approved); Feb 2026 US military team deployment confirmed"},{"src":"ACLED / Amnesty International","detail":"Attributed 250+ deaths to Lakurawa across 2024-25; documented mass-casualty village raids"}],"external":[{"actor":"🇺🇸 US","side":"Nigeria (counter-terror)","flow":"AFRICOM airstrikes on Lakurawa camps (Dec 2025); military advisory team deployment (Feb 2026)","tier":"documented","for":"Prevent IS-Sahel expansion toward strategic infrastructure + the littoral"},{"actor":"🏴 ISSP / ISWAP","side":"Lakurawa (aligned)","flow":"Ideological alignment + reinforcement pipeline from the central Sahel; operating 'under the Lakurawa label'","tier":"alleged-credible","for":"Extend Islamic State's reach from the Sahel toward coastal West Africa"},{"actor":"🏴 JNIM / Boko Haram (JAS)","side":"Lakurawa (cooperative)","flow":"Origin ties (Macina/JNIM) + operational cooperation with Boko Haram's JAS faction; fighter exchange from 2023","tier":"alleged-credible","for":"Cross-network logistics, sanctuary, and recruitment"}],"mil":"Lakurawa is a hybrid jihadist-criminal insurgency in the Nigeria-Niger-Benin tri-border, distinct from the Boko Haram/ISWAP conflict in the northeast. It emerged around 2017-18 from a merger of Malian Macina/JNIM-linked Fulani fighters and a Nigerien herder self-defense faction, was invited by Sokoto communities to fight bandits, then turned predatory. After Nigeria declared it a terrorist group, the violence escalated sharply: the US conducted airstrikes on its Sokoto camps on Christmas Day 2025, and in February 2026 the group massacred 162 civilians in the Kwara villages of Woro and Nuku after residents refused to let it preach. It has expanded south into Niger State's Borgu axis, where its operational leadership is now reportedly based.","pol":"The group governs where the state is absent — imposing 'zakat' taxation, confiscating livestock, enforcing a rigid religious code, and suppressing rival vigilante groups across roughly 500 villages. This coercive governance-through-extraction is the core of its model. Nigerian counter-operations (Operation Fansan Yamma) intensified from late 2025, but tension with Niger since its 2023 coup blocks the cross-border cooperation needed to defeat a group whose leader, Amir Tajudeen, moves freely between Nigeria, Niger, Mali, and Chad.","eco":"Lakurawa funds itself through the extraction it frames as religious obligation — taxation, extortion, livestock and produce confiscation, and high-value kidnapping (the Kebbi deputy speaker was ransomed for ~$140,600, partly in CFA francs, showing its cross-border reach). This crime-terror nexus makes it financially self-sustaining and less dependent on external patrons than the Sahel's larger franchises.","assess":"Lakurawa enters at 74 (ELEVATED, conflict-class), trend up — a distinct and rising Sahel threat the platform needed to break out from the broader Nigeria picture. Its significance is structural: it functions as a conduit linking the central Sahel's IS and al-Qaeda franchises (ISSP, JNIM) toward the Nigerian littoral and the Gulf of Guinea, threatening to connect the Sahel and Lake Chad theaters. The Christmas 2025 US airstrikes mark a notable escalation of direct American involvement in northwest Nigeria. It ties to the Nigeria, Niger, and Benin-Togo theaters and the Sahel security-vacuum dynamic. Watch the Borgu/Kwara southward expansion, the pace of Sahel reinforcement, and Nigeria-Niger cooperation. Trend estimate — newly entered tracking.","tier":"ELEVATED","domain_tag":"Military","econlev":[{"holder":"Lakurawa","channel":"'Zakat' taxation + livestock","exp":"HIGH","detail":"Governance-through-extraction across ~500 villages: coercive zakat, livestock confiscation, produce seizure; high-value kidnapping (Kebbi deputy speaker ~$140,600, partly in CFA francs) — self-financing, not patron-dependent"}],"contested":{"summary":"No significant narrative-war dimension identified in this theater at present. The main claims are broadly consistent with the evidence, or the disputes are policy disagreements rather than contested facts. This is stated affirmatively rather than left blank — the absence of an information operation is itself a finding.","claims":[]},"history":{"roots":"Lakurawa is new; the conditions that made it are not. Nigeria's northwest was the heart of the Sokoto Caliphate — Usman dan Fodio's 1804 jihad built one of precolonial Africa's largest states, a literate, administered polity whose emirate structures Britain then ruled through (indirect rule's original template, as Mamdani shows, hardening 'native authority' into decentralized despotism). Colonial and post-colonial neglect left the rural northwest with the country's deepest poverty and thinnest state presence; the bandit economy of the 2010s — mass kidnapping, cattle rustling, mining rackets — grew in that vacuum, and Nigerian scholar Murtala Ahmed Rufa'i's fieldwork documents how communities, abandoned by the state, first hired the armed men who then enslaved them. Lakurawa is that sequence's jihadist completion: Sahelian fighters invited as protectors, converting protection into governance — taxes, courts, levies — in the very country where dan Fodio's model of religious state-building is two centuries of living memory.","timeline":[{"date":"2010s","e":"Sahelian fighters drift into the Nigeria-Niger borderlands."},{"date":"~2018","e":"Local communities in Sokoto invite armed 'protectors' against bandits."},{"date":"2023","e":"Niger coup severs Nigeria-Niger security cooperation — the opening."},{"date":"Nov 2024","e":"'Lakurawa' emerges publicly; Nigerian military acknowledges the new front."},{"date":"2025-26","e":"Taxation, courts, and settlement pressure across ~500 villages in the NW tri-border; raids escalate."}],"actors":[{"name":"Lakurawa","bio":"The Sahel-origin jihadist implant in Nigeria's northwest — protection racket turned proto-governance, taxing and judging where the state doesn't reach."},{"name":"Nigerian military","bio":"Fighting a fourth front (after ISWAP, Boko Haram, bandits) with the same overstretched forces."},{"name":"The bandit economy","bio":"The northwest's mass-kidnapping industry — the labor pool and business model jihadism is absorbing."},{"name":"Niger (post-coup)","bio":"The severed partner — the border that used to be jointly policed is now the group's sanctuary line."}],"bridge":"The group's proto-governance works because it occupies a legitimacy vacuum with a familiar script: where the Nigerian state offers neither security nor justice, a tax-and-court order invoking the Sokoto inheritance finds takers — the same mechanism as al-Shabaab's courts and JNIM's zakat. The Niger coup's severing of Abuja-Niamey cooperation opened the border sanctuary; the bandit economy supplies the manpower market. Lakurawa is small, but it is the proof-of-concept that the Sahel model can be franchised into Nigeria's northwest — which is why this platform tracks it as its own theater.","sources":[{"work":"'I Am a Bandit': A Decade of Research in Zamfara State's Bandit Enclaves","author":"Murtala Ahmed Rufa'i (Usmanu Danfodiyo University, Sokoto)","year":"2021","note":"Nigerian fieldwork inside the bandit economy — the protection-to-predation sequence Lakurawa completes."},{"work":"Citizen and Subject: Contemporary Africa and the Legacy of Late Colonialism","author":"Mahmood Mamdani","year":"1996","note":"Indirect rule through the emirates — how 'native authority' became the decentralized despotism whose vacuum armed groups now fill."},{"work":"The Sokoto Caliphate","author":"Murray Last","year":"1967","note":"The dan Fodio state — the indigenous governance inheritance the region's jihadists invoke and invert."},{"work":"Nigeria conflict event data","author":"ACLED / Nigeria Security Tracker","year":"2024-26","note":"Primary tracking of Lakurawa's emergence and the NW tri-border violence."}]}},{"id":"cameroon","cat":"military","region":"Central Africa","subregion":"Central Africa","tclass":"conflict","name":"Cameroon — Twin Insurgencies + Succession Vacuum","sub":"Far North: BH/ISWAP spillover · Anglophone war · Biya (92) succession crisis","domain":"Multi-Front Insurgency / Regime Fragility","sev":"high","status":"escalating","since":"2014 (BH) / 2017 (Anglophone)","esc":69,"lat":10.6,"lon":14.3,"trend":"up","esc_history":[63,64,65,66,67,68,68,69,69,69],"hist_real":false,"as_of":"13 Jul 2026","tracked_since":"Wk15 (Jul 2026)","cas":"Q1 2026 Far North alone: 104 killed, 123 wounded, 128 abducted (OCHA); Mar 2025 Wulgo base attack killed 20 soldiers; Anglophone war ~6,000+ dead since 2017","disp":"500,000+ IDPs in Anglophone regions; 400,000+ refugees hosted (CAR/Nigeria/Chad)","flag":"🇨🇲","note":"NEW THEATER (Phase 4 · closes the Lake Chad gap) · TWIN INSURGENCIES + a succession vacuum · (1) FAR NORTH: Boko Haram/JAS + ISWAP spillover from Nigeria/Chad — Q1 2026: 104 killed, 123 wounded, 128 abducted (OCHA); raids in Mayo-Tsanaga, Mayo-Sava, Logone-et-Chari; 9 IED incidents, 2 schools + 4 health centers attacked · Mar 2025 Wulgo base attack: 20 soldiers killed, BH SEIZED ZSU-23-4 Shilka radar-guided AA guns + now uses explosive-laden DRONES · State Dept: ISWAP is the LARGEST IS affiliate in Africa · (2) ANGLOPHONE WAR (2017-): Ambazonia separatists vs govt in NW/SW; abductions, illegal taxation, roadblocks; Dec 2025-Jan 2026 attacks killed 23 (mostly women/children) in Wowo + Gidado · (3) SUCCESSION VACUUM: Biya, 92 — world's oldest head of state, in power since 1982 — won a disputed 8th term (Oct 2025); prolonged Switzerland medical absences; NO government appointed 8 months post-election; the new VP post (auto-successor) left UNFILLED; a man was arrested for trying to air a FAKE decree appointing a govt+VP · MNJTF (Nigeria-led) eroding; Niger's 2023 coup broke regional CT cooperation","leverage":[{"actor":"Boko Haram/JAS + ISWAP","asset":"Lake Chad island sanctuaries; captured Cameroonian heavy weapons (Shilka AA guns) + armed drones; cross-border mobility","str":"md"},{"actor":"Biya regime","asset":"Total executive control (appoints PM, judges, generals, governors) — but a 92-yr-old with no successor named; France/military backing","str":"md"},{"actor":"Ambazonia separatists","asset":"NW/SW territorial contest; diaspora funding; 'ghost town' shutdowns; parallel taxation","str":"md"},{"actor":"France","asset":"Foreign Legion units regionally; French firms run the offshore oil (off the Anglophone coast) — the extraction irony","str":"md"}],"gov":[{"src":"UN OCHA (Q1 2026)","detail":"Far North: 104 killed, 123 wounded, 128 abducted; 9 IED incidents; attacks on 2 schools and 4 health centres"},{"src":"US State Dept (Country Reports on Terrorism)","detail":"Identifies ISWAP as the LARGEST Islamic State affiliate in Africa; both BH and ISWAP are designated FTOs operating in Cameroon's Far North"},{"src":"Crisis Group","detail":"Biya's succession vacuum: no govt appointed 8 months after the election; VP post (automatic successor) left unfilled; Constitutional Council rejected opposition petitions"}],"econlev":[{"holder":"France / foreign majors","channel":"Offshore oil + mining","exp":"MED","detail":"Cameroon's oil lies off the ANGLOPHONE coast but French companies run the rigs — a core grievance fueling the separatist war; Douala/Kribi ports are Chad + CAR's Atlantic lifeline"}],"external":[{"actor":"🇫🇷 France","side":"Biya regime","flow":"Longstanding military/economic backing; Foreign Legion units regionally; French firms operate the offshore oil","tier":"documented","for":"Françafrique influence; energy + port access; regional stability"},{"actor":"🏴 ISWAP / Boko Haram","side":"insurgents","flow":"Cross-border operations from Nigeria/Chad/Niger; captured Cameroonian heavy weapons; drone attacks","tier":"documented","for":"Lake Chad caliphate project; taxation base expansion"},{"actor":"🇺🇸 US","side":"limited","flow":"Cut military aid + removed trade benefits over human-rights violations; $120M of $123M FY23 aid was health-only","tier":"documented","for":"Distancing from Biya's rights record while retaining CT interest"}],"mil":"Cameroon fights two wars at once. In the Far North, Boko Haram and ISWAP spill over from Nigeria and Chad — OCHA recorded 104 killed, 123 wounded, and 128 abducted in the first quarter of 2026 alone, with raids on villages, farms, fishing grounds, schools, and health centres. The capability gap is widening: in the March 2025 Wulgo attack, militants killed 20 Cameroonian soldiers and seized Soviet-made ZSU-23-4 Shilka radar-guided anti-aircraft guns, and they now deploy explosive-laden drones. In the Northwest and Southwest, the Anglophone separatist war grinds on with abductions, illegal taxation, roadblocks, and 'ghost town' shutdowns.","pol":"The deepest risk is the succession vacuum. President Paul Biya — 92 years old, the world's oldest head of state, in power since 1982 — won a disputed eighth term in October 2025 amid violent protests. He has made prolonged medical trips to Switzerland, has not appointed a government eight months after the election, and has left the newly created vice-presidency (whose holder would automatically assume power in a vacancy) unfilled. A man was arrested for attempting to trick state broadcasters into airing a fake decree naming a government and VP — a signal of hidden succession struggles. Regional counter-terrorism has also frayed: the Nigeria-led MNJTF's gains have eroded, and Niger's 2023 coup broke the cooperation the Lake Chad Basin depends on.","eco":"The extraction irony sits at the heart of the Anglophone war: Cameroon's oil lies off the English-speaking coast, but French companies run the rigs — a grievance about who benefits from whose resources that helped turn a lawyers' and teachers' protest into an armed rebellion. Cameroon's Douala and Kribi ports are the Atlantic lifeline for landlocked Chad and the Central African Republic, giving it regional economic weight it cannot convert into stability.","assess":"Cameroon enters at 69 (ELEVATED, conflict-class), trend up — closing the platform's Lake Chad Basin gap, which previously covered only Nigeria and Niger while the same insurgency burned across four countries. It is the clearest case of compounding fragility: two separate insurgencies, an eroding regional CT framework, and a 92-year-old president with no named successor and an unfilled vice-presidency. The armed-groups dimension is now tracked in the Groups board (ISWAP's Lake Chad taxation empire reaches here). Watch Biya's health, any VP appointment, the Far North's weapons-capability gap (Shilkas, drones), and further MNJTF erosion.","tier":"ELEVATED","domain_tag":"Military","contested":{"summary":"No significant narrative-war dimension identified in this theater at present. The main claims are broadly consistent with the evidence, or the disputes are policy disagreements rather than contested facts. This is stated affirmatively rather than left blank — the absence of an information operation is itself a finding.","claims":[]},"history":{"roots":"Cameroon's Anglophone war began with a decolonization France ensured stayed incomplete — and a liberation war Europe erased. The UPC (Union des Populations du Cameroun), the nationalist movement demanding real independence and reunification, was banned, its leaders assassinated (Um Nyobè 1958, Moumié poisoned in Geneva 1960, Ouandié executed 1971), and its maquis crushed in a Franco-Cameroonian counterinsurgency that killed tens of thousands — a war France only officially acknowledged in 2022, after Cameroonian and French historians (Mbembe among the former) spent decades documenting it. 'Independence' was granted instead to a client regime; the Anglophone territories, a former British mandate, federated in 1961 under promises of equal standing that Yaoundé's Francophone center dismantled step by step — federation abolished 1972, common-law courts and schools Frenchified — until the 2016 lawyers' and teachers' protests met bullets and became the Ambazonia war. Biya, in power since 1982 within the same client architecture, is the arrangement's caretaker more than its author.","timeline":[{"date":"1961","e":"British and French Cameroons federate — the Anglophone bargain later broken."},{"date":"1982","e":"Paul Biya takes power — still there four decades later."},{"date":"2014-","e":"Boko Haram war reaches the Far North."},{"date":"2016-17","e":"Anglophone protests met with force; separatist war begins."},{"date":"2025","e":"Biya, 92, wins re-election amid protests and killings."},{"date":"2026","e":"Both wars grind on; the succession vacuum is the real theater."}],"actors":[{"name":"Paul Biya","bio":"President since 1982 — rules through absence, patronage, and a security state; the succession he won't arrange is the country's biggest risk."},{"name":"Ambazonia separatists","bio":"Fragmented Anglophone armed groups — school bans, kidnappings, and a war neither side can win."},{"name":"Boko Haram / ISWAP","bio":"The Lake Chad insurgency's Cameroonian front — Far North raids and forced displacement."},{"name":"France","bio":"The post-colonial patron with deep commercial stakes — quietly central to any succession outcome."}],"bridge":"The Anglophone war is the 1961 federation's broken promise collecting; the UPC's erased war is why the state answers every grievance as sedition — it was born doing so, with French doctrine and hardware. The Far North's Boko Haram front burns in the country's poorest, least-administered region, and the succession vacuum around a nonagenarian president is Françafrique's client-state model reaching its actuarial limit with no legitimate mechanism behind it. Cameroon's three crises share one root: a state whose founding bargain was with its patron, not its peoples.","sources":[{"work":"Kamerun! Une guerre cachée aux origines de la Françafrique","author":"Thomas Deltombe, Manuel Domergue & Jacob Tatsitsa","year":"2011","note":"The buried Franco-Cameroonian war against the UPC — the founding counterinsurgency, since officially acknowledged by France (2022)."},{"work":"La naissance du maquis dans le Sud-Cameroun","author":"Achille Mbembe","year":"1996","note":"Cameroon's own leading scholar on the UPC insurgency's social roots."},{"work":"Nation of Outlaws, State of Violence: Nationalism, Grassfields Tradition, and State Building in Cameroon","author":"Meredith Terretta","year":"2013","note":"The nationalist movement from below and its suppression."},{"work":"Anglophone crisis documentation","author":"Human Rights Watch / ICG Cameroon reports","year":"2017-26","note":"Primary documentation of the Ambazonia war's abuses on both sides."}]},"human":{"dead":6500,"disp":1100000,"famine":false,"aid":"obstructed NW/SW","note":"Anglophone war ~6.5k dead, ~700k displaced + Far North Boko Haram displacement."}},{"id":"somalia","cat":"military","region":"Horn of Africa","subregion":"Horn / NE Africa","tclass":"conflict","name":"Somalia — Al-Shabaab Resurgence + Security Vacuum","sub":"ATMIS withdrawal → territory retaken · ISIS-Somalia in Puntland · 2026 election crisis","domain":"Insurgency / Post-Peacekeeping Collapse","sev":"high","status":"escalating","since":"2006 (Al-Shabaab)","esc":78,"lat":2.05,"lon":45.3,"trend":"up","esc_history":[71,72,73,75,76,77,77,78,78,78],"hist_real":false,"as_of":"15 Jul 2026","tracked_since":"Wk15 (Jul 2026)","cas":"Decades of war; Al-Shabaab attacks up 70% (68→116/month) after 2022; attacks on civilians surged 306%; 900+ children recruited, 663 abducted in a single year (UN)","disp":"~3.8M internally displaced; recurrent famine risk","flag":"🇸🇴","note":"NEW THEATER (Phase 4 · Horn) · TWO SEPARATE WARS + an election crisis · (1) AL-SHABAAB (al-Qaeda's wealthiest affiliate — the benchmark JNIM is measured against): exploiting the ATMIS→AUSSOM transition vacuum. ATMIS (18,000 troops, from AMISOM 2007) completed major withdrawal mid-2025; the SNA was NOT ready. By late 2025 Al-Shabaab had RETAKEN at least 5 districts in Lower Shabelle + Middle Jubba; offensive intensified in early 2026 · attacks rose from 68→116/month (+70%) after 2022; strikes on SNA special forces (Danab/Gorgor) surged 1,764% · Mar 2025: attempted to ASSASSINATE the president with an IED on his convoy in Mogadishu · controls large rural swathes of south-central Somalia + strongholds in the northern Al-Madow mountains · (2) ISIS-SOMALIA (Puntland): a DISTINCT theater — Puntland's independent 'Hilaac' (Lightning) offensive from Dec 2024; 364 PDF operations vs ISIS through Sept 2025; US + UAE airstrikes peaked Jul-Sept 2025; conducted independently of the federal govt · Feb 2025: 1st major US military op of the new administration targeted IS-Somalia · (3) POLITICS: AUSSOM replaced ATMIS (Jan 2025, 12,626 personnel cap) but is underfunded; 2026 election crisis — Puntland+Jubaland+opposition ('Somali Future Council') reject the FGS's one-person-one-vote plan","leverage":[{"actor":"Al-Shabaab","asset":"Wealthiest AQ affiliate — extortion/taxation state; deep clan integration; intelligence penetration of the govt enabling assassinations + insider attacks","str":"hi"},{"actor":"Federal Govt (FGS)","asset":"International backing (US strikes, AUSSOM, Turkey's largest overseas base) — but no monopoly on force; depends on clan militias (Ma'awisley)","str":"lo"},{"actor":"Puntland","asset":"Autonomous military capacity — runs its own anti-ISIS campaign with US/UAE air support, independent of Mogadishu","str":"md"},{"actor":"Turkey","asset":"Largest overseas military base (Mogadishu); trains/equips Somali forces; mediated the Ethiopia-Somalia row","str":"md"},{"actor":"UAE","asset":"Puntland's longtime patron; airstrikes vs ISIS; Bosaso airport access (until Somalia cancelled UAE agreements Jan 2026 over the RSF pipeline)","str":"md"}],"gov":[{"src":"UN Panel of Experts / Crisis Group","detail":"'Al-Shabaab remains the most significant threat to peace and security in Somalia'; ICG's 'After ATMIS: Somalia's Security Vacuum' (Jan 2026) documents the drawdown-driven collapse"},{"src":"Hiraal Institute (Feb 2026)","detail":"Attacks rose 68→116/month (+70%) post-2022; attacks on civilians +306%; strikes on SNA special forces +1,764%; 364 Puntland operations vs ISIS"},{"src":"UNSC / AUSSOM","detail":"AUSSOM replaced ATMIS Jan 2025 (up to 12,626 personnel); chronically underfunded — EU committed only $8.71M in Apr 2026"}],"econlev":[{"holder":"Al-Shabaab","channel":"Taxation + extortion state","exp":"HIGH","detail":"The WEALTHIEST al-Qaeda affiliate — runs a lucrative extortion/taxation business over businesses, checkpoints, ports, and the telecoms/hawala economy. Its revenue is the benchmark against which JNIM is measured (JNIM ranks second)."},{"holder":"Turkey","channel":"Base + port/airport concessions","exp":"MED","detail":"Largest overseas Turkish base; manages Mogadishu port and airport — a foothold traded for security provision"}],"external":[{"actor":"🇺🇸 US (AFRICOM)","side":"FGS + Puntland","flow":"Airstrikes vs both Al-Shabaab and IS-Somalia; killed senior leaders (Jaafar Gurey, Oct 2025); 1st major op of the new administration targeted IS-Somalia (Feb 2025)","tier":"documented","for":"Counter-terror; Red Sea/Gulf of Aden security"},{"actor":"🇹🇷 Turkey","side":"FGS","flow":"Largest overseas military base; trains/equips Somali forces; mediated the Ethiopia-Somalia Red Sea row","tier":"documented","for":"Horn influence; port/airport concessions; arms market"},{"actor":"🇦🇪 UAE","side":"Puntland","flow":"Longtime Puntland patron; airstrikes vs IS-Somalia; Bosaso airport — but Somalia CANCELLED all bilateral UAE agreements (Jan 2026) over the RSF supply pipeline","tier":"documented","for":"Red Sea/Gulf of Aden port network — the same strategy driving its Sudan intervention"},{"actor":"🇪🇹🇰🇪 Ethiopia/Kenya","side":"FGS (AUSSOM)","flow":"Troop contributors; Ethiopia's role strained by the Red Sea/Somaliland recognition row (Turkey-mediated)","tier":"documented","for":"Border security; Ethiopia's Red Sea access ambition"}],"mil":"Two distinct wars run in parallel. In the south, al-Shabaab — al-Qaeda's wealthiest affiliate — is exploiting the security vacuum left by the ATMIS withdrawal: the 18,000-strong African Union mission drew down through mid-2025, the Somali National Army was not ready to replace it, and by late 2025 the group had retaken at least five districts in Lower Shabelle and Middle Jubba. Its attack tempo rose from 68 to 116 per month, attacks on civilians surged 306%, and strikes on Somalia's US-trained special forces jumped more than seventeenfold. In March 2025 it came close to assassinating the president with an IED on his convoy. In the north, Puntland fights a separate war against ISIS-Somalia in the Bari mountains, running its own 'Hilaac' offensive with US and UAE airstrikes — independent of Mogadishu.","pol":"The state has never re-established a monopoly on force since 1991. AUSSOM replaced ATMIS in January 2025 with a 12,626-personnel cap but is chronically underfunded (the EU committed just $8.71M in April 2026). Meanwhile the 2026 election is fracturing the federation: Puntland, Jubaland, and the opposition 'Somali Future Council' reject the federal government's one-person-one-vote plan, and the political infighting is directly undermining the counterinsurgency — Jubaland's row with Mogadishu escalated to armed conflict, precluding joint operations.","eco":"Al-Shabaab's power is fiscal. It is the wealthiest al-Qaeda affiliate in the world — the benchmark against which JNIM's ~$100M Sahel economy is measured and found second — running a taxation and extortion state over businesses, checkpoints, ports, and the hawala economy. Its intelligence network penetrates government and security institutions, and its integration with clan structures makes it nearly impossible to dislodge. Turkey, meanwhile, has converted security provision into control of Mogadishu's port and airport.","assess":"Somalia enters at 78 (SEVERE, conflict-class), trend up — and it closes the platform's most conspicuous gap: al-Shabaab is the wealthiest al-Qaeda affiliate on earth, the explicit benchmark the Groups board uses to rank JNIM, yet it was untracked. Its significance is a warning the whole board should read: this is what happens when a peacekeeping force withdraws before the state can replace it. Territory declared 'liberated' was retaken within months. It also completes the UAE picture — Abu Dhabi patronizes Puntland for the same Red Sea port-network reasons it arms the RSF in Sudan, and Somalia cancelled its UAE agreements in January 2026 precisely over that pipeline. Watch the AUSSOM funding gap, the 2026 election fracture, and further al-Shabaab district seizures. Trend estimate — newly entered tracking.","tier":"SEVERE","domain_tag":"Military","contested":{"summary":"Whether al-Shabaab is 'losing' has been announced for 15 years; the narrative war is over momentum itself.","claims":[{"claim":"Government offensives have al-Shabaab on the verge of defeat.","who":"Mogadishu + successive AU/US statements — the momentum narrative that sustains funding and troop commitments.","evid":"Al-Shabaab retook much of what the 2022-23 offensive captured; it taxes the economy under the government's nose and is resurgent as AUSSOM shrinks. The 'verge of defeat' claim has been falsified repeatedly since 2011.","status":"CONTESTED — momentum claims vs territorial reality"},{"claim":"Al-Shabaab is a legitimate resistance to foreign occupation and a fairer justice provider.","who":"Al-Shabaab's own information operations — the governance-legitimacy pitch that aids recruitment and taxation.","evid":"Its courts are used even by non-supporters (documented) — but so are its massacres, forced recruitment of children, and famine-weaponization. The 'fair justice' brand is real as perception, monstrous as practice.","status":"CONTESTED — governance brand vs atrocity record"}]},"history":{"roots":"Somalia's condition was manufactured by partition. The Somali people — one language, one faith, a pastoral civilization with sophisticated indigenous governance (the xeer customary-law system, clan assemblies) — were split five ways by the Scramble: British Somaliland, Italian Somalia, French Djibouti, Ethiopia's Ogaden, and Kenya's Northern Frontier District. Independence (1960) unified only two of the five, making irredentism the state's founding purpose; the 1977 Ogaden war's defeat — when the superpowers switched sides — broke the project and, by 1991, the state. What outsiders call 'anarchy' Somali scholars describe differently: Barre's dictatorship destroyed the state's legitimacy, and the clan system both fragmented the war and, in Somaliland, rebuilt peace without any foreign force — the most successful indigenous state-reconstruction in modern Africa, still unrecognized. Al-Shabaab grew from the rubble of the 2006 Ethiopian invasion (US-backed), which destroyed the Islamic Courts Union — the one indigenous order that had unified the south.","timeline":[{"date":"1991","e":"Barre regime falls; the state collapses into clan warfare."},{"date":"1993","e":"US 'Black Hawk Down' battle in Mogadishu; US withdraws."},{"date":"2006","e":"Islamic Courts Union briefly unifies the south; Ethiopia invades."},{"date":"2007","e":"African Union force (AMISOM) deploys; al-Shabaab emerges."},{"date":"2012","e":"A federal government is re-established."},{"date":"2022-24","e":"Government offensives push al-Shabaab back, then stall."},{"date":"2025","e":"ATMIS ends; the under-funded AUSSOM mission takes over."},{"date":"2026","e":"Al-Shabaab resurgent amid the security-transition vacuum; US airstrikes continue."}],"actors":[{"name":"Al-Shabaab","bio":"Al-Qaeda's East Africa affiliate; controls rural southern Somalia, taxes the economy, and outlasts every foreign force."},{"name":"Federal Government (Hassan Sheikh Mohamud)","bio":"Internationally-backed but weak, dependent on AU troops and US strikes."},{"name":"AUSSOM (African Union)","bio":"The latest, under-funded AU stabilization mission; its drawdown is the immediate escalation driver."},{"name":"ISIS-Somalia","bio":"A smaller rival jihadist faction in Puntland, targeted by recent US strikes."}],"bridge":"Today's 'security transition crisis' repeats the pattern: external forces (AMISOM→ATMIS→AUSSOM) substitute for, rather than build, indigenous legitimacy — and each drawdown reveals the substitution. Al-Shabaab's taxation and courts work because they plug into the xeer expectation of order the federal state doesn't meet; Somaliland's unrecognized success and the Ogaden/NFD partitions remain the standing proof that the crisis was never Somali incapacity but the 1884 map plus repeated external decapitation of homegrown orders (1977, 2006). The famine-and-drone cycle is the partition still collecting.","sources":[{"work":"Africa's First Democrats: Somalia's Aden A. Osman and Abdirazak H. Hussein","author":"Abdi Ismail Samatar","year":"2016","note":"Somali scholarship recovering the democratic founding era erased by the 'failed state' frame."},{"work":"Oral Poetry and Somali Nationalism","author":"Said S. Samatar","year":"1982","note":"The indigenous political culture — poetry as politics — that partition cut across."},{"work":"Somalia: State Collapse and the Threat of Terrorism","author":"Ken Menkhaus","year":"2004","note":"The mechanics of collapse and the external-intervention paradox."},{"work":"Becoming Somaliland","author":"Mark Bradbury","year":"2008","note":"The indigenous peace-building (Borama conference tradition) that rebuilt the north without foreign troops."}]},"human":{"dead":50000,"disp":3800000,"famine":true,"aid":"al-Shabaab-taxed","note":"Conflict + drought compound; 3.8M displaced; famine-risk districts recurrent; aid access negotiated with the insurgency it feeds."}},{"id":"chad","cat":"military","region":"Central Africa","subregion":"Central Africa","tclass":"conflict","name":"Chad — The RSF Corridor Turns on Its Host","sub":"UAE arms transit · RSF now striking Chad · Zaghawa fracture in Déby's own army · Saudi hedge","domain":"Proxy-Corridor State / Regime Fragility","sev":"high","status":"escalating","since":"2023 (Sudan war)","esc":76,"lat":13.5,"lon":20.9,"trend":"up","esc_history":[69,70,72,73,74,75,76,76,76,76],"hist_real":false,"as_of":"15 Jul 2026","tracked_since":"Wk16 (Jul 2026)","cas":"Dec 2025: 2 soldiers killed by Sudan-origin drone · Jan 2026: 7 killed in RSF attack on a Chadian military camp · Feb 2026: 5 soldiers + 3 civilians killed at Tine · Mar 18 2026: drone strike on Ramadan Iftar gathering at Mabrouka (Wadi Fira) killed 16 civilians","disp":"918,760+ Sudanese refugees in eastern Chad (as of Mar 31) — one of the world's largest refugee burdens per capita","flag":"🇹🇩","note":"NEW THEATER (Wk16 · closes the platform's biggest structural gap — Chad was load-bearing in Sudan, Haiti, and gold-laundering but had no theater) · THE CORRIDOR: the UAE→RSF arms pipeline runs through Chad; a UAE-built airport at AMDJARASS/Amjarass (2023, officially a 'field hospital' for refugees) was found by UN investigators and journalists to be a weapons transit node · PAYMENT: Chad reportedly received ~$2B in UAE loans (incl. a $500M Abu Dhabi Fund loan at 1% over 18yr, 2024; a $200M offer in 2023) — transformative for a country with GDP/capita ~$3,000 · THE BLOWBACK — the corridor is now killing its host: RSF attacked a Chadian military camp (Jan, 7 dead); fighting at Tine spilled over (Feb, 8 dead); Chad CLOSED the Sudan border Feb 23 and deployed thousands of troops along the 1,400km frontier; a Sudan-origin drone killed 16 civilians at a Ramadan Iftar in Mabrouka (Mar 18) — Déby, in fatigues, called it 'outrageous and excessive aggression' and ordered retaliation · THE ETHNIC TRAP: the RSF is exterminating ZAGHAWA in Darfur — and the Zaghawa dominate Chad's military and security elite. Déby is Zaghawa. One officer: the war is now seen as 'a war between Zaghawa and Arabs' · Chadian Zaghawa militias DEFY government disarmament orders and fight alongside Sudanese Zaghawa in the Joint Force (SAF-aligned), using Chad as a rear base · Déby's cousin Ousmane Dillo is a Zaghawa rebel fighting the RSF in Darfur — his influence on the officer corps is a Crisis Group watch item · Hemedti's cousin Gen. Bichara Issa Djadalla is Déby's SPECIAL ADVISER · THE HEDGE: Déby flew to Saudi Arabia (May 2026) — the SAF's backer — to build a 'political firewall,' playing the two Gulf powers against each other · Egypt, Saudi Arabia and Somalia began DENYING UAE overflight (Jan 2026); Somalia cancelled all UAE agreements Jan 12; eastern Libya briefly closed al-Kufra — squeezing the alternatives and making the Chad route MORE critical · BOKO HARAM: JAS + ISWAP re-establishing a foothold in Lake province; state of emergency declared May 2026 · Déby won the 2026 African Peace Prize (Jan) for hosting refugees — while hosting the pipeline arming the force creating them","leverage":[{"actor":"UAE","asset":"~$2B in loans + political backing buying transit rights through Chadian territory — the payment that makes the corridor work","str":"hi"},{"actor":"Déby regime","asset":"Controls the transit territory both the UAE and the RSF need; can close the border (and did) — but depends on Emirati money to fund the patronage that keeps him in power","str":"md"},{"actor":"Zaghawa officer corps","asset":"Dominates Chad's military — and is watching its own kin exterminated by the force its president lets be armed. The regime's core constituency is its core vulnerability","str":"hi"},{"actor":"Saudi Arabia","asset":"The counter-patron — the SAF's backer, now courted by Déby as a firewall against total UAE dependence","str":"md"},{"actor":"RSF","asset":"Attacks Chad directly while depending on it for supply — betting Déby needs Emirati money too badly to retaliate seriously","str":"md"}],"gov":[{"src":"UN Panel of Experts","detail":"Found 'credible evidence' the UAE's Amdjarass 'field hospital' facility was used for arms transfers to the RSF"},{"src":"Crisis Group (On the Horizon, Jul-Dec 2026)","detail":"'The longer the Sudan war continues, the harder it may become for Déby to balance ties with the UAE, communal grievances and elite fragmentation. His grip on power could weaken' — though no Zaghawa figure yet commands enough support to challenge him"},{"src":"Africa Center for Strategic Studies","detail":"'Chad Risks Greater Instability from Engagement in Sudan's Conflict'; documents the $500M Abu Dhabi Fund loan (1%, 18yr) and border closure"},{"src":"Chad Presidency (Mar 18 2026)","detail":"Déby ordered the military to retaliate against any Sudanese forces attacking Chadian territory after the Mabrouka drone strike killed 16; convened emergency Defence and Security Council"},{"src":"ISW / Critical Threats (Africa File, Jan 22 2026)","detail":"Chadian security officials have criticized Déby for allowing UAE weapons transit; Egypt/Saudi/Somalia began denying UAE overflight, raising the stakes of the Chad route"}],"econlev":[{"holder":"UAE","channel":"Sovereign loans + patronage","exp":"HIGH","detail":"~$2B (incl. $500M Abu Dhabi Fund at 1%/18yr) — for a ~$3,000 GDP/capita state this is regime-defining money, and it buys transit rights. This is the purchase price of a corridor."},{"holder":"Chad (Déby)","channel":"Territorial transit rights","exp":"HIGH","detail":"The commodity Chad sells is geography — the 1,400km Darfur frontier. Adré and Amdjarass are the nodes; illicit economies have boomed since 2023."},{"holder":"Gold smuggling networks","channel":"Sudanese gold → Dubai","exp":"HIGH","detail":"Chad is a primary smuggling route for RSF-controlled Sudanese gold heading to the UAE — the loop that pays for the weapons that come back the other way"}],"external":[{"actor":"🇦🇪 UAE","side":"RSF (via Chad)","flow":"Runs the RSF arms pipeline through Chadian territory (Amdjarass airport); paid ~$2B in loans for the access; denies everything","tier":"alleged-credible","for":"Sudanese gold; Red Sea/Sahel position — Chad is the land bridge that makes the RSF resupply possible"},{"actor":"🇸🇦 Saudi Arabia","side":"Déby (hedge) / SAF","flow":"Déby's May 2026 Riyadh trip sought financial backing as a firewall; Saudi backs the SAF against the UAE's RSF","tier":"documented","for":"Counter-Emirati influence; a stable Chad that isn't wholly Abu Dhabi's"},{"actor":"🏴 RSF","side":"belligerent + client","flow":"Depends on Chadian transit for supply — while attacking Chadian military camps and killing Chadian civilians with drones","tier":"documented","for":"The supply line it cannot survive without, from a host it is simultaneously attacking"},{"actor":"🇫🇷 France","side":"Déby regime","flow":"Historic patron; military presence drawn down but influence persists","tier":"documented","for":"Sahel foothold after expulsion from Mali/Burkina/Niger"},{"actor":"🏴 Boko Haram / ISWAP","side":"insurgents","flow":"Re-establishing a foothold in Lake province after retrenchment; state of emergency declared May 2026","tier":"documented","for":"Lake Chad caliphate project — the second front Déby cannot afford"}],"mil":"Chad is being attacked by the force its own territory helps supply. Between December 2025 and March 2026 the war it was hosting came home: a Sudan-origin drone killed two Chadian soldiers in December, an RSF attack on a Chadian military camp killed seven in January, fighting at the border town of Tine killed five soldiers and three civilians in February, and on March 18 a drone struck a Ramadan Iftar gathering at Mabrouka in Wadi Fira, killing sixteen civilians. Déby appeared in military fatigues, called it 'outrageous and excessive aggression,' convened an emergency Defence and Security Council, and ordered retaliation. Chad closed its 1,400km border with Sudan in February and deployed thousands of troops — and the weapons kept moving anyway. A second front is opening in Lake province, where Boko Haram's JAS faction and ISWAP are re-establishing a foothold after months of retrenchment, prompting a state of emergency in May.","pol":"The trap is ethnic and it runs through the president's own army. The RSF is exterminating the Zaghawa in Darfur — and the Zaghawa dominate Chad's military and security elite. Déby is Zaghawa. When the RSF massacres Zaghawa communities in El Fasher, Chadian Zaghawa officers watch their own kin slaughtered by a force their president permits to be armed across his territory. One officer described the war as increasingly 'a war between Zaghawa and Arabs' — combustible language in a state defined by a delicate ethnic balance. Chadian Zaghawa militias now defy government disarmament orders and fight alongside Sudanese Zaghawa in the SAF-aligned Joint Force, using Chad as a rear base. Déby's own cousin, Ousmane Dillo, is a Zaghawa rebel fighting the RSF in Darfur. Meanwhile Hemedti's cousin, General Bichara Issa Djadalla, serves as Déby's special adviser. Crisis Group's assessment is blunt: the longer the war runs, the harder it becomes for Déby to balance Emirati money against communal grievance and elite fragmentation — and his grip could weaken, though no Zaghawa figure yet commands enough support to replace him.","eco":"Chad sells geography. The UAE built an airport at Amdjarass in 2023, officially a field hospital for refugees; UN investigators and journalists found it functioning as an arms-transfer node into RSF-held Darfur. In exchange Chad reportedly received roughly $2 billion in loans — including a $500 million Abu Dhabi Fund facility at 1% interest over eighteen years. For a country with GDP per capita around $3,000, that is regime-defining money, and it is the purchase price of a corridor. The loop closes on the other side: Chad is a primary smuggling route for RSF-controlled Sudanese gold moving to Dubai — the gold pays for the weapons that come back through the same desert. Meanwhile Chad hosts over 918,000 Sudanese refugees, one of the heaviest per-capita burdens on earth, and Déby collected the 2026 African Peace Prize in January for taking them in.","assess":"Chad enters at 76 (SEVERE, conflict-class), trend up — and it is the theater the board most needed, because Chad was already load-bearing in three places and tracked in none: the Sudan pipeline, the Haiti deployment, and the gold-laundering system all run through it. Its structural position is the platform's thesis in miniature. Déby sold transit rights to the UAE for about $2 billion, and the corridor is now killing its host: the RSF strikes Chadian camps and Chadian civilians while depending on Chadian territory to survive, betting that Déby needs Emirati money too badly to retaliate. The deeper fracture is ethnic — the force being armed across his territory is exterminating the Zaghawa, who are his own base and his own officer corps, and Zaghawa militias are already defying his disarmament orders to go fight it. The squeeze is tightening from outside too: Egypt, Saudi Arabia and Somalia have begun denying UAE overflight and eastern Libya briefly closed al-Kufra, which makes the Chad route more essential, not less. Déby's answer has been to fly to Riyadh and court the SAF's patron — playing both Gulf powers to build a firewall. Watch the Zaghawa officer corps, Ousmane Dillo's influence, the Tine border fighting, the depth of the Saudi hedge, and whether Boko Haram's Lake province revival opens a second front the regime cannot fund. This is the clearest case on the board of a state that monetized someone else's war and is now being consumed by it. Trend estimate — newly entered tracking.","tier":"SEVERE","domain_tag":"Military","contested":{"summary":"A president who won a peace prize for hosting the refugees, from a war he helps supply.","claims":[{"claim":"Chad and the UAE both deny that arms transit Chadian territory to the RSF.","who":"Déby — who cannot admit what the $2B bought — and the UAE, which needs the corridor deniable.","evid":"UN investigators found 'credible evidence' the Amdjarass 'field hospital' was an arms-transfer node. Journalists and Crisis Group document the loans. Analysts (Cameron Hudson, World Politics Review) describe Emirati financial and political support exchanged for territorial access. Chad closed the border in February 2026 and the weapons reportedly kept moving.","status":"DOCUMENTED-BUT-DENIED"},{"claim":"Déby was awarded the 2026 African Peace Prize for managing the political transition and hosting Sudanese refugees.","who":"Déby — international legitimacy is the counter-narrative to the corridor allegations.","evid":"Both are true, and that is the point. Chad genuinely hosts 918,760+ refugees at enormous cost. It also hosts the pipeline arming the force that created them. The prize does not disprove the corridor; the corridor does not erase the refugees.","status":"UNRESOLVED — both facts are real; only one is celebrated"},{"claim":"The RSF's cross-border attacks are framed as spillover or accident.","who":"The RSF, which cannot afford to lose Chadian transit, and Déby, who cannot afford to admit his patron's client is killing his people.","evid":"Four separate lethal incidents Dec 2025-Mar 2026, including a drone strike on a Ramadan Iftar that killed 16 civilians. Déby called it 'outrageous and excessive aggression' and ordered retaliation. Analysts read RSF overconfidence: a bet that Déby needs Emirati money too badly to respond.","status":"CONTESTED"}]},"history":{"roots":"Chad was colonized as an afterthought and governed as a barracks. France classified it 'Tchad utile' and 'Tchad inutile' — the cotton south worth administering, the Saharan north worth only garrisoning — a bifurcation that structured every conflict since. Marielle Debos's ethnography names the result: a state where 'living by the gun' is a profession, where power has changed hands by rebellion column (1979, 1982, 1990) rather than ballot, and where France intervened militarily again and again (against Libya in the 1980s, for Déby in 2008 and 2019) to keep its Sahel keystone in place — the garrison-state as a joint Franco-Chadian enterprise. Idriss Déby ruled for thirty years as the West's indispensable soldier (Chad's army carried the Sahel coalitions) and died as he ruled, at the front; the dynastic handover to Mahamat, blessed by Macron at the funeral, showed the arrangement outliving the man.","timeline":[{"date":"1960","e":"Independence from France; decades of rebellion and coups follow."},{"date":"1990","e":"Idriss Déby seizes power — the dynasty begins."},{"date":"2003-","e":"Darfur war spills over; Chad hosts refugees and rebels both."},{"date":"2021","e":"Idriss Déby killed at the front; son Mahamat installed."},{"date":"2023-","e":"Sudan war: ~1M refugees; UAE arms transit via Amdjarass to the RSF."},{"date":"2024","e":"French forces expelled — the last Sahel base falls."},{"date":"2025-26","e":"Mabrouka drone strike inside Chad; Zaghawa elite fractures over the RSF; border closures; Déby balances UAE money (CEPA talks) against the blowback."}],"actors":[{"name":"Mahamat Déby","bio":"Dynastic president since 2021 — running his father's security state while the Sudan war splits his Zaghawa base and the UAE relationship buys and endangers him at once."},{"name":"UAE","bio":"Loans and trade deals in exchange for the Amdjarass corridor — the RSF's supply line runs on Chadian tolerance."},{"name":"Zaghawa networks","bio":"The cross-border kin group spanning the Déby elite and Darfur's victims — the war forces a choice the regime can't safely make."},{"name":"France (departed)","bio":"The century-long patron whose 2024 exit left the vacuum Russia and the Gulf now contest."}],"bridge":"Today Chad is what happens when the garrison-state's patron leaves and its neighbors burn: France expelled (2024), the Sahel coalitions dead, and Sudan's war pressing the exact seam colonial rule built — the Zaghawa kin-networks spanning the Déby elite and Darfur's victims, now split by the UAE's RSF corridor running through Amdjarass with Abu Dhabi's loans as rent. A state constructed as a security subcontractor is discovering it has no other business model; the Mabrouka strike and the elite fracture are the invoice arriving.","sources":[{"work":"Living by the Gun in Chad: Combatants, Impunity and State Formation","author":"Marielle Debos","year":"2016","note":"The ethnography of Chad's métier des armes — the gun as profession and the state as its market."},{"work":"Historical Dictionary of Chad","author":"Mario Azevedo & Samuel Decalo","year":"2018 (4th ed.)","note":"The utile/inutile bifurcation and the rebellion-column pattern of power transfer."},{"work":"France's wars in Chad: Military intervention and decolonization in Africa","author":"Nathaniel K. Powell","year":"2020","note":"The Franco-Chadian garrison partnership — interventions 1968-90 as the keystone's maintenance."},{"work":"UN Panel of Experts on the Sudan (Chad corridor findings)","author":"UN Security Council","year":"2023-26","note":"Primary documentation of the Amdjarass supply route and UAE flights."}]},"patterns":["water-leverage"]},{"id":"yemen","cat":"military","region":"Middle East","subregion":"Middle East","tclass":"conflict","name":"Yemen — Houthis + the Second Chokepoint","sub":"Bab el-Mandeb blockade threat · 'Hormuz + Bab el-Mandeb together' · $200 oil scenario","domain":"Maritime Interdiction / Axis Proxy","sev":"critical","status":"escalating","since":"2014 (Houthi takeover)","esc":88,"lat":15.35,"lon":44.2,"trend":"up","esc_history":[71,73,75,78,80,81,82,83,84,88],"hist_real":false,"as_of":"15 Jul 2026","tracked_since":"Wk16 (Jul 2026)","cas":"100+ Houthi attacks on commercial vessels Nov 2023-Oct 2025 affecting 60+ nations; bulk carriers Magic Seas and Eternity C SUNK near Hodeidah (Jul 2025); seafarers killed and taken hostage","disp":"Yemen's own war: one of the world's largest humanitarian crises, millions displaced and food-insecure","flag":"🇾🇪","note":"JUL 13: Ansar Allah declared it will CLOSE BAB EL-MANDEB SIMULTANEOUSLY with Hormuz — \"Bab el-Mandeb will join with Hormuz, and the price of oil will rise to $200\" (political bureau member Mohammed al-Farah) · Gibson Shipping warns a prolonged dual closure against falling global reserves means far tighter supply, higher prices, tanker shortage · the two-chokepoint doctrine (Qaani: a \"security belt from Hormuz to Bab el-Mandeb\") is now stated by both ends of the Axis · NEW THEATER (Wk16 · closes the gap where Chokepoints tracked Bab el-Mandeb but the actor controlling it was untracked) · LIVE (Jul 13): Ansar Allah political bureau member Mohammed al-Farah declared the Houthis intend to BLOCK BAB EL-MANDEB SIMULTANEOUSLY with Iran's Hormuz closure — 'Bab el-Mandeb will join with Hormuz, and the price of oil will rise to $200' · Gibson Shipping warns a prolonged dual closure creates 'much more difficult supply conditions' against already-falling global oil reserves · the Houthis joined the Iran war (Mar-Apr 2026), resumed strikes on Israel, and on Jun 8 declared 'a complete and total ban on Israeli maritime navigation in the Red Sea' — all enemy movements 'legitimate military targets' · CAPABILITY IS PROVEN, NOT THEORETICAL: 100+ attacks on commercial vessels (Nov 2023-Oct 2025) affecting 60+ nations; they SANK the Magic Seas and Eternity C in Jul 2025 · arsenal: one-way UAV, USV (drone boats), UUV, ballistic + cruise anti-ship missiles, naval mines, small-boat/explosive-boat attacks, illegal boardings · oil through Bab el-Mandeb already fell 8.8M → ~4M bbl/day during the earlier campaign · ~12% of global maritime trade and ~10-12% of seaborne oil transits the 26-29km strait; ships must slow and funnel into predictable lanes within range of the Yemeni coast · IRGC Quds Force cmdr Qaani (Jun 9): escalation triggers an Axis 'security belt' from HORMUZ TO BAB EL-MANDEB — the two-chokepoint doctrine stated openly · UNSC Res 2722/2812 monthly reporting on Houthi attacks up for renewal 15 Jul · COUNTER-READ (logged): Amb. Qubaty argues the Houthis/Iran have historically AVOIDED full closure despite capability — sustained closure is too costly and risks direct confrontation with naval powers. Capability ≠ intent.","leverage":[{"actor":"Houthis (Ansar Allah)","asset":"Physical interdiction of Bab el-Mandeb — proven capability (2 ships sunk, 100+ attacked); the second half of the two-chokepoint squeeze","str":"hi"},{"actor":"Iran","asset":"The Houthis are the Axis arm that survived — with Hezbollah degraded and Hamas dismantled, Yemen is Tehran's most functional forward capability","str":"hi"},{"actor":"US / allied navies","asset":"Operation Rough Rider (2025) — hundreds of strikes; escort capability, but cannot compel safety through a 26km strait overlooked by a hostile coast","str":"md"},{"actor":"Global shipping","asset":"Can reroute around the Cape — at ~10-14 extra days, higher fuel and insurance; the cost that transmits to every economy","str":"md"}],"gov":[{"src":"UNSC Res 2722 (2024) / Res 2812","detail":"Demands the Houthis cease all attacks on merchant vessels; monthly Secretary-General reporting extended to 15 July 2026, renewal expected"},{"src":"US MARAD (Advisory 2026-006)","detail":"Vessels with Israeli/US/UK association at high risk in the southern Red Sea, Bab el-Mandeb and Gulf of Aden 'until further notice'; catalogues UAV, USV, UUV, ballistic/cruise missile, mine and boarding threats"},{"src":"Houthi armed forces (Brig. Gen. Yahya Sare'e)","detail":"Declared a 'complete and total ban on Israeli maritime navigation in the Red Sea'; all enemy movements are 'legitimate military targets'"}],"econlev":[{"holder":"Houthis","channel":"Bab el-Mandeb interdiction","exp":"HIGH","detail":"~12% of global maritime trade and ~10-12% of seaborne oil; traffic already fell from 8.8M to ~4M bbl/day under the earlier campaign. The strait is 26-29km wide — ships slow, funnel into predictable lanes, and pass within range of the coast."},{"holder":"Iran + Houthis (jointly)","channel":"The dual-chokepoint squeeze","exp":"HIGH","detail":"Hormuz (~1/5 of seaborne oil) + Bab el-Mandeb (~12% of trade) closed together is the scenario Ansar Allah has now named: '$200 oil.' This is the single largest tail risk on the board."}],"external":[{"actor":"🇮🇷 Iran","side":"Houthis","flow":"Arms, missile/drone technology, targeting support; IRGC-QF cmdr Qaani named a 'security belt from Hormuz to Bab el-Mandeb'","tier":"documented","for":"A second chokepoint — and the Axis arm that survived the 2026 war intact"},{"actor":"🇺🇸 US / 🇬🇧 UK","side":"counter-Houthi","flow":"Operation Rough Rider (2025): hundreds of strikes; naval escort; MARAD threat advisories","tier":"documented","for":"Freedom of navigation; protect the Suez-Red Sea artery"},{"actor":"🇮🇱 Israel","side":"target/belligerent","flow":"Houthi missile and drone strikes on Israeli territory resumed with the Iran war; Israel strikes Hodeidah port","tier":"documented","for":"Degrade the last functional Axis arm"},{"actor":"🇸🇦 Saudi Arabia","side":"reluctant belligerent","flow":"Houthis warn against Gulf states joining the US-Israel war on Iran; threaten to shutter Bab el-Mandeb if they do","tier":"documented","for":"Avoid a return to the Yemen war it spent a decade trying to exit"}],"mil":"The capability is proven, not theoretical. Between November 2023 and October 2025 the Houthis conducted more than 100 attacks on commercial vessels affecting over 60 nations, and in July 2025 they sank two bulk carriers — the Magic Seas and the Eternity C — near Hodeidah. Their arsenal spans one-way attack drones, unmanned surface and underwater vehicles, ballistic and cruise anti-ship missiles, naval mines, explosive boats, and armed boardings. The geography does the rest: Bab el-Mandeb is 26 to 29 kilometres wide, ships must slow and funnel into predictable lanes, and they pass within range of a coastline the Houthis control. The US ran Operation Rough Rider in 2025 — hundreds of strikes — and the group is still there, still armed, and now back at war.","pol":"The strategic picture changed on July 13. A member of Ansar Allah's political bureau, Mohammed al-Farah, declared the Houthis intend to block Bab el-Mandeb simultaneously with Iran's closure of Hormuz: 'Bab el-Mandeb will join with Hormuz, and the price of oil will rise to $200.' That is the doctrine IRGC Quds Force commander Esmail Qaani had already named in June — an Axis 'security belt' running from the Strait of Hormuz to the Bab el-Mandeb Strait. With Hezbollah degraded and Hamas dismantled, the Houthis are the Axis arm that survived the 2026 war intact, which makes Yemen Tehran's most functional forward capability. The counter-read is worth logging honestly: Ambassador Qubaty argues Iran and the Houthis have consistently avoided full closure despite having the capability, because sustained closure is too costly and risks direct confrontation with international naval power. Capability is not intent — but the threat is now explicit and the second chokepoint is live.","eco":"Roughly 12% of global maritime trade and a comparable share of seaborne oil passes through Bab el-Mandeb, and the earlier campaign already cut throughput from 8.8 million to around 4 million barrels per day. The scenario that matters is the combination: Hormuz (about a fifth of the world's seaborne oil) and Bab el-Mandeb closed at the same time. Gibson Shipping has warned that a prolonged dual closure, against already-declining global oil reserves, would create far more difficult supply conditions, higher prices, and a shortage of available tankers. The Houthis have now put a number on it themselves — $200 a barrel.","assess":"Yemen enters at 84 (SEVERE, conflict-class), trend up — and it closes a gap that mattered: the platform tracked Bab el-Mandeb inside Chokepoints while the actor who controls it went untracked. That is no longer tenable, because on July 13 Ansar Allah declared it will close Bab el-Mandeb simultaneously with Hormuz, naming $200 oil as the intended result. Read alongside Iran's declared Hormuz closure at 94, this is the single largest tail risk on the board: two chokepoints, one axis, roughly a third of seaborne energy trade. The capability is demonstrated — two ships sunk, a hundred attacked, a US air campaign that did not remove it. The honest caveat is that Iran and the Houthis have historically stopped short of full closure precisely because it invites the confrontation they cannot win, so the threat may be leverage rather than plan. Watch the UNSC reporting renewal (15 Jul), any strike on a non-Israeli-linked vessel, whether Gulf states enter the Iran war (the Houthis' stated trigger), and Bab el-Mandeb transit volumes — that number is the ground truth. Trend estimate — newly entered tracking.","tier":"SEVERE","domain_tag":"Military","contested":{"summary":"A threat to close the strait, from a group that has always stopped short of closing it.","claims":[{"claim":"The Houthis will block Bab el-Mandeb simultaneously with Hormuz, driving oil to $200.","who":"The Houthis and Iran — the threat itself is leverage, and costs nothing to make.","evid":"The capability is real (100+ attacks, 2 ships sunk, throughput already halved). But Amb. Qubaty notes Iran and the Houthis have consistently AVOIDED full closure despite capability, because sustained closure invites direct confrontation with naval powers they cannot defeat. Stated intent, proven capability, and a track record of stopping short — all three are true.","status":"CONTESTED — capability is not intent"},{"claim":"Houthi attacks are framed as targeting only Israeli-linked shipping.","who":"The Houthis — a limited frame keeps neutral states and their navies out of the fight.","evid":"MARAD's advisory covers vessels with Israeli, US, or UK association AND any vessel in a fleet whose company has called at Israeli ports — a definition broad enough to catch most global carriers. The Magic Seas and Eternity C sinkings killed and stranded seafarers with no stake in the war.","status":"CONTESTED — the stated target set and the actual one differ"}]},"history":{"roots":"Yemen's war is a local power struggle that became a regional and then global one. The 2011 Arab Spring ousted long-ruling Saleh; the transition failed, and in 2014 the Houthis — a Zaidi-Shia revivalist movement from the north — seized the capital Sanaa. A Saudi-led coalition intervened in 2015 to restore the government, producing the world's worst humanitarian crisis. Iran armed the Houthis, turning Yemen into a Saudi-Iranian proxy theater. After 2023 the Houthis globalized the war by attacking Red Sea shipping in solidarity with Gaza, drawing US and UK strikes. The roots: a north-south divide, Zaidi marginalization, and Yemen's position astride the Bab-el-Mandeb chokepoint.","timeline":[{"date":"1990","e":"North and South Yemen unify under Saleh."},{"date":"2011","e":"Arab Spring uprising ousts Saleh."},{"date":"2014","e":"Houthis seize Sanaa."},{"date":"2015","e":"Saudi-led coalition intervenes; humanitarian catastrophe begins."},{"date":"2022","e":"A UN truce sharply reduces frontline fighting."},{"date":"2023","e":"Houthis begin Red Sea shipping attacks over Gaza."},{"date":"2024-25","e":"US/UK airstrikes on the Houthis; shipping reroutes around Africa."},{"date":"2026","e":"Houthis entrenched as the dominant Yemeni power and a Red Sea veto-holder."}],"actors":[{"name":"Houthis (Ansar Allah)","bio":"Zaidi-Shia movement controlling northern Yemen and Sanaa; Iran-armed; wields the Bab-el-Mandeb chokepoint as leverage."},{"name":"Saudi Arabia","bio":"Led the 2015 intervention; now seeking an exit from a costly, unwinnable war."},{"name":"Iran","bio":"Arms and advises the Houthis as part of its 'Axis of Resistance.'"},{"name":"Internationally-recognized govt / PLC","bio":"The Saudi-backed, fragmented anti-Houthi coalition holding the south and east."}],"bridge":"The Houthis' Red Sea veto is the periphery's revenge at global scale: a movement from Yemen's marginalized highlands now prices Europe-Asia trade — Lackner's point that Yemen was never a 'failed state' but a deliberately starved one comes due at Bab el-Mandeb. The IRGC's all-regional-energy threat (Jul 2026) makes Yemen one arm of a two-strait pincer with Hormuz; the Saudi exit-seeking shows the intervener conceding the intervention. What began as a local settlement dispute after the Arab Spring now sits inside every tanker's insurance premium.","sources":[{"work":"Yemen in Crisis: The Road to War","author":"Helen Lackner","year":"2017 (rev. 2019)","note":"The structural account — water, land, and the deliberate starvation of the periphery."},{"work":"Destroying Yemen: What Chaos in Arabia Tells Us about the World","author":"Isa Blumi","year":"2018","note":"The anti-Eurocentric counter-history — Yemen as a target of extraction, not a basket case."},{"work":"UN Panel of Experts on Yemen reports","author":"UN Security Council","year":"2015-26","note":"Primary documentation of the war economy and arms flows on all sides."}]},"human":{"dead":377000,"disp":4500000,"famine":true,"aid":"chronically underfunded","note":"~377k dead by UN 2021 estimate (majority indirect: hunger/disease); the world's worst humanitarian crisis label predates and outlasts every ceasefire."}},{"id":"libya","cat":"military","region":"North Africa","subregion":"Horn / NE Africa","tclass":"conflict","name":"Libya — The Second RSF Corridor + Russia's Africa Bridge","sub":"al-Kufra arms route · Haftar-Russia-UAE triangle · Tobruk basing · divided state","domain":"Divided State / Arms Corridor","sev":"high","status":"volatile","since":"2011 (collapse) / 2014 (division)","esc":67,"lat":26.3,"lon":17.2,"trend":"up","esc_history":[63,64,65,65,66,66,67,67,67,67],"hist_real":false,"as_of":"15 Jul 2026","tracked_since":"Wk16 (Jul 2026)","cas":"No mass-casualty events currently; the harm is exported — Libya is a transit state whose cargo kills in Darfur","disp":"Migration corridor to Europe; internally displaced from the 2011-2020 wars","flag":"🇱🇾","note":"NEW THEATER (Wk16 · the OTHER half of the RSF pipeline — the platform tracked Chad but not the corridor that runs parallel to it) · TWO CORRIDORS, ONE WAR: the UAE runs RSF supply on two air routes — a NORTHERN one through Egyptian/Saudi airspace to LIBYA, and a SOUTHERN one through Ethiopian/Somali/South Sudanese airspace to Chad and Libya (ISW) · AL-KUFRA: the airport in Haftar-controlled southeastern Libya is the northern node — IL-76 and AN-26 cargo flights documented by satellite imagery and flight tracking moving arms to RSF-held Darfur; became the MAIN RSF supply node after Chad scaled back in 2025 · Jan 19 2026: eastern Libyan authorities temporarily CLOSED al-Kufra under Egyptian diplomatic pressure — which is why the Chad route matters more now · THE TRIANGLE: Haftar's LNA controls the southeast; his backers are the UAE and RUSSIA; Wagner/Africa Corps has moved SAM-7s and anti-aircraft systems through Kufra · RUSSIA'S BRIDGE: Feb 2025 tripartite agreement (Haftar-Russia-Belarus) on joint use of LNA logistics at TOBRUK (air base + port); satellite imagery shows reconstruction at al-Jufra air base through Apr 2026 — Moscow is building the North Africa foothold that supplies the Sahel Africa Corps deployments (Mali, Burkina, Niger) · CONTRADICTION: Moscow has shifted most Sudan support from the RSF to the SAF — but its forces in Libya do not interfere with Haftar's arms flow to the RSF (Jamestown) · Libya remains split: Tripoli (GNU, UN-recognized) vs Tobruk/Benghazi (Haftar/LNA); elections perpetually deferred · al-Wigh, Maaten al-Sarra, Brak al-Shati, al-Khadim, al-Jufra = the airbase network","leverage":[{"actor":"Haftar / LNA","asset":"Controls southeastern Libya incl. al-Kufra — the northern gate of the RSF pipeline; rents territory to the UAE and Russia simultaneously","str":"hi"},{"actor":"Russia (Africa Corps)","asset":"Tobruk basing agreement + al-Jufra reconstruction — the logistics bridge from the Mediterranean to the Sahel deployments","str":"hi"},{"actor":"UAE","asset":"Runs the northern arms route through Libyan airspace and airfields; Haftar's principal financier","str":"hi"},{"actor":"Egypt","asset":"Diplomatic pressure that briefly CLOSED al-Kufra (Jan 2026) — proof the corridor can be shut, and that no one has sustained the effort","str":"md"},{"actor":"GNU (Tripoli)","asset":"UN recognition and the west — but no control over the south, where the corridor runs","str":"lo"}],"gov":[{"src":"ISW / Critical Threats (Jan 2026)","detail":"Documents the two UAE air routes to the RSF (northern via Libya, southern via Chad); eastern Libyan authorities closed al-Kufra Airport Jan 19 2026 under Egyptian pressure"},{"src":"NGA/Tearline OSINT (Jun 2026)","detail":"Satellite imagery: Russia developing air-base infrastructure (al-Jufra hangar reconstruction through Apr 2026) to secure a North Africa and Sahel foothold; Feb 2025 Haftar-Russia-Belarus tripartite agreement on Tobruk"},{"src":"Jamestown Foundation","detail":"Moscow shifted most Sudan backing to the SAF, yet its forces in Libya do not interfere with Haftar's arms supply to the RSF"},{"src":"UN Panel of Experts / CNN flight-tracking","detail":"IL-76 and AN-26 cargo flights from Kufra to RSF-controlled Sudan documented repeatedly since 2023"}],"econlev":[{"holder":"Haftar / LNA","channel":"Territorial rent + oil","exp":"HIGH","detail":"Sells transit rights to the UAE and basing to Russia; the LNA also controls much of Libya's oil crescent — leverage over a state whose entire economy is hydrocarbons"},{"holder":"Russia","channel":"Basing-for-influence","exp":"HIGH","detail":"Tobruk port + al-Jufra air base = the logistics bridge sustaining Africa Corps in Mali, Burkina and Niger. Libya is how Russia's Sahel deployments get resupplied."},{"holder":"UAE","channel":"Arms transit","exp":"HIGH","detail":"The northern RSF route; Haftar's financier. Same pattern as Chad — buy a corridor, deny it exists."}],"external":[{"actor":"🇷🇺 Russia","side":"Haftar / LNA","flow":"Africa Corps (ex-Wagner) presence; Feb 2025 Tobruk basing agreement with Belarus; al-Jufra reconstruction; moved SAM-7s and AA systems through Kufra to the RSF","tier":"documented","for":"A Mediterranean+Sahel logistics bridge — the supply line for Africa Corps in Mali/Burkina/Niger"},{"actor":"🇦🇪 UAE","side":"Haftar / LNA + RSF","flow":"Haftar's principal backer; runs the northern RSF arms route through Libyan airspace and al-Kufra","tier":"alleged-credible","for":"Sudanese gold; a client state astride the central Mediterranean"},{"actor":"🇪🇬 Egypt","side":"Haftar (but anti-RSF)","flow":"Backs Haftar politically while pressuring eastern Libya to CLOSE the RSF route — Cairo backs the SAF against the UAE's client","tier":"documented","for":"Border security; Nile/Sudan alignment against the UAE-RSF axis"},{"actor":"🇹🇷 Turkey","side":"GNU (Tripoli)","flow":"Drones and military support that defeated Haftar's 2020 Tripoli offensive; maintains the western balance","tier":"documented","for":"Maritime EEZ claims; a foothold opposite Haftar's patrons"}],"mil":"Libya is not fighting a war so much as hosting one. The state has been split since 2014 between the UN-recognized GNU in Tripoli and Khalifa Haftar's LNA in the east and south, with elections perpetually deferred. The consequential military fact is the corridor: the UAE runs RSF resupply on two air routes, and the northern one lands in Haftar's Libya. Al-Kufra airport in the southeast is the node — IL-76 and AN-26 cargo flights documented by satellite imagery and flight tracking, carrying arms into RSF-held Darfur, including SAM-7s and anti-aircraft systems moved by Wagner. It became the RSF's main supply node after Chad scaled back in 2025, and eastern Libyan authorities briefly closed it on 19 January 2026 under Egyptian diplomatic pressure — which is precisely why the Chad route has become more critical.","pol":"The deeper story is Russia building its Africa bridge. In February 2025 Haftar signed a tripartite agreement with Russia and Belarus on joint use of LNA logistics facilities at Tobruk — an air base and a port — and satellite imagery through April 2026 shows reconstruction at al-Jufra air base. This is the infrastructure that sustains Africa Corps deployments in Mali, Burkina Faso and Niger: Libya is how Russia's Sahel presence gets resupplied. The contradiction is instructive. Moscow has shifted most of its Sudan support from the RSF to the SAF — yet its forces in Libya do not interfere with Haftar's arms flow to the RSF. Flow beats alignment, the same lesson the Myanmar theater teaches.","eco":"Haftar's business is renting geography. He sells transit rights to the UAE, basing to Russia, and sits on much of Libya's oil crescent in a state whose entire economy is hydrocarbons. Egypt backs him politically while simultaneously pressuring him to close the RSF route — because Cairo backs Sudan's army against Abu Dhabi's client. Libya is where three patrons' contradictory interests are all being served by the same man at the same time.","assess":"Libya enters at 67 (ELEVATED, conflict-class), trend up — the other half of a pipeline the board was tracking only half of. The Sudan theater's central scandal is who arms the RSF; the answer runs through two corridors, and until now MERIDIAN mapped Chad and missed Libya. Al-Kufra is the northern gate, and it was the RSF's main node after Chad scaled back. The January 2026 closure under Egyptian pressure proves the corridor can be shut — and that no one has sustained the effort. Layered on top is Russia's Africa bridge: Tobruk basing, al-Jufra reconstruction, and the logistics chain that keeps Africa Corps supplied in Mali, Burkina and Niger. That single fact ties Libya to five other theaters on this board. Watch al-Kufra's status, Russian construction at al-Jufra and Tobruk, whether Egypt sustains the pressure, and any move on the perpetually-deferred elections. Trend estimate — newly entered tracking.","tier":"ELEVATED","domain_tag":"Military","contested":{"summary":"Everyone denies the flights. The satellites keep photographing them.","claims":[{"claim":"Haftar denies taking sides in Sudan's war.","who":"Haftar — and the UAE and Russia, who need the corridor deniable.","evid":"Satellite imagery and flight tracking document IL-76 and AN-26 cargo flights from al-Kufra to RSF-held Sudan (CNN, Libya Observer, Agenzia Nova, repeatedly since 2023). The aircraft types are also Libyan-operated, which is exactly the ambiguity the route is designed to exploit — but the pattern, timing and destination are consistent.","status":"DOCUMENTED-BUT-DENIED"},{"claim":"Russia has shifted its Sudan support to the SAF.","who":"Moscow — the SAF offers a Red Sea naval base the RSF cannot.","evid":"True at the diplomatic level, and simultaneously irrelevant on the ground: Russian forces in Libya do not interfere with Haftar's arms flow to the RSF (Jamestown). Moscow backs the army in Port Sudan while its Libyan client supplies the militia. The alignment changed; the flow did not.","status":"CONTESTED — the policy and the pipeline point different directions"}]},"history":{"roots":"Libya's statelessness has an imperial author before it has a Libyan one. Italy's colonization (1911-43) was genocidal: Omar al-Mukhtar's twenty-year resistance was broken by concentration camps in which a quarter to a third of Cyrenaica's population died — a genocide documented by Libyan historian Ali Abdullatif Ahmida and long erased from European memory. The monarchy Italy's defeat produced was a thin Western client; Gaddafi's 1969 coup answered it with oil-funded personalist rule that deliberately kept institutions hollow so nothing could rival him — 42 years of statelessness-by-design beneath a state's costume. NATO's 2011 intervention decapitated the costume and, as the African Union had warned while proposing the negotiated transition NATO bypassed, left the design: no army, no parties, no institutions — just oil, militias, and geography.","timeline":[{"date":"1969","e":"Gaddafi's coup — 42 years of personalist rule begin."},{"date":"2011","e":"NATO-backed revolution kills Gaddafi; the state collapses."},{"date":"2014","e":"Second civil war; the Tripoli-east split hardens."},{"date":"2019-20","e":"Haftar's Tripoli offensive fails when Turkey intervenes."},{"date":"2020","e":"Ceasefire freezes the split; elections perpetually postponed."},{"date":"2023","e":"Derna dam collapse kills thousands — the hollowed state's price."},{"date":"2025-26","e":"Russia's Africa Corps entrenches east; al-Kufra becomes the RSF arms corridor; four new RSF camps identified (Jul 2026); Egypt/Saudi pressure Haftar over the Russia tilt."}],"actors":[{"name":"Khalifa Haftar (LNA)","bio":"The eastern strongman — octogenarian field marshal running a family franchise (sons Saddam and Khaled positioned to inherit); balances Russian patronage against Egyptian and Gulf pressure."},{"name":"Tripoli government (GNU)","bio":"UN-recognized, Turkey-protected, militia-dependent — controls the central bank and oil revenue, not the country."},{"name":"Russia (Africa Corps)","bio":"Eastern Libya as the logistics hub for the whole African project — Sahel supply, RSF arming, Mediterranean presence."},{"name":"UAE / Egypt","bio":"Haftar's original patrons — Abu Dhabi runs RSF supply through his territory; Cairo wants a stable buffer, not a Russian base."}],"bridge":"Every actor in Libya today is farming the hollowness: Haftar's family franchise in the east, militia cartels in Tripoli, Russia's Africa Corps using Cyrenaica — al-Mukhtar's Cyrenaica — as the logistics bridge to the Sahel, and the al-Kufra route arming Sudan's RSF. The migrant-interception economy the EU funds runs through the same detention-camp geography Italy built a century ago, a continuity Ahmida's work makes impossible to unsee. Libya is not a failed state; it is a succeeded design — built hollow twice, by Rome and by Gaddafi, and now rented out by the room.","sources":[{"work":"Genocide in Libya: Shar, a Hidden Colonial History","author":"Ali Abdullatif Ahmida","year":"2020","note":"The Libyan-authored recovery of Italy's concentration-camp genocide in Cyrenaica — the erased foundation."},{"work":"The Making of Modern Libya","author":"Ali Abdullatif Ahmida","year":"1994 (2nd ed. 2009)","note":"State formation, resistance, and the colonial economy from below."},{"work":"A History of Modern Libya","author":"Dirk Vandewalle","year":"2006 (2nd ed. 2012)","note":"The 'hydrocarbon state without institutions' analysis of the monarchy and Gaddafi eras."},{"work":"African Union Ad Hoc Committee on Libya communiqués","author":"African Union","year":"2011","note":"Primary record of the negotiated-transition roadmap NATO's operation bypassed."}]}},{"id":"syria","cat":"political","region":"Middle East","subregion":"Middle East","tclass":"conflict","name":"Syria — Post-Assad Consolidation + SDF Absorption","sub":"al-Sharaa consolidating · SDF forced into integration · Israel occupying the south · Iran expelled","domain":"Post-Regime Consolidation","sev":"high","status":"volatile","since":"Dec 2024 (Assad's fall)","esc":71,"lat":33.5,"lon":36.3,"trend":"ss","esc_history":[74,73,73,72,72,71,71,71,71,71],"hist_real":false,"as_of":"15 Jul 2026","tracked_since":"Wk16 (Jul 2026)","cas":"Jan 2026 NE offensive: SDF-government fighting incl. 40+ SDF suicide-drone strikes in 3 days; Jordanian strikes on Suwayda captagon infrastructure; sectarian killings (Alawite coast, Druze south) since Assad's fall","disp":"Millions still displaced from the 2011-2024 war; returns beginning but incomplete","flag":"🇸🇾","note":"JUL — Trump told Netanyahu in last week's call that Israel should start redeploying forces OUT of Syria — US pressure to unwind the post-Assad Israeli footprint · the US-backed Kirkuk-Baniyas pipeline restoration would run through Syria to the Mediterranean: al-Sharaa's state is being wired into the US-aligned energy map (cross-link: Iraq theater) · NEW THEATER (Wk16 · Syria was referenced across Lebanon/Iran/Gaza but untracked — the hinge of the whole regional realignment) · THE HINGE: Assad fell Dec 2024; Ahmed al-Sharaa (ex-HTS) now president; the Iranian land bridge to Hezbollah was SEVERED — which is why Lebanon's Hezbollah is degraded and why the Axis lost its depth · SDF ABSORBED: Jan 8 2026 the Syrian army attacked SDF positions in Aleppo (Ashrafieh/Sheikh Maqsoud); within 10 days the SDF was beaten and signed a 14-POINT CEASEFIRE AND FULL INTEGRATION AGREEMENT (brokered by US envoy Tom Barrack) handing over Raqqa, Deir ez-Zor, ALL border crossings, the OIL FIELDS, and the ISIS prisoner-of-war camps · 40+ SDF suicide-drone strikes on government targets Jan 24-26; Hasakeh remains SDF-held and contested · a longstanding US ALLY was pressured by its own patron into surrendering to a former al-Qaeda affiliate — Washington, Ankara, and Israel all pushed for it · US delisted al-Sharaa (Res 2799, Nov 2025); Trump-Sharaa call Jan 19; Putin congratulated Sharaa on 'restoring territorial integrity' (Moscow, Jan 28) — Russia, Turkey and the US all backing the same consolidation · ISRAEL occupies southern Syria and strikes at will — a standing Council dispute · JORDAN struck Suwayda (captagon labs, weapons warehouses, smuggling infrastructure) — the drug economy Assad built outliving him · Druze (al-Hijri, Suwayda) and Alawite coastal communities remain unabsorbed; ISIS camps now a government responsibility","leverage":[{"actor":"al-Sharaa government","asset":"Won the SDF war in 10 days; now holds the oil fields, border crossings, and international backing from the US, Turkey AND Russia simultaneously","str":"hi"},{"actor":"Turkey","asset":"The decisive external backer; got the SDF (its PKK-linked enemy) dismantled without firing a shot itself","str":"hi"},{"actor":"Israel","asset":"Occupies southern Syria, strikes freely, and vetoes any threat consolidating on its border","str":"hi"},{"actor":"SDF (Mazloum Abdi)","asset":"Residual force + Hasakeh + Kurdish population — but abandoned by its US patron and absorbed on Damascus's terms","str":"lo"},{"actor":"United States","asset":"Brokered the integration (Barrack), delisted Sharaa, and traded its Kurdish ally for a unified Syria aligned against Iran","str":"hi"}],"gov":[{"src":"UNSC Res 2799 (Nov 2025)","detail":"US-authored; delisted al-Sharaa and his interior minister from the sanctions list — formal Western rehabilitation"},{"src":"US Special Envoy Thomas Barrack","detail":"Brokered the January 2026 SDF integration agreement (credited by the UK at the 18 Mar Council meeting); chaired the Council session"},{"src":"14-Point Ceasefire and Full Integration Agreement (Jan 2026)","detail":"SDF integrates into the Syrian state; Raqqa and Deir ez-Zor handed over immediately, along with border crossings, oil fields, and ISIS POW camps"},{"src":"Middle East Institute (Jan 2026)","detail":"Government resorted to hostilities after repeated 'constructive talks → SDF consultation → zero implementation'; Hasakeh's status remains the contentious unresolved issue"}],"econlev":[{"holder":"Damascus (al-Sharaa)","channel":"Oil fields + border crossings","exp":"HIGH","detail":"The integration agreement transferred the northeast's OIL FIELDS and all border crossings to the government — the SDF's economic base, handed over. This is what the 10-day war was actually about."},{"holder":"Captagon networks","channel":"Narcotics","exp":"MED","detail":"Suwayda remains the production hub for the amphetamine trade Assad built; Jordan struck the labs and warehouses directly — the regime fell but its drug economy didn't"}],"external":[{"actor":"🇹🇷 Turkey","side":"Damascus","flow":"Decisive backer; celebrated the government's advance into SDF territory; got its PKK-linked enemy dismantled by proxy","tier":"documented","for":"Destroy the SDF/PKK border threat; a client state on its southern flank"},{"actor":"🇺🇸 US","side":"Damascus (pivot)","flow":"Delisted al-Sharaa (Res 2799); Barrack brokered the SDF's integration; Trump-Sharaa call affirming 'a strong and unified Syria'","tier":"documented","for":"A Syria permanently outside Iran's orbit — worth trading the Kurdish alliance for"},{"actor":"🇮🇱 Israel","side":"occupier/spoiler","flow":"Occupies southern Syria; strikes at will; a standing UNSC dispute","tier":"documented","for":"A weak, fragmented neighbour; permanent freedom of action"},{"actor":"🇷🇺 Russia","side":"Damascus (accommodation)","flow":"Putin congratulated Sharaa on restoring territorial integrity (Jan 2026); seeking to keep Tartus/Hmeimim basing under the new order","tier":"documented","for":"Retain its Mediterranean naval and air bases after backing the losing side"},{"actor":"🇯🇴 Jordan","side":"counter-narcotics","flow":"Struck captagon labs, weapons warehouses and smuggling infrastructure in Suwayda; new security coordination with Damascus","tier":"documented","for":"Kill the drug trade flooding across its border"}],"mil":"The consolidation war was short and decisive. On 8 January 2026 the Syrian army attacked SDF positions in the Ashrafieh and Sheikh Maqsoud districts of Aleppo; within ten days the SDF was beaten and Mazloum Abdi had signed a fourteen-point Ceasefire and Full Integration Agreement with President Ahmed al-Sharaa. The terms were comprehensive: Raqqa and Deir ez-Zor handed over immediately, along with every border crossing, the oil fields, and administration of the Islamic State prisoner-of-war camps. The SDF fought back hard — more than forty suicide-drone strikes on government targets between 24 and 26 January alone — but the outcome was already fixed. Hasakeh remains in SDF hands and remains the unresolved flashpoint. Israel meanwhile occupies southern Syria and strikes when it chooses, and Jordan has bombed captagon infrastructure in Suwayda.","pol":"This is the hinge of the entire regional realignment, and it explains half the board. Assad's fall in December 2024 severed Iran's land bridge to Hezbollah — which is why Lebanon's Hezbollah is degraded, why the Axis of Resistance lost its strategic depth, and why Iran fights the 2026 war without its forward arm. What followed is stranger: a former al-Qaeda affiliate now runs Damascus with the simultaneous backing of the United States, Turkey and Russia. Washington delisted al-Sharaa by Security Council resolution, its envoy brokered the SDF's surrender, and Putin congratulated him on restoring territorial integrity. The cost was paid by the Kurds: a longstanding US ally was pressured by its own patron into absorption by the government it had spent a decade resisting. The Middle East Institute's account is unsentimental — repeated cycles of talks, consultation, and zero implementation gave Damascus its pretext, and it took it.","eco":"The ten-day war was about the oil. The integration agreement transferred the northeast's oil fields and all border crossings from the SDF to Damascus — the economic base of Kurdish autonomy, signed away. Meanwhile the captagon economy Assad built has outlived him: Suwayda remains the production hub, and Jordan has resorted to airstrikes on the labs and smuggling infrastructure directly.","assess":"Syria enters at 71 (ELEVATED, conflict-class) — the theater the board most quietly depended on. It was referenced inside Lebanon ('supply lines degraded after Syria's fall'), inside Iran, inside Gaza, and tracked nowhere. Yet Assad's fall is the single event that explains the Axis of Resistance's collapse: cut the land bridge and Hezbollah withers, which is why Iran entered the 2026 war without its forward deterrent. The 2026 story is consolidation and its price. Al-Sharaa won the SDF war in ten days and took the oil fields, the crossings, and the ISIS camps — and he did it with the US, Turkey and Russia all backing him at once, which meant Washington brokered the surrender of its own Kurdish ally. Israel occupies the south and strikes at will; Jordan bombs the drug labs; the Druze and Alawite communities remain unabsorbed. Watch Hasakeh (the unresolved flashpoint), whether SDF integration actually implements or fractures, Israeli strike tempo, and any Alawite or Druze rupture. Trend estimate — newly entered tracking.","tier":"ELEVATED","domain_tag":"Political","contested":{"summary":"An integration agreement that was a surrender, brokered by the loser's own patron.","claims":[{"claim":"The SDF's absorption is framed as a negotiated 'integration agreement.'","who":"Damascus, Turkey, and the US — all three needed it to look voluntary.","evid":"It followed a 10-day military defeat. The Syrian army attacked Aleppo on 8 January; the SDF signed within days, handing over Raqqa, Deir ez-Zor, all border crossings, the oil fields and the ISIS camps. Abdi arrived in Damascus asking for the return of territory he had just lost. It was a capitulation with a signature on it.","status":"CONTESTED — 'integration' describes the paperwork, not the process"},{"claim":"The US supports 'a strong and unified Syria.'","who":"Washington — a unified Syria outside Iran's orbit is worth more than a Kurdish militia.","evid":"True, and it required Washington to pressure its own decade-long ally into surrendering to a former al-Qaeda affiliate it had itself delisted two months earlier. The UK explicitly credited the US, and Barrack personally, with brokering it. Both the policy and its cost are documented.","status":"DOCUMENTED"}]},"history":{"roots":"Syria's trajectory is the rise and collapse of the Arab world's most durable police state. The Assad family ruled for 54 years through the Baath party, the Alawite-dominated security services, and calibrated brutality — Hafez's 1982 Hama massacre set the template. The 2011 Arab Spring uprising became a multi-sided civil war that killed ~500,000, drew in Iran, Russia, Hezbollah, Turkey, and the US, and birthed ISIS. Assad survived by making Syria a client of Tehran and Moscow — until both patrons were bled (Ukraine, the Israel-Hezbollah war), and in December 2024 a lightning HTS offensive toppled him in eleven days. Ahmed al-Sharaa, once an al-Qaeda commander, now presides over the reconstruction of a shattered state — the hinge on which the whole regional realignment turns.","timeline":[{"date":"1970","e":"Hafez al-Assad seizes power; Alawite-security-state model established."},{"date":"1982","e":"Hama massacre (~20,000+ killed) crushes the Muslim Brotherhood."},{"date":"2011","e":"Arab Spring uprising; regime chooses repression; civil war begins."},{"date":"2013-14","e":"Chemical attacks; ISIS declares its caliphate from Raqqa."},{"date":"2015","e":"Russia intervenes, saving Assad; Iran/Hezbollah entrench."},{"date":"Dec 2024","e":"HTS offensive topples Assad in 11 days; he flees to Moscow."},{"date":"2025","e":"Ahmed al-Sharaa becomes president; sanctions relief begins; sectarian massacres test the new state."},{"date":"2026","e":"US backs Kirkuk-Baniyas pipeline through Syria; Trump presses Israel to redeploy out; the realignment hinge turns."}],"actors":[{"name":"Ahmed al-Sharaa","bio":"Ex-al-Qaeda/HTS commander (once Abu Mohammad al-Jolani, $10M US bounty) turned president — the most consequential rebrand in modern Middle East politics. Balancing Islamist base, minority fears, and Western courtship."},{"name":"Turkey","bio":"The new Syria's chief sponsor — backed the offensive that won, now shapes reconstruction and security; its influence is what Israel strikes to limit."},{"name":"Israel","bio":"Seized a buffer zone beyond the Golan after Assad fell and strikes military assets — under US pressure (Jul 2026) to redeploy out."},{"name":"Russia / Iran","bio":"The losers — Moscow bargaining over its Tartus/Hmeimim bases, Tehran's land bridge to Hezbollah severed. Their exit is the realignment."},{"name":"SDF / Kurds","bio":"The US-partnered northeast — negotiating integration with Damascus while Turkey watches; the unresolved piece of the new map."}],"bridge":"Al-Sharaa's Syria is the revolution's paradox come to power: al-Haj Saleh's 'impossible revolution' — crushed between the regime and the jihadists — ends with a jihadist-turned-statesman inheriting the ruins, courted by the same powers that watched the crushing. The Kirkuk-Baniyas pipeline and Israel's redeployment pressure show the new state's function in the regional order being negotiated over its head, as ever; whether the sectarian massacres of 2025 were birth pangs or preview is the live question every minority is hedging against.","sources":[{"work":"The Impossible Revolution: Making Sense of the Syrian Tragedy","author":"Yassin al-Haj Saleh","year":"2017","note":"The Syrian dissident-intellectual's account — 16 years in Assad's prisons behind it."},{"work":"Syria's Peasantry, the Descendants of Its Lesser Rural Notables, and Their Politics","author":"Hanna Batatu","year":"1999","note":"The social structure beneath Assadism — the Alawite security state's rural roots."},{"work":"Caesar photographs / UN Commission of Inquiry on Syria","author":"'Caesar' defector archive; UN HRC","year":"2014-26","note":"Primary atrocity documentation of the regime era — the record the new state inherits."}]},"human":{"dead":500000,"disp":12000000,"famine":false,"aid":"transition-fragile","note":"~500k dead across the civil war; 12M+ displaced (6M+ refugees) — the world's largest refugee crisis before Sudan; returns beginning, sectarian massacres deter."}},{"id":"russia-domestic","cat":"economic","region":"Europe / Russia","subregion":"Europe","tclass":"watch","name":"Russia — War Economy at Structural Exhaustion","sub":"Kiel: 'structural exhaustion' · NWF liquid 6.5%→1.8% of GDP · VAT hiked · China dependency","domain":"War Economy / Regime Sustainability","sev":"high","status":"escalating","since":"2022 (war footing)","esc":72,"lat":55.75,"lon":37.62,"trend":"up","esc_history":[66,67,68,69,70,71,71,72,72,72],"hist_real":false,"as_of":"15 Jul 2026","tracked_since":"Wk16 (Jul 2026)","cas":"Military casualties estimated in excess of 1.38M personnel since 2022; several hundred thousand skilled workers emigrated","disp":"Labour market structurally scarred — unemployment at 2.4% because the military absorbed the workers the civilian economy shed","flag":"🇷🇺","note":"NEW THEATER (Wk16 · the board tracked the WAR but not the STATE WAGING IT — the single largest structural gap in Europe coverage) · KIEL INSTITUTE (Jun 2026): Russia now faces 'STRUCTURAL EXHAUSTION' — the liquid portion of the National Wealth Fund has fallen from 6.5% of GDP (Feb 2022) to 1.8% (Apr 2026); federal deficit has exceeded full-year targets · SIPRI (Apr 2026): Russia spent $190B on its military in 2025 = 7.5% of GDP, the highest share since the USSR's collapse; now the world's 3rd-largest military spender · Q1 2026 military spending hit a RECORD 5.9tn roubles (~$75-80B), +30% y/y, nearly 5x the pre-invasion level — for the first time since Feb 2022, almost every SECOND rouble of federal spending went to military purposes; >1/3 of all budget expenditure is now CLASSIFIED (~84% of defence spending sits in classified lines) · THE BILL IS COMING DUE: GDP growth collapsed from 4%+ (2023-24) to ~1% (2025-26); the 'military Keynesianism' sugar rush is over · social spending fell from 38% to 25% of the federal budget; economic-development programmes cut to 10.9% (lowest in 2 decades) · VAT raised 20%→22% on Jan 1 2026; the SME VAT threshold slashed 60M→10M roubles; a new levy on electronics · interest rates 15-21% have collapsed capital investment; debt servicing now ~9% of public funds · Putin has begun asking OLIGARCHS to 'donate' to the budget · World Bank: Brent averaging ~$60 in 2026 (5-yr low) — BUT the Iran war and Hormuz closure are an unexpected oil windfall easing the budget (SIPRI notes this explicitly) · Ukrainian deep-strikes have cut refining to a 16-yr low; fuel stations in Belgorod stopped selling entirely (Jun 2026) · CARNEGIE: by 2026-27 the fiscal and social challenges could 'fully metastasise into a crisis' · COUNTER-READ LOGGED: this is not collapse — no bank runs, shelves stocked, and Connolly notes Russian inflation does not reliably produce mass dissatisfaction. Structurally exhausted ≠ broken.","leverage":[{"actor":"Putin / the Kremlin","asset":"Can still extract more — tax hikes, oligarch 'donations', classified reallocation, the President's Reserve Fund spendable at his sole discretion","str":"hi"},{"actor":"China","asset":"The oxygen supply — technology, dual-use components, and the oil market that keeps the war financed. The dependency is asymmetric and deepening","str":"hi"},{"actor":"Ukraine (deep-strike)","asset":"Refining at a 16-yr low; ~40% of export capacity intermittently halted — the one lever directly attacking the revenue base","str":"hi"},{"actor":"Gulf oil windfall (Hormuz)","asset":"The Iran war's price spike is the external lifeline nobody planned — it eases the 2026 budget precisely when it was tightest","str":"md"},{"actor":"Western sanctions architecture","asset":"Shrank oil-and-gas from 42% of budget revenue (2022) to ~22% (2026) — but SITE notes even harsher energy sanctions would not by themselves stop the war financing","str":"md"}],"gov":[{"src":"SIPRI (Apr 2026 + Insights 2026/01)","detail":"$190B spent in 2025 = 7.5% of GDP, highest share since the Soviet collapse; 2026 budget plans 14.9tn roubles (6.3% GDP) — but the budget was amended twice in 2025 and will likely be amended again"},{"src":"Kiel Institute for the World Economy (Jun 2026)","detail":"Russia faces 'structural exhaustion'; NWF liquid share down from 6.5% of GDP (Feb 2022) to 1.8% (Apr 2026); deficit exceeded full-year targets"},{"src":"Bank of Finland / BOFIT","detail":"Growth has returned to its long-term potential (~1%); external and internal risks 'significantly' up; recession a real possibility"},{"src":"Russian Presidential Academy economists","detail":"Warned the National Wealth Fund 'could be exhausted by 2026 if current economic trends persist' — extraordinary bluntness from inside the system"},{"src":"Defence Minister Belousov (Dec 2025)","detail":"Put 2025 defence spending at 7.3% of GDP — implying ~15.86tn roubles, well ABOVE the published budget figure"}],"econlev":[{"holder":"China","channel":"Technology + oil market","exp":"HIGH","detail":"The dependency asymmetry is the structural story: Beijing supplies the components and buys the crude that keep the war running, on terms it sets. Russia's survival is now a Chinese decision as much as a Russian one."},{"holder":"Russia","channel":"Gold + shadow-fleet oil","exp":"HIGH","detail":"Funding the war outside the dollar system — including African conflict gold routed via Africa Corps concessions in Mali, Burkina and Sudan. The Sahel theaters on this board are, in part, Russian war finance."},{"holder":"Russian households","channel":"Tax + inflation transfer","exp":"HIGH","detail":"VAT 20→22%, SME threshold cut 6x, electronics levy, social spending down 38%→25% of budget — the population is the financing mechanism of last resort"}],"external":[{"actor":"🇨🇳 China","side":"Russia (economic)","flow":"Dual-use components, machine tools, and the purchase of sanctioned crude; declines 'lethal aid' by a narrow definition","tier":"documented","for":"A dependent great-power partner and discounted energy — Russia's weakness is China's leverage"},{"actor":"🇰🇵 North Korea","side":"Russia","flow":"Troops fighting and dying in Ukraine, plus artillery and missiles, traded for technology, energy and food","tier":"documented","for":"Regime revenue and military technology from a great-power patron"},{"actor":"🇮🇷 Iran","side":"Russia","flow":"Shahed drone supply and production-line transfer — and now, indirectly, an oil-price windfall via the Hormuz closure","tier":"documented","for":"Anti-Western axis depth; combat-testing its drone ecosystem"},{"actor":"🇺🇸🇪🇺 US/EU","side":"sanctioning","flow":"Sanctions cut oil-and-gas from 42% (2022) to ~22% (2026) of budget revenue; the shadow fleet and Chinese purchases blunt the rest","tier":"documented","for":"Deny the war its financing — a lever that constrains without breaking"}],"ext_flag":true,"mil":"Not a front — this is the engine room of the front. In the first quarter of 2026 Russian military spending hit a record 5.9 trillion roubles (roughly $75-80 billion), nearly 30% higher than a year earlier and almost five times the pre-invasion level; for the first time since February 2022, close to every second rouble the federal government spent went to military purposes. SIPRI puts 2025 spending at $190 billion — 7.5% of GDP, the highest share since the Soviet Union collapsed, and third in the world behind only the United States and China. That ranking was not earned by growth; it was chosen, at the expense of nearly everything else. More than a third of all budget expenditure is now classified, with roughly 84% of defence spending hidden in closed lines, which means the published figures are a floor, not a measurement.","pol":"The Kremlin's fiscal room is narrowing and it is passing the bill to the population. VAT rose from 20% to 22% on 1 January 2026, the threshold at which small businesses must pay it was cut sixfold, and a new levy landed on electronics. Social spending has fallen from 38% to 25% of the federal budget and economic-development programmes to 10.9%, the lowest in at least two decades. Putin has begun asking oligarchs to 'donate' to the budget — a sign the state is no longer looking only downward for the money. Russia's own Presidential Academy economists warned that the National Wealth Fund could be exhausted in 2026, a remarkable admission from inside the system. What the budget does not show is a pivot to peace: defence and internal security together take roughly 38-40% of all spending, and the formal 'cut' to the defence line is an accounting convention, not a decision.","eco":"The Kiel Institute's June 2026 report is the anchor finding: Russia has reached 'structural exhaustion.' The liquid portion of the National Wealth Fund has collapsed from 6.5% of GDP in February 2022 to 1.8% in April 2026. Growth has fallen from over 4% in the wartime boom years to roughly 1%, which BOFIT judges to be simply the economy's long-run potential — the sugar rush of military Keynesianism is spent. Interest rates of 15-21% have crushed capital investment, debt service now consumes about 9% of public funds, and labour shortages are structural rather than cyclical after 1.38 million-plus military casualties and the emigration of several hundred thousand skilled workers. Two things are holding the ceiling up: China, which supplies the technology and buys the crude, and — with grim irony for this board — the Iran war, whose Hormuz closure has handed Moscow an oil-price windfall precisely when its budget needed one.","assess":"Russia enters at 72 (ELEVATED, strategic-watch), trend up — and it closes the largest single gap in the platform's Europe coverage: MERIDIAN tracked the war and not the state waging it. The finding is not that Russia is collapsing. It is that Russia is being consumed. Kiel calls it structural exhaustion; Carnegie warns the fiscal and social strains could metastasise into a crisis by 2026-27; and yet there are no bank runs, the shelves are stocked, and unemployment sits at 2.4% — because the military absorbed the workers the civilian economy shed. Endgames in authoritarian resource states do not arrive as events; they arrive as accumulating constraints punctuated by windfalls that create false dawns. The Hormuz oil spike is exactly such a windfall. The two variables that actually decide this theater are external: whether China keeps supplying the oxygen, and whether Ukraine's deep-strike campaign keeps cutting the revenue. Watch the NWF liquid balance, the classified-spending share, oil above or below $60, and any second mobilisation — each round of extraction now costs Putin more politically than the last.","tier":"ELEVATED","domain_tag":"Economic","contested":{"summary":"Everyone agrees the numbers are bad. Nobody agrees what they mean — and the loudest claim on both sides is wrong.","claims":[{"claim":"Russia's 2026 budget shows a REDUCTION in defence spending — evidence of restraint or of running out of money.","who":"Both sides read this one wrong. Moscow likes the optics of discipline; Western commentators like the optics of exhaustion.","evid":"It is an accounting artefact. Since 2023 the detailed expenditure structure has been classified, and the government may reallocate between lines without amending the budget law. Extra revenue can go straight into the President's Reserve Fund and be spent at his discretion. Meanwhile Q1 2026 actual military spending hit a RECORD 5.9tn roubles. The line went down; the spending went up.","status":"CONTESTED — the published cut is not a real cut"},{"claim":"The Russian war economy is collapsing / about to crash.","who":"Those who need sanctions to be working faster than they are.","evid":"Kiel says 'structural exhaustion'; BOFIT says recession is possible. But there are no bank runs, shelves are stocked, unemployment is 2.4%, and Connolly notes Russian inflation does not reliably translate into mass dissatisfaction. Structurally exhausted is not the same as broken — and the Hormuz oil windfall just bought another year.","status":"CONTESTED — deterioration is real, collapse is not imminent"},{"claim":"Sanctions have failed because Russia is still fighting.","who":"Sanctions sceptics — and Moscow, which has every reason to project invulnerability.","evid":"Oil-and-gas fell from 42% of budget revenue (2022) to ~22% (2026); the NWF's liquid cushion is nearly gone; taxes are rising on a population that was promised the war was free. SITE's point is sharper: sanctions did not stop the war, but they converted it from something Russia could afford into something Russia must extract from its own people to sustain.","status":"CONTESTED — judge the lever by what it actually does"}]},"history":{"roots":"Russia's present is Putin's answer to the 1990s — the humiliation of Soviet collapse, oligarchic looting, and NATO's advance, answered with recentralized power, resource-rent statehood, and revanchism. A quarter-century of Putinism hollowed every institution but the security services; the Ukraine war completed the transformation into a war economy and police state. Sanctions, 700k+ casualties, labor shortages and structural exhaustion (the Kiel Institute's read) grind beneath a stable surface. The system's core question was always succession — Putin has none — and its method is the export of instability: hybrid war on Europe as compensation for a stalemate it cannot win outright.","timeline":[{"date":"1991","e":"USSR collapses — the founding trauma of Putinism."},{"date":"2000","e":"Putin takes power; the vertical rebuilt on oil rents."},{"date":"2008/2014","e":"Georgia war; Crimea annexation — the revisionist turn."},{"date":"2022","e":"Full-scale Ukraine invasion; war economy begins."},{"date":"2023","e":"Prigozhin mutiny exposes the system's brittleness; he dies in a crash."},{"date":"2024-25","e":"Militarized budget (~40% security); shadow fleet + sabotage campaign on Europe."},{"date":"2026","e":"Structural exhaustion thesis (Kiel); hybrid escalation against NATO's flank as the war stalemates."}],"actors":[{"name":"Vladimir Putin","bio":"Ruler since 2000 — the system is him; no succession mechanism exists, which is itself the biggest risk in Russian politics."},{"name":"The siloviki / FSB","bio":"The security-service aristocracy running the war economy, the repression, and the sabotage campaign abroad (Centre 16 et al.)."},{"name":"The war economy","bio":"Defense-driven growth masking civilian decay — the Kiel thesis: structurally exhausted, politically locked in."},{"name":"China","bio":"The senior partner Russia pretends is an equal — buyer of its oil, supplier of its components, ceiling on its options."}],"bridge":"The structural-exhaustion thesis meets the escalation record: a war economy at ~40% of the budget cannot demobilize without recession nor win without mobilization it fears — so the system exports the pressure as hybrid war (the flank campaign) and imports substitution (North Korean shells, Chinese components). Frye's 'weak strongman' frame explains the paradox the sweeps keep logging: maximal external aggression, minimal internal slack, no succession mechanism. The theater's tripwire is not a coup date; it is whether exhaustion or escalation compounds faster.","sources":[{"work":"Weak Strongman: The Limits of Power in Putin's Russia","author":"Timothy Frye","year":"2021","note":"The political-science corrective to both 'master strategist' and 'collapsing regime' narratives."},{"work":"The Invention of Russia","author":"Arkady Ostrovsky","year":"2015","note":"How the 1990s trauma was converted into the media-state that sustains the war."},{"work":"Kiel Institute Russia analyses","author":"Kiel Institute for the World Economy","year":"2024-26","note":"Primary economic series behind the structural-exhaustion assessment this file cites."}]}},{"id":"nato-flank","cat":"military","region":"Europe / Russia","subregion":"Europe","tclass":"conflict","name":"NATO Eastern Flank — Eastern Sentry + the Drone Gap","sub":"Article 4 twice · airspace violated across 7 allies · $Mn jets vs $10k drones · 'drone wall' 2-3 yrs away","domain":"Gray-Zone Probing / Alliance Deterrence","sev":"high","status":"escalating","since":"Sep 2025 (Eastern Sentry)","esc":71,"lat":52.23,"lon":21.01,"trend":"up","esc_history":[62,63,64,65,66,67,67,68,68,71],"hist_real":false,"as_of":"15 Jul 2026","tracked_since":"Wk16 (Jul 2026)","cas":"No fatalities — by design. The entire campaign is calibrated to stay below the threshold that would trigger Article 5","disp":"N/A — airspace closures, airport shutdowns, and civil-aviation disruption across the eastern flank","flag":"🛡️","note":"JUL 15 — COORDINATED BALTIC WARNING DAY: Lithuania's Nausėda says intelligence shows Russia planning 'limited kinetic operations' against critical infrastructure in the Baltics/Poland — specifically naming the facilities synchronizing Baltic grids with continental Europe · Latvia's Rinkēvičs: Russia may 'indirectly test Article 5' — 'the next few months, even 12 months, will be crucial' · Poland intercepted Russian aircraft over the Baltic Tue+Wed surveilling Polish air defenses · JUL 13: EU+UK formally ATTRIBUTED the Dec cyber attack on a Polish heat/power plant (500k customers) to FSB Centre 16 — first formal state attribution of that strike · IISS: Russia likely used SHADOW-FLEET SHIPS to launch the 2024-26 drone incursions that disrupted European aviation · Russia ran its first live-fire snap exercise on its side of Lake Peipus (Estonia border) last week · context: Latvian PM Siliņa resigned in May over stray-drone handling; Vilnius saw NATO-capital-first shelter warnings in May · Merz: hybrid war on Germany 'already underway' · NEW THEATER (Wk16 · Europe had 2 theaters on a board of 45 — this is the NATO-Russia friction surface itself) · THE TRIGGER: 10 Sep 2025 — around 19-20 Russian drones penetrated POLISH airspace during strikes on Ukraine; allied aircraft shot several down — the FIRST known kinetic action by a NATO member against Russian assets in the war · Poland invoked ARTICLE 4; NATO launched OPERATION EASTERN SENTRY within 48 hours (12 Sep 2025, announced by SecGen Rutte + SACEUR Gen. Alexus Grynkewich) — multidomain, 'from the High North to the Black Sea,' no stated end date · a week later Russian MiG-31s violated ESTONIAN airspace → Estonia invoked ARTICLE 4 TOO · NATO's own count: Sept 2025 saw Russian drones and aircraft violate the airspace of ESTONIA, FINLAND, LATVIA, LITHUANIA, NORWAY, POLAND and ROMANIA — seven allies · builds on BALTIC SENTRY (launched 14 Jan 2025 after undersea-cable sabotage; NATO officials privately call it a success — no new cable cuts since) · FORCE: 9 multinational Forward Land Forces battlegroups (Bulgaria, Estonia, Finland, Hungary, Latvia, Lithuania, Poland, Romania, Slovakia); Canada to 2,200 troops in Latvia by 2026; 10,000+ US troops in Poland; France/Germany/Denmark/UK committed jets · THE STRUCTURAL PROBLEM — COST EXCHANGE: NATO is intercepting $10-20k Shahed-type drones with multimillion-dollar fighters and missiles. That trade loses even when every shot hits · THE FIX IS YEARS OUT: a European 'DRONE WALL' is 2-3 years away in the BEST case; interim measures = Latvia's acoustic sensors, cheaper air-launched munitions, and Ukrainian-style mobile fire teams · POLITICAL TELL: Trump suggested the Polish incursion 'could have been a mistake'; Tusk publicly contradicted him — a rare open break by a close ally · Russia's Nebenzya claimed the drones physically could not have reached Poland","leverage":[{"actor":"Russia","asset":"Deniable, cheap, repeatable probing — measuring NATO's language ('violation' vs 'aggression'), response times, and cohesion at a cost of a few drones","str":"hi"},{"actor":"NATO (SACEUR Grynkewich)","asset":"Eastern Sentry + 9 battlegroups + Article 5 — overwhelming at the top of the ladder, poorly matched at the bottom rung where the fighting actually is","str":"hi"},{"actor":"Poland","asset":"The alliance's frontline state and biggest defence spender by GDP share; hosts 10,000+ US troops; chose Article 4 CONSULTATION over escalation — keeping decision-space open while signalling resolve","str":"hi"},{"actor":"The cost-exchange gap","asset":"The real vulnerability: a $10k drone against a $2M interceptor is a losing trade at scale, and Moscow knows the arithmetic","str":"md"},{"actor":"Belarus","asset":"The launch platform and staging ground — Oreshnik-hosting, drone-corridor providing; the flank's threat geography runs through Minsk","str":"md"}],"gov":[{"src":"NATO / SecGen Rutte (12 Sep 2025)","detail":"Launched Eastern Sentry after Poland's Article 4 request; called the incursion 'the largest concentration of violations of NATO airspace' and 'not an isolated incident'"},{"src":"NATO (as of Jun 2026)","detail":"Nine multinational battlegroups on the eastern flank; Russian drones and planes violated the airspace of Estonia, Finland, Latvia, Lithuania, Norway, Poland and Romania in Sept 2025"},{"src":"SACEUR Gen. Alexus Grynkewich","detail":"Eastern Sentry is flexible and multidomain, covering the flank from the High North to the Black Sea and Mediterranean; 'NATO will defend every inch of its territory'"},{"src":"Polish government (Tusk / Pres. Nawrocki)","detail":"Called the incursion an 'attack,' rejected the suggestion it was a mistake; Nawrocki formalized consent for allied forces to deploy on Polish soil"}],"econlev":[{"holder":"Russia","channel":"Cost-imposition","exp":"HIGH","detail":"Each cheap drone forces a multimillion-dollar interception, an airspace closure, and an alliance-wide consultation. The economics of the probe are the point of the probe."},{"holder":"EU / NATO","channel":"Drone-wall procurement","exp":"MED","detail":"The EU has signalled readiness to fund a counter-UAS 'drone wall' — but it is 2-3 years away at best, which defines the window Moscow is currently operating inside"}],"external":[{"actor":"🇷🇺 Russia","side":"prober","flow":"Drone and fighter incursions across seven allies' airspace; undersea-cable sabotage in the Baltic; denies everything","tier":"documented","for":"Test alliance thresholds and cohesion below the Article 5 line — and find out what Washington will actually do"},{"actor":"🇧🇾 Belarus","side":"Russia","flow":"Territory used for drone routing into Ukraine (per Zelensky, Dec 2025) and now hosting Oreshnik IRBMs — 11 minutes from a Polish air base by Russian state media's own boast","tier":"documented","for":"Regime survival paid for in geography"},{"actor":"🇺🇸 US","side":"NATO","flow":"10,000+ troops in Poland; SACEUR is a US general; but Trump publicly floated that the incursion 'could have been a mistake'","tier":"documented","for":"Alliance leadership — while pressing Europe to carry more of it"},{"actor":"🇫🇷🇩🇪🇩🇰🇬🇧 France/Germany/Denmark/UK","side":"NATO","flow":"Rafales, Eurofighters, F-16s and an anti-air frigate committed to Eastern Sentry within days","tier":"documented","for":"Demonstrate that the flank defends the whole alliance — Rutte's line: Russian missiles could reach Madrid or London in minutes"}],"ext_flag":true,"mil":"On 10 September 2025 roughly nineteen to twenty Russian drones crossed into Polish airspace during a mass strike on Ukraine, and allied aircraft shot several of them down — the first known kinetic engagement between a NATO member and Russian assets in this war. Poland invoked Article 4. Within forty-eight hours NATO launched Operation Eastern Sentry, a multidomain reinforcement of the entire flank from the High North to the Black Sea, and a week later Russian MiG-31s violated Estonian airspace, prompting Tallinn to invoke Article 4 as well. NATO's own tally for that month lists airspace violations across seven allies: Estonia, Finland, Latvia, Lithuania, Norway, Poland and Romania. Nine multinational battlegroups now sit on the flank, and the operation has no stated end date.","pol":"The probing is political before it is military. Moscow is measuring language — whether allies say 'violation' or 'aggression' — along with response times and, above all, cohesion. It found a seam almost immediately: President Trump suggested the Polish incursion 'could have been a mistake,' and Prime Minister Tusk publicly contradicted him, a rare open break from one of Washington's closest allies. Poland's choice to consult under Article 4 rather than escalate kept decision-space open while signalling resolve — the correct move, and also an admission that the alliance has no good answer at this rung of the ladder. Russia's UN envoy simply denied the drones could physically have reached Poland.","eco":"The decisive fact is arithmetic. NATO is intercepting Shahed-type drones that cost ten to twenty thousand dollars using multimillion-dollar fighters and missiles — a trade the alliance loses even when every shot hits. That is the vulnerability the incursions are designed to expose, and closing it is slow: a European counter-drone 'wall' is two to three years away in the best case, even with EU funding. The interim fixes are borrowed from Ukraine and from the flank's own smallest states — Latvia's acoustic sensor work, cheaper air-launched munitions, and mobile fire teams. Baltic Sentry, launched in January 2025 after the undersea-cable sabotage, is the precedent that gives NATO officials some confidence: since it began, there have been no new cable cuts.","assess":"The NATO Eastern Flank enters at 68 (ELEVATED, conflict-class for the live kinetic engagements), trend up — and it is the theater the board's Europe coverage was built around without ever naming. Its defining feature is calibration: this is a campaign engineered to sit permanently one rung below Article 5, which makes miscalculation, not intent, the primary escalation risk — the same structure as the South China Sea, with the same danger. Two things make it worse than the Pacific analogue. First, the cost-exchange gap is a standing invitation: Russia can impose millions in cost and alliance-wide consultations for the price of a few drones, and the fix is years out. Second, the alliance's political cohesion is now itself a target, and Moscow has already found the seam between Warsaw and Washington. Watch the drone-wall procurement timeline, whether any incursion produces a fatality (the tripwire), the Belarus staging corridor, and any further public daylight between the US and the frontline states. Trend estimate — newly entered tracking.","tier":"ELEVATED","domain_tag":"Military","contested":{"summary":"Deny the drones, deny the intent, and let the alliance argue with itself about which word to use.","claims":[{"claim":"Russia denies the drone incursions — its UN envoy said the drones' 700km range made reaching Poland 'physically impossible.'","who":"Moscow — deniability is the entire operating principle of a probe. An admitted attack forces a response; an ambiguous one forces a debate.","evid":"Sixteen to twenty drones were recovered across hundreds of square miles of Polish territory. Poland shot several down. NATO recorded violations across seven allies in the same month. Rutte's formulation is the honest one: whether or not it was deliberate, Russia violated NATO airspace.","status":"DOCUMENTED-BUT-DENIED"},{"claim":"The incursion 'could have been a mistake.'","who":"Trump, who floated it — and Moscow, for whom an American president supplying the ambiguity is worth more than any denial it could issue itself.","evid":"Tusk publicly rejected it, calling the incursion an attack — a rare direct contradiction of a US president by a close ally. NATO called it the largest concentration of airspace violations of the war and 'not an isolated incident.' The pattern across seven allies is not consistent with error.","status":"CONTESTED — the alliance's own assessment says otherwise"}]},"history":{"roots":"The eastern flank is where NATO's Article 5 promise meets Russia's test of it. The Baltics and Poland — annexed or dominated by Moscow within living memory — joined NATO in 1999/2004 precisely against this day. Since 2022 the flank has absorbed the war's spillover: drone incursions, GPS jamming, cable cuttings, sabotage, and assassination plots — a calibrated campaign beneath the Article 5 threshold. The Suwałki Gap (the 65km Polish-Lithuanian corridor between Kaliningrad and Belarus) remains the alliance's most studied vulnerability. The strategic question of 2026: whether Russia, stalemated in Ukraine, tests the alliance indirectly — and whether the alliance's tripwire forces and its wobbling American anchor deter it.","timeline":[{"date":"1999/2004","e":"Poland, then the Baltics, join NATO — escape from the Russian sphere."},{"date":"2016","e":"Enhanced Forward Presence — tripwire battalions deploy east."},{"date":"2022","e":"Ukraine invasion; the flank becomes the frontier."},{"date":"2024-25","e":"Sabotage wave: cables, arson, drone incursions, Vilnius shelter warnings."},{"date":"Dec 2025","e":"Cyber attack on Polish power plant (500k customers) — later attributed to FSB Centre 16."},{"date":"Jul 2026","e":"Coordinated Baltic warnings: Lithuania cites intel of planned Russian 'limited kinetic operations'; Latvia warns of an indirect Article 5 test within 12 months."}],"actors":[{"name":"Poland + the Baltics","bio":"The flank states — highest defense spenders in NATO by GDP share, loudest warners, first in line."},{"name":"Russia (GRU/FSB)","bio":"The hybrid campaign's author — sabotage, cyber, drones, all calibrated to stay deniable and below the treaty threshold."},{"name":"Germany (Merz)","bio":"The awakened middle — 'hybrid war already underway'; rearmament as the flank's strategic depth."},{"name":"United States","bio":"The anchor whose reliability is the whole deterrent — and the variable every flank capital now hedges against."}],"bridge":"The July 2026 warning stack — Vilnius naming grid-sync targets, Riga putting a 12-month clock on an Article 5 test, the FSB Centre 16 attribution — converts the flank from a deterrence posture into a countdown ledger: the platform's own Watchlist now carries the exact scenario the region's intelligence services published. The strategic novelty is attribution-in-public: naming the sabotage author is itself the new deterrent, betting that documented culpability raises Russia's cost where ambiguity once lowered it.","sources":[{"work":"Lithuanian State Security (VSD) & Latvian SAB annual threat assessments","author":"Baltic intelligence services","year":"2024-26","note":"Primary published warnings — the source layer behind the July 2026 statements."},{"work":"EU/UK attribution of the Polish grid cyberattack to FSB Centre 16","author":"EU Council / UK NCSC","year":"Jul 2026","note":"Primary formal state attribution."},{"work":"IISS shadow-fleet and drone-incursion analyses","author":"IISS","year":"2025-26","note":"The maritime-launch assessment cited in this theater."}]}},{"id":"moldova","cat":"political","region":"Europe / Russia","subregion":"Europe","tclass":"watch","name":"Moldova — Transnistria Passportisation + the Donbas Template","sub":"Putin decree (15 May) · Shoigu: '220,000 Russian citizens under threat' · law permitting force abroad to protect them","domain":"Frozen Conflict / Passportisation","sev":"high","status":"volatile","since":"1992 (ceasefire)","esc":61,"lat":46.84,"lon":29.62,"trend":"up","esc_history":[52,52,53,55,58,60,61,61,61,61],"hist_real":false,"as_of":"15 Jul 2026","tracked_since":"Wk16 (Jul 2026)","cas":"No current combat deaths — the 1992 war ended in a ceasefire that has held; ~1,500 Russian troops remain deployed","disp":"N/A — Transnistria's ~350,000-455,000 residents live under an unrecognized administration inside Moldova's borders","flag":"🇲🇩","note":"JUL — Sandu visited Kyiv (Moscow spinning it as 'arms transit through Moldova' groundwork); Russian MFA now formally advises Russians that Moldova is 'not a safe country for travel' — the rhetorical escalation track continues; Merz named Moldova alongside the Baltics as a target of Russia's next-phase aggression · NEW THEATER (Wk16 · the Donbas playbook, running live, on a second border) · THE SEQUENCE IS THE STORY — (1) APR 2026: Sergei Shoigu warned that more than 220,000 RUSSIAN CITIZENS in Transnistria were 'under threat' and that Russia could use 'all available constitutional means' to protect them · (2) 15 MAY 2026: Putin signed a decree granting FAST-TRACK Russian citizenship to any adult resident of Transnistria — waiving the 5-year residency rule, the language test, and the history/law exams · (3) 20 MAY 2026: the Russian FEDERATION COUNCIL finalised legislation ALLOWING THE KREMLIN TO DEPLOY THE MILITARY ABROAD to protect Russian nationals facing legal action by foreign courts Moscow does not recognise · (4) Zakharova: 'Any aggression against our fellow citizens living in Transnistria will receive an immediate and adequate response' · that is the Donbas architecture assembled in five weeks: manufacture the citizens, declare them threatened, legislate the right to intervene · CONTEXT — of ~350,000-455,000 residents, an estimated 200,000-250,000 ALREADY hold Russian passports; ~1,500 Russian troops have been there since 1992, most of them locals with Russian passports · WHAT PROVOKED IT: Moldova is winning the slow war. Chișinău passed a Dec 2025 law stripping Moldovan citizenship from Transnistrians serving in its security organs; pushed VAT/excise/customs harmonisation; and circulated a reintegration 'non-paper' to European partners. Russian energy subsidies — the model that sustained Transnistria — have collapsed. Even the SHERIFF conglomerate, the region's economic spine, has reoriented toward EU markets · GMF's READ (Jun 2026): passportisation here is a sign of Russian WEAKNESS, not strength — Moscow rebuilding leverage precisely because its older instruments have failed · SANDU: the decree is probably about 'needing more people to send to the war in Ukraine' · ZELENSKY: it is 'Russia's way of staking a claim to Transnistria's territory' · PRECEDENT: the identical decree was issued for Abkhazia and South Ossetia in May 2025, and for occupied Ukraine in March","leverage":[{"actor":"Russia","asset":"An extraterritorial legal constituency of 220,000+ 'citizens' inside another state's borders — plus a fresh law authorising force to protect them. The pretext is now pre-built.","str":"hi"},{"actor":"Moldova (Sandu)","asset":"Economic strangulation that is working — customs duties, tax harmonisation, and a reintegration blueprint drawing Transnistria into Moldova's legal and fiscal space, step by step","str":"md"},{"actor":"Transnistria (Tiraspol) / Sheriff","asset":"The dominant conglomerate has reoriented toward EUROPEAN markets — the elite's own money is quietly voting against Moscow","str":"md"},{"actor":"Geography","asset":"The decisive constraint: Ukraine's border is CLOSED. Russia cannot physically reinforce Transnistria without going through Ukraine or Moldova. The threat is real; the logistics are not.","str":"hi"},{"actor":"Ukraine","asset":"Zelensky has ordered joint assessment and possible joint response with Chișinău — the 1,500 Russian troops sit on Ukraine's southwestern flank","str":"md"}],"gov":[{"src":"Russian Presidential Decree (15 May 2026)","detail":"Simplified citizenship for adults permanently resident in Transnistria; waives residency, language, and history/law exam requirements; justified as protecting 'rights and freedoms' under international law"},{"src":"Russian Federation Council (20 May 2026)","detail":"Finalised legislation permitting military deployment abroad to protect Russian nationals subject to legal action or detention by foreign courts Moscow does not recognise"},{"src":"Sergei Shoigu (Apr 2026)","detail":"Warned 220,000+ Russian citizens in Transnistria were 'under threat'; Russia could use 'all available constitutional means' to protect them"},{"src":"President Maia Sandu (16 May 2026)","detail":"'Probably they need more people to send to the war in Ukraine' — reads the decree as a mobilisation instrument"},{"src":"German Marshall Fund (Jun 2026)","detail":"Passportisation is Moscow rebuilding leverage at the moment Moldova's instruments against it are becoming consequential — a response to Russian weakness, not a plan born of strength"}],"econlev":[{"holder":"Moldova (Chișinău)","channel":"Customs + tax harmonisation","exp":"HIGH","detail":"Double duties, VAT and excise alignment, and a reintegration non-paper are pulling Transnistria into Moldova's fiscal space without a shot fired — the quiet annexation Russia is trying to interrupt"},{"holder":"Russia","channel":"Energy subsidy (collapsed)","exp":"MED","detail":"Free gas was the mechanism that sustained Transnistria for three decades. The war ended it. The passports are what Moscow reached for when the gas ran out."},{"holder":"Sheriff conglomerate","channel":"Market reorientation","exp":"MED","detail":"The region's dominant economic force has pivoted toward European markets — the elite's balance sheet is drifting west while its politics stay east"}],"external":[{"actor":"🇷🇺 Russia","side":"Transnistria","flow":"~1,500 troops since 1992; mass passportisation; a new law authorising force to protect 'citizens' abroad; Zakharova threatens 'immediate and adequate response'","tier":"documented","for":"A frozen conflict kept freezable — leverage over Moldova's EU trajectory, and possibly mobilisation manpower"},{"actor":"🇺🇦 Ukraine","side":"Moldova","flow":"Border with Transnistria closed since 2022 — the logistical fact that makes the Russian threat mostly rhetorical; Zelensky ordered joint response coordination with Chișinău","tier":"documented","for":"Deny Russia a second front on its southwestern flank"},{"actor":"🇪🇺 EU / 🇷🇴 Romania","side":"Moldova","flow":"Accession trajectory, financing, and energy substitution after Russian gas ended; Romania's ethno-linguistic tie gives Bucharest a direct stake","tier":"documented","for":"Complete the European integration of a state Russia considers its own sphere"}],"ext_flag":true,"mil":"There is no fighting — and that is exactly what makes the last three months alarming, because what was assembled instead was a legal architecture for intervention. In April 2026 Sergei Shoigu declared that more than 220,000 Russian citizens in Transnistria were under threat and that Moscow could use all available constitutional means to protect them. On 15 May Putin signed a decree granting fast-track Russian citizenship to any adult resident of the territory, waiving residency, language and civics requirements. On 20 May the Federation Council finalised a law permitting the deployment of the Russian military abroad to protect Russian nationals. Manufacture the citizens, declare them threatened, legislate the right to intervene — that is the Donbas playbook, executed in five weeks. The hard constraint is logistics: roughly 1,500 Russian troops sit in Transnistria, and with Ukraine's border closed there is no route to reinforce them.","pol":"The provocation was Moldova's success. Chișinău has been winning the slow war — a December 2025 law strips Moldovan citizenship from Transnistrians serving in the region's security organs, customs and VAT harmonisation is pulling the territory into Moldova's fiscal space, and a reintegration non-paper has been circulated to European partners. Russia's older instruments have failed: the free-gas subsidy that sustained Transnistria for thirty years collapsed with the war, and even the Sheriff conglomerate, the region's economic spine, has reoriented toward European markets. The German Marshall Fund's reading is the one to hold onto: this passportisation is a symptom of Russian weakness, not a demonstration of strength. President Sandu believes the decree is really about manpower for Ukraine; President Zelensky calls it Moscow staking a claim to territory. Both can be true.","eco":"Transnistria's economy was a Russian subsidy in the shape of a state, and the subsidy is gone. Heating and energy provision have degraded, public services have thinned, and the elite's own conglomerate is trading with Europe. Moldova's leverage is fiscal rather than military: double duties, tax harmonisation, and the slow legal absorption of a territory it never controlled. The Kremlin's counter-lever costs nothing to issue and creates an obligation it may not be able to honor — 220,000 passports, and no road to reach them.","assess":"Moldova enters at 61 (ELEVATED, strategic-watch), trend up — because the legal machinery of the Donbas was rebuilt on a second border in the space of five weeks, and this board should be tracking it while it is still paper. The correct read is dual and the board should hold both halves: the pretext is real and now fully constructed, and the capability to act on it is not there, because Ukraine's closed border strands the 1,500 Russian troops already inside. That is what makes this a watch theater rather than a conflict one. The deeper point is the one GMF makes: Moscow reached for passports precisely because the gas ran out, the Sheriff went west, and Chișinău's customs code was doing what tanks could not. It is a weakness move — which does not make it safe, because weakness moves are how frozen conflicts unfreeze. Watch the pace of passport uptake, any Russian attempt to open a land or air corridor, Moldova's reintegration timetable, and whether the new Federation Council law is invoked anywhere at all. Trend estimate — newly entered tracking.","tier":"ELEVATED","domain_tag":"Political","contested":{"summary":"A state manufactures citizens inside its neighbour, then legislates the right to defend them. Both sides are telling the truth about the other.","claims":[{"claim":"Russia frames passportisation as protecting the rights and freedoms of compatriots under international law.","who":"Moscow — 'protection of citizens' is the only frame under which intervention reads as obligation rather than aggression.","evid":"The decree text says exactly that. It is also the identical instrument used in Abkhazia, South Ossetia, occupied Ukraine, and the Donbas before 2022, followed within weeks by a law authorising military deployment abroad to protect those same citizens. The sequence is the evidence.","status":"DOCUMENTED — the pattern is the intent"},{"claim":"This is Donbas repeating on the Dniester.","who":"Kyiv and Chișinău — and it is a reasonable fear, not a manufactured one.","evid":"GMF cautions against reading it reductively. Ukraine's border is CLOSED; Russia cannot reinforce its 1,500 troops. The decree came after Moldova's economic strangulation was working and Russian patronage had collapsed. This is Moscow rebuilding leverage it has lost — the architecture of Donbas without the logistics of Donbas.","status":"CONTESTED — the pretext is Donbas; the capability is not"},{"claim":"Russia is simply responding to Moldova's own citizenship-stripping law and economic pressure on Transnistria.","who":"Moscow and Tiraspol — and the fact is real even if the conclusion isn't.","evid":"Moldova did pass a December 2025 law depriving Transnistrian security personnel of Moldovan citizenship, and has imposed duties that damaged the local budget. Both things are true at once: Chișinău is squeezing, and Moscow is answering with an instrument that has ended in war three times before.","status":"UNRESOLVED — both grievances are documented"}]},"history":{"roots":"Moldova is the small state Russia never let go. Carved from Romania by the 1940 Soviet annexation, independent since 1991 but with a Russian garrison still squatting in breakaway Transnistria, it has swung between Moscow and Brussels for three decades. Maia Sandu's pro-EU governments broke the oligarchic grip and won EU candidacy — through energy blackmail, a coup plot (2023), and industrial-scale election interference (the 2024-25 vote-buying operations). Ukraine's war made Moldova the next-domino question: Russian missiles cross its airspace, its Gagauz and Transnistrian levers are pre-positioned, and Merz names it alongside the Baltics as a target of Russia's next phase.","timeline":[{"date":"1940","e":"Soviet annexation from Romania — the origin of the identity split."},{"date":"1992","e":"Transnistria war; Russian 14th Army freezes the separation."},{"date":"2022","e":"EU candidacy granted as the war closes in."},{"date":"2023","e":"Russian coup plot exposed; energy blackmail peaks."},{"date":"2024-25","e":"Referendum + elections survive massive vote-buying interference."},{"date":"2026","e":"Sandu in Kyiv; Moscow's rhetoric escalates ('not a safe country'); the next-domino watch."}],"actors":[{"name":"Maia Sandu","bio":"The pro-EU president who broke the oligarchs and holds the westward course through every hybrid assault."},{"name":"Transnistria","bio":"The Russian-garrisoned sliver — a frozen conflict kept thawable, with ~1,500 Russian troops and a giant ammo dump at Cobasna."},{"name":"Russia","bio":"Runs the full hybrid playbook here: energy, clergy, Gagauzia, vote-buying, coup plots — Moldova as the lab."},{"name":"EU / Romania","bio":"The anchor pulling Moldova west — accession talks as the counter-offer to coercion."}],"bridge":"Moldova is the hybrid-war laboratory whose results now read as a syllabus: energy blackmail (failed), clergy networks, Gagauz separatist levers, industrial vote-buying (absorbed), coup plotting (exposed) — each survived round strengthened Chișinău's westward case and raised Moscow's next bid. King's 'Moldovans' thesis — a nation built between Romanian and Russian projects — explains why the identity fight is the terrain itself. Transnistria's garrison and the Cobasna dump remain the pre-positioned escalation; Merz naming Moldova beside the Baltics moves it formally onto NATO's warning map without NATO's guarantee — the most exposed position in Europe.","sources":[{"work":"The Moldovans: Romania, Russia, and the Politics of Culture","author":"Charles King","year":"2000","note":"The standard on Moldovan identity formation between two projects."},{"work":"Moldovan election-interference documentation","author":"Promo-LEX / EU election observation","year":"2024-25","note":"Primary record of the vote-buying operations' scale."},{"work":"OSCE records on Transnistria / Cobasna","author":"OSCE","year":"ongoing","note":"The frozen-conflict architecture and the ammunition-depot file."}]}},{"id":"belarus","cat":"military","region":"Europe / Russia","subregion":"Europe","tclass":"watch","name":"Belarus — Oreshnik Host + the Prisoner-for-Potash Trade","sub":"Oreshnik IRBM on combat duty · nuclear drills · 250 prisoners freed for potash sanctions relief","domain":"Nuclear Basing / Hostage Diplomacy","sev":"high","status":"volatile","since":"2022 (invasion staging)","esc":64,"lat":53.9,"lon":27.57,"trend":"ss","esc_history":[60,61,63,64,64,64,64,64,64,64],"hist_real":false,"as_of":"15 Jul 2026","tracked_since":"Wk16 (Jul 2026)","cas":"No combat casualties on Belarusian soil — the harm is exported (staging ground for the 2022 invasion; drone corridor into Ukraine)","disp":"1,000+ political prisoners still held on politically motivated grounds; opposition in exile under Tsikhanouskaya","flag":"🇧🇾","note":"NEW THEATER (Wk16 · Belarus was load-bearing in the Ukraine and NATO-flank theaters and tracked in neither) · THE NUCLEAR FACT: Russia deployed the ORESHNIK intermediate-range ballistic missile to Belarus in DEC 2025 — Lukashenko confirmed it entered combat duty; Russian MoD video (30 Dec) showed mobile launchers in Belarusian forests · Belarus already hosts several dozen Russian TACTICAL nuclear weapons; the 2024 Russian nuclear doctrine formally placed Belarus under Moscow's umbrella · Putin: Russia retains control of the warheads, but MINSK MAY SELECT THE TARGETS · Russian state media boasted Oreshnik needs 11 MINUTES to reach a Polish air base and 17 to reach NATO HQ in Brussels · MAY 2026: joint Russia-Belarus drills PRACTISING NUCLEAR WEAPONS USE (Asipovichy, Mogilev region) · JUL 2026 Lukashenko: the deployment 'can temper even the most heated minds' · THE OTHER TRACK — HOSTAGE DIPLOMACY: Lukashenko is simultaneously courting Washington. Dec 2025: freed 123 political prisoners incl. Nobel laureate ALES BIALIATSKI, and the US lifted sanctions on Belarusian POTASH — the country's key export earner. MAR 2026: 250 more released (largest single release to date) for further partial sanctions relief · 1,000+ remain imprisoned; critics say the releases amount to TRADING IN HUMAN LIVES — a hostage market with a price list · EU went the other way: Dec 2025 broadened sanctions to cover HYBRID activities incl. the deliberate instrumentalisation of migrants at the eastern border; extended Feb 2026 · UKRAINE PRESSURE WORKS: after a Ukrainian ultimatum, Zelensky said Belarus HALTED the equipment used to guide Russian strikes — 'as of today, the equipment is no longer operating' · TSIKHANOUSKAYA: 'The deployment of Oreshnik turns Belarus into a target and militarizes the country'","leverage":[{"actor":"Russia","asset":"Owns the warheads, the doctrine, and the regime's survival — Belarus is less an ally than a forward deployment zone with a flag","str":"hi"},{"actor":"Lukashenko","asset":"The hostage market — 1,000+ political prisoners as a renewable currency, redeemable against sanctions relief; plus the territory Moscow needs","str":"md"},{"actor":"United States","asset":"Potash sanctions — the single lever Lukashenko actually responds to, and the one Washington keeps spending on prisoner releases rather than on the war","str":"md"},{"actor":"Ukraine","asset":"Direct coercion that WORKED — an ultimatum shut down the strike-guidance equipment operating from Belarusian territory","str":"md"},{"actor":"Belarusian opposition (Tsikhanouskaya)","asset":"Moral standing and Western recognition — but no leverage over the arsenal now parked in the forests","str":"lo"}],"gov":[{"src":"Lukashenko (Dec 2025 + Jul 2026)","detail":"Confirmed Oreshnik arrived and entered combat duty; says the deployment plus tactical nuclear weapons 'significantly enhances our defence and can temper even the most heated minds'"},{"src":"Russian MoD (30 Dec 2025)","detail":"Released video showing multiple Oreshnik mobile launchers deployed in Belarusian forests"},{"src":"US–Belarus deal (Dec 2025 / Mar 2026)","detail":"123 political prisoners released incl. Ales Bialiatski, followed by 250 more — in exchange for lifting US sanctions on the Belarusian potash sector"},{"src":"EU Council (Dec 2025, extended Feb 2026)","detail":"Broadened the Belarus sanctions regime to cover hybrid activities including the deliberate instrumentalisation of migrants at the EU's eastern border"},{"src":"President Zelensky","detail":"Said Belarus halted the equipment used to guide Russian strikes following a Ukrainian ultimatum — 'as of today, the equipment is no longer operating'"}],"econlev":[{"holder":"United States","channel":"Potash sanctions","exp":"HIGH","detail":"Potash is Belarus's key export earner and the only lever Lukashenko has visibly responded to. Washington has spent it twice — on prisoners, not on the war effort or the missiles."},{"holder":"Lukashenko","channel":"Political prisoners","exp":"HIGH","detail":"1,000+ still held. Each release is priced. The supply is replenishable, which is precisely what makes it a market rather than a reform."},{"holder":"Russia","channel":"Subsidy + nuclear umbrella","exp":"HIGH","detail":"Energy subsidies and security guarantees keep the regime solvent; the price is territory, airspace, and now nuclear basing"}],"external":[{"actor":"🇷🇺 Russia","side":"regime","flow":"Oreshnik IRBMs (Dec 2025) + tactical nuclear weapons; the 2024 doctrine extends the nuclear umbrella over Belarus; joint nuclear-use drills (May 2026); staged the 2022 invasion from Belarusian soil","tier":"documented","for":"A forward nuclear platform 11 minutes from Polish airbases — and a client whose survival depends on Moscow"},{"actor":"🇺🇸 US","side":"transactional","flow":"Lifted potash sanctions in exchange for prisoner releases (123 in Dec 2025, 250 in Mar 2026); seeking a thaw even as the missiles arrive","tier":"documented","for":"Prisoner releases and a wedge — however small — between Minsk and Moscow"},{"actor":"🇪🇺 EU","side":"sanctioning","flow":"Extended sanctions to hybrid activities including weaponized migration at the eastern border; no thaw","tier":"documented","for":"Deny Minsk the reward Washington is offering — an open transatlantic split on Belarus policy"},{"actor":"🇺🇦 Ukraine","side":"coercing","flow":"Ultimatum forced Belarus to shut down strike-guidance equipment; accuses Belarusian territory of hosting drone corridors into Ukraine","tier":"documented","for":"Close the northern approach"}],"ext_flag":true,"mil":"Belarus is now a forward nuclear platform. Russia deployed the Oreshnik intermediate-range ballistic missile there in December 2025 — Lukashenko confirmed it entered combat duty, and the Russian Defence Ministry released video of mobile launchers in Belarusian forests on 30 December. The country already hosts several dozen Russian tactical nuclear weapons, and Moscow's 2024 doctrine formally placed it under the Russian nuclear umbrella. The arrangement is deliberately ambiguous: Putin says Russia keeps control of the warheads but Minsk may select the targets. Russian state media put the flight time at eleven minutes to a Polish air base and seventeen to NATO headquarters in Brussels, which is the entire point of saying it out loud. In May 2026 the two militaries ran joint drills practising nuclear weapons use.","pol":"Lukashenko is running two policies at once. While hosting the missiles, he has been selling political prisoners to Washington: 123 released in December 2025, including Nobel laureate Ales Bialiatski, in exchange for the lifting of US sanctions on Belarusian potash — the country's key export earner — followed by 250 more in March 2026, the largest single release to date, for further partial relief. More than a thousand remain imprisoned, which is what makes it a market rather than a reform: the currency is renewable. The EU has moved in the opposite direction, extending sanctions to cover hybrid operations including the weaponization of migrants at its eastern border, leaving an open transatlantic split. Ukraine, meanwhile, demonstrated that direct coercion works — after an ultimatum, Zelensky reported that the equipment guiding Russian strikes from Belarusian territory had stopped operating.","eco":"Potash is the hinge. It is Belarus's principal export earner, the one sanction Lukashenko visibly feels, and the price Washington has now paid twice — for prisoners, not for the missiles and not for the drone corridors. Russian energy subsidies and security guarantees cover the rest of the regime's balance sheet, and the payment for those is territory, airspace, and now nuclear basing. Tsikhanouskaya's warning is the honest ledger: the deployment 'turns Belarus into a target and militarizes the country' — Minsk is accumulating risk it does not control in exchange for solvency it cannot generate.","assess":"Belarus enters at 64 (ELEVATED, strategic-watch) — a theater the board was already leaning on without tracking, since Belarus is the staging ground in the Ukraine theater and the launch geography in the NATO Eastern Flank theater. Its significance is the two-track contradiction: Lukashenko hosts Oreshnik missiles eleven minutes from Polish airbases while simultaneously trading political prisoners to Washington for potash relief — and both tracks are working. That contradiction is the finding. It tells you the US thaw is not buying strategic change (the missiles arrived anyway, the nuclear drills went ahead anyway), and it tells you Minsk has correctly identified that hostages are cheaper to produce than concessions. The one intervention that produced a real behavioral change was Ukraine's ultimatum on the strike-guidance equipment — coercion, not inducement. Watch the Oreshnik deployment posture, the next prisoner-release tranche and what it costs, the EU-US split on sanctions, and any Belarusian involvement in a NATO-flank incursion. Trend estimate — newly entered tracking.","tier":"ELEVATED","domain_tag":"Military","contested":{"summary":"Prisoners are released, sanctions are lifted, and the nuclear missiles arrive anyway. Ask what was actually bought.","claims":[{"claim":"The US prisoner-for-sanctions deals represent progress and a thaw with Minsk.","who":"Washington, which needs a win — and Lukashenko, who needs the potash revenue.","evid":"373 prisoners have been freed across two tranches, which is real and matters to 373 families. In the same window Belarus took delivery of Oreshnik IRBMs, ran joint nuclear-use drills with Russia, and kept 1,000+ prisoners in custody. Critics call it trading in human lives; the supply is renewable, so the price will be paid again. The Atlantic Council's position is that relief should have bought limits on Belarusian facilitation of the war — it did not.","status":"CONTESTED — the releases are real; the strategic return is not"},{"claim":"Lukashenko says the nuclear deployment is purely defensive — 'we're not raising these issues to scare anyone.'","who":"Minsk — a deterrent framing is the only one available to a state that has no say over the warheads on its own soil.","evid":"Russian state media itself advertised the flight times to Poland and Brussels. Putin says Moscow retains control of the weapons while Minsk may pick targets — an arrangement that gives Belarus the risk and Russia the decision. Tsikhanouskaya's counter is the plain one: it makes Belarus a target.","status":"CONTESTED — the deterrent belongs to Moscow; the target is Belarus"}]},"history":{"roots":"Belarus is the state that never left the Soviet Union in spirit — and after 2020, lost even nominal independence. Lukashenko has ruled since 1994 as Europe's last dictator; when the 2020 election fraud triggered mass protests, he survived only on Russian backing, and the price was sovereignty: Russian troops, nuclear weapons, and the use of Belarusian territory to invade Ukraine. The regime's exports are manufactured crises — the weaponized-migrant operations on the Polish/Lithuanian borders — and its function in Russian strategy is geographic: the northern vector against Kyiv and the western platform against NATO. The succession question (Lukashenko is 71, ailing) is Moscow's to answer now.","timeline":[{"date":"1994","e":"Lukashenko elected — never leaves."},{"date":"2020","e":"Stolen election; mass protests crushed with Russian backing — sovereignty mortgaged."},{"date":"2021","e":"Ryanair hijacking; weaponized-migrant crisis on EU borders."},{"date":"2022","e":"Belarusian territory used to invade Ukraine."},{"date":"2023","e":"Russian tactical nuclear weapons deployed."},{"date":"2025-26","e":"Prisoner-release diplomacy with the US; drills near the border; the platform state endures."}],"actors":[{"name":"Alexander Lukashenko","bio":"Ruler since 1994 — survived 2020 by selling sovereignty to Moscow; now balancing token US outreach against total Russian dependence."},{"name":"Russia","bio":"The owner — troops, nukes, and union-state integration make Belarus the western military district in all but name."},{"name":"The exiled opposition (Tsikhanouskaya)","bio":"The 2020 movement's government-in-exile — legitimacy without leverage."},{"name":"Poland / Lithuania","bio":"The targets of the border-weaponization operations and the hosts of the exile."}],"bridge":"Belarus completes the platform-state model: sovereignty mortgaged in 2020, territory lent for invasion in 2022, nuclear weapons hosted by 2023 — Wilson's 'last dictatorship' now less a dictatorship than a leased military district whose dictator's remaining leverage is his own succession. The weaponized-migrant operations and border drills are the rent Belarus pays in kind; the token US prisoner-diplomacy is Lukashenko probing whether any western door remains ajar. The tripwire here is actuarial: the transition after a 71-year-old ruler in a Russian-garrisoned state is Moscow's to script, and Europe's to absorb.","sources":[{"work":"Belarus: The Last European Dictatorship","author":"Andrew Wilson","year":"2011 (rev. 2021)","note":"The standard political history through the 2020 uprising."},{"work":"Viasna human-rights documentation","author":"Viasna Centre (Ales Bialiatski, Nobel 2022)","year":"2020-26","note":"Primary record of the repression from Belarus's own rights movement."},{"work":"OSCE Moscow Mechanism reports on Belarus","author":"OSCE","year":"2020-23","note":"The formal international findings on the stolen election and crackdown."}]}},{"id":"georgia","cat":"political","region":"South Caucasus","subregion":"Caucasus","tclass":"watch","name":"Georgia — Captured State + the Abkhazia Naval Base","sub":"EU accession frozen to 2028 · 365+ days of protest · Russia building a naval base at Ochamchire","domain":"Democratic Capture / Russian Re-absorption","sev":"medium","status":"escalating","since":"2024 (foreign agents law)","esc":57,"lat":41.72,"lon":44.79,"trend":"up","esc_history":[50,51,52,54,55,56,57,57,57,57],"hist_real":false,"as_of":"14 Jul 2026","tracked_since":"Wk16 (Jul 2026)","cas":"200+ reported injuries across protesters and police; no fatalities — the coercion is legal and administrative rather than lethal","disp":"20% of Georgian territory occupied (Abkhazia, South Ossetia) since 2008; activists, journalists and opposition figures detained","flag":"🇬🇪","note":"NEW THEATER (Wk16 · the Caucasus theater tracked the TRIPP corridor and Armenia-Azerbaijan — but not the country Russia is actually taking back) · THE CAPTURE: Georgian Dream (founded by billionaire BIDZINA IVANISHVILI, in power since 2012) passed a Russian-modelled 'FOREIGN AGENTS' law (May 2024), won an October 2024 election the European Parliament called neither free nor fair, and on 28 Nov 2024 SUSPENDED EU ACCESSION until at least 2028 · the EU formally froze the accession process in Dec 2024; the US and EU cut funding, suspended partnerships, and sanctioned officials involved in the crackdown — AND THE PRESSURE MISFIRED: Georgian Dream reframed it as Brussels using membership as 'blackmail' and hardened · THE CONTRADICTION AT THE CORE: ~80% of Georgians support EU integration, and the Georgian CONSTITUTION MANDATES Euro-Atlantic integration — the government is in breach of its own founding document · PROTESTS: 365+ consecutive days outside parliament; up to ~500 nightly; 200+ injuries; the state has answered with fines, detentions of activists, opposition figures and journalists, and new laws criminalising criticism of officials — a slow legal strangulation rather than a massacre · THE HARD FACT UNDERNEATH: RUSSIA HAS BEGUN CONSTRUCTION OF A NAVAL BASE IN OCCUPIED ABKHAZIA (Ochamchire) — the first new Russian Black Sea basing since the war began, on Georgian sovereign territory · PASSPORTISATION CROSS-LINK: in MAY 2025 Putin issued the SAME simplified-citizenship decree for ABKHAZIA and SOUTH OSSETIA that he issued for Transnistria in May 2026 — one instrument, three borders · Tbilisi is also increasing outreach to CHINA · 20% of Georgia has been occupied since 2008; many Georgians treat Russian re-absorption as a question of WHEN, not IF","leverage":[{"actor":"Bidzina Ivanishvili / Georgian Dream","asset":"Total institutional capture — parliament, courts, the foreign-agents law, and a compliant electoral process; sanctioned by Washington and still governing","str":"hi"},{"actor":"Russia","asset":"20% of the country already occupied; a naval base under construction at Ochamchire; passportisation in Abkhazia and South Ossetia; and a government in Tbilisi that no longer resists","str":"hi"},{"actor":"The Georgian street","asset":"365+ days of continuous protest and ~80% public support for EU accession — genuine legitimacy, and no institutional route to convert it into power","str":"md"},{"actor":"EU","asset":"The accession carrot — which Georgian Dream has now DECLINED, converting the EU's main lever into a grievance it campaigns on","str":"lo"},{"actor":"China","asset":"The alternative patron Tbilisi is courting as Western funding and partnerships are withdrawn","str":"md"}],"gov":[{"src":"European Council (Dec 2024) / European Parliament","detail":"Formally suspended Georgia's accession process; the EP called the October 2024 election neither free nor fair and condemned 'Russia's systematic interference in Georgia's democratic processes'"},{"src":"Venice Commission (Opinion 1201/2024)","detail":"Criticised the 'Law on Transparency of Foreign Influence' as incompatible with European standards"},{"src":"US State Department","detail":"Suspended the strategic partnership and sanctioned officials responsible for violence against protesters; 'the Georgian people overwhelmingly support integration with Europe'"},{"src":"OSAC / Human Rights Watch (World Report 2026)","detail":"365+ days of protests; 200+ injuries; escalating fines, detentions of activists, opposition members and journalists; restrictions on criticism of officials"}],"econlev":[{"holder":"Russia","channel":"Trade + occupied territory","exp":"HIGH","detail":"Georgian Dream spent a decade threading favorable economic dealings with Moscow against a Western political alignment. The thread has snapped, and only the Russian half remains — with a naval base now going up on occupied Georgian soil."},{"holder":"EU","channel":"Accession + funding (withdrawn)","exp":"LOW","detail":"The accession carrot was the West's only real lever, and Georgian Dream chose to refuse it — which converted the lever into a campaign issue. Sanctions and funding cuts have not moved the government."},{"holder":"China","channel":"Alternative patronage","exp":"MED","detail":"Tbilisi's increasing outreach to Beijing and other autocratic partners is the exit route from Western conditionality — the same substitution the Sahel juntas made"}],"external":[{"actor":"🇷🇺 Russia","side":"Georgian Dream (de facto)","flow":"Occupies 20% of the country; building a naval base at Ochamchire in occupied Abkhazia; passportised Abkhazia and South Ossetia by decree (May 2025); systematic interference documented by the European Parliament","tier":"documented","for":"Re-absorb a state that spent two decades trying to leave — and gain a new Black Sea naval base outside Ukrainian reach"},{"actor":"🇪🇺 EU","side":"Georgian society","flow":"Froze accession, cut funding, threatened sanctions on those undermining Georgian democracy — and watched the pressure misfire into a sovereignty grievance","tier":"documented","for":"Complete the Euro-Atlantic integration ~80% of Georgians want"},{"actor":"🇺🇸 US","side":"pressure","flow":"Suspended the strategic partnership; sanctioned officials involved in the crackdown, including figures around Ivanishvili","tier":"documented","for":"Prevent a Black Sea state from flipping into Moscow's orbit"},{"actor":"🇨🇳 China","side":"Georgian Dream","flow":"Growing outreach and partnership as Western funding is withdrawn","tier":"alleged-credible","for":"A Black Sea / Middle Corridor foothold offered without democratic conditionality"}],"ext_flag":true,"mil":"Not a shooting war — a re-absorption. Twenty percent of Georgia has been under Russian occupation since 2008, and Moscow has now begun construction of a naval base at Ochamchire in occupied Abkhazia: the first new Russian Black Sea basing of the war era, built on Georgian sovereign territory, positioned beyond the reach of Ukrainian naval drones. In May 2025 Putin extended the same simplified-citizenship decree to Abkhazia and South Ossetia that he would issue for Transnistria a year later — one instrument, deployed on three borders. The domestic coercion is legal rather than lethal: fines, detentions of activists, opposition figures and journalists, and laws criminalising criticism of officials. Over 200 people have been injured in protests; nobody has been killed.","pol":"This is the clearest case of democratic capture on the board. Georgian Dream, founded by billionaire Bidzina Ivanishvili and in power since 2012, passed a Russian-modelled foreign-agents law in May 2024, won an October election the European Parliament judged neither free nor fair, and on 28 November 2024 suspended EU accession talks until at least 2028 — in a country whose constitution mandates Euro-Atlantic integration and roughly 80% of whose citizens support it. The government is in open breach of its own founding document, and it is winning. Western pressure misfired: the EU froze accession, Washington sanctioned officials and suspended the strategic partnership, and Georgian Dream simply reframed the whole thing as Brussels using membership as blackmail against Georgian sovereignty. Protesters have now been outside parliament for over a year.","eco":"Georgian Dream's original bargain was to thread favorable economic dealings with Russia through a pro-Western political alignment. The thread has snapped and only the Russian half is left. Western funding and partnership programmes have been cut, which removed the conditionality but also the leverage, and Tbilisi has increased outreach to China and other autocratic partners — the same substitution the Sahel juntas made when they expelled France. The EU's accession carrot was the only lever that ever worked here, and the government's answer was to refuse it and campaign on the refusal.","assess":"Georgia enters at 57 (ELEVATED, strategic-watch), trend up — and it fills the hole in the Caucasus: the platform tracked the TRIPP corridor and the Armenia-Azerbaijan settlement while missing the country Russia is quietly taking back. The finding that should unsettle the board is that Western pressure has been tried here and has failed. Sanctions, funding cuts, suspended partnerships and a frozen accession process were all deployed, and the government hardened, reframed the pressure as blackmail, and turned to Beijing. Meanwhile the concrete goes up at Ochamchire — a new Russian Black Sea naval base on occupied Georgian soil, out of Ukrainian reach. The passportisation cross-link is the thread to pull: the identical decree Putin signed for Abkhazia and South Ossetia in May 2025 he signed for Transnistria in May 2026. One instrument, three borders, and a board that should now be watching all three. Watch the Ochamchire construction, the protest movement's endurance, further criminalization of dissent, and any move toward formal annexation of the occupied territories. Trend estimate — newly entered tracking.","tier":"ELEVATED","domain_tag":"Political","contested":{"summary":"A government that froze EU accession says it is defending sovereignty. Eighty percent of the country and the constitution disagree.","claims":[{"claim":"Georgian Dream says it suspended EU accession to defend Georgian sovereignty against Brussels' 'blackmail.'","who":"Ivanishvili's party — sovereignty is the only frame under which abandoning the EU reads as patriotism rather than capture.","evid":"Around 80% of Georgians support EU integration and the constitution MANDATES Euro-Atlantic integration. The European Parliament called the election that produced this government neither free nor fair and condemned systematic Russian interference. The 'sovereignty' being defended is the party's, not the country's.","status":"CONTESTED — the mandate claimed does not exist"},{"claim":"Western sanctions and funding cuts will pressure Georgian Dream back toward Europe.","who":"Brussels and Washington, which had no other instruments to try.","evid":"It has been tried and it misfired. The government reframed the pressure as blackmail, hardened the crackdown, and expanded outreach to China. Meanwhile Russia is building a naval base at Ochamchire. The lever did not fail because it was too weak; it failed because it was the only one, and refusing it cost the party nothing.","status":"CONTESTED — the pressure campaign is the case study in what does not work"}]},"history":{"roots":"Georgia is the cautionary tale of a westward turn reversed from within. The 2003 Rose Revolution made it the post-Soviet reform star; the 2008 Russian invasion (over South Ossetia) showed the cost, freezing 20% of its territory under occupation. Bidzina Ivanishvili's Georgian Dream party, in power since 2012, executed a slow-motion capture: courts, media, election machinery — culminating in the 2024 'foreign agents' law, a disputed election, the suspension of EU accession, and mass protests met with force. Georgia now sits where Belarus was in 2019: formally sovereign, functionally realigning toward Moscow, with its society in the streets against it.","timeline":[{"date":"2003","e":"Rose Revolution — the pro-Western reform era."},{"date":"2008","e":"Russian invasion; Abkhazia + South Ossetia occupied."},{"date":"2012","e":"Ivanishvili's Georgian Dream takes power."},{"date":"2024","e":"'Foreign agents' law; disputed election; EU accession suspended; protests begin."},{"date":"2025-26","e":"Protest crackdowns, opposition arrests — the capture consolidates; the West sanctions individuals, hesitates on more."}],"actors":[{"name":"Bidzina Ivanishvili","bio":"The billionaire behind Georgian Dream — made his fortune in Russia, runs the state from behind a rotating cast of premiers."},{"name":"The protest movement","bio":"The pro-EU street — nightly demonstrations since 2024, the society the government is governing against."},{"name":"Russia","bio":"Occupier of 20% of the territory and beneficiary of the drift — winning without invading again."},{"name":"EU","bio":"The suspended destination — candidacy frozen, leverage reduced to visas and sanctions."}],"bridge":"Georgia tests whether a society can be re-captured against its majority: the nightly protests are the EU-candidate public, the state machinery is Ivanishvili's, and the 20% occupation is Russia's standing veto on the outcome. De Waal's Caucasus frame — small states as instruments of larger balances — explains the West's hesitation: Georgia is punished with suspension, not rescued with leverage, because its capture costs Brussels less than its defense would. The Caucasus corridor politics (TRIPP) now route around Georgia's uncertainty — drift has a price, and it is being paid in relevance.","sources":[{"work":"The Caucasus: An Introduction","author":"Thomas de Waal","year":"2010 (2nd ed. 2018)","note":"The standard regional frame — small-state agency inside great-power balances."},{"work":"OSCE/ODIHR reports on Georgian elections and the foreign-agents law","author":"OSCE/ODIHR; Venice Commission","year":"2024-25","note":"Primary institutional findings on the capture instruments."},{"work":"EU Council conclusions suspending accession","author":"European Council","year":"2024","note":"The primary record of the suspension and its conditions."}]}},{"id":"turkey","cat":"military","region":"Middle East","subregion":"Middle East","tclass":"watch","name":"Turkey — Drone Empire + Neo-Ottoman Overreach","sub":"65%+ of the global drone market · bases from Syria to the Horn · 'Turkey is bigger than Turkey'","domain":"Regional Power Projection / Arms Diplomacy","sev":"high","status":"escalating","since":"2016 (expeditionary turn)","esc":68,"lat":39.93,"lon":32.86,"trend":"up","esc_history":[60,61,62,63,64,65,65,66,66,68],"hist_real":false,"as_of":"15 Jul 2026","tracked_since":"Wk16 (Jul 2026)","cas":"No direct Turkish combat casualties currently — power is projected through proxies, drones, and bases rather than large deployments","disp":"Hosts ~3M+ Syrian refugees; Kurdish populations displaced by cross-border operations in Syria and Iraq","flag":"🇹🇷","note":"JUL — TURKEY'S MOMENT: hosted the NATO leaders summit (Ankara); Trump floated F-35 SALES to Turkey at the summit — Israel objecting hard · Netanyahu to CNN: Erdoğan 'threatens to destroy my country... not exactly a model ally' — the Turkey-Israel collision is now open and personal, raised directly in Trump-Netanyahu calls (security zones + Erdoğan rhetoric) · Erdoğan accuses Israel of undermining the US-Iran MoU · Turkey now anchors the new Saudi-led axis (with Qatar/Pakistan/Egypt, without UAE) and its KAAN fighter has Saudi investment — Ankara converted the Iran war into centrality · NEW THEATER (Wk16 · the single most load-bearing untracked actor on the board — Turkey appears in Syria, Somalia, Libya, Sudan, Ethiopia, Gaza, the Caucasus and NATO-flank theaters and was tracked in none) · THE DRONE EMPIRE: Turkey controls 65%+ of the global drone market (